{"title_page": "Rani ki vav", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2019}}\n{{italics title}}\n{{Infobox UNESCO World Heritage Site\n| WHS           = Rani-ki-Vav (the Queen\u2019s Stepwell) at Patan, Gujarat\n| image         = Rani ki vav 02.jpg\n| image_upright = 1.2\n| caption       = Rani-ki-Vav\n| location      = [[Patan, Gujarat|Patan]], [[Patan district]], [[Gujarat]], [[India]], <!-- make selection: P17 (country) and possibly P131 (administrative subdivision of country) suffice in most cases -->\n| part_of       = \n| includes      = <!--replace by summary if the list of sub-entities is too large or incomplete-->\n| criteria      = {{UNESCO WHS type|(i), (iv)}}(i), (iv)\n| ID            = 922\n| coordinates   = {{coord|23|51|32|N|72|6|6|E|region:IN-GJ_type:landmark|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| year          = 2014\n| area          = {{convert|4.68|ha|acre|abbr=on}}\n| buffer_zone   = {{convert|125.44|ha|acre|abbr=on}}\n| locmapin      = India Gujarat#India\n| map_caption   = \n}}\n'''''Rani ki Vav''''' or '''''Ranki vav''''' ({{literally|'''Queen\u2019s stepwell'''}}) is a [[stepwell]] situated in the town of [[Patan, Gujarat|Patan]] in [[Gujarat]] state of [[India]]. It is located on the banks of [[Saraswati River, Gujarat|Saraswati river]]. Its construction is attributed to Udayamati, daughter of [[Khengara]] of Saurashtra, queen of the 11th-century [[Chaulukya dynasty]] and spouse of [[Bhima I]]. Silted over, it was rediscovered in 1940s and restored in 1980s by the [[Archaeological Survey of India]]. It has been listed as one of [[UNESCO World Heritage Sites in India|UNESCO's World Heritage Sites]] since 2014.\n\nThe finest and one of the largest example of [[History of stepwells in Gujarat|its kind]] and designed as an inverted temple highlighting the sanctity of water, the stepwell is divided into seven levels of stairs with sculptural panels; more than 500 principle sculptures and over a thousand minor ones combine religious, mythological and secular imagery.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Rani ki vav1.jpg|thumb|250px|Inside Rani ki vav|left]]\n[https://www.ranikivav.com/ Rani ki vav] was constructed during the rule of the [[Chaulukya dynasty]]. It is located on the banks of [[Saraswati River, Gujarat|Saraswati river]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/922|title=Rani-ki-Vav (the Queen's Stepwell) at Patan, Gujarat \u2013 UNESCO World Heritage Centre|website=whc.unesco.org|language=en|accessdate=2015-12-05}}</ref> ''[[Prabandha-Chintamani]]'', composed by the Jain monk [[Merutunga]] in 1304, mentions: \"Udayamati, the daughter of Naravaraha [[Khengara|Khangara]], built this novel stepwell at Shripattana (Patan) surpassing the glory of the [[Sahastralinga Tank]]\". According to it, the stepwell was commissioned in 1063 and was completed after 20 years. It is generally assumed that it was built in the memory of [[Bhima I]] ({{reign|{{circa|1022}}|1064}}) by his queen Udayamati and probably completed by Udayamati and [[Karna (Chaulukya dynasty)|Karna]] after his death but the view, whether she was a widow when she commissioned it, is disputed. Commissariat puts the date of construction to 1032 based on the architectural similarity to [[Dilwara Temples|Vimalavasahi temple on Mount Abu]] built in the same year.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.325016|title=Gujaratlo Rajkiya Ane Sanskritik Itihas Granth Part-iii Itihasni Gujaratlo Rajkiya Ane Sanskritik Itihas Granth Part-iv Solanki|last=Shastri|first=Hariprasadji|date=1976|publisher=|isbn=|location=|pages=135\u2013137}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Vinod Chandra Srivastava |title=History of Agriculture in India, Up to C. 1200 A.D. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FvjZVwYVmNcC&pg=PA857 |year=2008 |publisher=Concept |isbn=978-81-8069-521-6 |page=857}}</ref>\n\nThe stepwell was later flooded by the nearby Saraswati river and silted over.<ref name=\":6\" /> In 1890s, Henry Cousens and [[James Burgess (archaeologist)|James Burgess]] visited it when it was completely buried under the earth and only well shaft and few pillars were visible. They called it huge pit measuring {{convert|87|m|ft}}. In  ''Travels in Western India,'' [[James Tod]] mentioned that the material from the stepwell was reused in the other stepwell built in modern Patan, probably Trikam Barot ni Vav (Bahadur Singh stepwell).<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|title=Steps to Water : The Ancient Stepwells of India|last=Livingston|first=Morna|last2=Beach|first2=Milo|publisher=Princeton Architectural Press|year=2002|isbn=1568983247|edition=1st|location=New York|pages=63\u201364|oclc=48263695|author-link2=Milo C. Beach}}</ref> In 1940s, the excavations carried out under the [[Baroda State]] revealed the stepwell. In 1986, the major excavation and restoration was carried out by the [[Archaeological Survey of India]] (ASI). An image of Udayamati was also recovered during the excavation. The restoration was carried out from 1981 to 1987.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=Her Space, Her Story : Exploring the Stepwells of Gujarat|last=Mehta Bhatt|first=Purnima|publisher=Zubaan|others=del Solar, Daniel|year=2014|isbn=9789383074495|location=New Delhi|pages=72\u201390|chapter=7. Queen's Stepwell (Rani ni Vav) - Patan, Gujarat|oclc=898408173}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bhopal/archeologist-who-restored-rani-ka-vav-recalls-his-role/story-R3Mq3CWwJYGfXSwiOQvYIN.html|title=Archeologist who restored Rani Ka Vav recalls his role|last=Tomar|first=Shruti|last2=Faruqui|first2=Mujeeb|date=2018-07-26|website=|publisher=Hindustan Times|location=Bhopal|language=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-06-20}}</ref>\n\nRani ki vav is declared the Monument of National Importance and protected by the ASI. It was added to the list of [[UNESCO World Heritage Sites in India|UNESCO's World Heritage Sites]] on 22 June 2014.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/news/1157|title=Four new cultural sites inscribed on World Heritage List|date=2014-06-22|work=UNESCO World Heritage Centre|accessdate=2014-10-11}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/06/gujarats-rani-ki-vav-added-to-unesco-world-heritage-site-list/|title=Gujarat's Rani ki Vav added to UNESCO World Heritage site List|work=IANS|publisher=news.biharprabha.com|accessdate=22 June 2014}}</ref> It was named India's \"Cleanest Iconic Place\" at the 2016 Indian Sanitation Conference.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/gujarat-world-heritage-site-rani-ki-vav-bags-cleanest-iconic-place-award/|title=Gujarat world heritage site: Rani ki Vav bags 'Cleanest Iconic Place' award|website=indianexpress.com|language=en|accessdate=2016-10-25}}</ref>\n\n== Architecture ==\n[[File:Rani Ki Vav, Above View.JPG|thumb|Rani ki vav, view from the top|left]]\nRani ki vav is considered as the finest and one of the largest example of stepwell architecture in Gujarat. It was built at the height of craftsmens\u2019 ability in stepwell construction and the [[Maru-Gurjara architecture]] style, reflecting mastery of this complex technique and beauty of detail and proportions. The architecture and sculptures is similar to the [[Dilwara Temples|Vimalavasahi temple on Mount Abu]] and [[Sun Temple, Modhera|Sun temple at Modhera]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIt is classified as a ''Nanda''-type stepwell. It measures approximately {{convert|65|m|ft}} long, {{convert|20|m|ft}} wide and {{convert|28|m|ft}} deep. The fourth level is the deepest and leads into a rectangular tank {{convert|9.5|m|ft}} by {{convert|9.4|m|ft}}, at a depth of {{convert|23|m|ft}}. The entrance is located in the east while the well is located at the westernmost end and consists of a shaft {{convert|10|m|ft}} in diameter and {{convert|30|m|ft}} deep.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> The stepwell is divided into seven levels of stairs which lead down to deep circular well. A stepped corridor is compartmentalized at regular intervals with pillared multistory pavilions. The walls, pillars, columns, brackets and beams are ornamented with carvings and scroll work. The niches in the side walls are ornamented with beautiful and delicate figures and sculptures. There are 212 pillars in the stepwell.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Sculptures ===\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Rani ki Vav Vishnu.jpg|[[Varaha]] (centre), woman with snake (left)\nFile:Rani ki Vaav 15.jpg|[[Vaman]] incarnation\nFile:Rani ki Vav - Vishnu.jpg|Rama incarnation\nFile:Kalki on Stone Panel.JPG|Kalki (centre), women with lipstick or twig (left) and with monkey (right)\nFile:Gujarat heritage.jpg|Woman pulling a beard of a dwarf-like man (left)\nFile:Ganesha, Sculptures at Rani ki Vav (15778247014).jpg|Ganesha and Apsaras\nFile:Maa Durga idol in rani ki vav.jpg|Durga/Mahishasurmardini\n</gallery>\n[[File:Rani Ki Vav - Patan, Gujarat.jpg|thumb|Wall with sculptural panels]]\n[[File:Queens stepwell, patan, gujarat.JPG|thumb|Wall with sculptural panels]]\n[[File:Rani ki vav 08.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Carved pillars]]\nThere are more than 500 principle sculptures and over a thousand minor ones combine religious, mythological and secular imagery, often referencing literary works.<ref name=\":4\" /> The ornamentation of stepwell depicts the entire universe inhabited by gods and goddesses; celestial beings; men and women; monks, priests and laity; animals, fishes and birds including real and mythical ones; as well as plants and trees.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":7\" />\n\nThe stepwell is designed as an underground shrine or inverted temple. It has spiritual significance and represents the sanctity of water.<ref name=\":4\" /> The sculptures in stepwell depicts numerous Hindu deities including [[Brahma]], [[Vishnu]], [[Shiva]], goddesses (''[[Devi]]''), [[Ganesha]], [[Kubera]], [[Lakulisha]], [[Bhairava]], [[Surya]], [[Indra]] and [[Hayagriva]]. The sculptures associated with Vishnu outnumbers all which include Sheshashayi Vishnu (Vishnu reclined on thousand hooded snake [[Shesha]] in the celestial ocean), Vishwarupa Vishnu (Cosmic form of Vishnu), twenty four forms as well as [[Dashavatara]] (ten incarnations) of Vishnu.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|title=The Stepwells of Gujarat. In Art-historical Perspective|last=Jain-Neubauer|first=Jutta|publisher=Abhinav Publications|year=1981|isbn=0391022849|edition=1st|location=New Delhi|pages=35|oclc=19399030}}</ref>\n\nThe sculptures of deities with their families such as Brahma-Savitri, Uma-Maheshwar and Lakshmi-Narayan are there. Notable among other sculptures are [[Ardhanarishvara|Ardhanarishwara]] as well as large number of goddesses such as [[Lakshmi]], [[Parvati]],  [[Saraswati]], [[Chamunda]], [[Durga]]/Mahishasurmardini with twenty hands, Kshemankari, Suryani and [[Matrikas|Saptamatrika]]<nowiki/>s. There are images of [[Navagraha]] (nine plantets) as well.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n\nThere are a large number of celestial beings (''[[Apsara]]''s). One sculpture of Apsara depicts either applying lipstick to her lips or chewing on aromatic twig while a man is ticking her feet. On the northern side of the third storey pavilion, there is a sculpture of an Apsara warding off a money clanged to her leg and pulling her clothes revealing her seductive body. At her feet, there is a nude female with a snake around her neck probably representing erotic motif. A sculpture of Nagkanya (serpent princess) with long hair and swan as well as sculptures of celestial dancers in classical dance positions are there.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThere are large number of sculptures portraying women in their everyday life and activities. One sculpture depicts a woman combing her hair, adjusting her earring  and looking herself in the mirror. Another sculptures include a woman writing a letter, a young woman with scorpion climbing her right leg and her clothes sliding off unknowingly, a young woman pulling a beard of a dwarf-like man, a woman with fish plate in her hands with a snake encircling her leg and reaching out to fish. One sculpture depicts a young women coming out of bath with her wet hair and a swan catching droplets of water falling from her hairs as if they are pearls. These women sculptures are adorned with jewelry including bangles, earrings, necklaces, waist girdles, anklets and others as well as with elegant clothes and well combed hairs. The variety of expressions and emotions are depicted in them. They represent beauty as well love in its sublime and seductive form signaling eroticism. There are sculptures representing maternal love such as a woman holding her child and pointing to moon to divert his attention, a woman raising her child high to let him pick a mango from tree, a woman in a mango grove with children with her.<ref name=\":3\" />\n[[File:Rani Ka Vav, Patan, Gujarat.jpg|thumb|Cantilevered brackets in well shaft]]\n[[File:Inside rani ki vav another wall structure.jpg|thumb|Geometric lattice patterns and designs resembling [[Patola Sari|Patola]] textile designs]]\nThere are gradually increasing cantilevered brackets in the well shaft which are profusely ornamented.<ref name=\":7\" /> There [[kalpavriksha]] carvings on the wall repents fertility and nature worship while [[kirtimukha]]<nowiki/>s and [[Makara (Hindu mythology)|makara]]<nowiki/>s adorn the basements and capitals of pillars.<ref name=\":3\" /> On the northern side wall of entrance of the stepwell, there are geometric lattice patterns and designs resembling designs of local textile tradition of [[Patola Sari|Patola]]. They may have been adapted from the wood carvings and the ceilings of the temples.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":7\" /> Animal figures of horses, elephants and lions are used as decoration of pillars and basement moldings.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Depiction ==\nSince July 2018, the [[Indian 100-rupee note|{{INR}}100]] banknote of [[Mahatma Gandhi New Series]], features Rani ki vav on the rear side.<ref>{{Cite web|title = RBI to Issue New Design \u20b9 100 Denomination Banknote|url = https://rbi.org.in/Scripts/BS_PressReleaseDisplay.aspx?prid=44533|website =rbi.org.in|accessdate = 2018-07-19|language = en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n*\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=Fu7VAAAAMAAJ|title=The Queen's stepwell at Patan|last=Mankodi|first=Kirit|publisher=Project for Indian Cultural Studies|year=1991|isbn=978-81-900184-0-1|location=Bombay|pages=|language=English|oclc=28801053}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.cyark.org/projects/rani-ki-vav 3D Model]\n\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{World Heritage Sites in India}}\n\n[[Category:Rajput era]]\n[[Category:Stepwells in Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Patan district]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Sites in India]]\n[[Category:Cultural history of Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Monuments of National Importance in Gujarat]]\n[[Category:M\u0101ru-Gurjara architecture]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2019}}\n{{italics title}}\n{{Infobox UNESCO World Heritage Site\n| WHS           = Rani-ki-Vav (the Queen\u2019s Stepwell) at Patan, Gujarat\n| image         = Rani ki vav 02.jpg\n| image_upright = 1.2\n| caption       = Rani-ki-Vav\n| location      = [[Patan, Gujarat|Patan]], [[Patan district]], [[Gujarat]], [[India]], <!-- make selection: P17 (country) and possibly P131 (administrative subdivision of country) suffice in most cases -->\n| part_of       = \n| includes      = <!--replace by summary if the list of sub-entities is too large or incomplete-->\n| criteria      = {{UNESCO WHS type|(i), (iv)}}(i), (iv)\n| ID            = 922\n| coordinates   = {{coord|23|51|32|N|72|6|6|E|region:IN-GJ_type:landmark|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| year          = 2014\n| area          = {{convert|4.68|ha|acre|abbr=on}}\n| buffer_zone   = {{convert|125.44|ha|acre|abbr=on}}\n| locmapin      = India Gujarat#India\n| map_caption   = \n}}\n'''''Rani ki Vav''''' or '''''Ranki vav''''' ({{literally|'''Queen\u2019s stepwell'''}}) is a [[stepwell]] situated in the town of [[Patan, Gujarat|Patan]] in [[Gujarat]] state of [[India]]. It is located on the banks of [[Saraswati River, Gujarat|Saraswati river]]. Its construction is attributed to Udayamati, daughter of [[Khengara]] of Saurashtra, queen of the 11th-century [[Chaulukya dynasty]] and spouse of [[Bhima I]]. Silted over, it was rediscovered in 1940s and restored in 1980s by the [[Archaeological Survey of India]]. It has been listed as one of [[UNESCO World Heritage Sites in India|UNESCO's World Heritage Sites]] since 2014.\n\nThe finest and one of the largest example of [[History of stepwells in Gujarat|its kind]] and designed as an inverted temple highlighting the sanctity of water, the stepwell is divided into seven levels of stairs with sculptural panels; more than 500 principle sculptures and over a thousand minor ones combine religious, mythological and secular imagery.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Rani ki vav1.jpg|thumb|250px|Inside Rani ki vav|left]]\nRani ki vav was constructed during the rule of the [[Chaulukya dynasty]]. It is located on the banks of [[Saraswati River, Gujarat|Saraswati river]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/922|title=Rani-ki-Vav (the Queen's Stepwell) at Patan, Gujarat \u2013 UNESCO World Heritage Centre|website=whc.unesco.org|language=en|accessdate=2015-12-05}}</ref> ''[[Prabandha-Chintamani]]'', composed by the Jain monk [[Merutunga]] in 1304, mentions: \"Udayamati, the daughter of Naravaraha [[Khengara|Khangara]], built this novel stepwell at Shripattana (Patan) surpassing the glory of the [[Sahastralinga Tank]]\". According to it, the stepwell was commissioned in 1063 and was completed after 20 years. It is generally assumed that it was built in the memory of [[Bhima I]] ({{reign|{{circa|1022}}|1064}}) by his queen Udayamati and probably completed by Udayamati and [[Karna (Chaulukya dynasty)|Karna]] after his death but the view, whether she was a widow when she commissioned it, is disputed. Commissariat puts the date of construction to 1032 based on the architectural similarity to [[Dilwara Temples|Vimalavasahi temple on Mount Abu]] built in the same year.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.325016|title=Gujaratlo Rajkiya Ane Sanskritik Itihas Granth Part-iii Itihasni Gujaratlo Rajkiya Ane Sanskritik Itihas Granth Part-iv Solanki|last=Shastri|first=Hariprasadji|date=1976|publisher=|isbn=|location=|pages=135\u2013137}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Vinod Chandra Srivastava |title=History of Agriculture in India, Up to C. 1200 A.D. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FvjZVwYVmNcC&pg=PA857 |year=2008 |publisher=Concept |isbn=978-81-8069-521-6 |page=857}}</ref>\n\nThe stepwell was later flooded by the nearby Saraswati river and silted over.<ref name=\":6\" /> In 1890s, Henry Cousens and [[James Burgess (archaeologist)|James Burgess]] visited it when it was completely buried under the earth and only well shaft and few pillars were visible. They called it huge pit measuring {{convert|87|m|ft}}. In  ''Travels in Western India,'' [[James Tod]] mentioned that the material from the stepwell was reused in the other stepwell built in modern Patan, probably Trikam Barot ni Vav (Bahadur Singh stepwell).<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|title=Steps to Water : The Ancient Stepwells of India|last=Livingston|first=Morna|last2=Beach|first2=Milo|publisher=Princeton Architectural Press|year=2002|isbn=1568983247|edition=1st|location=New York|pages=63\u201364|oclc=48263695|author-link2=Milo C. Beach}}</ref> In 1940s, the excavations carried out under the [[Baroda State]] revealed the stepwell. In 1986, the major excavation and restoration was carried out by the [[Archaeological Survey of India]] (ASI). An image of Udayamati was also recovered during the excavation. The restoration was carried out from 1981 to 1987.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=Her Space, Her Story : Exploring the Stepwells of Gujarat|last=Mehta Bhatt|first=Purnima|publisher=Zubaan|others=del Solar, Daniel|year=2014|isbn=9789383074495|location=New Delhi|pages=72\u201390|chapter=7. Queen's Stepwell (Rani ni Vav) - Patan, Gujarat|oclc=898408173}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bhopal/archeologist-who-restored-rani-ka-vav-recalls-his-role/story-R3Mq3CWwJYGfXSwiOQvYIN.html|title=Archeologist who restored Rani Ka Vav recalls his role|last=Tomar|first=Shruti|last2=Faruqui|first2=Mujeeb|date=2018-07-26|website=|publisher=Hindustan Times|location=Bhopal|language=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-06-20}}</ref>\n\nRani ki vav is declared the Monument of National Importance and protected by the ASI. It was added to the list of [[UNESCO World Heritage Sites in India|UNESCO's World Heritage Sites]] on 22 June 2014.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/news/1157|title=Four new cultural sites inscribed on World Heritage List|date=2014-06-22|work=UNESCO World Heritage Centre|accessdate=2014-10-11}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/06/gujarats-rani-ki-vav-added-to-unesco-world-heritage-site-list/|title=Gujarat's Rani ki Vav added to UNESCO World Heritage site List|work=IANS|publisher=news.biharprabha.com|accessdate=22 June 2014}}</ref> It was named India's \"Cleanest Iconic Place\" at the 2016 Indian Sanitation Conference.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/gujarat-world-heritage-site-rani-ki-vav-bags-cleanest-iconic-place-award/|title=Gujarat world heritage site: Rani ki Vav bags 'Cleanest Iconic Place' award|website=indianexpress.com|language=en|accessdate=2016-10-25}}</ref>\n\n== Architecture ==\n[[File:Rani Ki Vav, Above View.JPG|thumb|Rani ki vav, view from the top|left]]\nRani ki vav is considered as the finest and one of the largest example of stepwell architecture in Gujarat. It was built at the height of craftsmens\u2019 ability in stepwell construction and the [[Maru-Gurjara architecture]] style, reflecting mastery of this complex technique and beauty of detail and proportions. The architecture and sculptures is similar to the [[Dilwara Temples|Vimalavasahi temple on Mount Abu]] and [[Sun Temple, Modhera|Sun temple at Modhera]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIt is classified as a ''Nanda''-type stepwell. It measures approximately {{convert|65|m|ft}} long, {{convert|20|m|ft}} wide and {{convert|28|m|ft}} deep. The fourth level is the deepest and leads into a rectangular tank {{convert|9.5|m|ft}} by {{convert|9.4|m|ft}}, at a depth of {{convert|23|m|ft}}. The entrance is located in the east while the well is located at the westernmost end and consists of a shaft {{convert|10|m|ft}} in diameter and {{convert|30|m|ft}} deep.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> The stepwell is divided into seven levels of stairs which lead down to deep circular well. A stepped corridor is compartmentalized at regular intervals with pillared multistory pavilions. The walls, pillars, columns, brackets and beams are ornamented with carvings and scroll work. The niches in the side walls are ornamented with beautiful and delicate figures and sculptures. There are 212 pillars in the stepwell.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Sculptures ===\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Rani ki Vav Vishnu.jpg|[[Varaha]] (centre), woman with snake (left)\nFile:Rani ki Vaav 15.jpg|[[Vaman]] incarnation\nFile:Rani ki Vav - Vishnu.jpg|Rama incarnation\nFile:Kalki on Stone Panel.JPG|Kalki (centre), women with lipstick or twig (left) and with monkey (right)\nFile:Gujarat heritage.jpg|Woman pulling a beard of a dwarf-like man (left)\nFile:Ganesha, Sculptures at Rani ki Vav (15778247014).jpg|Ganesha and Apsaras\nFile:Maa Durga idol in rani ki vav.jpg|Durga/Mahishasurmardini\n</gallery>\n[[File:Rani Ki Vav - Patan, Gujarat.jpg|thumb|Wall with sculptural panels]]\n[[File:Queens stepwell, patan, gujarat.JPG|thumb|Wall with sculptural panels]]\n[[File:Rani ki vav 08.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Carved pillars]]\nThere are more than 500 principle sculptures and over a thousand minor ones combine religious, mythological and secular imagery, often referencing literary works.<ref name=\":4\" /> The ornamentation of stepwell depicts the entire universe inhabited by gods and goddesses; celestial beings; men and women; monks, priests and laity; animals, fishes and birds including real and mythical ones; as well as plants and trees.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":7\" />\n\nThe stepwell is designed as an underground shrine or inverted temple. It has spiritual significance and represents the sanctity of water.<ref name=\":4\" /> The sculptures in stepwell depicts numerous Hindu deities including [[Brahma]], [[Vishnu]], [[Shiva]], goddesses (''[[Devi]]''), [[Ganesha]], [[Kubera]], [[Lakulisha]], [[Bhairava]], [[Surya]], [[Indra]] and [[Hayagriva]]. The sculptures associated with Vishnu outnumbers all which include Sheshashayi Vishnu (Vishnu reclined on thousand hooded snake [[Shesha]] in the celestial ocean), Vishwarupa Vishnu (Cosmic form of Vishnu), twenty four forms as well as [[Dashavatara]] (ten incarnations) of Vishnu.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|title=The Stepwells of Gujarat. In Art-historical Perspective|last=Jain-Neubauer|first=Jutta|publisher=Abhinav Publications|year=1981|isbn=0391022849|edition=1st|location=New Delhi|pages=35|oclc=19399030}}</ref>\n\nThe sculptures of deities with their families such as Brahma-Savitri, Uma-Maheshwar and Lakshmi-Narayan are there. Notable among other sculptures are [[Ardhanarishvara|Ardhanarishwara]] as well as large number of goddesses such as [[Lakshmi]], [[Parvati]],  [[Saraswati]], [[Chamunda]], [[Durga]]/Mahishasurmardini with twenty hands, Kshemankari, Suryani and [[Matrikas|Saptamatrika]]<nowiki/>s. There are images of [[Navagraha]] (nine plantets) as well.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n\nThere are a large number of celestial beings (''[[Apsara]]''s). One sculpture of Apsara depicts either applying lipstick to her lips or chewing on aromatic twig while a man is ticking her feet. On the northern side of the third storey pavilion, there is a sculpture of an Apsara warding off a money clanged to her leg and pulling her clothes revealing her seductive body. At her feet, there is a nude female with a snake around her neck probably representing erotic motif. A sculpture of Nagkanya (serpent princess) with long hair and swan as well as sculptures of celestial dancers in classical dance positions are there.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThere are large number of sculptures portraying women in their everyday life and activities. One sculpture depicts a woman combing her hair, adjusting her earring  and looking herself in the mirror. Another sculptures include a woman writing a letter, a young woman with scorpion climbing her right leg and her clothes sliding off unknowingly, a young woman pulling a beard of a dwarf-like man, a woman with fish plate in her hands with a snake encircling her leg and reaching out to fish. One sculpture depicts a young women coming out of bath with her wet hair and a swan catching droplets of water falling from her hairs as if they are pearls. These women sculptures are adorned with jewelry including bangles, earrings, necklaces, waist girdles, anklets and others as well as with elegant clothes and well combed hairs. The variety of expressions and emotions are depicted in them. They represent beauty as well love in its sublime and seductive form signaling eroticism. There are sculptures representing maternal love such as a woman holding her child and pointing to moon to divert his attention, a woman raising her child high to let him pick a mango from tree, a woman in a mango grove with children with her.<ref name=\":3\" />\n[[File:Rani Ka Vav, Patan, Gujarat.jpg|thumb|Cantilevered brackets in well shaft]]\n[[File:Inside rani ki vav another wall structure.jpg|thumb|Geometric lattice patterns and designs resembling [[Patola Sari|Patola]] textile designs]]\nThere are gradually increasing cantilevered brackets in the well shaft which are profusely ornamented.<ref name=\":7\" /> There [[kalpavriksha]] carvings on the wall repents fertility and nature worship while [[kirtimukha]]<nowiki/>s and [[Makara (Hindu mythology)|makara]]<nowiki/>s adorn the basements and capitals of pillars.<ref name=\":3\" /> On the northern side wall of entrance of the stepwell, there are geometric lattice patterns and designs resembling designs of local textile tradition of [[Patola Sari|Patola]]. They may have been adapted from the wood carvings and the ceilings of the temples.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":7\" /> Animal figures of horses, elephants and lions are used as decoration of pillars and basement moldings.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Depiction ==\nSince July 2018, the [[Indian 100-rupee note|{{INR}}100]] banknote of [[Mahatma Gandhi New Series]], features Rani ki vav on the rear side.<ref>{{Cite web|title = RBI to Issue New Design \u20b9 100 Denomination Banknote|url = https://rbi.org.in/Scripts/BS_PressReleaseDisplay.aspx?prid=44533|website =rbi.org.in|accessdate = 2018-07-19|language = en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n*\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=Fu7VAAAAMAAJ|title=The Queen's stepwell at Patan|last=Mankodi|first=Kirit|publisher=Project for Indian Cultural Studies|year=1991|isbn=978-81-900184-0-1|location=Bombay|pages=|language=English|oclc=28801053}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.cyark.org/projects/rani-ki-vav 3D Model]\n\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{World Heritage Sites in India}}\n\n[[Category:Rajput era]]\n[[Category:Stepwells in Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Patan district]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Sites in India]]\n[[Category:Cultural history of Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Monuments of National Importance in Gujarat]]\n[[Category:M\u0101ru-Gurjara architecture]]\n", "name_user": "Jaiminmodi17", "label": "safe", "comment": "Official wesite link add", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rani_ki_vav"}
{"title_page": "Onslow S. Rolfe", "text_new": "{{short description|United States general}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name          = Onslow S. Rolfe\n|image         = Onslow Stearns Rolfe (US Army Brigadier General).jpg\n|caption       = 1953 photo of Rolfe as commander of Headquarters and Service Command, [[Far East Command (United States)|Far East Command]].\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date|1895|01|16}}\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1985|01|29|1895|01|16}}\n|birth_place   = [[Concord, New Hampshire]]\n|death_place   = [[Winter Park, Florida]]\n|placeofburial = [[Arlington National Cemetery]]\n|allegiance    = {{flag|United States of America|1912}}\n|branch        = {{army|USA}}\n|serviceyears  = 1917\u20131954\n|rank          = [[File:US-O7 insignia.svg|30px]] [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]]\n|commands      = 1st Battalion, [[87th Infantry Regiment (United States)|87th Mountain Infantry Regiment]]<br/>[[87th Infantry Regiment (United States)|87th Mountain Infantry Regiment]]<br/>Mountain Training Center, [[Camp Hale]], [[Colorado]]<br/>Land Area [[Salzburg]]<br/>[[71st Infantry Division (United States)|71st Infantry Division]]<br/>Northern Command Area, Japan Logistics Command<br/>Headquarters and Service Command, [[Far East Command (United States)|Far East Command]]\n|unit          = [[Infantry Branch (United States)|United States Infantry Branch]]\n|battles = [[World War I]]<br/>[[World War II]]<br/>[[Korean War]]\n|awards        = [[Distinguished Service Cross (United States)|Distinguished Service Cross]]<br/>[[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Distinguished Service Medal]]<br/>[[Legion of Merit]]<br/>[[Purple Heart]]\n|relations     = [[Onslow Stearns]] (grandfather)\n|laterwork     =\n}}\n\n'''Onslow S. Rolfe''' (January 16, 1895 \u2013 January 29, 1985) was a career officer in the [[United States Army]].  He attained the rank of [[Brigadier general (United States)|brigadier general]] during [[World War II]] as commander of the Mountain Training Center at [[Camp Hale]], [[Colorado]], and the [[71st Infantry Division (United States)|71st Infantry Division]].\n\nRolfe graduated from West Point shortly before U.S. involvement in [[World War I]].  He served in combat with the [[7th Infantry Regiment (United States)|7th Infantry Regiment]], and received the [[Distinguished Service Cross (United States)|Distinguished Service Cross]] for heroism and the [[Purple Heart]] for wounds suffered in a gas attack.\n\nBetween World Wars I and II, Rolfe carried out a variety of assignments with increasing rank and responsibility, including professor of military science at [[Rutgers University]], and senior observer and advisor for the [[Wisconsin Army National Guard|Wisconsin National Guard]]. He also graduated from the [[United States Army Command and General Staff College|Command and General Staff College]] and the [[Field Artillery Branch (United States)|Field Artillery]] Officer Course, after which he served as senior Infantry instructor at the Fort Sill [[United States Army Field Artillery School|Field Artillery School]].\n\nDuring [[World War II]], Rolfe specialized in winter operations and mountain warfare; he commanded 1st Battalion, [[87th Infantry Regiment (United States)|87th Mountain Infantry Regiment]], then advanced to command of the regiment.  After promotion to [[Brigadier general (United States)|brigadier general]], he commanded the [[Camp Hale]], [[Colorado]] Mountain Training Center, where he oversaw organization and training of the [[10th Mountain Division|10th Light Division (Alpine)]].\n\nNear the end of World War II, Rolfe went to France as deputy commander of the [[71st Infantry Division (United States)|71st Infantry Division]], and took part in the [[Allied advance from Paris to the Rhine#Germany west of the Rhine|Rhineland campaign]] and the [[Western Allied invasion of Germany]].\n\nRolfe performed post-war occupation duty in [[Austria]], and commanded Land Area [[Salzburg]] and the [[71st Infantry Division (United States)|71st Infantry Division]].\n\nAfter World War II, Rolfe was chief of the development section in the research and development office at Headquarters, [[Army Ground Forces|Army Field Forces]].  During the [[Korean War]], he commanded the Japan Logistics Command's Northern Command Area, and then Headquarters and Service Command, [[Far East Command (United States)|Far East Command]].\n\nAfter his 1954 retirement, Rolfe resided in [[Winter Park, Florida]].  He died there on January 29, 1985, and was buried at [[Arlington National Cemetery]].\n\n==Early life==\nOnslow Sherburne Rolfe was born in [[Concord, New Hampshire]] on January 16, 1895.{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}  His father was Army [[colonel (United States)|Colonel]] Robert H. Rolfe, and his mother was Grace Stearns, the daughter of New Hampshire Governor [[Onslow Stearns]].{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}\n\nRolfe attended schools in several states, [[Cuba]], and [[Japan]] while his family moved for his father's military postings.{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}} He completed high school at St. Luke's Episcopal School in [[Wayne, Pennsylvania]], and then attended Columbia Preparatory School in [[Washington, DC]] in anticipation of applying for admission to the [[United States Military Academy]].{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}\n\n==Start of career==\nRolfe was admitted to West Point in 1914; his classmates nicknamed him \"Pinkey\" because of his red hair and flushed complexion, and the nickname stuck with him for the rest of his career.{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}  He graduated in August 1917, ranked 109th of 151 students.{{sfn|Biographical Register, 1920}}  He was commissioned as a [[Second lieutenant#United States|second lieutenant]] of [[Infantry Branch (United States)|Infantry]], and was assigned to the [[7th Infantry Regiment (United States)|7th Infantry Regiment]].{{sfn|Biographical Register, 1920}}  He was promoted to [[First lieutenant#U.S. Army.2C U.S. Marine Corps and U.S. Air Force|first lieutenant]] on August 30.{{sfn|Biographical Register, 1920}}\n\nIn October 1917 Rolfe joined his regiment in [[Gettysburg, Pennsylvania]].{{sfn|Biographical Register, 1920}}  In late October and November, he attended the Infantry School of Arms at [[Fort Sill]], [[Oklahoma]].{{sfn|Biographical Register, 1920}}  He then joined his regiment at [[Camp Greene]], [[North Carolina]], and took part in pre-deployment training prior to going overseas.{{sfn|Biographical Register, 1920}}  The regiment departed for [[France]] in March 1918.{{sfn|Biographical Register, 1920}}\n\n==World War I==\nAfter arriving in France the regiment took part in combat operations as part of the [[3rd Infantry Division (United States)|3rd Division]].{{sfn|Biographical Register, 1920}}  Rolfe was a participant in the [[Second Battle of the Marne]] in July and August 1918, and received the [[Distinguished Service Cross (United States)|Distinguished Service Cross]] for heroism while moving and positioning [[3rd Infantry Division (United States)|3rd Division]] reinforcements during a critical juncture in the battle.{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}  He was promoted to [[Captain (United States O-3)|captain]] in September 1918, and took part in the [[Meuse-Argonne Offensive]].{{sfn|Biographical Register, 1920}}  Rolfe was wounded as the result of a gas attack in October, for which he received the [[Purple Heart]].{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}{{sfn|Casualty List}}  He convalesced at a hospital in France until January 1919.{{sfn|Biographical Register, 1920}}\n\n==Post-World War I==\nRolfe's post-war assignments included the 131st Military Police Battalion ([[Fort Dix]], [[New Jersey]]), 3rd Division Demobilization Group (Camp Pike, [[Arkansas]]), and Machine Gun Company, [[4th Infantry Regiment (United States)|4th Infantry Regiment]] ([[Fort Benning]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]).{{sfn|Biographical Register, 1920}}\n\nIn the 1920s and 1930s, Rolfe's assignments included postings with the 4th, [[18th Infantry Regiment (United States)|18th]], and [[27th Infantry Regiment (United States)|27th]] Infantry Regiments.{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}  In addition, he was professor of military science at [[Rutgers University]], and senior observer and advisor for the [[Wisconsin Army National Guard|Wisconsin National Guard]].{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}  Rolfe graduated from the [[United States Army Command and General Staff College|Command and General Staff College]] in 1936,{{sfn|Command and General Staff College Annual Report}} and then completed the [[Field Artillery Branch (United States)|Field Artillery]] Officer Course, after which he was assigned as senior Infantry instructor at the Fort Sill [[United States Army Field Artillery School|Field Artillery School]].{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}\n\n==World War II==\nAt the start of [[World War II]] the Army began to create and field units of light Infantry troops designed to operate in cold weather and at high altitudes.{{sfn|Camp Hale History}}  Rolfe was assigned to command 1st Battalion, [[87th Infantry Regiment (United States)|87th Mountain Infantry Regiment]].{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}  His success at organizing this battalion and leading it during its initial training led to assignment as commander of the regiment and promotion to [[Colonel (United States)|colonel]].{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}  Unknown Army planners apparently thought assigning Rolfe to command a unit that would train to use skis and snowshoes was logical, because he had been born in New Hampshire; they were apparently unaware that he had left the state at six years old and had virtually no experience in winter sports.{{sfn|World War II at Camp Hale}}  Despite his unfamiliarity with skiing and snowshoeing, Rolfe soon became proficient, and ensured that the soldiers in his regiment did likewise.{{sfn|World War II at Camp Hale}}\n\nFrom 1942 to 1945 Rolfe commanded the [[Camp Hale]], [[Colorado]] Mountain Training Center, and received promotion to [[Brigadier general (United States)|brigadier general]].{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}  During his command of Camp Hale, the [[85th Infantry Regiment (United States)|85th]], [[86th Infantry Regiment (United States)|86th]], and [[87th Infantry Regiment (United States)|87th]] Mountain Infantry Regiments were organized as the [[10th Mountain Division|10th Light Division (Alpine)]], and Rolfe was responsible for ensuring that the division had the facilities and equipment necessary to complete its training, to include ski slopes, cliffs for rappelling, skis, and winter camouflage uniforms.{{sfn|US 10th Mountain Division in World War II}}{{sfn|Ski Soldiers Train in Pikes Peak Region}}\n\nRolfe joined the [[71st Infantry Division (United States)|71st Infantry Division]] as assistant division commander in January 1945.{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}  The division took part in the [[Allied advance from Paris to the Rhine#Germany west of the Rhine|Rhineland campaign]] and the [[Western Allied invasion of Germany]].{{sfn|Army Lineage Series}}  The 71st Division participated in the liberation of several concentration camps, including one in [[Austria]] called Gunskirchen Lager, a subcamp of the [[Mauthausen-Gusen concentration camp|Mauthausen-Gusen]] facility.{{sfn|In Final Defense of the Reich}}  The 71st Division advanced further east than any other Allied unit, and made contact with [[Union of Soviet Socialist Republics|Soviet]] forces near [[Linz]] on May 8, 1945.{{sfn|Extreme War}}\n\n==Post-World War II==\nThe 71st Division carried out occupation duties in Austria after hostilities ceased, and Rolfe commanded Land Area [[Salzburg]].{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}  From August 17 to October 10, 1945 Rolfe was commander of the 71st Infantry Division.{{sfn|Combat Chronicle, 71st Infantry Division}}\n\nRolfe returned to the United States in 1947 and was assigned as chief of the development section in the research and development office at Headquarters, [[Army Ground Forces|Army Field Forces]].{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}\n\n==Korean War==\nIn 1952, Rolfe was assigned as commander of the Japan Logistics Command's Northern Command Area.{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}{{sfn|Names Commander}}  From 1953 until his 1954 retirement, Rolfe served as commander of Headquarters and Service Command, [[Far East Command (United States)|Far East Command]].{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}\n\n==Awards==\nIn addition to the Distinguished Service Cross and Purple Heart, Rolfe received the [[Legion of Merit]] for his service with the 71st Infantry Division, and the [[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Distinguished Service Medal]] for his post-World War II service in Japan.{{sfn|Awards and Citations, Onslow Sherburne Rolfe}}\n\n===Distinguished Service Cross citation===\n\nThe President of the United States of America, authorized by Act of Congress, July 9, 1918, takes pleasure in presenting the Distinguished Service Cross to Captain (Infantry) Onslow Sherburne Rolfe, United States Army, for extraordinary heroism in action while serving with 7th Infantry Regiment, 3d Division, A.E.F., near Fossoy, France, July 14\u201315, 1918. During the heavy enemy bombardment proceeding the second battle of the Marne, Captain Rolfe, regimental intelligence officer, voluntarily carried an important message, in full view of the enemy, across an open field to the support and reserve battalions for the purpose of bringing up reinforcements.\n\n'''General Orders:''' War Department, General Orders No. 116 (1919) '''Action Date:''' July 14\u201315, 1918 '''Service:''' Army '''Rank:''' Captain '''Regiment:''' 7th Infantry Regiment '''Division:''' 3rd Division, American Expeditionary Forces{{sfn|Awards and Citations, Onslow Sherburne Rolfe}}\n\n==Retirement==\nIn retirement, Rolfe resided in [[Winter Park, Florida]].{{sfn|Florida Lives}}  He died in Winter Park on January 29, 1985.{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}   Rolfe was buried at [[Arlington National Cemetery]], Section 3, Site 1829-B.{{sfn|Arlington National Cemetery}}\n\n==Family==\nIn 1917, Rolfe married Nan Elizabeth Belles of [[New Brighton, Pennsylvania]].{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}} They were the parents of a daughter, Ann Sherburne Rolfe, who was the wife of Brigadier General Charles A. Symroski.{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources==\n===Books===\n* {{cite book |last1=Cullum |first1=George W. |last2=Robinson |first2=Wirt |date=1920 |title=Biographical Register of the Officers and Graduates of the U.S. Military Academy |volume=VI B |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SSHcAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA1956&lpg=PA1956 |location=Saginaw & Peters |publisher=Seeman & Peters |page=1956 |ref={{sfnRef|Biographical Register, 1920}}}}\n* {{cite book |last=Poulos |first=Terrence |date=2004 |title=Extreme War: The Biggest, Best, Bloodiest, and Worst in Warfare |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Latur74gkwMC&pg=PA386 |location=New York |publisher=Citadel Press |page=386 |isbn=978-0-8065-2730-7 |ref={{sfnRef|Extreme War}}}}\n* {{cite book |last=Rottman |first=Gordon L. |date=2012 |title=US 10th Mountain Division in World War II |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gqm6CwAAQBAJ&pg=PA11 |location=Oxford, United Kingdom |publisher=Osprey Publishing |page=11 |isbn=978-1-84908-808-4 |ref={{sfnRef|US 10th Mountain Division in World War II}}}}\n* {{cite book |last=Rusiecki |first=Stephen M. |date=2010 |title=In Final Defense of the Reich: The Destruction of the 6th SS Mountain Division \"Nord\" |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xCoTjyrLTM8C&pg=PA327 |location=Annapolis, MD |publisher=Naval Institute Press |page=327 |isbn=978-1-59114-744-2 |ref={{sfnRef|In Final Defense of the Reich}}}}\n* {{cite book |last=Trinkner |first=Charles L. |date=1966 |title=Florida Lives: The Sunshine State Who's Who, a Reference Edition Recording the Biographies of Contemporary Leaders in Florida |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WNHiAAAAMAAJ&q=%22onslow%22+%22rolfe%22+%22winter+park%22&dq=%22onslow%22+%22rolfe%22+%22winter+park%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi9h-nQrbjPAhVHLB4KHdWPAw8Q6AEIHDAA |location=Hopkinsville, KY |publisher=Historical Record Association |page=454 |ref={{sfnRef|Florida Lives}}}}\n* {{cite book |last=United States Army Command and General Staff College |date=1936 |title=Annual Report |url=http://usacac.army.mil/sites/default/files/documents/cace/CARL/Reports/rep1936.pdf |location=Ft. Leavenworth, KS |publisher=Command and General Staff School Press |page=5 |ref={{sfnRef|Command and General Staff College Annual Report}}}}\n* {{cite book |last=Wilson |first=John B. |date=1999 |title=Army Lineage Series: Armies, Corps, Divisions and Separate Brigades |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tGAarOMP5VMC&pg=PA409 |location=Washington, DC |publisher=US Government Printing Office |page=409 |isbn=978-0-16-049992-0 |ref={{sfnRef|Army Lineage Series}}}}\n* {{cite book |last=Witte |first=David R. |date=2015 |title=World War II at Camp Hale: Blazing a New Trail in the Rockies |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=27FxCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA212 |location=Charleston, SC |publisher=History Press |page=212 |isbn=978-1-46711-854-5 |ref={{sfnRef|World War II at Camp Hale}}}}\n\n===Newspapers===\n*{{cite news |agency=American Expeditionary Forces |date=February 13, 1919 |title=Casualty List: Wounded Slightly |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/49389438/ |newspaper=Reading Times |location=Reading, PA |page=6 |url-access=subscription |ref={{sfnRef|Casualty List}}}}\n*{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |date=September 15, 1952 |title=Names Commander |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/148481362/ |newspaper=Reno Gazette-Journal |location=Reno, NV |page=13 |url-access=subscription |ref={{sfnRef|Names Commander}}}}\n*{{cite news |agency=International News Service |date=January 11, 1943 |title=Ski Soldiers Train in Pikes Peak Region |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/161703299/ |newspaper=Wilmington Journal |location=Wilmington, DE |page=9 |url-access=subscription |ref={{sfnRef|Ski Soldiers Train in Pikes Peak Region}}}}\n\n===Internet===\n* {{cite web |last=Arlington National Cemetery |url=http://www.arlingtoncemetery.mil/Explore/Find-a-Grave |title=Burial Record, Onslow S. Rolfe |website=arlingtoncemetery.mil/ |publisher=U.S. Army |location=Arlington, VA |access-date=September 30, 2016 |ref={{sfnRef|Arlington National Cemetery}}}}\n* {{cite web |last=Center of Military History |url=http://www.history.army.mil/html/forcestruc/cbtchron/cc/071id.htm |title=Combat Chronicle, 71st Infantry Division |website=history.army.mil/ |publisher=US Army Center of Military History |location=Washington, DC |access-date=September 30, 2016 |ref={{sfnRef|last=Combat Chronicle, 71st Infantry Division}}}}\n* {{cite web |last=Metropolitan State University |url=https://www.msudenver.edu/camphale/camphalehistory/ |title=Camp Hale History |website=msudenver.edu/ |publisher=Metropolitan State University of Denver |location=Denver, CO |access-date=September 30, 2016 |ref={{sfnRef|Camp Hale History}}}}\n* {{cite web |last=Military Times |url=http://valor.militarytimes.com/recipient.php?recipientid=14397 |title=Awards and Citations, Onslow Sherburne Rolfe |website=Hall of Valor |publisher=Military Times |location=Springfield, VA |access-date=September 30, 2016 |ref={{sfnRef|Awards and Citations, Onslow Sherburne Rolfe}}}}\n* {{cite web |last=Symroski |first=Charles A. |url=http://apps.westpointaog.org/Memorials/Article/5849/ |title=Obituary, Onslow S. Rolfe, 1917 |website=westpointaog.org/ |publisher=West Point Association of Graduates |location=West Point, NY |access-date=September 30, 2016 |ref={{sfnRef|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Findagrave|59700511}}\n* [http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/osrolfe.htm Onslow S. Stearns] at ''[http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/ Arlington Cemetery.net]''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rolfe, Onslow S.}}\n[[Category:1895 births]]\n[[Category:1985 deaths]]\n[[Category:United States Army generals]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the Korean War]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Service Cross (United States)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Service Medal (US Army)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Merit]]\n[[Category:United States Military Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Burials at Arlington National Cemetery]]\n[[Category:People from Concord, New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:People from Winter Park, Florida]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name          = Onslow S. Rolfe\n|image         = Onslow Stearns Rolfe (US Army Brigadier General).jpg\n|caption       = 1953 photo of Rolfe as commander of Headquarters and Service Command, [[Far East Command (United States)|Far East Command]].\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date|1895|01|16}}\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1985|01|29|1895|01|16}}\n|birth_place   = [[Concord, New Hampshire]]\n|death_place   = [[Winter Park, Florida]]\n|placeofburial = [[Arlington National Cemetery]]\n|allegiance    = {{flag|United States of America|1912}}\n|branch        = {{army|USA}}\n|serviceyears  = 1917\u20131954\n|rank          = [[File:US-O7 insignia.svg|30px]] [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]]\n|commands      = 1st Battalion, [[87th Infantry Regiment (United States)|87th Mountain Infantry Regiment]]<br/>[[87th Infantry Regiment (United States)|87th Mountain Infantry Regiment]]<br/>Mountain Training Center, [[Camp Hale]], [[Colorado]]<br/>Land Area [[Salzburg]]<br/>[[71st Infantry Division (United States)|71st Infantry Division]]<br/>Northern Command Area, Japan Logistics Command<br/>Headquarters and Service Command, [[Far East Command (United States)|Far East Command]]\n|unit          = [[Infantry Branch (United States)|United States Infantry Branch]]\n|battles = [[World War I]]<br/>[[World War II]]<br/>[[Korean War]]\n|awards        = [[Distinguished Service Cross (United States)|Distinguished Service Cross]]<br/>[[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Distinguished Service Medal]]<br/>[[Legion of Merit]]<br/>[[Purple Heart]]\n|relations     = [[Onslow Stearns]] (grandfather)\n|laterwork     =\n}}\n\n'''Onslow S. Rolfe''' (January 16, 1895 \u2013 January 29, 1985) was a career officer in the [[United States Army]].  He attained the rank of [[Brigadier general (United States)|brigadier general]] during [[World War II]] as commander of the Mountain Training Center at [[Camp Hale]], [[Colorado]], and the [[71st Infantry Division (United States)|71st Infantry Division]].\n\nRolfe graduated from West Point shortly before U.S. involvement in [[World War I]].  He served in combat with the [[7th Infantry Regiment (United States)|7th Infantry Regiment]], and received the [[Distinguished Service Cross (United States)|Distinguished Service Cross]] for heroism and the [[Purple Heart]] for wounds suffered in a gas attack.\n\nBetween World Wars I and II, Rolfe carried out a variety of assignments with increasing rank and responsibility, including professor of military science at [[Rutgers University]], and senior observer and advisor for the [[Wisconsin Army National Guard|Wisconsin National Guard]]. He also graduated from the [[United States Army Command and General Staff College|Command and General Staff College]] and the [[Field Artillery Branch (United States)|Field Artillery]] Officer Course, after which he served as senior Infantry instructor at the Fort Sill [[United States Army Field Artillery School|Field Artillery School]].\n\nDuring [[World War II]], Rolfe specialized in winter operations and mountain warfare; he commanded 1st Battalion, [[87th Infantry Regiment (United States)|87th Mountain Infantry Regiment]], then advanced to command of the regiment.  After promotion to [[Brigadier general (United States)|brigadier general]], he commanded the [[Camp Hale]], [[Colorado]] Mountain Training Center, where he oversaw organization and training of the [[10th Mountain Division|10th Light Division (Alpine)]].\n\nNear the end of World War II, Rolfe went to France as deputy commander of the [[71st Infantry Division (United States)|71st Infantry Division]], and took part in the [[Allied advance from Paris to the Rhine#Germany west of the Rhine|Rhineland campaign]] and the [[Western Allied invasion of Germany]].\n\nRolfe performed post-war occupation duty in [[Austria]], and commanded Land Area [[Salzburg]] and the [[71st Infantry Division (United States)|71st Infantry Division]].\n\nAfter World War II, Rolfe was chief of the development section in the research and development office at Headquarters, [[Army Ground Forces|Army Field Forces]].  During the [[Korean War]], he commanded the Japan Logistics Command's Northern Command Area, and then Headquarters and Service Command, [[Far East Command (United States)|Far East Command]].\n\nAfter his 1954 retirement, Rolfe resided in [[Winter Park, Florida]].  He died there on January 29, 1985, and was buried at [[Arlington National Cemetery]].\n\n==Early life==\nOnslow Sherburne Rolfe was born in [[Concord, New Hampshire]] on January 16, 1895.{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}  His father was Army [[colonel (United States)|Colonel]] Robert H. Rolfe, and his mother was Grace Stearns, the daughter of New Hampshire Governor [[Onslow Stearns]].{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}\n\nRolfe attended schools in several states, [[Cuba]], and [[Japan]] while his family moved for his father's military postings.{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}} He completed high school at St. Luke's Episcopal School in [[Wayne, Pennsylvania]], and then attended Columbia Preparatory School in [[Washington, DC]] in anticipation of applying for admission to the [[United States Military Academy]].{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}\n\n==Start of career==\nRolfe was admitted to West Point in 1914; his classmates nicknamed him \"Pinkey\" because of his red hair and flushed complexion, and the nickname stuck with him for the rest of his career.{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}  He graduated in August 1917, ranked 109th of 151 students.{{sfn|Biographical Register, 1920}}  He was commissioned as a [[Second lieutenant#United States|second lieutenant]] of [[Infantry Branch (United States)|Infantry]], and was assigned to the [[7th Infantry Regiment (United States)|7th Infantry Regiment]].{{sfn|Biographical Register, 1920}}  He was promoted to [[First lieutenant#U.S. Army.2C U.S. Marine Corps and U.S. Air Force|first lieutenant]] on August 30.{{sfn|Biographical Register, 1920}}\n\nIn October 1917 Rolfe joined his regiment in [[Gettysburg, Pennsylvania]].{{sfn|Biographical Register, 1920}}  In late October and November, he attended the Infantry School of Arms at [[Fort Sill]], [[Oklahoma]].{{sfn|Biographical Register, 1920}}  He then joined his regiment at [[Camp Greene]], [[North Carolina]], and took part in pre-deployment training prior to going overseas.{{sfn|Biographical Register, 1920}}  The regiment departed for [[France]] in March 1918.{{sfn|Biographical Register, 1920}}\n\n==World War I==\nAfter arriving in France the regiment took part in combat operations as part of the [[3rd Infantry Division (United States)|3rd Division]].{{sfn|Biographical Register, 1920}}  Rolfe was a participant in the [[Second Battle of the Marne]] in July and August 1918, and received the [[Distinguished Service Cross (United States)|Distinguished Service Cross]] for heroism while moving and positioning [[3rd Infantry Division (United States)|3rd Division]] reinforcements during a critical juncture in the battle.{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}  He was promoted to [[Captain (United States O-3)|captain]] in September 1918, and took part in the [[Meuse-Argonne Offensive]].{{sfn|Biographical Register, 1920}}  Rolfe was wounded as the result of a gas attack in October, for which he received the [[Purple Heart]].{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}{{sfn|Casualty List}}  He convalesced at a hospital in France until January 1919.{{sfn|Biographical Register, 1920}}\n\n==Post-World War I==\nRolfe's post-war assignments included the 131st Military Police Battalion ([[Fort Dix]], [[New Jersey]]), 3rd Division Demobilization Group (Camp Pike, [[Arkansas]]), and Machine Gun Company, [[4th Infantry Regiment (United States)|4th Infantry Regiment]] ([[Fort Benning]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]).{{sfn|Biographical Register, 1920}}\n\nIn the 1920s and 1930s, Rolfe's assignments included postings with the 4th, [[18th Infantry Regiment (United States)|18th]], and [[27th Infantry Regiment (United States)|27th]] Infantry Regiments.{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}  In addition, he was professor of military science at [[Rutgers University]], and senior observer and advisor for the [[Wisconsin Army National Guard|Wisconsin National Guard]].{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}  Rolfe graduated from the [[United States Army Command and General Staff College|Command and General Staff College]] in 1936,{{sfn|Command and General Staff College Annual Report}} and then completed the [[Field Artillery Branch (United States)|Field Artillery]] Officer Course, after which he was assigned as senior Infantry instructor at the Fort Sill [[United States Army Field Artillery School|Field Artillery School]].{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}\n\n==World War II==\nAt the start of [[World War II]] the Army began to create and field units of light Infantry troops designed to operate in cold weather and at high altitudes.{{sfn|Camp Hale History}}  Rolfe was assigned to command 1st Battalion, [[87th Infantry Regiment (United States)|87th Mountain Infantry Regiment]].{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}  His success at organizing this battalion and leading it during its initial training led to assignment as commander of the regiment and promotion to [[Colonel (United States)|colonel]].{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}  Unknown Army planners apparently thought assigning Rolfe to command a unit that would train to use skis and snowshoes was logical, because he had been born in New Hampshire; they were apparently unaware that he had left the state at six years old and had virtually no experience in winter sports.{{sfn|World War II at Camp Hale}}  Despite his unfamiliarity with skiing and snowshoeing, Rolfe soon became proficient, and ensured that the soldiers in his regiment did likewise.{{sfn|World War II at Camp Hale}}\n\nFrom 1942 to 1945 Rolfe commanded the [[Camp Hale]], [[Colorado]] Mountain Training Center, and received promotion to [[Brigadier general (United States)|brigadier general]].{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}  During his command of Camp Hale, the [[85th Infantry Regiment (United States)|85th]], [[86th Infantry Regiment (United States)|86th]], and [[87th Infantry Regiment (United States)|87th]] Mountain Infantry Regiments were organized as the [[10th Mountain Division|10th Light Division (Alpine)]], and Rolfe was responsible for ensuring that the division had the facilities and equipment necessary to complete its training, to include ski slopes, cliffs for rappelling, skis, and winter camouflage uniforms.{{sfn|US 10th Mountain Division in World War II}}{{sfn|Ski Soldiers Train in Pikes Peak Region}}\n\nRolfe joined the [[71st Infantry Division (United States)|71st Infantry Division]] as assistant division commander in January 1945.{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}  The division took part in the [[Allied advance from Paris to the Rhine#Germany west of the Rhine|Rhineland campaign]] and the [[Western Allied invasion of Germany]].{{sfn|Army Lineage Series}}  The 71st Division participated in the liberation of several concentration camps, including one in [[Austria]] called Gunskirchen Lager, a subcamp of the [[Mauthausen-Gusen concentration camp|Mauthausen-Gusen]] facility.{{sfn|In Final Defense of the Reich}}  The 71st Division advanced further east than any other Allied unit, and made contact with [[Union of Soviet Socialist Republics|Soviet]] forces near [[Linz]] on May 8, 1945.{{sfn|Extreme War}}\n\n==Post-World War II==\nThe 71st Division carried out occupation duties in Austria after hostilities ceased, and Rolfe commanded Land Area [[Salzburg]].{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}  From August 17 to October 10, 1945 Rolfe was commander of the 71st Infantry Division.{{sfn|Combat Chronicle, 71st Infantry Division}}\n\nRolfe returned to the United States in 1947 and was assigned as chief of the development section in the research and development office at Headquarters, [[Army Ground Forces|Army Field Forces]].{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}\n\n==Korean War==\nIn 1952, Rolfe was assigned as commander of the Japan Logistics Command's Northern Command Area.{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}{{sfn|Names Commander}}  From 1953 until his 1954 retirement, Rolfe served as commander of Headquarters and Service Command, [[Far East Command (United States)|Far East Command]].{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}\n\n==Awards==\nIn addition to the Distinguished Service Cross and Purple Heart, Rolfe received the [[Legion of Merit]] for his service with the 71st Infantry Division, and the [[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Distinguished Service Medal]] for his post-World War II service in Japan.{{sfn|Awards and Citations, Onslow Sherburne Rolfe}}\n\n===Distinguished Service Cross citation===\n\nThe President of the United States of America, authorized by Act of Congress, July 9, 1918, takes pleasure in presenting the Distinguished Service Cross to Captain (Infantry) Onslow Sherburne Rolfe, United States Army, for extraordinary heroism in action while serving with 7th Infantry Regiment, 3d Division, A.E.F., near Fossoy, France, July 14\u201315, 1918. During the heavy enemy bombardment proceeding the second battle of the Marne, Captain Rolfe, regimental intelligence officer, voluntarily carried an important message, in full view of the enemy, across an open field to the support and reserve battalions for the purpose of bringing up reinforcements.\n\n'''General Orders:''' War Department, General Orders No. 116 (1919) '''Action Date:''' July 14\u201315, 1918 '''Service:''' Army '''Rank:''' Captain '''Regiment:''' 7th Infantry Regiment '''Division:''' 3rd Division, American Expeditionary Forces{{sfn|Awards and Citations, Onslow Sherburne Rolfe}}\n\n==Retirement==\nIn retirement, Rolfe resided in [[Winter Park, Florida]].{{sfn|Florida Lives}}  He died in Winter Park on January 29, 1985.{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}   Rolfe was buried at [[Arlington National Cemetery]], Section 3, Site 1829-B.{{sfn|Arlington National Cemetery}}\n\n==Family==\nIn 1917, Rolfe married Nan Elizabeth Belles of [[New Brighton, Pennsylvania]].{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}} They were the parents of a daughter, Ann Sherburne Rolfe, who was the wife of Brigadier General Charles A. Symroski.{{sfn|Obituary, West Point Association of Graduates}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources==\n===Books===\n* {{cite book |last1=Cullum |first1=George W. |last2=Robinson |first2=Wirt |date=1920 |title=Biographical Register of the Officers and Graduates of the U.S. Military Academy |volume=VI B |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SSHcAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA1956&lpg=PA1956 |location=Saginaw & Peters |publisher=Seeman & Peters |page=1956 |ref={{sfnRef|Biographical Register, 1920}}}}\n* {{cite book |last=Poulos |first=Terrence |date=2004 |title=Extreme War: The Biggest, Best, Bloodiest, and Worst in Warfare |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Latur74gkwMC&pg=PA386 |location=New York |publisher=Citadel Press |page=386 |isbn=978-0-8065-2730-7 |ref={{sfnRef|Extreme War}}}}\n* {{cite book |last=Rottman |first=Gordon L. |date=2012 |title=US 10th Mountain Division in World War II |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gqm6CwAAQBAJ&pg=PA11 |location=Oxford, United Kingdom |publisher=Osprey Publishing |page=11 |isbn=978-1-84908-808-4 |ref={{sfnRef|US 10th Mountain Division in World War II}}}}\n* {{cite book |last=Rusiecki |first=Stephen M. |date=2010 |title=In Final Defense of the Reich: The Destruction of the 6th SS Mountain Division \"Nord\" |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xCoTjyrLTM8C&pg=PA327 |location=Annapolis, MD |publisher=Naval Institute Press |page=327 |isbn=978-1-59114-744-2 |ref={{sfnRef|In Final Defense of the Reich}}}}\n* {{cite book |last=Trinkner |first=Charles L. |date=1966 |title=Florida Lives: The Sunshine State Who's Who, a Reference Edition Recording the Biographies of Contemporary Leaders in Florida |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WNHiAAAAMAAJ&q=%22onslow%22+%22rolfe%22+%22winter+park%22&dq=%22onslow%22+%22rolfe%22+%22winter+park%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi9h-nQrbjPAhVHLB4KHdWPAw8Q6AEIHDAA |location=Hopkinsville, KY |publisher=Historical Record Association |page=454 |ref={{sfnRef|Florida Lives}}}}\n* {{cite book |last=United States Army Command and General Staff College |date=1936 |title=Annual Report |url=http://usacac.army.mil/sites/default/files/documents/cace/CARL/Reports/r