{"title_page": "South by Southwest", "text_new": "{{about|the annual festival}}\n{{short description|Annual festival held in Austin}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox recurring event\n| name = South by Southwest\n| image = SxSW logo.png\n| caption = The official logo for SXSW, 2017\n| location = [[Austin, Texas]], U.S.\n| years_active = {{age|1987|3|10}}\n| first = 1987\n| founders = Roland Swenson, Louis Jay Meyers, Louis Black, Nick Barbaro\n| dates = March (dates vary but generally coinciding with [[University of Texas at Austin]] [[spring break]] and also usually includes [[St. Patrick's Day]])\n| frequency = Annual\n| next = March 12th \u2013 March 20th, 2021\n| attendance = {{ubl|SXSW Music: 28,119|SXSW Interactive: 30,621|SXSW Film: 16,297|SXSW EDU: 4,260|Other Exhibits/Parties: 152,000}}\n| genre = [[Conference]] and [[festival]]\n| budget =\n| patron =\n| organized = SXSW, LLC\n| website = {{url|sxsw.com}}\n}}\n\n'''South by Southwest''' (stylized as '''SXSW''' and colloquially referred to as '''South By''') is an annual conglomeration of parallel film, [[interactive media]], and [[music festival]]s and [[Convention (meeting)|conferences]] organized jointly that take place in mid-March in [[Austin, Texas]], [[United States]]. It began in 1987 and has continued to grow in both scope and size every year. In 2017, the conference lasted for 10 days with the interactive track lasting for five days, music for seven days, and film for nine days.\n\nSXSW is run by the company SXSW, LLC, which organizes conferences, trade shows, festivals, and other events.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sxswedu.com/about/history |title=Sxsw Inc |publisher=Sxswedu.com |date= |accessdate=March 25, 2014}}</ref> In addition to the three main South by Southwest festivals, the company runs other conferences: [[Sxswedu.com|SXSW EDU]], a conference on educational innovation, held in Austin,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sxswedu.com/about |title=About SXSW EDU |publisher=Sxswedu.com |date= |accessdate=April 15, 2013}}</ref> and the [[Me-convention.com|me Convention]] (Started in 2017), held in [[Frankfurt]], Germany and in Stockholm, Sweden, in collaboration with [[Mercedes-Benz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://media.daimler.com/marsMediaSite/en/instance/ko/South-by-Southwest-SXSW-to-collaborate-with-Mercedes-Benz-at-IAA-International-Motor-Show-in-Frankfurt-Premiere-at-IAA-International-me-Convention.xhtml?oid=16074145|title=South by Southwest (SXSW) to collaborate with Mercedes-Benz at IAA International Motor Show in Frankfurt: Premiere at IAA: International me Convention|last=Schultz|first=Ina|date=March 11, 2017|website=media.daimler.com|language=en-EN|access-date=2017-08-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sxsw.com/news/2017/sxsw-joins-mercedes-benz-host-future-focused-convention-frankfurt/|title=SXSW and Mercedes-Benz Announce Initial Programming for Collaborative Future-Focused Event in Europe|last=Roberts|first=Jordan|date=2017-06-14|work=SXSW|access-date=2017-08-23|language=English}}</ref> Former conferences run by the SXSW organization include SXSW Eco, a conference focusing on social and environmental issues through the lens of technology, creativity and design held in Austin from 2011 to 2016;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sxsweco.com/about |title=About SXSW Eco |publisher=Sxsweco.com |date= |accessdate=April 15, 2013}}</ref> and another in Las Vegas: [[SXSW V2V]], a conference focused on innovative [[startup company|startups]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.statesman.com/news/technology/sxsw-interactive-expanding-next-year-with-las-vega/nSmFZ/ |title= SXSW Interactive expanding next year with Las Vegas startup conference|last=Gallaga|first=Omar L.|newspaper=Austin American-Statesman |date=October 23, 2012 |accessdate=August 8, 2013}}</ref> which ran from 2013 to 2015. Previously, SXSW produced music festivals North by Northwest (NXNW) in Portland, Oregon, [[North by Northeast]] (NXNE) in Toronto, and West by Southwest (WXSW) in Tucson, Arizona.\n\nFor the first time, the 2020 event was cancelled as a result of local health concerns about the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/6/21162247/sxsw-2020-cancelled-coronavirus-austin-texas-virus-fears-public-health-event|title=SXSW 2020 canceled due to coronavirus|last=Statt|first=Nick|date=2020-03-06|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kvue.com/article/entertainment/events/sxsw/sxsw-austin-2020-cancelled-petition-coronavirus/269-3423a862-7cd7-49be-8125-41d84b8c6a13|title=SXSW canceled: Austin officials end 2020 festival amid coronavirus concerns|website=KVUE|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n== Divisions ==\n[[File:Sixth Street SXSW 2013-025426539592444897.jpg|thumb|A view of [[Sixth Street (Austin, Texas)|6th Street]] in downtown Austin, Texas, during SXSW 2013]]\n\n=== Music ===\nSXSW Music is the largest [[music festival]] of its kind in the world, with more than 2,000 acts as of 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title = SXSW 2015: The festival changes, but for the better?|url = https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-sxsw-music-wrap-20150323-story.html|website = latimes.com|accessdate = 2015-11-16|date = 2015-03-23}}</ref> SXSW Music offers artist-provided music and video samples of featured artists at each festival via their official YouTube channel.<ref>{{cite web |last=Birney |first=Adrienne |authorlink= |title=SXSW Technical Coordinator |publisher= |date= |url=http://sxsw.com/ |doi= |accessdate=November 28, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sites.sxsw.com/|title=The Official SXSW site|publisher=Sites.sxsw.com|accessdate=2015-08-13}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe music event has grown from 700 registrants in 1987, the first year of the conference, to over 161,000 attendees in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.cnn.com/2013/09/13/us/south-by-southwest-fast-facts/index.html |work = CNN |title = South by Southwest Fast Facts |date = September 13, 2013 }}</ref> SXSW Film and SXSW Interactive events have grown every year, bringing over 32,000 registrants to Austin in March 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sxsw.com/about/history |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813151035/http://sxsw.com/about/history |archivedate=2011-08-13 |title=About SXSW |accessdate=March 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\nBands must cover their own expenses for travel and lodging at the event. All performers are offered a cash payment or a wristband package that allows access to all music events.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/zackomalleygreenburg/2013/03/18/why-most-acts-dont-get-paid-at-south-by-southwest/ |title=Why Most Acts Don't Get Paid At South By Southwest |magazine=Forbes |date=March 18, 2013 |accessdate=March 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Film ===\nSXSW Film Conference spans five days of conference panels and sessions, and welcomes filmmakers of all levels. Programming consists of keynote speakers, panels, workshops, mentor sessions and more, with expert filmmakers and industry leaders.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sxsw.com/film/history |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150404164219/http://sxsw.com/film/history |archivedate=2015-04-04 |title= History |publisher= SXSW.com |date= |accessdate=2015-04-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the SXSW Film Conference programmed over 250 sessions with 735 speakers. Past speakers include [[Jon Favreau]], [[Mark Duplass]], [[Ava DuVernay]], [[Ryan Gosling]], [[Nicolas Cage]], [[Alejandro Jodorowsky]], [[Tilda Swinton]], [[Amy Schumer]], [[Sally Field]], [[Joss Whedon]], [[Christine Vachon]], [[RZA]], [[Matthew McConaughey]], [[Danny Boyle]], [[Seth MacFarlane]], [[Catherine Hardwicke]], [[Richard Linklater]], [[David Gordon Green]], [[Harmony Korine]], [[Henry Rollins]], [[Sarah Green (film producer)|Sarah Green]] and [[Robert Rodriguez]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sxsw.com/film/conference/past-speakers |title=SXSW LLC. |publisher=sxsw.com |date= |accessdate=July 14, 2015}}</ref>\nAlthough the film festival often highlights independently produced films and emerging directing talent with unique visions,<ref>{{cite web |last=Peters |first=Yves |title=''Man & Gun'' and ''Les Bleus de Ramville'' Win SXSW Film Design Awards|url=http://fontfeed.com/archives/man-film-design-awards/ |publisher=The Font Feed |accessdate=January 11, 2013 |date=March 31, 2012}}</ref> the festival has long served studios as a starting point for their comedies, using enthusiastic fans as a barometer of how they might play in wide release.<ref name=\"Murphy\">{{cite news |last=Murphy |first=Mekado |title=SXSW 2015: Films That Were the Talk of the Festival |url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/03/19/sxsw-2015-films-that-were-the-talk-of-the-festival/ |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=July 11, 2015 |date=March 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe SXSW Film Festival runs nine days, simultaneously with the SXSW Film Conference, and celebrates raw innovation and emerging talent both behind and in front of the camera.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sxsw.com/film/about |title=SXSW LLC. |publisher=sxsw.com |date= |accessdate=July 14, 2015}}</ref> Festival programming categories include: Special Events, Headliners, Narrative Spotlight, Documentary Spotlight, Narrative Competition, Documentary Competition, Visions, Midnighters, 24 Beats Per Second, SXGlobal, Episodic, Festival Favorites, and Short Film Programs. The SXSW Film Awards, which occur on the last day of the Film Conference, honor films selected by the Feature and Short Film Juries.\n\nIn 2015, the SXSW Film Festival programmed 150 feature films and 106 short films, selected from 7,361 submissions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sxsw.com/sites/default/files/attachments/SXSW-FILM-FESTIVAL-ANNOUNCES-2015%20COMPLETE-CONFERENCE-LINEUP-AND-ADDITIONAL-FESTIVAL-TITLES-IMMEDIATE.pdf |title=SXSW LLC. |publisher=sxsw.com |accessdate=July 14, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924112924/http://www.sxsw.com/sites/default/files/attachments/SXSW-FILM-FESTIVAL-ANNOUNCES-2015%20COMPLETE-CONFERENCE-LINEUP-AND-ADDITIONAL-FESTIVAL-TITLES-IMMEDIATE.pdf |archivedate=September 24, 2015 }}</ref> Past notable world premieres include ''[[Furious 7]]'', ''[[Neighbors (2014 film)|Neighbors]]'', ''[[Chef (2014 film)|Chef]]'', ''[[21 Jump Street (film)|21 Jump Street]]'', ''[[The Cabin in the Woods]]'', ''[[Bridesmaids (2011 film)|Bridesmaids]]'' and ''[[Insidious (film)|Insidious]]'', and the TV series ''[[Girls (TV series)|Girls]]'', ''[[Silicon Valley (TV series)|Silicon Valley]]'' and ''[[Penny Dreadful (TV series)|Penny Dreadful]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sxsw.com/film/screenings/past-films |title=Past Films at SXSW &#124; South by Southwest 2016 Music, Film and Interactive Festivals \u2013 Austin Texas |publisher=Sxsw.com |accessdate=2015-08-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150609232442/http://www.sxsw.com/film/screenings/past-films |archivedate=2015-06-09 }}</ref>\n\n=== Interactive ===\nSXSW Interactive is focused on emerging technology.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sxsw.com/interactive/about |title=Interactive News &#124; SXSW 2013 |publisher=Sxsw.com |date= |accessdate=April 15, 2013}}</ref> The festival includes a trade show, speakers, parties, and a startup accelerator.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sxsw.com/interactive/accelerator |title=March 8\u20139: SXSW Accelerator Presented by Oracle Helps Uncover Amazing New Startups &#124; SXSW 2014 |publisher=Sxsw.com |date=November 10, 2013 |accessdate=March 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:SXSW2020CommunityMeetupWeWorkTheHub.jpg|thumb|SXSW employee giving an introduction of the event at a community meetup.]]\n\n=== Inauguration \u2013 1980s ===\nIn July 1986, the organizers of the [[New York City]] music festival [[New Music Seminar]] contacted Roland Swenson, a staffer at the [[alternative weekly]] ''[[The Austin Chronicle]]'', talked about organizing an extension of that festival into Austin, thereafter announced they were going to hold a \"New Music Seminar Southwest\".<ref>{{cite web|author=van Arts Labor |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iH02tbDy_6M&t=1m19s&list=UUgk1rvr62MBcRrTBgI4oEUg |title=SXSW documentary 'Outside Industry' |publisher=Youtube.com |date=February 28, 2014 |accessdate=March 25, 2014}}</ref> The plans did not materialize, so Swenson decided to instead co-organize a local music festival, with the help of two other people at the ''Chronicle'': editor and co-founder Louis Black, and publisher Nick Barbaro. Louis Meyers, a [[booking agent]] and musician, was also brought on board.<ref>[http://www.lib.utexas.edu/taro/utcah/01476/cah-01476.html A Guide to the South By Southwest, Inc., Records, 1987\u20131997], Briscoe Center for American History, The University of Texas at Austin</ref> Black came up with the name, as a play on the name of the [[Alfred Hitchcock]] film ''[[North by Northwest]]''. While Southwest by South is an actual [[Points of the compass|point on a compass]], South by Southwest is not (SWbS is a heading of 213.75 degrees).\n\nThe event was first held in March 1987. The organizers considered it a regional event and expected around 150 attendees to show up, but over 700 came, and according to Black \"it was national almost immediately.\"<ref name=\"sxsw stays course\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20110311034107/http://www.dailytexanonline.com/content/sxsw-stays-course-continues-growth SXSW stays course, continues growth], Alex Geiser, ''[[The Daily Texan]]'', March 18, 2010</ref> Meyers left Austin and the festival in the early 1990s, but Black, Barbaro and Swenson remained the festival's key organizers as of 2010.<ref name=\"sxsw stays course\" />\n\n=== 1990s ===\nSinger-songwriter [[Michelle Shocked]] was the keynote speaker at the 1992 South by Southwest. She caused controversy by delivering a speech, written by her then-husband [[Bart Bull]], criticizing white musicians for stealing music from [[African American]] artists; and then later during the same conference when she tried to kick the band [[Two Nice Girls]] off of a benefit concert, a move that some called anti-gay, due to Two Nice Girls' overtly [[lesbian]] image.<ref>[http://www.dallasobserver.com/1996-04-25/music/the-education-of-michelle-shocked/ The Education of Michelle Shocked], Robert Wilonsky, ''[[Dallas Observer]]'', April 25, 1996</ref>\n\nIn 1993, SXSW moved into the [[Austin Convention Center]], where it is still held.<ref>[http://sxsw.com/node/5521] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322004257/http://sxsw.com/node/5521|date=March 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, SXSW added a component for film and other media, named the \"SXSW Film and Multimedia Conference\".<ref name=\"sxsw stays course\" /> [[Johnny Cash]] was the keynote speaker.<ref name=\"Cohen2012\">{{cite news|last1=Cohen|first1=Jason|title=SXSW: The Ten Best Music Keynote Speakers|url=http://www.texasmonthly.com/story/sxsw-ten-best-music-keynote-speakers|accessdate=13 June 2014|work=[[Texas Monthly]]|publisher=Emmis Publishing, L.P.|date=15 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nThat year, the three brothers of the band [[Hanson (band)|Hanson]] were brought to SXSW by their father in order to perform impromptu auditions for music executives, in the hopes of getting industry attention. Among the people who heard them was A&R executive [[Christopher Sabec]], who became their manager, and would soon afterward get them signed to [[Mercury Records]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oklahomatoday.com/Site/pdf/1997Hanson.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101104185941/http://www.oklahomatoday.com/Site/pdf/1997Hanson.pdf |archivedate=2010-11-04 |title= 1997 Oklahoman of the Year |publisher= Oklahoma Today |date= |accessdate=4 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, the SXSW Film and Multimedia Conference was split into two separate events, \"SXSW Film\" and \"SXSW Multimedia\".<ref name=\"sxsw stays course\" /> In 1999, SXSW Multimedia was renamed \"SXSW Interactive\".<ref name=\"sxsw stays course\" />\n\n=== 2000s ===\nSinger-songwriter [[John Mayer]]'s performance at the 2000 SXSW Music festival led to his signing soon thereafter with [[Aware Records]], his first [[record label]].\n\nA performance by the band [[The Polyphonic Spree]] at the 2002 SXSW Music festival helped bring them to national attention before they had signed with a major label.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/1471511/20030424/polyphonic_spree.jhtml|title=Polyphonic Spree: From Voices In A Singer's Head To Voices On The Stage \u2013 News \u2013 VH1.com|date=19 October 2011|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111019215642/http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/1471511/20030424/polyphonic_spree.jhtml|archivedate=19 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2002 SXSW Film Festival, the film ''[[Manito (film)|Manito]]'' won the jury award for narrative feature, while the documentary ''[[Spellbound (2002 film)|Spellbound]]'' won the jury award for documentary feature.\n\nBritish singer [[James Blunt]] was discovered by producer [[Linda Perry]] while playing a small show at the 2004 SXSW Music festival, and was signed to Perry's [[Custard Records]] soon thereafter,<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Miller |first=Nancy |url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1174154,00.html |title=Five rounds with James Blunt |magazine=EW.com |date=2006-03-17 |accessdate=2015-08-13}}</ref> where he would go on to release all three of his subsequent albums.\n\nThe 2005 SXSW Film is considered by some to be the origin of the [[mumblecore]] film genre. A number of films now classified as mumblecore, including ''[[The Puffy Chair]]'', ''[[Kissing on the Mouth]]'', ''[[Four Eyed Monsters]]'' and ''[[Mutual Appreciation]]'', were screened, and [[Eric Masunaga]], a musician and the [[audio engineering|sound editor]] on ''Mutual Appreciation'', is credited with coining the term \"mumblecore\" at a bar while at the festival.<ref>Lim, Dennis (August 19, 2007). \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/19/movies/19lim.html?8dpc Mumblecore \u2013 The New Talkies: Generation DIY]\". ''[[The New York Times]]''.</ref>\n\nThe film ''[[Hooligans (film)|Hooligans]]'' won both the Feature Film Jury Award and the Feature Film Audience Award for narrative feature, while ''The Puffy Chair'' won the Feature Film Audience Award in the \"Emerging Visions\" category. The documentary film ''[[Cowboy del Amor]]'' won the SXSW Competition Award and the Audience Award.\n\nA secret concert at the 2006 SXSW Music by the band [[The Flaming Lips]] was called one of the \"Top 10 Music-Festival Moments\" of all time by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine in 2010.<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1885895_1885893_1885860,00.html Top 10 Music-Festival Moments: Flaming Lips at SXSW \u2013 2006], Dan Fletcher, ''Time'', March 18, 2010</ref>\n\nThe 2006 SXSW Interactive featured a keynote panel of Wikipedia co-founder [[Jimmy Wales]] and [[Craigslist]] founder [[Craig Newmark]].<ref>[http://www.auscillate.com/post/95 SXSW 2006 Panel: Craig Newmark & Jimmy Wales Keynote], ''Auscillate'' blog, March 13, 2006</ref>\n\nThat year, \"Screenburn at SXSW\", a component for [[video game]]s, was added to SXSW Interactive.<ref name=\"sxsw stays course\" />\n\n==== 2007 ====\nThe 2007 music festival took place from March 14 to 18, and more than 1,400 acts performed.\n\nTwo of the top film premieres that year were ''[[Elvis and Anabelle]]'' and ''[[Skills Like This]]''.\n\nThe [[social media]] platform [[Twitter]] notably gained a good deal of early traction and buzz at the 2007 SXSW Interactive,{{better source|date=August 2019}} though it did not launch at SXSW 2007 as is sometimes reported.<ref name=\"sxsw stays course\" />\n\n==== 2008 ====\nThe 2008 SXSW Interactive got media attention due to a keynote interview of [[Facebook]] CEO [[Mark Zuckerberg]] by technology journalist [[Sarah Lacy]] that was considered by some observers to be a \"train wreck\" due to an audience perception that Lacy was asking uninteresting questions, as well as mocking or terse answers in response from Zuckerberg.<ref>[http://news.cnet.com/8301-13772_3-9889528-52.html A journalist becomes the story at Mark Zuckerberg SXSWi keynote], Daniel Terdiman, ''CNET'' \"Geek Gestalt\" blog, March 9, 2008</ref>\n\nIn 2008, a comedy element was added to SXSW; it was held for one night. (By 2012, comedy performances occurred on all nights of the festival.)<ref>{{cite web |title=Messin' with Texas: Why Doesn't SXSW Pay its Comedians? |url=http://splitsider.com/2012/01/messin-with-texas-why-doesnt-sxsw-pay-its-comedians/ |publisher=[[Splitsider]] |first=Richard |last=Morgan |date=January 23, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==== 2009 ====\nThe 2009 festival was held March 13\u201322. The Interactive section of SXSW in particular drew larger attendance levels; the influx strained the networks of providers such as [[AT&T]] (primarily due to heavy [[iPhone]] usage).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blog.wired.com/business/2009/03/sxsw-atts-spott.html |title=SXSW: IPhone Influx Pushes AT&T to the Limit |work=Epicenter (blog.wired.com) |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast Publications|Conde Nast]] |date=March 14, 2009 |first=Michael |last=Calore}}</ref> Also new was the founding of an international organization for those not attending, dubbed NotAtSXSW. Coordinating through [[Twitter]] and other online tools, notatsxsw events were held in London, New York, Wisconsin, Portland, Oregon and Miami.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2009/mar/18/notatsxsw-festival-twitter |title= Can't make it to SXSW this year? Go to #notatsxsw instead |date=March 18, 2009 |work=[[The Guardian]] | location=London | accessdate=May 23, 2010 | first=Ruth | last=Jamieson}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Foursquare-logo.png|thumb|The mobile app, Foursquare, was launched at SXSW 2009.]]\nThe 2009 SXSW Interactive saw the launch of the [[Foursquare (social network)|Foursquare]] application, which was called \"the breakout [[mobile app]]\" of the event by the ''[[Mashable]]'' blog.<ref>{{cite web|last=Van |first=Jennifer |url=http://mashable.com/2009/03/16/foursquare/ |title=Foursquare is the Breakout Mobile App at SXSW |publisher=Mashable.com |date=2009-03-16 |accessdate=2015-08-13}}</ref>\n\n2009 also saw the first Indian classical music artists perform at SXSW. Canadians [[Cassius Khan]], a renowned tabla player and singer performed with [[Amika Kushwaha]] on harmonium and were featured Canadians on CBC Canada's most favorite list.\n\nThe 2009 SXSW Film screened 250 films, including 54 world premieres. The event was notable for having the United States premiere of the film ''[[The Hurt Locker]]'', which went on to win the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]] in 2010.<ref name=\"sxsw stays course\" /> The winners of the feature jury awards were, for documentary feature, ''[[45365]]'', and for narrative feature, ''[[Made in China (2009 film)|Made in China]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiewire.com/article/made_in_china_and_45365_take_top_sxsw_jury_prizes/ |title=\"Made in China\" and \"45365\" Take Top SXSW Jury Prizes |work=Indiewire |date=March 18, 2009 |accessdate=February 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== 2010s ===\n==== 2010 ====\nThe 2010 music festival, which took place March 12\u201321, was dedicated to [[Alex Chilton]], who died shortly before he was to perform with [[Big Star]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/big-star-singer-and-cult-icon-alex-chilton-dead-at-59-20100317|title=Big Star Singer and Cult Icon Alex Chilton Dead at 59|date=March 17, 2010|accessdate=September 24, 2014}}</ref> A tribute concert was performed in his honor on March 20, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sxsw.tewspaper.com/at-the-big-star-tribute-to-alex-chilton-sxsw-32010|title=SXSW Tribute Concert for Alex Chilton|date=March 20, 2010|accessdate=March 24, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716212414/http://sxsw.tewspaper.com/at-the-big-star-tribute-to-alex-chilton-sxsw-32010|archivedate=July 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2010 festival, nearly 2,000 bands were officially scheduled to perform,<ref name=\"SXSW 2010 Draws to a Close\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnewyork.com/entertainment/music/SXSW-2010-Draws-to-a-Close-88819997.html|title=SXSW 2010 Draws to a Close|publisher=nbcnewyork.com|date=March 22, 2010 |accessdate=April 8, 2010}}</ref> and festival reps estimated that over 13,000 industry representatives attended.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyfinance.com/story/media/scenes-from-the-geekfest-at-sxsw-interactive/19398388|title=Scenes From the Geekfest at SXSW|publisher=DailyFinance.com |date=March 14, 2010 |accessdate=April 8, 2010}}</ref> Though traditionally the Austin Music Awards kick off the festival, that year organizers slated it as the closing act. Local musician [[Bob Schneider]] earned 6 awards, including Song of the Year, Singer of the Year, and Band of the Year (with [[Lonelyland]].)<ref name=\"SXSW 2010 Draws to a Close\" /> The 2010 festival was also notable for appearances by the surviving members of the band [[Moby Grape]].<ref>Raul Hernandez, [http://www.austinchronicle.com/gyrobase/Issue/review?oid=oid%3A985722 Live Shots: SXSW Music 2010], [[Austin Chronicle]], March 26, 2010.</ref>\n\nAt the 2010 Film festival, [[Magnolia Pictures]] bought the film rights to the science-fiction film ''[[Monsters (2010 film)|Monsters]]'' on the night it screened, in what was the first-ever \"overnight acquisition\" at SXSW. Journalist Meredith Melnick of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine called this purchase a turning point for SXSW, leading to a greater interest among film studio executives in attending the festival in person.<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,2062263,00.html Art of the Film Deal: Is South by Southwest Becoming the New Sundance?], Meredith Melnick, ''Time'', April 1, 2011</ref> That year also saw the premiere of the indie favorite ''[[Tiny Furniture]]'', which won the award for Best Narrative Feature.\n\nThe 2010 Interactive festival had an estimated 12\u201313,000 paying attendees, which represented a 40% jump over the previous year.<ref name=\"interactive surpasses music\">[http://www.austin360.com/blogs/content/shared-gen/blogs/austin/digitalsavant/entries/2010/03/17/confirmed_sxsw.html Confirmed: SXSW Interactive paid registration surpasses Music], Omar L. Gallaga, ''Austin360.com'', March 17, 2010</ref> This was the first year in which the interactive festival's attendance surpassed the music festival's.<ref name=\"interactive surpasses music\" /> The keynote presentation was an interview of then-Twitter CEO [[Evan Williams (Internet entrepreneur)|Evan Williams]] by Umair Haque, an interview that many in the audience found disappointingly superficial.<ref>[http://www.statesman.com/business/sxsw-organizers-concede-keynote-flubs-with-twitter-q-374628.html SXSW organizers concede keynote flubs with Twitter Q&A], Omar L. Gallaga, ''Austin American-Statesman'', March 16, 2010</ref> Also during the interactive festival, the first-ever (and so far only) \"Hive Awards For the Unsung Heroes of the Internet\" were held.\n\n==== 2011 ====\n[[File:Conan O'Brien - SXSW - Mar 2011.jpg|thumb|[[Conan O'Brien]] promoting ''[[Conan O'Brien Can't Stop]]'' at SXSW 2011]]\nThe 2011 SXSW festival ran from March 11 to 20.\n\nThe keynote presenter for SXSW Interactive was [[Seth Priebatsch]], founder and CEO of the mobile-gaming platform [[SCVNGR]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/8301-14013_1-20042504-284.html|title=SCVNGR at SXSW\u2014high-flying, or head in the clouds?|date=March 12, 2011|accessdate=March 12, 2011}}</ref> The 2011 Interactive festival was by far the largest it had ever been, with an estimated 20,000 attendees.<ref name=\"where the geeks are\">[http://www.dailyfinance.com/story/where-the-geeks-are-dispatches-from-the-largest-sxsw-interactiv/19880235/ Where the Geeks Are: Dispatches From the Largest SXSW Interactive Ever], L. A. Lorek, ''Daily Finance'', March 15, 2011</ref>\n\nAlso in attendance at SXSW was boxing legend [[Mike Tyson]], promoting his new iPhone game with [[RockLive]] at the Screenburn Arcade.<ref>{{cite web|last=McCarthy |first=Caroline |url=https://www.cnet.com/8301-14013_1-20042682-284.html |title=Mike Tyson wants to be an iPhone knockout &#124; SXSW \u2013 CNET Blogs |publisher=Cnet.com |date=March 13, 2011 |accessdate=April 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAt least two films screened at the SXSW Film festival gained distribution deals: the documentary ''[[Undefeated (2011 film)|Undefeated]]'' (which went on to win the [[Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature]]) and the thriller ''[[The Divide (2011 film)|The Divide]]''. As a result, film critic Christopher Kelly wrote that in 2011, SXSW Film went from being \"a well-regarded but fundamentally regional event\" to having \"joined the big leagues of film festivals around the world.\"<ref>[http://www.dfw.com/2011/03/17/424689/commentary-south-by-southwest.html Commentary: South by Southwest is in danger of losing its indie film cred] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315165235/http://www.dfw.com/2011/03/17/424689/commentary-south-by-southwest.html |date=2012-03-15 }}, Christopher Kelly, DFW.com, March 17, 2011</ref> That festival was also notable for having the premiere of the film ''[[Bridesmaids (2011 film)|Bridesmaids]]''.<ref name=\"bridesmaids bouquet\">[http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/movies/2012/03/sxsw-2012-21-jump-street-cabin-in-the-woods-aspire-to-bridesmaids-style-success-.html SXSW: '21 Jump St.,' 'Cabin in the Woods' eye 'Bridesmaids' bouquet], Mark Olsen, ''24 Frames'' (''Los Angeles Times'' blog), March 8, 2012</ref>\n\nThe March 15th screening of the [[Foo Fighters]] documentary ''[[Back and Forth (documentary)|Back and Forth]]'' was followed by a surprise live performance by the band itself, with a setlist that included the entirety of the then-upcoming album ''[[Wasting Light]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.vh1.com/2011-03-16/foo-fighters-documentary-premiere-followed-by-surprise-show/|title=Foo Fighters Documentary Premiere Followed By Surprise Show|work=VH1 Blog Reality TV News and Gossip|access-date=2011-12-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208075146/http://blog.vh1.com/2011-03-16/foo-fighters-documentary-premiere-followed-by-surprise-show|archive-date=2012-02-08|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==== 2012 ====\nSXSW 2012 ran from March 9 to 18.\n\nThe standout technology of the 2012 SXSW Interactive was generally stated to be \"[[social discovery platform|social discovery]]\" mobile apps, which let users locate other nearby users. Social discovery apps that had a presence at SXSW included [[Highlight (application)|Highlight]], Glancee, Sonar and Kismet.<ref>[http://news.cnet.com/8301-1035_3-57393877-94/hottest-new-apps-out-of-sxsw-2012/ Hottest new apps out of SXSW 2012], Jaymar Cabebe and Jason Parker, ''CNET'', March 12, 2012</ref><ref>[http://content.usatoday.com/communities/livefrom/post/2012/03/sxsw-2012-the-highlight-of-the-festival/1#.T8SqJUWmgrU SXSW 2012: The 'Highlight' of the festival], Jon Swartz, ''USA Today'', March 13, 2012</ref>\n\nSXSW Film saw the premiere of two major Hollywood films: ''[[The Cabin in the Woods]]''<ref>[http://www.statesman.com/news/texas/in-shadows-of-hype-dialogue-of-too-much-2235412.html In shadows of hype, dialogue of 'too much' at SXSW], Jake Coyle, ''The Associated Press\" March 13, 2012 {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> and ''[[21 Jump Street (film)|21 Jump Street]]''.<ref name=\"bridesmaids bouquet\" /> Two films obtained distribution deals: ''[[Girls Against Boys (film)|Girls Against Boys]]'' and ''[[The Tall Man (2012 film)|The Tall Man]]''.<ref>[http://thefilmstage.com/news/sxsw-features-girls-against-boys-and-the-tall-man-picked-up-for-distribution-barrymore-to-finally-see-light-of-day/ SXSW Features \u2018Girls Against Boys\u2019 and \u2018The Tall Man\u2019 Picked Up For Distribution; \u2018Barrymore\u2019 To Finally See Light Of Day], Amanda Waltz, ''The Film Stage'', March 13, 2012</ref> Another film, ''[[Gimme the Loot (film)|Gimme the Loot]]'', which won the SXSW Narrative Feature Grand Jury Prize, got a distribution deal a week after the festival.<ref>[http://insidemovies.ew.com/2012/03/19/sxsw-gimme-the-loot-adam-leon-sundance-select/ SXSW: 'Gimme the Loot' director Adam Leon on winning big, landing distribution deal], Karen Valby, ''Entertainment Weekly: Inside Movies'', March 19, 2012</ref> ''[[Bay of All Saints (film)|Bay of All Saints]]'' received the Audience Award for Best Feature Documentary.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/bay-all-saints-sxsw-film-review-301724|title=Bay of All Saints: SXSW Review|author=John DeFore|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=March 19, 2012}}</ref>\n\n2012 was also the first year the music portion was expanded to Tuesday. The musical festival included rappers such as [[Talib Kweli]] and [[Lil' Wayne]], along with surprise appearances by [[Big Sean]] and [[Kanye West]]; indie bands that appeared included [[MENEW]] and [[The Shins]]. [[Bruce Springsteen]] was the keynote speaker for the music festival.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/events/sxsw/501218/bruce-springsteens-sxsw-keynote-stay-hard-stay-hungry |title=Bruce Springsteen's SXSW Keynote: 'Stay Hard, Stay Hungry' |magazine=Billboard |date=March 15, 2012 |accessdate=April 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==== 2013 ====\nSXSW 2013 ran from March 8 to 17.\n\nThe big-budget films ''[[The Incredible Burt Wonderstone]]'' and ''[[Evil Dead (2013 film)|Evil Dead]]'' premiered at the 2013 SXSW Film, and ''[[Spring Breakers]]'' had its U.S. premiere.<ref>[http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/sxsw-2013-brings-burt-wonderstone-spring-breakers-evil-dead-drinking-buddies-more-to-austin-20130115 SXSW 2013 Brings 'Burt Wonderstone,' Spring Breakers,' 'Evil Dead,' 'Drinking Buddies' & More To Austin], Kevin Jagernauth, ''Indiewire'', January 15, 2013</ref> The film ''[[Short Term 12]]'' won the grand jury award for Best Narrative Feature. The films ''[[Awful Nice]]'', ''[[Cheap Thrills (film)|Cheap Thrills]]'', and ''[[Haunter (film)|Haunter]]'' received distribution deals,<ref>{{cite news |title=SXSW 2013: 'Short Term 12' wins feature prize |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/moviesnow/la-et-mn-sxsw-wrapup-20130313,0,1786750.story |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=March 12, 2013 |first=Mark |last=Olsen}}</ref> and ''[[Drinking Buddies]]'' obtained a distribution deal several days later.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Magnolia Acquires SXSW Pic 'Drinking Buddies' |url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/03/drinking-buddies-magnolia-pictures-acquired-sxsw-joe-swanberg/ |date=March 19, 2013 |first=Jen |last=Yamato |magazine=Deadline}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title=Todd Sklar's 'Awful Nice' Gets U.S. Distribution |url=https://variety.com/2013/film/news/todd-sklars-awful-nice-gets-u-s-distribution-1200560667/ |magazine=Variety}}</ref>\n\nThe 2013 SXSW Interactive saw another huge jump in registration, now with 30,621 paying attendees.<ref>Nicole Villalpando, [http://www.statesman.com/news/events/biggest-interactive-yet-as-sxsw-begins-music-hands/nWqPc/ \"Biggest Interactive yet as SXSW begins Music, hands out Film Awards\"], ''Austin American Statesman'', March 12, 2013. Retrieved on March 13, 2013</ref> This was over three times the number that had attended in 2008 (9,000), just five years previously.<ref>[http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/2008-sxsw-interactive-festival-wraps-up-strong-year-57369557.html 2008 SXSW Interactive Festival Wraps Up Strong Year], ''PRNewswire'', March 31, 2008</ref> The keynote talk for the 2013 SXSW Interactive was given by [[SpaceX]] CEO [[Elon Musk]].<ref name=\"brought to you by\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/innovations/post/sxsw-2013-this-revolution-is-brought-to-you-by/2013/03/11/b47dfa10-8a95-11e2-8d72-dc76641cb8d4_blog.html SXSW 2013: This revolution is brought to you by...], Hamdan Azhar, ''Washington Post'' ideas@innovations blog, March 11, 2013</ref> The \"Screenburn\" and \"Arcade\" components were renamed to \"SXSW Gaming\" and \"SXSW Gaming Expo\", respectively.<ref>[http://iqu.com/blog/south-by-southwest-interactive-video-games SXSW Interactive: A Growing Outlet For Video Games], Matt Clark, ''iQU', March 14, 2012 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130524055251/http://iqu.com/blog/south-by-southwest-interactive-video-games |date=May 24, 2013 }}</ref> The Interactive conference had an increased corporate presence, featuring major participation by [[Samsung]], [[3M]], [[Target Corporation|Target]], [[American Airlines]], [[Adobe Systems]] and [[AT&T]], among others.<ref name=\"brought to you by\" /><ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/03/11/us-sxsw-startups-idUSBRE92A10I20130311 At South by Southwest, fewer startups, more marketers and media], Gerry Shih, Reuters, March 11, 2013</ref> According to [[CNN]], [[CBS]] and [[CNET]] called [[Grumpy Cat]] the undisputed \"biggest star\" of SXSW Interactive over Musk, [[Al Gore]] and [[Neil Gaiman]].<ref name=\"cnn\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/03/10/tech/web/grumpy-cat-sxsw/index.html |title=The unlikely star of SXSW: Grumpy Cat |publisher=CNN.com |date=November 14, 2011 |accessdate=March 11, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/8301-205_162-57573676/as-sxsw-interactive-winds-down-grumpy-cat-is-clear-winner/ |title=As SXSW Interactive winds down, Grumpy cat is clear winner |publisher=CBS News |date= |accessdate=March 3, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Terdiman |first=Daniel |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-14013_3-57573517/if-grumpy-cat-is-the-biggest-news-of-all-is-sxsw-in-trouble/ |title=If Grumpy Cat is the biggest news of all, is SXSW in trouble? &#124; SXSW \u2013 CNET News |publisher=News.cnet.com |date=January 23, 2013 |accessdate=March 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==== 2014 ====\nSXSW 2014 ran from March 7 to 16.\n\nSXSW Film had premieres of the big-budget films ''[[Neighbors (2014 film)|Neighbors]]'', ''[[Veronica Mars (film)|Veronica Mars]]'' and ''[[Chef (2014 film)|Chef]]'', and ''[[Cesar Chavez (film)|Cesar Chavez]]'' had its North American premiere.<ref>{{cite news |title=South by Southwest Adds a TV Section |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/31/business/media/south-by-southwest-festival-adds-a-tv-section.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |first=Michael |last=Cieply |date=January 30, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"five movie stories\">{{cite news |title=SXSW 2014: Five movie stories, including 'Chef' and 'Veronica Mars' |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-sxsw-film-festival-reviews-chef-neighbors-veronica-mar-20140310,0,5139256.story |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |first=Oliver |last=Gettell |date=March 10, 2014}}</ref> A clip for the big-budget film ''[[Godzilla (2014 film)|Godzilla]]'' was also screened. The films ''[[Space Station 76]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.socialitelife.com/matt-bomers-space-station-76-lands-a-distribution-deal-at-sxsw-03-2014|title=Matt Bomer's 'Space Station 76\u2032 Lands A Distribution Deal At SXSW \u2013 Socialite Life Socialite Life|work=Socialite Life|access-date=2015-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402103719/http://www.socialitelife.com/matt-bomers-space-station-76-lands-a-distribution-deal-at-sxsw-03-2014|archive-date=2015-04-02|url-status=dead}}</ref> and ''[[Exists (film)|Exists]]'' got distribution deals at the festival,<ref name=\"five movie stories\" /> while ''[[Fort Tilden (film)|Fort Tilden]]'' (which won the Narrative Feature Grand Jury Prize) and ''[[Open Windows (film)|Open Windows]]'' got distribution deals shortly afterward.<ref>{{cite news |title=Elijah Wood-Sasha Grey's South by Southwest Thriller Gets U.S. Distribution |url=http://bostonherald.com/entertainment/movies/movie_news/2014/04/elijah_wood_sasha_greys_south_by_southwest_thriller_gets_us | newspaper=Boston Herald |date=April 1, 2014 |first=Dave |last=McNary}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/fort-tilden-distribution-sxsw-orion-1201455504/ | work=Variety | first=Dave | last=McNary | title=SXSW 2014 Winner 'Fort Tilden' Gets U.S. Distribution From Orion | date=March 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\nA new section, \"Episodic\" (on television programming) was introduced to SXSW Film. Television series that previewed at the festival include ''[[Silicon Valley (TV series)|Silicon Valley]]'' and ''[[From Dusk till Dawn: The Series]]''. The talk show ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'' was taped for a week at the festival; it joined the talk show ''[[Watch What Happens: Live]]'', which began taping at SXSW in 2013.<ref>{{cite web |title=Move over, Jimmy Kimmel: SXSW welcomes back Bravo's Andy Cohen \u2013 and his show |url=http://austin.culturemap.com/news/entertainment/01-20-14-hey-jimmy-kimmel-bravo-tv-host-andy-cohen-sxsw/ |publisher=CultureMap Austin |first=John |last=Egan |date=January 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\nSXSW Interactive featured a keynote speech by [[NSA]] leaker [[Edward Snowden]], via streaming video, about privacy rights. The festival also featured a talk from another famous leaker, [[Julian Assange]], also speaking remotely.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.philly.com/2014-03-12/news/48122662_1_edward-snowden-nsa-leaker-snowden-southwest-interactive |newspaper=[[Philadelphia Inquirer]] |first=Dan |last=DeLuca |date=March 12, 2014 |title=NSA leaker Snowden is the rock star of SXSW Interactive}}</ref> Besides privacy issues, another major focus of the Interactive festival was [[wearable technology]], including devices for [[augmented reality]], [[activity tracker|activity tracking]], identity authentication, charging cell phones and others.<ref>{{cite news |title=5 things we learned at SXSW Interactive|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/03/13/tech/web/sxsw-wrapup/ |publisher=CNN |last1= Gross |first1= Doug | last2 = Griggs| first2 = Brandon |date=March 13, 2014}}</ref> ''[[Computerworld]]'' magazine called the [[Oculus Rift]], a [[virtual reality]] gaming headset, the \"sleeper hit\" of the festival, although it was displayed not at the Interactive but at the Film portion, as part of a ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' exhibit.<ref>{{cite web |title=Oculus Rift is the sleeper hit of SXSW |url=http://blogs.computerworld.com/computer-peripherals/23634/oculus-rift-sleeper-hit-sxsw-itbwgk |magazine=Computerworld |first=Richi |last=Jennings |date=March 10, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316165841/http://blogs.computerworld.com/computer-peripherals/23634/oculus-rift-sleeper-hit-sxsw-itbwgk |archivedate=March 16, 2014 }}</ref> The SXSW Gaming section introduced its [[SXSW Gaming Awards]] to recognize achievement in video and other types of gaming, which has continued through future SXSW festivals.\n\nThe keynote presenter and headline act this year for Stubb's was [[Lady Gaga]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5930106/lady-gaga-to-headline-stubbs-at-sxsw |magazine=[[Billboard.com]] |first=Andrew |last=Hampp |date=March 11, 2014 |title=Lady Gaga to Headline Stubb's at SXSW}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title=Lady Gaga to Present Keynote Address at SXSW |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5930300/lady-gaga-to-present-keynote-address-at-sxsw |magazine=[[Billboard.com]] |first=Rutherford |last=Halperin |date=March 11, 2014}}</ref> To promote her upcoming album, ''[[Food (Kelis album)|Food]]'', [[Kelis]] cooked and served barbecue-style food from a food truck to festival attendees.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/video/2014/mar/14/sxsw-2014-kelis-food-van-austin-texas-video |title=SXSW 2014: Kelis takes her food van to the streets of Austin, Texas \u2013 video |work=The Guardian |date=March 14, 2014 |accessdate=March 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rap-up.com/2014/03/14/kelis-serves-up-jerk-ribs-at-sxsw-food-truck/ |title=Kelis Serves Up Jerk Ribs at SXSW Food Truck |work=[[Rap-Up]] |date=March 14, 2014 |accessdate=March 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, 2014, a drunk driver, Rashad Charjuan Owens, drove his car into a crowd of festival attendees while trying to evade a traffic stop.<ref>{{cite news |title=Man who drove car into SXSW festival was wannabe rapper with six kids |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2014/03/14/man-who-drove-car-into-swsx-festival-was-wannabe-rapper-with-six-kids/?tid=pm_national_pop |newspaper=Washington Post |first=Lindsey |last=Bever |date=March 14, 2014}}</ref> Two people were killed immediately, another two died later from their injuries and another 21 were injured but survived.<ref name=\"4thAP\">{{cite news |title=4th Person Dies After SXSW Car Crash |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/03/27/sxsw-crash-death_n_5044750.html |work=Huffington Post|date=March 27, 2014 |accessdate=March 29, 2014}}</ref> Owens was convicted of [[capital murder]] charges after a November 2015 trial in which eyewitnesses testified that about \"a chaotic and harrowing scene\" on the night, as hundreds of people ran and screamed as the car sped through crowds of people.<ref>Philip Jankowski & Jazmine Ulloa, [http://www.statesman.com/news/news/crime-law/three-new-pieces-of-evidence-in-the-rashad-owens-c/npHXR/ Rashad Owens guilty of capital murder in deadly SXSW crash], ''Austin American-Statesman'' (November 6, 2016).</ref><ref>Philip Jankowski & Jazmine Ulloa, [http://www.statesman.com/news/news/crime-law/follow-the-capital-murder-trial-of-sxsw-crash-susp/npDh4/ Sixteen people, most eyewitnesses, testify in Rashad Owens trial], ''Austin American-Statesman'' (November 2, 2016).</ref> Owens was given an automatic sentence of [[life without parole|life imprisonment without the possibility of parole]].<ref>Ralph Ellis, [http://www.cnn.com/2015/11/06/us/texas-sxsw-crash/ Man who plowed car into SXSW festival crowd given life sentence], CNN (November 6, 2015).</ref>\n\nOn March 15, 2014, rapper [[Tyler, the Creator]] was arrested on [[misdemeanor]] charges of \"[[inciting to riot]]\" after yelling to fans to push their way past security guards at a sold-out show the previous day.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rapper Tyler, The Creator arrested at South By Southwest|url=http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2014/03/16/rapper-tyler-creator-arrested-at-south-by-southwest/ |agency=Associated Press |date=March 16, 2014}}</ref> In February 2016, the riot charges were dropped against Tyler, The Creator pursuant to a [[plea agreement]] with prosecutors (under which the rapper pleaded guilty to the lesser offense of [[disorderly conduct]] and paid a $100 fine, with the case to be dismissed if he stays out of trouble for three months).<ref>Jazmine Ulloa, [http://www.mystatesman.com/news/news/crime-law/prosecutors-drop-riot-charge-against-rapper-tyler-/nqRYL/ As rapper's riot charge is dropped, legal experts question arrest], ''Austin American-Statesman'' (February 17, 2016).</ref>\n\n==== 2015 ====\n[[File:Crayon Pop filming at SXSW Austin Texas 2015 --2.jpg|thumb|[[Crayon Pop]] filming \"Can't Stop Crayon Pop\" for [[Funny or Die]] before [[K-Pop Night Out at SXSW]]]]\nSXSW 2015 took place from March 13 to 22.\n\nSXSW Film screened 145 feature films, an all-time high for the festival.<ref>{{cite news|title=SXSW 2015 film lineup adds mainstream appeal|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/feb/03/sxsw-2015-film-lineup-mainstream-appeal|accessdate=February 6, 2015|date=February 3, 2015}}</ref> The big-budget films ''[[Furious 7]]'' (which was a last-minute addition to the lineup),<ref>{{cite magazine|last= Setoodeh|first= Ramin |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/furious-7-premieres-at-sxsw-to-cheers-for-paul-walker-1201453405/ |title='Furious 7' Premieres at SXSW to Cheers for Paul Walker |magazine=Variety |date=2015-03-16 |accessdate=2015-08-13}}</ref> ''[[Get Hard]]'', ''[[Spy (2015 film)|Spy]]'', a rough cut of ''[[Trainwreck (film)|Trainwreck]]'', ''[[Moonwalkers (film)|Moonwalkers]]'' and ''[[The Final Girls]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2015/03/10-most-anticipated-films-at-sxsw-2015/full-post/|title=10 Most Anticipated Films at SXSW 2015|work=Consequence of Sound|date=March 9, 2015}}</ref> had their world premieres, as did the documentaries ''[[Danny Says (film)|Danny Says]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://schedule.sxsw.com/2015/events/event_FS18314|title=Danny Says \u2013 SXSW 2015 Event Schedule|website=SXSW Schedule 2015}}</ref> ''Steve Jobs: The Man in the Machine'' and ''[[Brand: A Second Coming]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=SXSW Premieres Include Judd Apatow's 'Trainwreck,' Melissa McCarthy in 'Spy' |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sxsw-premieres-include-judd-apatows-769769 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |first=Seth |last=Abramovitch |date=February 3, 2015}}</ref> ''[[Ex Machina (film)|Ex Machina]]'' had its North American premiere. ''[[6 Years]]'', ''Manson Family Vacation'' and ''Steve Jobs: The Man in the Machine'' all got distribution deals at the festival.<ref>{{cite news |title=SXSW 2015: Films That Were the Talk of the Festival |url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/03/19/sxsw-2015-films-that-were-the-talk-of-the-festival/ |work=The New York Times |first=Mekado |last=Murphy |date=March 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe 2015 festival hosted the swearing-in ceremony of [[Michelle K. Lee]] as the new head of the [[United States Patent and Trademark Office]] (USPTO). [[Secretary of Commerce]] [[Penny Pritzker]] administered the oath of office to Lee at the festival on Friday, March 13.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Schwartz |first1=Eric Hal |title=New Patent Office Director Sworn In by Commerce Secretary at SXSW |url=http://dcinno.streetwise.co/2015/03/13/new-us-patent-chief-sworn-in-at-sxsw/ |accessdate=March 16, 2015 |work=DCInno |publisher=Streetwise Media |date=March 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nVarious sources called [[Meerkat (app)|Meerkat]], an iOS app that had launched two weeks earlier that lets users livestream video via Twitter, the breakout technology of SXSW Interactive.<ref name=\"flying cars\">{{cite news |title=Flying cars, tracking chips: The near future, from SXSW |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2015/03/18/sxsw-flying-cars-tracking-chips-wearables-meerkat/24926781/ |work=USA Today |first=Jefferson |last=Graham |date=March 18, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"2015 5 standout moments\">{{cite web |title=SXSW 2015: 5 Standout Moments in Technology |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Technology/sxsw-2015-standout-moments-technology/story?id=29722900 |work=ABC News |first=Alyssa |last=Newcomb |date=March 18, 2015}}</ref> Another product that got significant buzz was a prototype of the [[roadable aircraft]] [[AeroMobil]].<ref name=\"flying cars\" /><ref name=\"2015 5 standout moments\" />\n\n==== 2016 ====\nSXSW 2016 began on March 11 and ended on March 20.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sxsw.com/schedule | title=Schedule | work=SXSW.com | accessdate=13 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, President [[Barack Obama]] gave a speech at SXSW Interactive in which he called on the technology industry to help solve many of America's problems, such as upgrading outdated networks, helping balance security and privacy, and the [[FBI\u2013Apple encryption dispute]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2016/03/11/obama-tech-sxsw-apple-fbi/81628850/ | title=Obama calls on tech industry at SXSW to help solve nation's problems | work=USA Today | date=11 March 2016 | accessdate=13 March 2016 | last=Jervis | first=Rick}}</ref>\n\nFilms that premiered at SXSW Film include ''[[Everybody Wants Some!! (film)|Everybody Wants Some!!]]'', ''[[Keanu (film)|Keanu]]'', ''[[Sausage Party]]'', ''[[Pee-wee's Big Holiday]]'' and ''[[Don't Think Twice (film)|Don't Think Twice]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=The 16 Buzziest Movies at SXSW Film Festival |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/sxsw-buzziest-movies-2016-festival-1201728130/ |magazine=Variety |last1= Setoodeh |first1= Ramin | last2 = Chang| first2 = Justin | last3 = Leydon| first3 = Joe | last4 = Barker| first4 = Andrew |date=March 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn the night of March 20, gunshots rang out on 6th Street causing mass hysteria and panic. No injuries were reported and a man from Memphis was arrested with discharging a firearm and [[Breach of the peace|disturbing the peace]].{{citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\n==== 2017 ====\nFilms that premiered at SXSW Film include ''[[Song to Song]]'', ''[[Baby Driver (film)|Baby Driver]]'', ''[[Atomic Blonde]]'', ''[[Gemini (2017 film)|Gemini]]'',<ref name=\"sxsw 2017 premieres\">{{cite magazine |title=SXSW: Ryan Gosling, Charlize Theron Take Austin for 'Song to Song,' 'Atomic Blonde' Premieres |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/gallery/sxsw-2017-movie-tv-premieres-gallery-song-song-baby-driver-atomic-blonde-american-gods-985632/1-song-to-song |magazine=Hollywood Reporter |date=March 14, 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Ballad of Lefty Brown]]''. ''[[Spettacolo]]'' and ''[[The Disaster Artist (film)|The Disaster Artist]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=James Franco's 'The Disaster Artist' to Premiere at SXSW |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/festivals/james-franco-the-disaster-artist-premiering-at-sxsw-1201979745/ |first=Dave |last=McNary |magazine=Variety |date=February 7, 2017}}</ref> Television shows that were previewed include ''[[The Son (TV series)|The Son]]'', ''[[Dear White People (TV series)|Dear White People]]'' and ''[[American Gods (TV series)|American Gods]]''.<ref name=\"sxsw 2017 premieres\" /> To promote the [[Hulu]] original series ''[[The Handmaid's Tale (TV series)|The Handmaid's Tale]]'', dozens of actresses silently walked the streets of downtown Austin costumed in red \"handmaid\" dresses.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://adage.com/article/special-report-sxsw/sxsw-hulu-make-a-political-statement-handmaids-tale/308253/|title=SXSW: Hulu Says It's Not Making a Political Statement With 'Handmaids Tale'|access-date=2017-07-22|language=en}}</ref> To promote the third season of the [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] original series ''[[Better Call Saul]]'' (a spin-off prequel of ''[[Breaking Bad]]''), a pop-up \"[[Los Pollos Hermanos]]\" restaurant, representing the fictional fast food chain featured in both series, appeared in downtown Austin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/austin/news/2017/03/10/sxsw-insider-why-the-los-pollos-hermanos-pop-up.html|title=SXSW Insider: Why the Los Pollos Hermanos pop-up came to Austin|last=Anderson|first=Will|date=March 10, 2017|website=www.bizjournals.com|access-date=2017-08-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.adweek.com/brand-marketing/have-a-look-inside-amcs-perfect-replica-of-breaking-bads-los-pollos-hermanos-at-sxsw/|title=Have a Look Inside AMC's Perfect Replica of Breaking Bad's Los Pollos Hermanos at SXSW|last=Maskeroni|first=Alfred|date=March 10, 2017|work=Adweek|access-date=2017-08-22|language=English}}</ref>\n\nGuest speakers included former mayor of Newark, NJ and current Senator [[Cory Booker]] (D-New Jersey),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2017/03/10/technology/sxsw-cory-booker/index.html|title=Cory Booker: We need to love each other|last=O'Brien|first=Sara Ashley|date=2017-03-10|website=CNNMoney|access-date=2017-07-22}}</ref> political activist and commentator [[Van Jones]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/daily/screens/2017-03-11/sxsw-panel-the-messy-truth-with-van-jones/|title=SXSW Panel: ''The Messy Truth'' With Van Jones|access-date=2017-07-22|language=English}}</ref> and former Vice President [[Joe Biden]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-joe-biden-cancer-sxsw-trump-2017-story.html|title=Joe Biden calls for SXSW tech innovators to join 'the only bipartisan thing left in America'|date=2017-03-12|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2017-07-22|language=English|issn=0458-3035}}</ref> who spoke about his cancer research initiative. [[Nile Rodgers]] gave the keynote address for the music portion of the festival,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/events/sxsw/7727781/sxsw-nile-rodgers-keynote-address|title=Nile Rodgers Talks Making Hits & Not Being a Music Snob During SXSW Keynote Address|work=Billboard|access-date=2017-07-22}}</ref> while filmmakers [[Gareth Edwards (director)|Gareth Edwards]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/gareth-edwards-rogue-one-sxsw-1202007727/|title=SXSW: Gareth Edwards Explains How a Starbucks Cup Influenced 'Rogue One'|last=Valentini|first=Valentina I.|date=2017-03-13|work=Variety|access-date=2017-07-22|language=English}}</ref> and [[Lee Daniels]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sxsw-lee-daniels-explains-why-trump-will-be-good-hollywood-details-childhood-ghetto-985428|title=SXSW: Lee Daniels Explains Why Trump Will Be Good for Hollywood, Details Childhood in \"the Ghetto\"|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2017-07-22|language=en}}</ref> gave the keynote presentations for the film portion.\n\nMajor companies and brands which exhibited at SXSW (many with standalone \"brand activation\" pavilions) included [[IBM]], [[Intel]], [[Panasonic]], [[Nintendo]], [[General Electric|GE]], [[Armani|Giorgio Armani]], [[Mazda]] and [[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]].\n\nMajor performers during the music component of the festival included [[Garth Brooks]], [[Lana Del Rey]], [[Lil Yachty]], [[The Roots]], [[The Avett Brothers]], [[Willie Nelson]], [[Solange Knowles]], [[Rae Sremmurd]], [[Migos]], and [[The Chainsmokers]] among others.\n\nEn route to SXSW 2017, [[Italy|Italian]] [[post-punk]] band Soviet Soviet, traveling on the [[Visa Waiver Program]], was denied entry to the United States, detained overnight and [[deportation|deported]] after an [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection|immigration officer]] at [[Seattle\u2013Tacoma International Airport]] claimed they were planning on conducting a paid performance, which would have required a work visa. The band presented a letter from their American [[record label]] stating that both their performances at [[KEXP-FM|KEXP]] (which was what had brought the band to Seattle) and at SXSW were for promotional purposes only, but this failed to convince officials at the airport.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tsioulcas|first1=Anastasia|title=Italian Band Soviet Soviet Denied Entry To The U.S., Jailed And Then Deported|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/therecord/2017/03/10/519707931/italian-band-soviet-soviet-denied-entry-to-the-u-s-jailed-and-then-deported|website=NPR|publisher=NPR|accessdate=13 March 2017}}</ref> There was a \"Contrabanned\" showcase on March 17, featuring various artists and musicians (residents of the U.S. and Canada) who are natives of, or have family connections to, countries affected by the [[Executive Order 13769|2017 U.S. travel ban]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/ct-sxsw-contrabanned-showcase-20170318-column.html|title=SXSW: Artists representing Muslim-majority countries band together|last=Kot|first=Greg|work=chicagotribune.com|access-date=2017-08-22|language=English}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/03/19/520752751/faarrow-joins-south-by-southwest-bands-in-drawing-attention-to-travel-ban|title=FAARROW Joins SXSW Bands In Drawing Attention To Travel Ban|website=NPR.org|access-date=2017-08-22}}</ref>\n\n[[Uber]] and [[Lyft]] pulled out of Austin in May 2016 as a result of a city ordinance mandating fingerprint-based background checks for drivers of any [[transportation network company]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bizjournals.com/austin/news/2016/05/07/uber-lyft-defeated-in-prop-1-referendum.html | title=Uber, Lyft defeated in Prop. 1 referendum | last=Theis | first=Michael | work=[[American City Business Journals]] | date=May 7, 2016}}</ref> However, other services such as (locally based) RideAustin, [[Fasten (company)|Fasten]] and Fare, were available, although in high demand. Uber and Lyft resumed service in Austin in May 2017.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/gulliver/2017/05/not-missed | title=An inglorious return to Austin for Uber and Lyft | work=[[The Economist]] | date=May 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== 2018 ====\n[[File:(L to R) IGN's Laura Prudom, Dan Jurgens, Jim Lee, Frank Miller, Brian Michael Bendis at SXSW 2018.jpg|alt=The panel seated in director's chairs|thumb|[[IGN]]'s Laura Prudom (far left) hosts a panel at 2018's South by Southwest convention discussing Superman's eightieth anniversary and the release of [[Action Comics 1000|''Action Comics'' #1000]], with (left to right): [[Dan Jurgens]], [[Jim Lee]], [[Frank Miller (comics)|Frank Miller]], and [[Brian Michael Bendis]].]]\nSXSW 2018 ran from March 9 to 18.\n\nFinalists of the 2018 SXSW Accelerator Pitch Event included Cambridge Cancer Genomics and Bluefield Technologies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sxsw.com/interactive/2018/50-startup-finalists-announced-for-2018-sxsw-accelerator-pitch-event/|title=SXSW 2018|date=January 16, 2018|website=www.sxsw.com|access-date=2018-01-16}}</ref> Two winners of the event were Austin-based: GrubTubs (in the Hyper-Connected Communities category) and ICON 3D (in the Social and Culture category).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.512tech.com/technology/two-austin-startups-win-big-sxsw-accelerator-pitch-event/OBntFCMxvqyf4wwYgmqegM/|title=Two Austin startups win big at SXSW Accelerator pitch event|last=|first=|date=|work=512 tech (Austin American-Statesman)|access-date=2018-03-18}}</ref>\n\nGuest speakers included politicians [[Bernie Sanders]], [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] and [[Sadiq Khan]]; journalists [[Christiane Amanpour]] and [[Ta-Nehisi Coates]]; filmmakers [[Barry Jenkins]], [[Darren Aronofsky]] and [[Steven Spielberg]]; and others including [[Elon Musk]] and [[David Banner]]. Actor and comedian [[Bill Murray]] appeared at several unofficial functions during SXSW.\n\nMajor performers during SXSW Music included [[Tinashe]], [[Rae Sremmurd]], [[Rita Coolidge]], [[Salt-N-Pepa]] and [[Khalid (singer)|Khalid]]. There was an apparent increased emphasis on locally based performers, international acts and relative unknowns.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bagot |first1=Hayden |title=Announcing 200+ Showcasing Artists for the 2018 SXSW Music Festival |url=https://www.sxsw.com/music/2017/2018-music-festival-artist-announcement-round-one/ |website=SXSW |accessdate=10 July 2019|date=2017-10-11 }}</ref>\n\nNew games announced during the 2018 SXSW Gaming Expo included ''[[Sonic Mania Plus]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bleedingcool.com/2018/03/16/sonic-mania-plus-announced-at-sxsw-with-physical-edition-and-new-characters/|title=Sonic Mania Plus Announced at SXSW with Physical Edition and New Characters|date=2018-03-16|work=Bleeding Cool News And Rumors|access-date=2018-03-17|language=en-US}}</ref> At the SXSW Gaming Awards (held March 17), the award for Game of the Year went to ''[[The Legend of Zelda: Breath of the Wild]].''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.512tech.com/technology/pubg-and-legend-zelda-take-top-prizes-2018-sxsw-gaming-awards/aP9g20knujXrF5T2CfxcbJ/|title='Legend of Zelda' and 'PUBG' top winners at SXSW Gaming Awards|last=|first=|date=|work=512tech (Austin American-Statesman)|access-date=2018-03-18}}</ref>\n\nFilms that premiered at the 2018 South By Southwest Film Festival include ''[[A Quiet Place (film)|A Quiet Place]],'' ''[[Blockers (film)|Blockers]]'' and ''[[Ready Player One (film)|Ready Player One]]''.<ref name=\"unveils 2018\">{{cite magazine |title=SXSW Unveils 2018 Festival Lineup, With John Krasinski's 'A Quiet Place' Opening-Night Film |url=https://deadline.com/2018/01/sxsw-2018-south-by-southwest-features-lineup-john-krasinksi-a-quiet-place-1202274955/ |magazine=Deadline |first=Dino-Ray |last=Ramos |date=January 31, 2018}}</ref> Films that had their U.S. premiere include ''[[Final Portrait]]'' and ''[[Who We Are Now]]''.<ref name=\"unveils 2018\" /> The film ''[[Thunder Road (2018 film)|Thunder Road]]'' won the grand jury prize. TV series that previewed include ''[[Barry (TV series)|Barry]]'', ''[[Krypton (TV series)|Krypton]]'', ''[[The Last O.G.]]''<ref name=\"unveils 2018\" /> and ''[[Cloak & Dagger (TV series)|Cloak & Dagger]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Marvel's 'Cloak & Dagger' holds watch party at SXSW |url=http://www.kvue.com/article/life/events/sxsw/marvels-cloak-dagger-holds-watch-party-at-sxsw/269-527699516 |publisher=KVUE |last1= Knight |first1= Drew | last2 = Yeates| first2 = Daysi |date=March 11, 2018}}</ref> To promote the second season of the HBO series ''[[Westworld (TV series)|Westworld]]'', a recreation of the show's fictional Western \"town\" of Sweetwater was built on two acres of open land just outside Austin. Fans took shuttles to the site, which was dressed in the Old West style, with over 60 actors playing the parts of the android \"hosts\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.adweek.com/brand-marketing/inside-hbo-and-giant-spoons-massive-immersive-westworld-activation-at-sxsw/|title=Inside HBO and Giant Spoon's Massive Immersive Westworld Activation at SXSW|access-date=2018-03-11|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/hbo-brings-westworld-to-sxsw/|title='Westworld's gritty western fantasy comes to life at SXSW|date=2018-03-09|work=CNET|access-date=2018-03-11|language=en}}</ref>\n\nSXSW 2018 coincided with a [[Austin serial bombings|string of bombings in Austin]], which had begun on March 2 and ended on March 21, when the presumed perpetrator, Mark Anthony Conditt, blew himself up after being discovered by police.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.statesman.com/news/crime--law/the-suspect-family-mark-conditt-grieving-and-shock/CQUCcXNJ9nb2iFs8sSq0pK/|title=THE SUSPECT: Family of Mark A. Conditt 'grieving' and 'in shock'|last=American-Statesman Staff|work=Austin American-Statesman|access-date=2018-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180322214622/https://www.statesman.com/news/crime--law/the-suspect-family-mark-conditt-grieving-and-shock/CQUCcXNJ9nb2iFs8sSq0pK/|archive-date=2018-03-22|url-status=dead}}</ref> Two of the bombings occurred during SXSW. On March 17, Live Nation Music, a company organizing events for SXSW, received a bomb threat via email. Police searched the area mentioned in the email and found nothing of concern, but planned performances by [[The Roots]] and [[Ludacris]], among others, were canceled.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/music/news/the-roots-sxsw-concert-cancelled-due-to-security-concern-1202729636/|title=The Roots' SXSW Concert Canceled Due to 'Security Concern'|date=2018-03-18|work=Variety|access-date=2018-03-22|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2018/03/18/594776934/man-arrested-for-bomb-threat-at-sxsw-festival-in-austin-texas|title=Austin Police Warn People To Avoid Packages After 4th Explosion Injures 2|work=NPR.org|access-date=2018-03-22|language=en}}</ref> Police arrested 26-year-old Trevor Weldon Ingram the next day; Ingram was charged with making a terroristic threat, a third-degree felony, in connection with the email.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trevor-weldon-ingram-arrested-for-austin-sxsw-bomb-threat/|title=Man arrested for bomb threat that shut down Roots concert at South by Southwest in Austin|last=|first=|date=March 18, 2018|work=CBS News|access-date=2018-03-22|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== 2019 ====\nSouth by Southwest 2019 ran from March 8 to March 17.\n\nFilms entered at SXSW Film included ''[[Us (2019 film)|Us]]'', ''[[The Beach Bum]]'', ''[[Long Shot (2019 film)|Long Shot]]'', ''[[Booksmart (film)|Booksmart]]'' and ''[[The Highwaymen (film)|The Highwaymen]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title='The Beach Bum,' 'Us,' Johnny Cash Doc Lead 2019 SXSW Film Festival |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-news/the-beach-bum-us-johnny-cash-doc-2019-sxsw-film-festival-780147/ |date=January 16, 2019 |first=Daniel |last=Kreps |work=Rolling Stone}}</ref> TV series that previewed included [[FX (TV channel)|FX]]\u2019s ''[[What We Do in the Shadows (TV series)|What We Do in the Shadows]]'', [[Hulu]]\u2019s ''[[Shrill (TV series)|Shrill]]'' and [[Oprah Winfrey Network|OWN]]\u2019s ''[[David Makes Man]]''.\n\nAt the SXSW Gaming Awards (held March 16), the award for Game of the Year went to ''[[God of War (2018 video game)|God of War.]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.austin360.com/news/20190317/god-of-war-takes-top-honor-at-sxsw-gaming-awards|title='God of War' takes top honor at SXSW Gaming Awards|last=Gonzales|first=Chloe|date=March 17, 2019|website=Austin 360|language=en|access-date=2019-03-18}}</ref>\n\nMajor performers for SXSW Music included [[Edie Brickell & New Bohemians]] (their first-ever appearance at SXSW).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/events/sxsw/8502481/edie-brickell-new-bohemians-first-sxsw-set|title=Edie Brickell & New Bohemians Play Tight, Career-Spanning Set at SXSW|last=Graff|first=Gary|date=March 14, 2019|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-03-15}}</ref>\n\nWinners of the 2019 SXSW Pitch event, in which emerging startups pitch to potential investors, included Derq, Pathway and ENZO Tyres. The \u201cBest In Show\" winner was [[Nebula Genomics]];<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2018/11/15/667946213/startup-offers-to-sequence-your-genome-free-of-charge-then-let-you-profit-from-i|title=Startup Offers To Sequence Your Genome Free Of Charge, Then Let You Profit From It|last=Harris|first=Richard|date=November 15, 2018|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-03-15}}</ref> the \u201cBest Bootstrap\" award went to TwentyTables and the \u201cBest Speed Pitch\u201d went to Xplosion Tech.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/sxsw-announces-2019-winners-of-11th-annual-pitch-event-300809776.html|title=SXSW Announces 2019 Winners of 11th Annual Pitch Event|date=March 11, 2019|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-15}}</ref>\n\nSome of the first forums of the [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 presidential race]] took place at SXSW, with [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] presidential candidates [[Pete Buttigieg]], [[Julian Castro]], [[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|John Delaney]], [[Tulsi Gabbard]], [[John Hickenlooper]], [[Jay Inslee]], [[Amy Klobuchar]], [[Beto O'Rourke]], [[Elizabeth Warren]] and [[Andrew Yang]] all making appearances at the festival (though some had not yet announced their candidacy at the time).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sacbee.com/latest-news/article227347884.html|title=2020 Democrats flock to trendy SXSW festival in Texas|last=WEBER|first=PAUL J.|work=The Sacramento Bee|access-date=2019-03-09|language=en-US|issn=0890-5738}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Democratic Candidates Target Tech Giants, Who Are Major Party Donors |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/03/11/702102576/democratic-candidates-target-tech-giants-who-are-major-party-donors |first=Aarti |last=Shahani |date=March 11, 2019 |publisher=NPR}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freep.com/story/news/nation/2019/03/07/sxsw-austin-politics-president-2020-race-candidates-trump/3050647002/|title=The new Iowa? 2020 presidential candidates descend on Austin for SXSW conference|website=Detroit Free Press|language=en|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> Other scheduled guest speakers included politicians [[Mazie Hirono]] and [[Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez]]; musicians [[David Byrne]] and [[Wyclef Jean]]; actors and comedians [[Aidy Bryant]], [[Kathy Griffin]], [[Ethan Hawke]], [[Trevor Noah]] and [[Zoe Saldana]]; businessmen [[Tim Ferriss]], [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]] and [[Guy Kawasaki]]; and others including [[Priscilla Chan]], [[Neil Gaiman]], [[Valerie Jarrett]], [[Bill Nye]], [[Robert Rodriguez]] and [[Maria Shriver]].\n\nTo promote the final season of ''[[Game of Thrones]]'', [[HBO]] organized a [[blood donation|blood drive]] with the [[American Red Cross]] titled \"Bleed for the Throne\" which included actors in costumes similar to those on the series.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.adweek.com/digital/snap-and-hbo-use-ar-at-game-of-thrones-sxsw-experience/|title=Snap and HBO Use AR at Game of Thrones SXSW Experience|last=Swant|first=Marty|date=March 7, 2019|work=Adweek|access-date=2019-03-08|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.texasmonthly.com/the-culture/at-sxsw-hbo-and-amazon-go-over-the-top-on-immersive-experiences/|title=At SXSW, HBO and Amazon Go Over-the-Top on \"Immersive Experiences\"|last=Solomon|first=Dan|date=2019-03-08|website=Texas Monthly|language=en|access-date=2019-03-10}}</ref>\n\nTo promote the [[Amazon Prime]] original limited series ''[[Good Omens (TV series)|Good Omens]]'', a brand activation experience called \"Garden of Earthly Delights\" was installed in downtown Austin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cbsaustin.com/news/local/amazon-prime-brings-a-garden-of-earthly-delights-to-sxsw|title=Amazon Prime brings a Garden of Earthly Delights to SXSW|last=Cross|first=Bettie|date=2019-03-09|website=KEYE|access-date=2019-03-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/good-omens-sxsw-activation-amazon-prime-video-neil-gaiman-terry-pratchett-michael-cheen-david-tennant-1202572210/|title='Good Omens' Celebrates End Of Times With Elixirs, Manicures And Puppies At SXSW|last=Ramos|first=Dino-Ray|date=2019-03-08|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-03-10}}</ref>\n\n=== 2020 cancellation ===\nSouth by Southwest 2020 was scheduled to run from March 13 to March 22, but was officially cancelled on March 6 due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/sxsw-canceled-coronavirus|title=SXSW 2020 Has Been Cancelled Following Coronavirus Fears|date=2020-03-06|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> the result of an order by the city of Austin.<ref name=\"city of austin cancels\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sxsw.com/2020-event-update/|title=City of Austin Cancels SXSW March Events|date=2020-03-06|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> The city's Mayor [[Steve Adler (politician)|Steve Adler]] announced the cancellation of the 2020 SXSW and also declared a local state of emergency.<ref>https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/austin-considers-spring-festivals-sxsw-in-light-of-covid-19-spread/2325885/</ref>\n\nIn the month prior to the conference, SXSW organizers had resisted calls to cancel the conference. On February 28, a spokesperson said:\n{{Quote\n| text=The SXSW 2020 event is proceeding as planned. Safety is a top priority for SXSW, and we work closely with local, state, and federal agencies year-round to plan for a safe event. Where travel has been impacted, especially in the case of China, we are seeing a handful of cancellations. However, we are on par with years past in regard to registrants who are unable to attend. We are increasing our efforts to prevent the spread of disease per Austin Public Health\u2019s recommendations. We will continue to monitor the situation closely and will provide updates as necessary.\n| author=SXSW spokesperson|source=Recode, Vox Media <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/2/27/21156676/coronavirus-facebook-f8-canceled-major-tech-conferences-covid-19|title=Here are all the major tech conferences canceled so far because of coronavirus\n| date=2020-02-28|website=Vox|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>\n}}\n\nHowever, in the run up to the conference, numerous companies and organizations began cancelling their SXSW attendance, including [[Twitter]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cbsaustin.com/news/local/twitter-cancels-sxsw-appearance-over-coronavirus-concerns|title=Twitter CEO cancels SXSW appearance over coronavirus concerns\n| date=2020-03-02|website=CBS Austin|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.twitter.com/en_us/topics/company/2020/keeping-our-employees-and-partners-safe-during-coronavirus.html|title=Keeping our employees and partners safe during #coronavirus\n| date=2020-03-01|website=Twitter|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref> [[Facebook]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/2/21162250/facebook-pulls-out-sxsw-conference-coronavirus-concerns|title=Facebook pulls out of the SXSW conference citing coronavirus concerns|date=2020-03-02|website=The Verge|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref> [[Vevo]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://adage.com/article/digital/facebook-and-vevo-cancel-sxsw-plans-amid-coronavirus-fears/2241951|title=FACEBOOK AND VEVO CANCEL SXSW PLANS AMID CORONAVIRUS FEARS|date=2020-03-02|website=Ad Age|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref> [[Intel]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303145813/https://www.kxan.com/news/coronavirus/facebook-intel-join-twitter-in-pulling-out-of-sxsw-over-coronavirus-fears/|title=Facebook, Intel join Twitter in pulling out of SXSW over coronavirus fears|date=2020-03-03|website=KXAN|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> [[Mashable]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/mashable/status/1234878736832647172|title=We\u2019ve decided to cancel the Mashable House and MashBash at SXSW|date=2020-03-03|website=Twitter|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> [[Universal Music Group]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/record-labels/9327781/record-labels-travel-coronavirus|title=Record Labels Restrict Travel Amid Escalating Coronavirus Threat|date=2020-03-03|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/amazon-studios-sxsw-2020-cancellation-coronavirus-1202873881/|title= Amazon Studios Pulls Out Of Fest Over Coronavirus Concerns|date=2020-03-03|website=Deadline|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> [[TikTok]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/tiktok-pulls-out-sxsw-amid-coronavirus-961657/|title=TikTok Is Pulling Out of SXSW Amid the Coronavirus Scare|date=2020-03-03|website=Rolling Stone|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> [[SAP SE|SAP]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SAP/status/1235012712209567744|title=We have made the decision to cancel all SAP in-person events for the month of March 2020|date=2020-03-04|website=Twitter|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> [[Netflix]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/netflix-cancels-sxsw-2020-1203524545/|title=Netflix Cancels SXSW 2020 Screenings, Panels Amid Coronavirus Fears (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Low|first=Elaine|last2=Low|first2=Elaine|date=2020-03-05|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> [[Apple Inc.|Apple]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/digital/news/apple-cancels-sxsw-2020-coronavirus-1203524430/|title=Apple Pulls Out of SXSW 2020 Over Coronavirus Concerns|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=2020-03-05|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> [[Indeed]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305101441/https://www.statesman.com/business/20200304/as-virus-concerns-swirl-austin-based-indeed-tells-employees-to-work-from-home|title=Austin-based Indeed tells employees to work from home|date=2020-03-04|website=Statesman|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> [[WarnerMedia]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306091637/https://www.kxan.com/news/sxsw/warnermedia-joins-list-of-companies-pulling-out-of-sxsw/|title=WarnerMedia joins list of companies pulling out of SXSW|date=2020-03-05|website=KXAN.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/davejorgenson/status/1235200866715566080|title= The Post has cancelled all non-essential business travel|date=2020-03-04|website=Twitter|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> and [[IBM]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305101903/https://www.statesman.com/business/20200304/ibm-to-skip-on-sxsw-after-issuing-travel-restrictions-due-to-coronavirus|title=IBM to skip on SXSW after issuing travel restrictions due to coronavirus|date=2020-03-04|website=Statesman|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> Additionally, many individual attendees, headliners and speakers had decided not to attend, including keynote speaker [[Tim Ferriss]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304090009/https://www.austin360.com/entertainment/20200303/sxsw-2020-and-coronavirus-herersquos-whos-not-coming|title=SXSW 2020 and coronavirus: Here's who's not coming|date=2020-03-03|website=Austin 360|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.crunchbase.com/news/not-worth-the-risk-startups-vcs-backing-out-of-sxsw-due-to-coronavirus-concerns/|title='Not Worth The Risk': Startups, VCs Backing Out Of SXSW Due To Coronavirus Concerns|date=2020-03-03|website=Crunchbase|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> and artists such as the [[Beastie Boys]], [[Ozzy Osbourne]] and [[Trent Reznor]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/beastie-boys-ozzy-osbourne-trent-reznor-pull-out-of-sxsw/|title=Beastie Boys, Ozzy Osbourne, Trent Reznor Pull Out of SXSW Due to Coronavirus|last=Bloom|first=Madison|date=2020-03-06|website=Pitchfork|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref>\n\nAn online petition was started that called for SXSW 2020 to be cancelled due to health concerns; by the time of the cancellation, it exceeded 50,000 signatures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/10000-call-for-sxsw-to-be-canceled-over-coronavirus-fears-2020-3|title=Nearly 15,000 sign petition calling for SXSW to be canceled over mounting coronavirus worries|date=2020-03-02|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/health/2020/03/02/coronavirus-outbreak-fears-spurs-petition-calling-halt-sxsw/4930937002/\n| title=Fears of coronavirus prompt online petition to cancel SXSW gathering in Austin\n| date=2020-03-02|website=USA Today|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n\nSXSW organizers said that they were \"devastated\" by the cancellation, stating that, \"'The show must go on' is in our DNA.\"<ref name=\"city of austin cancels\" /> They wrote that they were attempting to reschedule the event, and were at the same time working to create an online SXSW for 2020.<ref name=\"city of austin cancels\" />\n\nSXSW co-founder Nick Barbaro said the organization did not have cancellation insurance relating to a disease pandemic or triggered by the city declaring a \u201clocal state of disaster.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/daily/news/2020-03-06/sxsw-cancellation-not-covered-by-insurance/|title=SXSW Cancellation Not Covered by Insurance|last=Curtin|first=Kevin|last2=|date=2020-02-06|website=www.austinchronicle.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-07|last3=|first3=|last4=}}</ref>\n\nDespite the cancellation of SXSW 2020 amid concerns over COVID-19, unofficial SXSW events, as well as \u201calternative\u201d SXSW events, have gained momentum trying to rally around the local workers and businesses who would be hurt most by the cancellation.<ref>https://www.kxan.com/news/local/austin/despite-sxsw-cancellation-unofficial-and-alternative-events-look-to-gain-momentum/</ref>\n\nThe Austin Community Foundation launched a \u201cStand with Austin Fund\u201d for donations to \u201cindividuals and small businesses most negatively impacted by the cancellation of SXSW and least able to recover on their own.\u201d<ref>https://www.austincf.org/Stand-with-Austin</ref>\n\nA fundraiser called \"Banding Together\" was started by the Red River Cultural District to provide financial relief for artists venues and events within the district.\n\nOn March 13, 2020 festival organizers announced that they will proceed with juried and special awards, with judges viewing submissions via digital links.<ref>{{cite news|title=SXSW Revives Film Competition Digitally After Festival Cancellation|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sxsw-revives-film-competition-digitally-festival-cancellation-1284529?utm_source=twitter&utm_medium=social|magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collider.com/sxsw-2020-film-competition-digital-details/|title=SXSW Film Competition Going Digital in the Wake of Festival Cancellation| date=2020-03-13|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, SXSW announced the winners of the 2020 SXSW Gaming Awards on the SXSW website, and the honorees recorded acceptance messages for the SXSW [[YouTube]] channel and the SXSW website<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sxsw.com/news/2020/announcing-the-2020-sxsw-gaming-awards-winners/|title=Announcing the 2020 SXSW Gaming Awards Winners|date=2020-03-24|website=SXSW|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>. ''[[Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice]]'' was awarded Video Game of the Year.\n\nOn March 30, SXSW added a page on its website offering official merchandise intended for the 2020 event, such as t-shirts and posters, for sale online<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sxsw.com/news/2020/shop-official-2020-sxsw-merch/|title=Shop Official SXSW 2020 Merch|date=2020-03-31|website=SXSW|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>.\n\nOn April 2, SXSW announced a joint venture with [[Prime Video|Amazon Prime Video]] to launch a film festival collection. Filmmakers scheduled to screen films at SXSW were notified April 2, and will be able to opt in; those who do so will see their films play exclusively on Prime Video in the U.S. for the 10-day \"virtual film festival,\" which Amazon will likely launch in late April. The online event will be available in front of the Prime Video paywall and free to U.S. audiences.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/amazon-teams-sxsw-launch-a-virtual-fest-1288163|title=Amazon Teams With SXSW to Launch a Virtual Fest|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sxsw.com/film/2020/amazon-prime-video-presents-the-sxsw-2020-film-festival-collection/|title=Amazon Prime Video Presents the SXSW 2020 Film Festival Collection|date=2020-04-02|website=SXSW|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n== Economic impact ==\nSXSW is the highest revenue-producing event outside of athletic and other events associated with [[The University of Texas at Austin]] for the Austin economy, with an estimated economic impact of $190.3 million in 2012<ref>{{cite news|title=Report: SXSW's 2012 economic impact was $190 million|url=http://www.statesman.com/news/business/sxsws-2012-economic-impact-190-million/nSTKt/|newspaper=Austin American Statesman|accessdate=April 1, 2013}}</ref> increasing to $218 million in 2013,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.austinchamber.com/blog/2013/09/18/sxsw-announces-2013-impact-on-the-austin-economy/ |title=SXSW Announces 2013 Impact on the Austin Economy &#124; Austin Chamber Divisional Blogs |publisher=Austinchamber.com |date=September 18, 2013 |accessdate=March 17, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316024643/https://www.austinchamber.com/blog/2013/09/18/sxsw-announces-2013-impact-on-the-austin-economy/ |archivedate=March 16, 2014 }}</ref> $315 million in 2014,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.texasmonthly.com/the-daily-post/sxsws-economic-impact-on-austin-in-2014-was-worth-315-million/|title=SXSW's Economic Impact On Austin In 2014 Was Worth $315 Million|date=2014-09-12|work=Texas Monthly|access-date=2017-08-11|language=English}}</ref> $317 million in 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/austin/blog/techflash/2015/09/sxsw-economic-impact-grows-slightly-from-2014.html|title=SXSW economic impact grows slightly from 2014|last=Swiatecki|first=Chad|date=September 15, 2015|website=www.bizjournals.com|access-date=2017-08-11}}</ref> and $325 million in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/austin/news/2016/09/07/sxsw-economic-impact-up-slightly-in-2016-hotel.html|title=SXSW economic impact up slightly in 2016; hotel rates hit new high|last=Theis|first=Michael|date=September 7, 2016|website=www.bizjournals.com|access-date=2017-08-11}}</ref> (In comparison, [[Super Bowl LI]] brought a $347 million economic impact to the Houston economy<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/houston/news/2017/05/25/results-are-in-how-much-the-2017-super-bowl.html|title=Results are in: How much the 2017 Super Bowl brought to Houston|last=Martin|first=Joe|date=May 25, 2017|website=www.bizjournals.com/houston|access-date=2017-07-22}}</ref> and the [[2017 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|2017 Final Four]] brought a $324 million economic impact to the economy of Phoenix, Arizona.)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/money/business/2017/08/11/final-four-gave-phoenix-area-325-million-economic-slam-dunk-asu-study-says/555967001/|title=Final Four gave Phoenix area a $325 million economic slam dunk, ASU study says|last=Wiles|first=Russ|date=August 11, 2017|work=azcentral|access-date=2017-08-11|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, demand for hotel rooms in the Austin area continued to outstrip supply, pushing average nightly room rates up to an all-time high of $350 in 2016, a 60 percent increase over the average room rate seen during 2011's edition of SXSW. The average SXSW registrant also stayed in Austin longer in 2016, spending an average of 5.2 nights, up from 4.9 nights in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/austin/news/2016/09/07/sxsw-economic-impact-up-slightly-in-2016-hotel.html|title=SXSW economic impact up slightly in 2016; hotel rates hit new high|last=Theis|first=Michael|date=September 7, 2016|website=www.bizjournals.com|access-date=2017-07-22}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\nThe growth of the festival has brought concerns about violence, [[crowd control]], and safety.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.suntimes.com/music/2011/03/violence_and_crowd_control_pro.html|title=Violence and crowd control problems cause SXSW to consider limiting events|newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|accessdate=2015-08-13|first=Thomas|last=Conner|date=March 21, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141208100955/http://blogs.suntimes.com/music/2011/03/violence_and_crowd_control_pro.html|archivedate=December 8, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/03/27/sxsw-accident-fourth-death/6970477/|title=SXSW accident claims fourth life|last= Owens|first= Marjorie |date=27 March 2014|newspaper=USA Today|accessdate=2015-08-13}}</ref>{{update after|2018|11|28}}<!-- and then what? What happened with this 2014 lawsuit? Was the festival implicated? Festival organizers? Or was it just a drunk driving accident that, sadly, still happens a couple million times annually. -->\n\nThe 2014 drunk-driving incident prompted discussion about whether the festival had grown too large and raucous.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-sxsw-car-accident-tragedy-20140314,0,4850567.story |title=A tragic wake-up call for SXSW? |publisher=latimes.com |date=March 13, 2014 |first1=Mikael |last1=Wood |first2=August |last2=Brown}}</ref> The organizers of the festival\u2014SXSW Holdings LLC and SXSW Holdings Inc.\u2014were sued by families of the four victims.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170629220217/https://www.kxan.com/2014/12/18/lawsuits-deadly-sxsw-crash-could-have-been-prevented/|title=Lawsuits: Deadly SXSW crash could have been prevented|publisher=KXAN|accessdate=2015-08-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150824065806/http://kxan.com/2014/12/18/lawsuits-deadly-sxsw-crash-could-have-been-prevented/|archive-date=2015-08-24|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, partially motivated by the 2014 crash, Austin's Urban Transportation Commission announced that it was seeking to enhance safety at the festival, with an initial focus on implementing transportation measures to resolve issues linked to the festival. The Austin Music Commission also met to discuss music venues and sound problems linked to the festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khou.com/news/texas-news?fId=259080131&fPath=/news/local/&fDomain=10232 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140517065154/http://www.khou.com/news/texas-news?fId=259080131&fPath=/news/local/&fDomain=10232 |url-status=dead |archive-date=May 17, 2014 |accessdate=May 18, 2014 }}</ref> The city voted to limit the number of special events which would be approved to 114, a 32 percent decrease from the number of approved events during the 2014 festival.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/austin/blog/creative/2015/02/a-smaller-sxsw-austin-halts-applications-for.html|title=A smaller SXSW? Austin halts applications for special events|date=11 February 2015|work=Austin Business Journal}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, NPR writer Andrea Swensson wrote that she had decided to stop attending the festival, writing, \"I can't help but feel that it has strayed far away from its original premise as a grassroots gathering place for new, undiscovered talent and increasingly feels like a big ol' [[Times Square]] billboard-sized commercial.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Why I'm Not Going To SXSW This Year |url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/therecord/2013/03/05/173097673/why-im-not-going-to-sxsw-this-year |publisher=NPR |date=March 5, 2013 |first=Andrea |last=Swensson}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, SXSW cancelled two video game panels (\"#SavePoint: A Discussion on the Gaming Community\" and \"Level Up: Overcoming Harassment In Games\") scheduled for the 2016 festival due to threats of violence made to the festival hosting the sessions.<ref name=\"wash_SXSW\">{{Cite news | title = SXSW canceled two panels after threats \u2013 but did nothing when female panelists asked about harassment | last = Dewey | first = Caitlin | work = Washington Post | date = October 27, 2015 | accessdate = 2015-10-28 | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-intersect/wp/2015/10/27/sxsw-canceled-two-panels-after-threats-but-did-nothing-when-female-panelists-asked-about-harassment/ | language = | quote = }}</ref> In response to the cancellations, [[Buzzfeed]] and [[Vox Media]] made statements saying they would pull out of the festival if the two panels weren't reinstated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tech.blog.austin360.com/2015/10/26/sxsw-interactive-cancels-two-2016-panels-due-to-threats/|title=SXSW Interactive cancels two 2016 panels due to threats|last=Gallaga|first=Omar L.|work=[[Austin 360]]|date=October 27, 2015|accessdate=October 27, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305084400/http://tech.blog.austin360.com/2015/10/26/sxsw-interactive-cancels-two-2016-panels-due-to-threats/|archive-date=2016-03-05|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"reco_Buzz\">{{Cite news | title = BuzzFeed and Vox Media Threaten to Bail on SXSW Unless Canceled Panels Are Reinstated | last = Kulwin | first = Noah | work = Re/code | date = October 27, 2015 | accessdate = 2015-10-28 | url = https://recode.net/2015/10/27/buzzfeed-to-withdraw-from-sxsw-unless-organizers-reverse-panel-cancelations/ | quote = }}</ref> Organizers then apologized for the cancellations. In lieu of a panel, South by Southwest hosted a daylong \"online harassment summit\" on March 12, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title='We Made a Mistake': SXSW to Host Online Harassment Summit|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/we-made-mistake-sxsw-host-online-harassment-summit-n454651|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=30 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n* Comedian and actor [[Fred Armisen]] began his comic career with the short film ''Fred Armisen's Guide to Music and SXSW'', released in 1998, in which he poses as various characters, asking silly questions of musicians and other attendees at that year's SXSW Music Conference.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ifc.com/shows/portlandia/cast-and-crew/fred-armisen-co-creator-co-writer-co-star |title=Portlandia \u2013 Fred Armisen \u2013 co-creator, co-writer, co-star \u2013 IFC |publisher=Ifc.com |date=2011-02-23 |accessdate=2015-08-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150804085943/http://www.ifc.com/shows/portlandia/cast-and-crew/fred-armisen-co-creator-co-writer-co-star |archivedate=2015-08-04 }}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|tOp1uPpjYgo|Fred Armisen's Guide to Music and SXSW}}</ref>\n* SXSW was featured during the 2005 season of [[MTV]]'s, ''[[The Real World: Austin|The Real World]]''. Cast members were tasked with shooting and editing their own documentary on the music festival.\n* The 2011 documentary ''[[Winning America]]'' is about a US tour of Canadian band [[Said the Whale]] that culminates in that year's SXSW Music Festival.\n* In the 2014 British film ''[[Frank (film)|Frank]]'', an experimental band (led by the title character) is booked to play a show at the SXSW Music Festival, but the gig leads to the band's breakup.\n* In the 2019 anime ''[[Carole & Tuesday]]'', the titular duo is booked to perform at the SXSW Music Festival.\n\n== Similar festivals ==\nThe creators of South by Southwest co-created two similar festivals in 1995: North by Northwest (NXNW) in [[Portland, Oregon]] (co-founded by the ''[[Willamette Week]]''), and [[North by Northeast]] (NXNE) in [[Toronto]] (co-founded by ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now]]'').<ref name=\"four-letter festivals\">{{cite web |title=Alt-Weeklies' Four-Letter Festivals: Movement Grows as Silicon Valley Launches C2SV |url=http://www.altweeklies.com/aan/alt-weeklies-four-letter-festivals-movement-grows-as-silicon-valley-launches-c2sv/Article?oid=7274104 |publisher=AAN News |date=September 20, 2013}}</ref> North by Northwest ended in 2001, and was replaced by [[MusicfestNW]] (MFNW), an event run entirely by the ''Willamette Week''. It was joined by [[TechfestNW]], a technology conference, in 2012.<ref>[http://tech.fortune.cnn.com/2012/08/28/tech-may-have-found-its-next-sxsw/ Tech may have found its next SXSW], John Patrick Pullen, ''CNNMoney'', August 28, 2012</ref> From 2006 to 2010, SXSW organizers also ran West by Southwest (WXSW) in [[Tucson, Arizona]], a music festival which occurred directly before South by Southwest and mostly featured bands that were also booked for SXSW.<ref>[http://tucsoncitizen.com/morgue2/2006/03/09/115421-go-west-by-southwest-young-band/ Go West (by Southwest), young band] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303232623/http://tucsoncitizen.com/morgue2/2006/03/09/115421-go-west-by-southwest-young-band/ |date=2016-03-03 }}, Polly Higgins, ''[[Tucson Citizen]]'', March 9, 2006</ref>\n\nOther active festivals inspired by SXSW include the following:\n* [[Web Summit]] \u2013 [[Lisbon, Portugal]]\n* Live at Heart \u2013 [[\u00d6rebro, Sweden]]\n* South by Due East \u2013 [[Houston, Texas]]\n* The Goa Project \u2013 [[Goa, India]]\n* [[The Great Escape Festival]] \u2013 [[Brighton, England]]\n* [[Tech Open Air]] (TOA) \u2013 [[Berlin]]\n* [[XOXO (festival)|XOXO]]<ref>{{cite web |title=XOXO Aims to Be an Alternative to South by Southwest |url=https://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/25/xoxo-aims-to-be-an-alternative-to-south-by-southwest/ |first=Jenna |last=Wortham |work=The New York Times Bits blog |date=May 25, 2012}}</ref> \u2013 [[Portland, Oregon]]\n\nFestivals inspired by SXSW that are no longer running include:\n* [[35 Denton]] (originally known as \"North by 35\" or \"NX35\", then \"35 Conferette\") \u2013 [[Denton, Texas]] (2009\u20132016)\n* [[C2SV]] (originally known as \"SVSX\") \u2013 [[San Jose, California]] (2012\u20132016)\n* [[Incubate (festival)|Incubate]] (originally known as \"ZXZW\") \u2013 [[Tilburg, Netherlands]] (2005\u20132016)\n* [[MidPoint Music Festival]] (MPMF) \u2013 [[Cincinnati, Ohio]] (2001\u20132017)\n* [[MoSo]] \u2013 [[Saskatoon, Canada]] (2011\u20132016)\n* So What?! Music Fest (originally known as \"South by So What?!\") \u2013 [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth Metroplex]] (2006\u20132017)\n* Sounds by South Bend (originally known as \"South by South Bend\") \u2013 [[South Bend, Indiana]] (2013\u20132015)\n* Yes and Yes Yes (YXYY) (originally known as \"Yes by Yes Yes\") \u2013 [[Palm Springs, California]] (2013\u20132017)\n\nFestivals inspired by South by Southwest have been collectively nicknamed \"four-letter festivals\". ''[[Metro Silicon Valley]]'', which founded C2SV, wrote in 2013 that such festivals were important revenue sources for the [[alternative newspaper|alternative weekly newspapers]] that founded them.<ref name=\"four-letter festivals\" />\n\nOn October 3, 2016, a one-day festival, called \"South by [[South Lawn]]\" (SXSL), was held at the [[White House]]; it was a collaboration between SXSW, US President [[Barack Obama]], and the [[American Film Institute]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/2016/09/01/announcing-south-south-lawn-white-house-festival-ideas-art-and-action|title=Announcing South by South Lawn: A White House Festival of Ideas, Art, and Action|date=1 September 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Austin}}\n{{Music venues of Texas}}\n\n[[Category:Conferences in the United States]]\n[[Category:Film festivals in Austin, Texas]]\n[[Category:Annual events in Texas]]\n[[Category:Music festivals in Texas]]\n[[Category:March events]]\n[[Category:Music conferences]]\n[[Category:Electronic music festivals in the United States]]\n[[Category:Rock festivals in the United States]]\n[[Category:Computer conferences]]\n[[Category:Technology conferences]]\n[[Category:Music festivals established in 1987]]\n[[Category:Film festivals established in 1987]]\n[[Category:1987 establishments in Texas]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the annual festival}}\n{{short description|Annual festival held in Austin}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox recurring event\n| name = South by Southwest\n| image = SxSW logo.png\n| caption = The official logo for SXSW, 2017\n| location = [[Austin, Texas]], U.S.\n| years_active = {{age|1987|3|10}}\n| first = 1987\n| founders = Roland Swenson, Louis Jay Meyers, Louis Black, Nick Barbaro\n| dates = March (dates vary but generally coinciding with [[University of Texas at Austin]] [[spring break]] and also usually includes [[St. Patrick's Day]])\n| frequency = Annual\n| next = March 12th \u2013 March 20th, 2021\n| attendance = {{ubl|SXSW Music: 28,119|SXSW Interactive: 30,621|SXSW Film: 16,297|SXSW EDU: 4,260|Other Exhibits/Parties: 152,000}}\n| genre = [[Conference]] and [[festival]]\n| budget =\n| patron =\n| organized = SXSW, LLC\n| website = {{url|sxsw.com}}\n}}\n\n'''South by Southwest''' (stylized as '''SXSW''' and colloquially referred to as '''South By''') is an annual conglomeration of parallel film, [[interactive media]], and [[music festival]]s and [[Convention (meeting)|conferences]] organized jointly that take place in mid-March in [[Austin, Texas]], [[United States]]. It began in 1987 and has continued to grow in both scope and size every year. In 2017, the conference lasted for 10 days with the interactive track lasting for five days, music for seven days, and film for nine days.\n\nSXSW is run by the company SXSW, LLC, which organizes conferences, trade shows, festivals, and other events.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sxswedu.com/about/history |title=Sxsw Inc |publisher=Sxswedu.com |date= |accessdate=March 25, 2014}}</ref> In addition to the three main South by Southwest festivals, the company runs other conferences: [[Sxswedu.com|SXSW EDU]], a conference on educational innovation, held in Austin,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sxswedu.com/about |title=About SXSW EDU |publisher=Sxswedu.com |date= |accessdate=April 15, 2013}}</ref> and the [[Me-convention.com|me Convention]] (Started in 2017), held in [[Frankfurt]], Germany and in Stockholm, Sweden, in collaboration with [[Mercedes-Benz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://media.daimler.com/marsMediaSite/en/instance/ko/South-by-Southwest-SXSW-to-collaborate-with-Mercedes-Benz-at-IAA-International-Motor-Show-in-Frankfurt-Premiere-at-IAA-International-me-Convention.xhtml?oid=16074145|title=South by Southwest (SXSW) to collaborate with Mercedes-Benz at IAA International Motor Show in Frankfurt: Premiere at IAA: International me Convention|last=Schultz|first=Ina|date=March 11, 2017|website=media.daimler.com|language=en-EN|access-date=2017-08-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sxsw.com/news/2017/sxsw-joins-mercedes-benz-host-future-focused-convention-frankfurt/|title=SXSW and Mercedes-Benz Announce Initial Programming for Collaborative Future-Focused Event in Europe|last=Roberts|first=Jordan|date=2017-06-14|work=SXSW|access-date=2017-08-23|language=English}}</ref> Former conferences run by the SXSW organization include SXSW Eco, a conference focusing on social and environmental issues through the lens of technology, creativity and design held in Austin from 2011 to 2016;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sxsweco.com/about |title=About SXSW Eco |publisher=Sxsweco.com |date= |accessdate=April 15, 2013}}</ref> and another in Las Vegas: [[SXSW V2V]], a conference focused on innovative [[startup company|startups]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.statesman.com/news/technology/sxsw-interactive-expanding-next-year-with-las-vega/nSmFZ/ |title= SXSW Interactive expanding next year with Las Vegas startup conference|last=Gallaga|first=Omar L.|newspaper=Austin American-Statesman |date=October 23, 2012 |accessdate=August 8, 2013}}</ref> which ran from 2013 to 2015. Previously, SXSW produced music festivals North by Northwest (NXNW) in Portland, Oregon, [[North by Northeast]] (NXNE) in Toronto, and West by Southwest (WXSW) in Tucson, Arizona.\n\nFor the first time, the 2020 event was cancelled as a result of local health concerns about the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/6/21162247/sxsw-2020-cancelled-coronavirus-austin-texas-virus-fears-public-health-event|title=SXSW 2020 canceled due to coronavirus|last=Statt|first=Nick|date=2020-03-06|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kvue.com/article/entertainment/events/sxsw/sxsw-austin-2020-cancelled-petition-coronavirus/269-3423a862-7cd7-49be-8125-41d84b8c6a13|title=SXSW canceled: Austin officials end 2020 festival amid coronavirus concerns|website=KVUE|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n==Divisions==\n[[File:Sixth Street SXSW 2013-025426539592444897.jpg|thumb|A view of [[Sixth Street (Austin, Texas)|6th Street]] in downtown Austin, Texas, during SXSW 2013]]\n\n=== Music ===\nSXSW Music is the largest [[music festival]] of its kind in the world, with more than 2,000 acts as of 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title = SXSW 2015: The festival changes, but for the better?|url = https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-sxsw-music-wrap-20150323-story.html|website = latimes.com|accessdate = 2015-11-16|date = 2015-03-23}}</ref> SXSW Music offers artist-provided music and video samples of featured artists at each festival via their official YouTube channel.<ref>{{cite web |last=Birney |first=Adrienne |authorlink= |title=SXSW Technical Coordinator |publisher= |date= |url=http://sxsw.com/ |doi= |accessdate=November 28, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sites.sxsw.com/|title=The Official SXSW site|publisher=Sites.sxsw.com|accessdate=2015-08-13}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe music event has grown from 700 registrants in 1987, the first year of the conference, to over 161,000 attendees in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.cnn.com/2013/09/13/us/south-by-southwest-fast-facts/index.html |work = CNN |title = South by Southwest Fast Facts |date = September 13, 2013 }}</ref> SXSW Film and SXSW Interactive events have grown every year, bringing over 32,000 registrants to Austin in March 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sxsw.com/about/history |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813151035/http://sxsw.com/about/history |archivedate=2011-08-13 |title=About SXSW |accessdate=March 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\nBands must cover their own expenses for travel and lodging at the event. All performers are offered a cash payment or a wristband package that allows access to all music events.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/zackomalleygreenburg/2013/03/18/why-most-acts-dont-get-paid-at-south-by-southwest/ |title=Why Most Acts Don't Get Paid At South By Southwest |magazine=Forbes |date=March 18, 2013 |accessdate=March 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Film ===\nSXSW Film Conference spans five days of conference panels and sessions, and welcomes filmmakers of all levels. Programming consists of keynote speakers, panels, workshops, mentor sessions and more, with expert filmmakers and industry leaders.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sxsw.com/film/history |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150404164219/http://sxsw.com/film/history |archivedate=2015-04-04 |title= History |publisher= SXSW.com |date= |accessdate=2015-04-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the SXSW Film Conference programmed over 250 sessions with 735 speakers. Past speakers include [[Jon Favreau]], [[Mark Duplass]], [[Ava DuVernay]], [[Ryan Gosling]], [[Nicolas Cage]], [[Alejandro Jodorowsky]], [[Tilda Swinton]], [[Amy Schumer]], [[Sally Field]], [[Joss Whedon]], [[Christine Vachon]], [[RZA]], [[Matthew McConaughey]], [[Danny Boyle]], [[Seth MacFarlane]], [[Catherine Hardwicke]], [[Richard Linklater]], [[David Gordon Green]], [[Harmony Korine]], [[Henry Rollins]], [[Sarah Green (film producer)|Sarah Green]] and [[Robert Rodriguez]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sxsw.com/film/conference/past-speakers |title=SXSW LLC. |publisher=sxsw.com |date= |accessdate=July 14, 2015}}</ref>\nAlthough the film festival often highlights independently produced films and emerging directing talent with unique visions,<ref>{{cite web |last=Peters |first=Yves |title=''Man & Gun'' and ''Les Bleus de Ramville'' Win SXSW Film Design Awards|url=http://fontfeed.com/archives/man-film-design-awards/ |publisher=The Font Feed |accessdate=January 11, 2013 |date=March 31, 2012}}</ref> the festival has long served studios as a starting point for their comedies, using enthusiastic fans as a barometer of how they might play in wide release.<ref name=\"Murphy\">{{cite news |last=Murphy |first=Mekado |title=SXSW 2015: Films That Were the Talk of the Festival |url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/03/19/sxsw-2015-films-that-were-the-talk-of-the-festival/ |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=July 11, 2015 |date=March 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe SXSW Film Festival runs nine days, simultaneously with the SXSW Film Conference, and celebrates raw innovation and emerging talent both behind and in front of the camera.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sxsw.com/film/about |title=SXSW LLC. |publisher=sxsw.com |date= |accessdate=July 14, 2015}}</ref> Festival programming categories include: Special Events, Headliners, Narrative Spotlight, Documentary Spotlight, Narrative Competition, Documentary Competition, Visions, Midnighters, 24 Beats Per Second, SXGlobal, Episodic, Festival Favorites, and Short Film Programs. The SXSW Film Awards, which occur on the last day of the Film Conference, honor films selected by the Feature and Short Film Juries.\n\nIn 2015, the SXSW Film Festival programmed 150 feature films and 106 short films, selected from 7,361 submissions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sxsw.com/sites/default/files/attachments/SXSW-FILM-FESTIVAL-ANNOUNCES-2015%20COMPLETE-CONFERENCE-LINEUP-AND-ADDITIONAL-FESTIVAL-TITLES-IMMEDIATE.pdf |title=SXSW LLC. |publisher=sxsw.com |accessdate=July 14, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924112924/http://www.sxsw.com/sites/default/files/attachments/SXSW-FILM-FESTIVAL-ANNOUNCES-2015%20COMPLETE-CONFERENCE-LINEUP-AND-ADDITIONAL-FESTIVAL-TITLES-IMMEDIATE.pdf |archivedate=September 24, 2015 }}</ref> Past notable world premieres include ''[[Furious 7]]'', ''[[Neighbors (2014 film)|Neighbors]]'', ''[[Chef (2014 film)|Chef]]'', ''[[21 Jump Street (film)|21 Jump Street]]'', ''[[The Cabin in the Woods]]'', ''[[Bridesmaids (2011 film)|Bridesmaids]]'' and ''[[Insidious (film)|Insidious]]'', and the TV series ''[[Girls (TV series)|Girls]]'', ''[[Silicon Valley (TV series)|Silicon Valley]]'' and ''[[Penny Dreadful (TV series)|Penny Dreadful]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sxsw.com/film/screenings/past-films |title=Past Films at SXSW &#124; South by Southwest 2016 Music, Film and Interactive Festivals \u2013 Austin Texas |publisher=Sxsw.com |accessdate=2015-08-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150609232442/http://www.sxsw.com/film/screenings/past-films |archivedate=2015-06-09 }}</ref>\n\n=== Interactive ===\nSXSW Interactive is focused on emerging technology.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sxsw.com/interactive/about |title=Interactive News &#124; SXSW 2013 |publisher=Sxsw.com |date= |accessdate=April 15, 2013}}</ref> The festival includes a trade show, speakers, parties, and a startup accelerator.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sxsw.com/interactive/accelerator |title=March 8\u20139: SXSW Accelerator Presented by Oracle Helps Uncover Amazing New Startups &#124; SXSW 2014 |publisher=Sxsw.com |date=November 10, 2013 |accessdate=March 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:SXSW2020CommunityMeetupWeWorkTheHub.jpg|thumb|SXSW employee giving an introduction of the event at a community meetup.]]\n\n===Inauguration \u2013 1980s===\nIn July 1986, the organizers of the [[New York City]] music festival [[New Music Seminar]] contacted Roland Swenson, a staffer at the [[alternative weekly]] ''[[The Austin Chronicle]]'', talked about organizing an extension of that festival into Austin, thereafter announced they were going to hold a \"New Music Seminar Southwest\".<ref>{{cite web|author=van Arts Labor |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iH02tbDy_6M&t=1m19s&list=UUgk1rvr62MBcRrTBgI4oEUg |title=SXSW documentary 'Outside Industry' |publisher=Youtube.com |date=February 28, 2014 |accessdate=March 25, 2014}}</ref> The plans did not materialize, so Swenson decided to instead co-organize a local music festival, with the help of two other people at the ''Chronicle'': editor and co-founder Louis Black, and publisher Nick Barbaro. Louis Meyers, a [[booking agent]] and musician, was also brought on board.<ref>[http://www.lib.utexas.edu/taro/utcah/01476/cah-01476.html A Guide to the South By Southwest, Inc., Records, 1987\u20131997], Briscoe Center for American History, The University of Texas at Austin</ref> Black came up with the name, as a play on the name of the [[Alfred Hitchcock]] film ''[[North by Northwest]]''. While Southwest by South is an actual [[Points of the compass|point on a compass]], South by Southwest is not (SWbS is a heading of 213.75 degrees).\n\nThe event was first held in March 1987. The organizers considered it a regional event and expected around 150 attendees to show up, but over 700 came, and according to Black \"it was national almost immediately.\"<ref name=\"sxsw stays course\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20110311034107/http://www.dailytexanonline.com/content/sxsw-stays-course-continues-growth SXSW stays course, continues growth], Alex Geiser, ''[[The Daily Texan]]'', March 18, 2010</ref> Meyers left Austin and the festival in the early 1990s, but Black, Barbaro and Swenson remained the festival's key organizers as of 2010.<ref name=\"sxsw stays course\" />\n\n===1990s===\nSinger-songwriter [[Michelle Shocked]] was the keynote speaker at the 1992 South by Southwest. She caused controversy by delivering a speech, written by her then-husband [[Bart Bull]], criticizing white musicians for stealing music from [[African American]] artists; and then later during the same conference when she tried to kick the band [[Two Nice Girls]] off of a benefit concert, a move that some called anti-gay, due to Two Nice Girls' overtly [[lesbian]] image.<ref>[http://www.dallasobserver.com/1996-04-25/music/the-education-of-michelle-shocked/ The Education of Michelle Shocked], Robert Wilonsky, ''[[Dallas Observer]]'', April 25, 1996</ref>\n\nIn 1993, SXSW moved into the [[Austin Convention Center]], where it is still held.<ref>[http://sxsw.com/node/5521] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322004257/http://sxsw.com/node/5521|date=March 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, SXSW added a component for film and other media, named the \"SXSW Film and Multimedia Conference\".<ref name=\"sxsw stays course\" /> [[Johnny Cash]] was the keynote speaker.<ref name=\"Cohen2012\">{{cite news|last1=Cohen|first1=Jason|title=SXSW: The Ten Best Music Keynote Speakers|url=http://www.texasmonthly.com/story/sxsw-ten-best-music-keynote-speakers|accessdate=13 June 2014|work=[[Texas Monthly]]|publisher=Emmis Publishing, L.P.|date=15 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nThat year, the three brothers of the band [[Hanson (band)|Hanson]] were brought to SXSW by their father in order to perform impromptu auditions for music executives, in the hopes of getting industry attention. Among the people who heard them was A&R executive [[Christopher Sabec]], who became their manager, and would soon afterward get them signed to [[Mercury Records]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oklahomatoday.com/Site/pdf/1997Hanson.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101104185941/http://www.oklahomatoday.com/Site/pdf/1997Hanson.pdf |archivedate=2010-11-04 |title= 1997 Oklahoman of the Year |publisher= Oklahoma Today |date= |accessdate=4 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, the SXSW Film and Multimedia Conference was split into two separate events, \"SXSW Film\" and \"SXSW Multimedia\".<ref name=\"sxsw stays course\" /> In 1999, SXSW Multimedia was renamed \"SXSW Interactive\".<ref name=\"sxsw stays course\" />\n\n===2000s===\nSinger-songwriter [[John Mayer]]'s performance at the 2000 SXSW Music festival led to his signing soon thereafter with [[Aware Records]], his first [[record label]].\n\nA performance by the band [[The Polyphonic Spree]] at the 2002 SXSW Music festival helped bring them to national attention before they had signed with a major label.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/1471511/20030424/polyphonic_spree.jhtml|title=Polyphonic Spree: From Voices In A Singer's Head To Voices On The Stage - News - VH1.com|date=19 October 2011|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111019215642/http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/1471511/20030424/polyphonic_spree.jhtml|archivedate=19 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2002 SXSW Film Festival, the film ''[[Manito (film)|Manito]]'' won the jury award for narrative feature, while the documentary ''[[Spellbound (2002 film)|Spellbound]]'' won the jury award for documentary feature.\n\nBritish singer [[James Blunt]] was discovered by producer [[Linda Perry]] while playing a small show at the 2004 SXSW Music festival, and was signed to Perry's [[Custard Records]] soon thereafter,<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Miller |first=Nancy |url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1174154,00.html |title=Five rounds with James Blunt |magazine=EW.com |date=2006-03-17 |accessdate=2015-08-13}}</ref> where he would go on to release all three of his subsequent albums.\n\nThe 2005 SXSW Film is considered by some to be the origin of the [[mumblecore]] film genre. A number of films now classified as mumblecore, including ''[[The Puffy Chair]]'', ''[[Kissing on the Mouth]]'', ''[[Four Eyed Monsters]]'' and ''[[Mutual Appreciation]]'', were screened, and [[Eric Masunaga]], a musician and the [[audio engineering|sound editor]] on ''Mutual Appreciation'', is credited with coining the term \"mumblecore\" at a bar while at the festival.<ref>Lim, Dennis (August 19, 2007). \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/19/movies/19lim.html?8dpc Mumblecore \u2013 The New Talkies: Generation DIY]\". ''[[The New York Times]]''.</ref>\n\nThe film ''[[Hooligans (film)|Hooligans]]'' won both the Feature Film Jury Award and the Feature Film Audience Award for narrative feature, while ''The Puffy Chair'' won the Feature Film Audience Award in the \"Emerging Visions\" category. The documentary film ''[[Cowboy del Amor]]'' won the SXSW Competition Award and the Audience Award.\n\nA secret concert at the 2006 SXSW Music by the band [[The Flaming Lips]] was called one of the \"Top 10 Music-Festival Moments\" of all time by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine in 2010.<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1885895_1885893_1885860,00.html Top 10 Music-Festival Moments: Flaming Lips at SXSW \u2013 2006], Dan Fletcher, ''Time'', March 18, 2010</ref>\n\nThe 2006 SXSW Interactive featured a keynote panel of Wikipedia co-founder [[Jimmy Wales]] and [[Craigslist]] founder [[Craig Newmark]].<ref>[http://www.auscillate.com/post/95 SXSW 2006 Panel: Craig Newmark & Jimmy Wales Keynote], ''Auscillate'' blog, March 13, 2006</ref>\n\nThat year, \"Screenburn at SXSW\", a component for [[video game]]s, was added to SXSW Interactive.<ref name=\"sxsw stays course\" />\n\n==== 2007 ====\nThe 2007 music festival took place from March 14 to 18, and more than 1,400 acts performed.\n\nTwo of the top film premieres that year were ''[[Elvis and Anabelle]]'' and ''[[Skills Like This]]''.\n\nThe [[social media]] platform [[Twitter]] notably gained a good deal of early traction and buzz at the 2007 SXSW Interactive,{{better source|date=August 2019}} though it did not launch at SXSW 2007 as is sometimes reported.<ref name=\"sxsw stays course\" />\n\n==== 2008 ====\nThe 2008 SXSW Interactive got media attention due to a keynote interview of [[Facebook]] CEO [[Mark Zuckerberg]] by technology journalist [[Sarah Lacy]] that was considered by some observers to be a \"train wreck\" due to an audience perception that Lacy was asking uninteresting questions, as well as mocking or terse answers in response from Zuckerberg.<ref>[http://news.cnet.com/8301-13772_3-9889528-52.html A journalist becomes the story at Mark Zuckerberg SXSWi keynote], Daniel Terdiman, ''CNET'' \"Geek Gestalt\" blog, March 9, 2008</ref>\n\nIn 2008, a comedy element was added to SXSW; it was held for one night. (By 2012, comedy performances occurred on all nights of the festival.)<ref>{{cite web |title=Messin' with Texas: Why Doesn't SXSW Pay its Comedians? |url=http://splitsider.com/2012/01/messin-with-texas-why-doesnt-sxsw-pay-its-comedians/ |publisher=[[Splitsider]] |first=Richard |last=Morgan |date=January 23, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==== 2009 ====\nThe 2009 festival was held March 13\u201322. The Interactive section of SXSW in particular drew larger attendance levels; the influx strained the networks of providers such as [[AT&T]] (primarily due to heavy [[iPhone]] usage).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blog.wired.com/business/2009/03/sxsw-atts-spott.html |title=SXSW: IPhone Influx Pushes AT&T to the Limit |work=Epicenter (blog.wired.com) |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast Publications|Conde Nast]] |date=March 14, 2009 |first=Michael |last=Calore}}</ref> Also new was the founding of an international organization for those not attending, dubbed NotAtSXSW. Coordinating through [[Twitter]] and other online tools, notatsxsw events were held in London, New York, Wisconsin, Portland, Oregon and Miami.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2009/mar/18/notatsxsw-festival-twitter |title= Can't make it to SXSW this year? Go to #notatsxsw instead |date=March 18, 2009 |work=[[The Guardian]] | location=London | accessdate=May 23, 2010 | first=Ruth | last=Jamieson}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Foursquare-logo.png|thumb|The mobile app, Foursquare, was launched at SXSW 2009.]]\nThe 2009 SXSW Interactive saw the launch of the [[Foursquare (social network)|Foursquare]] application, which was called \"the breakout [[mobile app]]\" of the event by the ''[[Mashable]]'' blog.<ref>{{cite web|last=Van |first=Jennifer |url=http://mashable.com/2009/03/16/foursquare/ |title=Foursquare is the Breakout Mobile App at SXSW |publisher=Mashable.com |date=2009-03-16 |accessdate=2015-08-13}}</ref>\n\n2009 also saw the first Indian classical music artists perform at SXSW. Canadians [[Cassius Khan]], a renowned tabla player and singer performed with [[Amika Kushwaha]] on harmonium and were featured Canadians on CBC Canada's most favorite list.\n\nThe 2009 SXSW Film screened 250 films, including 54 world premieres. The event was notable for having the United States premiere of the film ''[[The Hurt Locker]]'', which went on to win the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]] in 2010.<ref name=\"sxsw stays course\" /> The winners of the feature jury awards were, for documentary feature, ''[[45365]]'', and for narrative feature, ''[[Made in China (2009 film)|Made in China]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiewire.com/article/made_in_china_and_45365_take_top_sxsw_jury_prizes/ |title=\"Made in China\" and \"45365\" Take Top SXSW Jury Prizes |work=Indiewire |date=March 18, 2009 |accessdate=February 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===2010s===\n====2010====\nThe 2010 music festival, which took place March 12\u201321, was dedicated to [[Alex Chilton]], who died shortly before he was to perform with [[Big Star]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/big-star-singer-and-cult-icon-alex-chilton-dead-at-59-20100317|title=Big Star Singer and Cult Icon Alex Chilton Dead at 59|date=March 17, 2010|accessdate=September 24, 2014}}</ref> A tribute concert was performed in his honor on March 20, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sxsw.tewspaper.com/at-the-big-star-tribute-to-alex-chilton-sxsw-32010|title=SXSW Tribute Concert for Alex Chilton|date=March 20, 2010|accessdate=March 24, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716212414/http://sxsw.tewspaper.com/at-the-big-star-tribute-to-alex-chilton-sxsw-32010|archivedate=July 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2010 festival, nearly 2,000 bands were officially scheduled to perform,<ref name=\"SXSW 2010 Draws to a Close\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnewyork.com/entertainment/music/SXSW-2010-Draws-to-a-Close-88819997.html|title=SXSW 2010 Draws to a Close|publisher=nbcnewyork.com|date=March 22, 2010 |accessdate=April 8, 2010}}</ref> and festival reps estimated that over 13,000 industry representatives attended.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyfinance.com/story/media/scenes-from-the-geekfest-at-sxsw-interactive/19398388|title=Scenes From the Geekfest at SXSW|publisher=DailyFinance.com |date=March 14, 2010 |accessdate=April 8, 2010}}</ref> Though traditionally the Austin Music Awards kick off the festival, that year organizers slated it as the closing act. Local musician [[Bob Schneider]] earned 6 awards, including Song of the Year, Singer of the Year, and Band of the Year (with [[Lonelyland]].)<ref name=\"SXSW 2010 Draws to a Close\" /> The 2010 festival was also notable for appearances by the surviving members of the band [[Moby Grape]].<ref>Raul Hernandez, [http://www.austinchronicle.com/gyrobase/Issue/review?oid=oid%3A985722 Live Shots: SXSW Music 2010], [[Austin Chronicle]], March 26, 2010.</ref>\n\nAt the 2010 Film festival, [[Magnolia Pictures]] bought the film rights to the science-fiction film ''[[Monsters (2010 film)|Monsters]]'' on the night it screened, in what was the first-ever \"overnight acquisition\" at SXSW. Journalist Meredith Melnick of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine called this purchase a turning point for SXSW, leading to a greater interest among film studio executives in attending the festival in person.<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,2062263,00.html Art of the Film Deal: Is South by Southwest Becoming the New Sundance?], Meredith Melnick, ''Time'', April 1, 2011</ref> That year also saw the premiere of the indie favorite ''[[Tiny Furniture]]'', which won the award for Best Narrative Feature.\n\nThe 2010 Interactive festival had an estimated 12\u201313,000 paying attendees, which represented a 40% jump over the previous year.<ref name=\"interactive surpasses music\">[http://www.austin360.com/blogs/content/shared-gen/blogs/austin/digitalsavant/entries/2010/03/17/confirmed_sxsw.html Confirmed: SXSW Interactive paid registration surpasses Music], Omar L. Gallaga, ''Austin360.com'', March 17, 2010</ref> This was the first year in which the interactive festival's attendance surpassed the music festival's.<ref name=\"interactive surpasses music\" /> The keynote presentation was an interview of then-Twitter CEO [[Evan Williams (Internet entrepreneur)|Evan Williams]] by Umair Haque, an interview that many in the audience found disappointingly superficial.<ref>[http://www.statesman.com/business/sxsw-organizers-concede-keynote-flubs-with-twitter-q-374628.html SXSW organizers concede keynote flubs with Twitter Q&A], Omar L. Gallaga, ''Austin American-Statesman'', March 16, 2010</ref> Also during the interactive festival, the first-ever (and so far only) \"Hive Awards For the Unsung Heroes of the Internet\" were held.\n\n====2011====\n[[File:Conan O'Brien - SXSW - Mar 2011.jpg|thumb|[[Conan O'Brien]] promoting ''[[Conan O'Brien Can't Stop]]'' at SXSW 2011]]\nThe 2011 SXSW festival ran from March 11 to 20.\n\nThe keynote presenter for SXSW Interactive was [[Seth Priebatsch]], founder and CEO of the mobile-gaming platform [[SCVNGR]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/8301-14013_1-20042504-284.html|title=SCVNGR at SXSW\u2014high-flying, or head in the clouds?|date=March 12, 2011|accessdate=March 12, 2011}}</ref> The 2011 Interactive festival was by far the largest it had ever been, with an estimated 20,000 attendees.<ref name=\"where the geeks are\">[http://www.dailyfinance.com/story/where-the-geeks-are-dispatches-from-the-largest-sxsw-interactiv/19880235/ Where the Geeks Are: Dispatches From the Largest SXSW Interactive Ever], L. A. Lorek, ''Daily Finance'', March 15, 2011</ref>\n\nAlso in attendance at SXSW was boxing legend [[Mike Tyson]], promoting his new iPhone game with [[RockLive]] at the Screenburn Arcade.<ref>{{cite web|last=McCarthy |first=Caroline |url=https://www.cnet.com/8301-14013_1-20042682-284.html |title=Mike Tyson wants to be an iPhone knockout &#124; SXSW \u2013 CNET Blogs |publisher=Cnet.com |date=March 13, 2011 |accessdate=April 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAt least two films screened at the SXSW Film festival gained distribution deals: the documentary ''[[Undefeated (2011 film)|Undefeated]]'' (which went on to win the [[Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature]]) and the thriller ''[[The Divide (2011 film)|The Divide]]''. As a result, film critic Christopher Kelly wrote that in 2011, SXSW Film went from being \"a well-regarded but fundamentally regional event\" to having \"joined the big leagues of film festivals around the world.\"<ref>[http://www.dfw.com/2011/03/17/424689/commentary-south-by-southwest.html Commentary: South by Southwest is in danger of losing its indie film cred] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315165235/http://www.dfw.com/2011/03/17/424689/commentary-south-by-southwest.html |date=2012-03-15 }}, Christopher Kelly, DFW.com, March 17, 2011</ref> That festival was also notable for having the premiere of the film ''[[Bridesmaids (2011 film)|Bridesmaids]]''.<ref name=\"bridesmaids bouquet\">[http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/movies/2012/03/sxsw-2012-21-jump-street-cabin-in-the-woods-aspire-to-bridesmaids-style-success-.html SXSW: '21 Jump St.,' 'Cabin in the Woods' eye 'Bridesmaids' bouquet], Mark Olsen, ''24 Frames'' (''Los Angeles Times'' blog), March 8, 2012</ref>\n\nThe March 15th screening of the [[Foo Fighters]] documentary ''[[Back and Forth (documentary)|Back and Forth]]'' was followed by a surprise live performance by the band itself, with a setlist that included the entirety of the then-upcoming album ''[[Wasting Light]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.vh1.com/2011-03-16/foo-fighters-documentary-premiere-followed-by-surprise-show/|title=Foo Fighters Documentary Premiere Followed By Surprise Show|work=VH1 Blog Reality TV News and Gossip|access-date=2011-12-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208075146/http://blog.vh1.com/2011-03-16/foo-fighters-documentary-premiere-followed-by-surprise-show|archive-date=2012-02-08|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====2012====\nSXSW 2012 ran from March 9 to 18.\n\nThe standout technology of the 2012 SXSW Interactive was generally stated to be \"[[social discovery platform|social discovery]]\" mobile apps, which let users locate other nearby users. Social discovery apps that had a presence at SXSW included [[Highlight (application)|Highlight]], Glancee, Sonar and Kismet.<ref>[http://news.cnet.com/8301-1035_3-57393877-94/hottest-new-apps-out-of-sxsw-2012/ Hottest new apps out of SXSW 2012], Jaymar Cabebe and Jason Parker, ''CNET'', March 12, 2012</ref><ref>[http://content.usatoday.com/communities/livefrom/post/2012/03/sxsw-2012-the-highlight-of-the-festival/1#.T8SqJUWmgrU SXSW 2012: The 'Highlight' of the festival], Jon Swartz, ''USA Today'', March 13, 2012</ref>\n\nSXSW Film saw the premiere of two major Hollywood films: ''[[The Cabin in the Woods]]''<ref>[http://www.statesman.com/news/texas/in-shadows-of-hype-dialogue-of-too-much-2235412.html In shadows of hype, dialogue of 'too much' at SXSW], Jake Coyle, ''The Associated Press\" March 13, 2012 {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> and ''[[21 Jump Street (film)|21 Jump Street]]''.<ref name=\"bridesmaids bouquet\" /> Two films obtained distribution deals: ''[[Girls Against Boys (film)|Girls Against Boys]]'' and ''[[The Tall Man (2012 film)|The Tall Man]]''.<ref>[http://thefilmstage.com/news/sxsw-features-girls-against-boys-and-the-tall-man-picked-up-for-distribution-barrymore-to-finally-see-light-of-day/ SXSW Features \u2018Girls Against Boys\u2019 and \u2018The Tall Man\u2019 Picked Up For Distribution; \u2018Barrymore\u2019 To Finally See Light Of Day], Amanda Waltz, ''The Film Stage'', March 13, 2012</ref> Another film, ''[[Gimme the Loot (film)|Gimme the Loot]]'', which won the SXSW Narrative Feature Grand Jury Prize, got a distribution deal a week after the festival.<ref>[http://insidemovies.ew.com/2012/03/19/sxsw-gimme-the-loot-adam-leon-sundance-select/ SXSW: 'Gimme the Loot' director Adam Leon on winning big, landing distribution deal], Karen Valby, ''Entertainment Weekly: Inside Movies'', March 19, 2012</ref> ''[[Bay of All Saints (film)|Bay of All Saints]]'' received the Audience Award for Best Feature Documentary.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/bay-all-saints-sxsw-film-review-301724|title=Bay of All Saints: SXSW Review|author=John DeFore|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=March 19, 2012}}</ref>\n\n2012 was also the first year the music portion was expanded to Tuesday. The musical festival included rappers such as [[Talib Kweli]] and [[Lil' Wayne]], along with surprise appearances by [[Big Sean]] and [[Kanye West]]; indie bands that appeared included [[MENEW]] and [[The Shins]]. [[Bruce Springsteen]] was the keynote speaker for the music festival.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/events/sxsw/501218/bruce-springsteens-sxsw-keynote-stay-hard-stay-hungry |title=Bruce Springsteen's SXSW Keynote: 'Stay Hard, Stay Hungry' |magazine=Billboard |date=March 15, 2012 |accessdate=April 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\n====2013====\nSXSW 2013 ran from March 8 to 17.\n\nThe big-budget films ''[[The Incredible Burt Wonderstone]]'' and ''[[Evil Dead (2013 film)|Evil Dead]]'' premiered at the 2013 SXSW Film, and ''[[Spring Breakers]]'' had its U.S. premiere.<ref>[http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/sxsw-2013-brings-burt-wonderstone-spring-breakers-evil-dead-drinking-buddies-more-to-austin-20130115 SXSW 2013 Brings 'Burt Wonderstone,' Spring Breakers,' 'Evil Dead,' 'Drinking Buddies' & More To Austin], Kevin Jagernauth, ''Indiewire'', January 15, 2013</ref> The film ''[[Short Term 12]]'' won the grand jury award for Best Narrative Feature. The films ''[[Awful Nice]]'', ''[[Cheap Thrills (film)|Cheap Thrills]]'', and ''[[Haunter (film)|Haunter]]'' received distribution deals,<ref>{{cite news |title=SXSW 2013: 'Short Term 12' wins feature prize |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/moviesnow/la-et-mn-sxsw-wrapup-20130313,0,1786750.story |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=March 12, 2013 |first=Mark |last=Olsen}}</ref> and ''[[Drinking Buddies]]'' obtained a distribution deal several days later.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Magnolia Acquires SXSW Pic 'Drinking Buddies' |url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/03/drinking-buddies-magnolia-pictures-acquired-sxsw-joe-swanberg/ |date=March 19, 2013 |first=Jen |last=Yamato |magazine=Deadline}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title=Todd Sklar's 'Awful Nice' Gets U.S. Distribution |url=https://variety.com/2013/film/news/todd-sklars-awful-nice-gets-u-s-distribution-1200560667/ |magazine=Variety}}</ref>\n\nThe 2013 SXSW Interactive saw another huge jump in registration, now with 30,621 paying attendees.<ref>Nicole Villalpando, [http://www.statesman.com/news/events/biggest-interactive-yet-as-sxsw-begins-music-hands/nWqPc/ \"Biggest Interactive yet as SXSW begins Music, hands out Film Awards\"], ''Austin American Statesman'', March 12, 2013. Retrieved on March 13, 2013</ref> This was over three times the number that had attended in 2008 (9,000), just five years previously.<ref>[http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/2008-sxsw-interactive-festival-wraps-up-strong-year-57369557.html 2008 SXSW Interactive Festival Wraps Up Strong Year], ''PRNewswire'', March 31, 2008</ref> The keynote talk for the 2013 SXSW Interactive was given by [[SpaceX]] CEO [[Elon Musk]].<ref name=\"brought to you by\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/innovations/post/sxsw-2013-this-revolution-is-brought-to-you-by/2013/03/11/b47dfa10-8a95-11e2-8d72-dc76641cb8d4_blog.html SXSW 2013: This revolution is brought to you by...], Hamdan Azhar, ''Washington Post'' ideas@innovations blog, March 11, 2013</ref> The \"Screenburn\" and \"Arcade\" components were renamed to \"SXSW Gaming\" and \"SXSW Gaming Expo\", respectively.<ref>[http://iqu.com/blog/south-by-southwest-interactive-video-games SXSW Interactive: A Growing Outlet For Video Games], Matt Clark, ''iQU', March 14, 2012 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130524055251/http://iqu.com/blog/south-by-southwest-interactive-video-games |date=May 24, 2013 }}</ref> The Interactive conference had an increased corporate presence, featuring major participation by [[Samsung]], [[3M]], [[Target Corporation|Target]], [[American Airlines]], [[Adobe Systems]] and [[AT&T]], among others.<ref name=\"brought to you by\" /><ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/03/11/us-sxsw-startups-idUSBRE92A10I20130311 At South by Southwest, fewer startups, more marketers and media], Gerry Shih, Reuters, March 11, 2013</ref> According to [[CNN]], [[CBS]] and [[CNET]] called [[Grumpy Cat]] the undisputed \"biggest star\" of SXSW Interactive over Musk, [[Al Gore]] and [[Neil Gaiman]].<ref name=\"cnn\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/03/10/tech/web/grumpy-cat-sxsw/index.html |title=The unlikely star of SXSW: Grumpy Cat |publisher=CNN.com |date=November 14, 2011 |accessdate=March 11, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/8301-205_162-57573676/as-sxsw-interactive-winds-down-grumpy-cat-is-clear-winner/ |title=As SXSW Interactive winds down, Grumpy cat is clear winner |publisher=CBS News |date= |accessdate=March 3, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Terdiman |first=Daniel |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-14013_3-57573517/if-grumpy-cat-is-the-biggest-news-of-all-is-sxsw-in-trouble/ |title=If Grumpy Cat is the biggest news of all, is SXSW in trouble? &#124; SXSW \u2013 CNET News |publisher=News.cnet.com |date=January 23, 2013 |accessdate=March 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\n====2014====\nSXSW 2014 ran from March 7 to 16.\n\nSXSW Film had premieres of the big-budget films ''[[Neighbors (2014 film)|Neighbors]]'', ''[[Veronica Mars (film)|Veronica Mars]]'' and ''[[Chef (2014 film)|Chef]]'', and ''[[Cesar Chavez (film)|Cesar Chavez]]'' had its North American premiere.<ref>{{cite news |title=South by Southwest Adds a TV Section |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/31/business/media/south-by-southwest-festival-adds-a-tv-section.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |first=Michael |last=Cieply |date=January 30, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"five movie stories\">{{cite news |title=SXSW 2014: Five movie stories, including 'Chef' and 'Veronica Mars' |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-sxsw-film-festival-reviews-chef-neighbors-veronica-mar-20140310,0,5139256.story |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |first=Oliver |last=Gettell |date=March 10, 2014}}</ref> A clip for the big-budget film ''[[Godzilla (2014 film)|Godzilla]]'' was also screened. The films ''[[Space Station 76]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.socialitelife.com/matt-bomers-space-station-76-lands-a-distribution-deal-at-sxsw-03-2014|title=Matt Bomer's 'Space Station 76\u2032 Lands A Distribution Deal At SXSW \u2013 Socialite Life Socialite Life|work=Socialite Life|access-date=2015-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402103719/http://www.socialitelife.com/matt-bomers-space-station-76-lands-a-distribution-deal-at-sxsw-03-2014|archive-date=2015-04-02|url-status=dead}}</ref> and ''[[Exists (film)|Exists]]'' got distribution deals at the festival,<ref name=\"five movie stories\" /> while ''[[Fort Tilden (film)|Fort Tilden]]'' (which won the Narrative Feature Grand Jury Prize) and ''[[Open Windows (film)|Open Windows]]'' got distribution deals shortly afterward.<ref>{{cite news |title=Elijah Wood-Sasha Grey's South by Southwest Thriller Gets U.S. Distribution |url=http://bostonherald.com/entertainment/movies/movie_news/2014/04/elijah_wood_sasha_greys_south_by_southwest_thriller_gets_us | newspaper=Boston Herald |date=April 1, 2014 |first=Dave |last=McNary}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/fort-tilden-distribution-sxsw-orion-1201455504/ | work=Variety | first=Dave | last=McNary | title=SXSW 2014 Winner 'Fort Tilden' Gets U.S. Distribution From Orion | date=March 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\nA new section, \"Episodic\" (on television programming) was introduced to SXSW Film. Television series that previewed at the festival include ''[[Silicon Valley (TV series)|Silicon Valley]]'' and ''[[From Dusk till Dawn: The Series]]''. The talk show ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'' was taped for a week at the festival; it joined the talk show ''[[Watch What Happens: Live]]'', which began taping at SXSW in 2013.<ref>{{cite web |title=Move over, Jimmy Kimmel: SXSW welcomes back Bravo's Andy Cohen \u2013 and his show |url=http://austin.culturemap.com/news/entertainment/01-20-14-hey-jimmy-kimmel-bravo-tv-host-andy-cohen-sxsw/ |publisher=CultureMap Austin |first=John |last=Egan |date=January 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\nSXSW Interactive featured a keynote speech by [[NSA]] leaker [[Edward Snowden]], via streaming video, about privacy rights. The festival also featured a talk from another famous leaker, [[Julian Assange]], also speaking remotely.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.philly.com/2014-03-12/news/48122662_1_edward-snowden-nsa-leaker-snowden-southwest-interactive |newspaper=[[Philadelphia Inquirer]] |first=Dan |last=DeLuca |date=March 12, 2014 |title=NSA leaker Snowden is the rock star of SXSW Interactive}}</ref> Besides privacy issues, another major focus of the Interactive festival was [[wearable technology]], including devices for [[augmented reality]], [[activity tracker|activity tracking]], identity authentication, charging cell phones and others.<ref>{{cite news |title=5 things we learned at SXSW Interactive|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/03/13/tech/web/sxsw-wrapup/ |publisher=CNN |last1= Gross |first1= Doug | last2 = Griggs| first2 = Brandon |date=March 13, 2014}}</ref> ''[[Computerworld]]'' magazine called the [[Oculus Rift]], a [[virtual reality]] gaming headset, the \"sleeper hit\" of the festival, although it was displayed not at the Interactive but at the Film portion, as part of a ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' exhibit.<ref>{{cite web |title=Oculus Rift is the sleeper hit of SXSW |url=http://blogs.computerworld.com/computer-peripherals/23634/oculus-rift-sleeper-hit-sxsw-itbwgk |magazine=Computerworld |first=Richi |last=Jennings |date=March 10, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316165841/http://blogs.computerworld.com/computer-peripherals/23634/oculus-rift-sleeper-hit-sxsw-itbwgk |archivedate=March 16, 2014 }}</ref> The SXSW Gaming section introduced its [[SXSW Gaming Awards]] to recognize achievement in video and other types of gaming, which has continued through future SXSW festivals.\n\nThe keynote presenter and headline act this year for Stubb's was [[Lady Gaga]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5930106/lady-gaga-to-headline-stubbs-at-sxsw |magazine=[[Billboard.com]] |first=Andrew |last=Hampp |date=March 11, 2014 |title=Lady Gaga to Headline Stubb's at SXSW}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title=Lady Gaga to Present Keynote Address at SXSW |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5930300/lady-gaga-to-present-keynote-address-at-sxsw |magazine=[[Billboard.com]] |first=Rutherford |last=Halperin |date=March 11, 2014}}</ref> To promote her upcoming album, ''[[Food (Kelis album)|Food]]'', [[Kelis]] cooked and served barbecue-style food from a food truck to festival attendees.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/video/2014/mar/14/sxsw-2014-kelis-food-van-austin-texas-video |title=SXSW 2014: Kelis takes her food van to the streets of Austin, Texas \u2013 video |work=The Guardian |date=March 14, 2014 |accessdate=March 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rap-up.com/2014/03/14/kelis-serves-up-jerk-ribs-at-sxsw-food-truck/ |title=Kelis Serves Up Jerk Ribs at SXSW Food Truck |work=[[Rap-Up]] |date=March 14, 2014 |accessdate=March 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, 2014, a drunk driver, Rashad Charjuan Owens, drove his car into a crowd of festival attendees while trying to evade a traffic stop.<ref>{{cite news |title=Man who drove car into SXSW festival was wannabe rapper with six kids |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2014/03/14/man-who-drove-car-into-swsx-festival-was-wannabe-rapper-with-six-kids/?tid=pm_national_pop |newspaper=Washington Post |first=Lindsey |last=Bever |date=March 14, 2014}}</ref> Two people were killed immediately, another two died later from their injuries and another 21 were injured but survived.<ref name=\"4thAP\">{{cite news |title=4th Person Dies After SXSW Car Crash |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/03/27/sxsw-crash-death_n_5044750.html |work=Huffington Post|date=March 27, 2014 |accessdate=March 29, 2014}}</ref> Owens was convicted of [[capital murder]] charges after a November 2015 trial in which eyewitnesses testified that about \"a chaotic and harrowing scene\" on the night, as hundreds of people ran and screamed as the car sped through crowds of people.<ref>Philip Jankowski & Jazmine Ulloa, [http://www.statesman.com/news/news/crime-law/three-new-pieces-of-evidence-in-the-rashad-owens-c/npHXR/ Rashad Owens guilty of capital murder in deadly SXSW crash], ''Austin American-Statesman'' (November 6, 2016).</ref><ref>Philip Jankowski & Jazmine Ulloa, [http://www.statesman.com/news/news/crime-law/follow-the-capital-murder-trial-of-sxsw-crash-susp/npDh4/ Sixteen people, most eyewitnesses, testify in Rashad Owens trial], ''Austin American-Statesman'' (November 2, 2016).</ref> Owens was given an automatic sentence of [[life without parole|life imprisonment without the possibility of parole]].<ref>Ralph Ellis, [http://www.cnn.com/2015/11/06/us/texas-sxsw-crash/ Man who plowed car into SXSW festival crowd given life sentence], CNN (November 6, 2015).</ref>\n\nOn March 15, 2014, rapper [[Tyler, the Creator]] was arrested on [[misdemeanor]] charges of \"[[inciting to riot]]\" after yelling to fans to push their way past security guards at a sold-out show the previous day.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rapper Tyler, The Creator arrested at South By Southwest|url=http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2014/03/16/rapper-tyler-creator-arrested-at-south-by-southwest/ |agency=Associated Press |date=March 16, 2014}}</ref> In February 2016, the riot charges were dropped against Tyler, The Creator pursuant to a [[plea agreement]] with prosecutors (under which the rapper pleaded guilty to the lesser offense of [[disorderly conduct]] and paid a $100 fine, with the case to be dismissed if he stays out of trouble for three months).<ref>Jazmine Ulloa, [http://www.mystatesman.com/news/news/crime-law/prosecutors-drop-riot-charge-against-rapper-tyler-/nqRYL/ As rapper's riot charge is dropped, legal experts question arrest], ''Austin American-Statesman'' (February 17, 2016).</ref>\n\n====2015====\n[[File:Crayon Pop filming at SXSW Austin Texas 2015 --2.jpg|thumb|[[Crayon Pop]] filming \"Can't Stop Crayon Pop\" for [[Funny or Die]] before [[K-Pop Night Out at SXSW]]]]\nSXSW 2015 took place from March 13 to 22.\n\nSXSW Film screened 145 feature films, an all-time high for the festival.<ref>{{cite news|title=SXSW 2015 film lineup adds mainstream appeal|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/feb/03/sxsw-2015-film-lineup-mainstream-appeal|accessdate=February 6, 2015|date=February 3, 2015}}</ref> The big-budget films ''[[Furious 7]]'' (which was a last-minute addition to the lineup),<ref>{{cite magazine|last= Setoodeh|first= Ramin |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/furious-7-premieres-at-sxsw-to-cheers-for-paul-walker-1201453405/ |title='Furious 7' Premieres at SXSW to Cheers for Paul Walker |magazine=Variety |date=2015-03-16 |accessdate=2015-08-13}}</ref> ''[[Get Hard]]'', ''[[Spy (2015 film)|Spy]]'', a rough cut of ''[[Trainwreck (film)|Trainwreck]]'', ''[[Moonwalkers (film)|Moonwalkers]]'' and ''[[The Final Girls]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2015/03/10-most-anticipated-films-at-sxsw-2015/full-post/|title=10 Most Anticipated Films at SXSW 2015|work=Consequence of Sound|date=March 9, 2015}}</ref> had their world premieres, as did the documentaries ''[[Danny Says (film)|Danny Says]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://schedule.sxsw.com/2015/events/event_FS18314|title=Danny Says - SXSW 2015 Event Schedule|website=SXSW Schedule 2015}}</ref> ''Steve Jobs: The Man in the Machine'' and ''[[Brand: A Second Coming]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=SXSW Premieres Include Judd Apatow's 'Trainwreck,' Melissa McCarthy in 'Spy' |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sxsw-premieres-include-judd-apatows-769769 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |first=Seth |last=Abramovitch |date=February 3, 2015}}</ref> ''[[Ex Machina (film)|Ex Machina]]'' had its North American premiere. ''[[6 Years]]'', ''Manson Family Vacation'' and ''Steve Jobs: The Man in the Machine'' all got distribution deals at the festival.<ref>{{cite news |title=SXSW 2015: Films That Were the Talk of the Festival |url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/03/19/sxsw-2015-films-that-were-the-talk-of-the-festival/ |work=The New York Times |first=Mekado |last=Murphy |date=March 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe 2015 festival hosted the swearing-in ceremony of [[Michelle K. Lee]] as the new head of the [[United States Patent and Trademark Office]] (USPTO). [[Secretary of Commerce]] [[Penny Pritzker]] administered the oath of office to Lee at the festival on Friday, March 13.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Schwartz |first1=Eric Hal |title=New Patent Office Director Sworn In by Commerce Secretary at SXSW |url=http://dcinno.streetwise.co/2015/03/13/new-us-patent-chief-sworn-in-at-sxsw/ |accessdate=March 16, 2015 |work=DCInno |publisher=Streetwise Media |date=March 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nVarious sources called [[Meerkat (app)|Meerkat]], an iOS app that had launched two weeks earlier that lets users livestream video via Twitter, the breakout technology of SXSW Interactive.<ref name=\"flying cars\">{{cite news |title=Flying cars, tracking chips: The near future, from SXSW |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2015/03/18/sxsw-flying-cars-tracking-chips-wearables-meerkat/24926781/ |work=USA Today |first=Jefferson |last=Graham |date=March 18, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"2015 5 standout moments\">{{cite web |title=SXSW 2015: 5 Standout Moments in Technology |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Technology/sxsw-2015-standout-moments-technology/story?id=29722900 |work=ABC News |first=Alyssa |last=Newcomb |date=March 18, 2015}}</ref> Another product that got significant buzz was a prototype of the [[roadable aircraft]] [[AeroMobil]].<ref name=\"flying cars\" /><ref name=\"2015 5 standout moments\" />\n\n====2016====\nSXSW 2016 began on March 11 and ended on March 20.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sxsw.com/schedule | title=Schedule | work=SXSW.com | accessdate=13 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, President [[Barack Obama]] gave a speech at SXSW Interactive in which he called on the technology industry to help solve many of America's problems, such as upgrading outdated networks, helping balance security and privacy, and the [[FBI\u2013Apple encryption dispute]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2016/03/11/obama-tech-sxsw-apple-fbi/81628850/ | title=Obama calls on tech industry at SXSW to help solve nation's problems | work=USA Today | date=11 March 2016 | accessdate=13 March 2016 | last=Jervis | first=Rick}}</ref>\n\nFilms that premiered at SXSW Film include ''[[Everybody Wants Some!! (film)|Everybody Wants Some!!]]'', ''[[Keanu (film)|Keanu]]'', ''[[Sausage Party]]'', ''[[Pee-wee's Big Holiday]]'' and ''[[Don't Think Twice (film)|Don't Think Twice]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=The 16 Buzziest Movies at SXSW Film Festival |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/sxsw-buzziest-movies-2016-festival-1201728130/ |magazine=Variety |last1= Setoodeh |first1= Ramin | last2 = Chang| first2 = Justin | last3 = Leydon| first3 = Joe | last4 = Barker| first4 = Andrew |date=March 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn the night of March 20, gunshots rang out on 6th Street causing mass hysteria and panic. No injuries were reported and a man from Memphis was arrested with discharging a firearm and [[Breach of the peace|disturbing the peace]].{{citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\n====2017====\nFilms that premiered at SXSW Film include ''[[Song to Song]]'', ''[[Baby Driver (film)|Baby Driver]]'', ''[[Atomic Blonde]]'', ''[[Gemini (2017 film)|Gemini]]'',<ref name=\"sxsw 2017 premieres\">{{cite magazine |title=SXSW: Ryan Gosling, Charlize Theron Take Austin for 'Song to Song,' 'Atomic Blonde' Premieres |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/gallery/sxsw-2017-movie-tv-premieres-gallery-song-song-baby-driver-atomic-blonde-american-gods-985632/1-song-to-song |magazine=Hollywood Reporter |date=March 14, 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Ballad of Lefty Brown]]''. ''[[Spettacolo]]'' and ''[[The Disaster Artist (film)|The Disaster Artist]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=James Franco's 'The Disaster Artist' to Premiere at SXSW |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/festivals/james-franco-the-disaster-artist-premiering-at-sxsw-1201979745/ |first=Dave |last=McNary |magazine=Variety |date=February 7, 2017}}</ref> Television shows that were previewed include ''[[The Son (TV series)|The Son]]'', ''[[Dear White People (TV series)|Dear White People]]'' and ''[[American Gods (TV series)|American Gods]]''.<ref name=\"sxsw 2017 premieres\" /> To promote the [[Hulu]] original series ''[[The Handmaid's Tale (TV series)|The Handmaid's Tale]]'', dozens of actresses silently walked the streets of downtown Austin costumed in red \"handmaid\" dresses.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://adage.com/article/special-report-sxsw/sxsw-hulu-make-a-political-statement-handmaids-tale/308253/|title=SXSW: Hulu Says It's Not Making a Political Statement With 'Handmaids Tale'|access-date=2017-07-22|language=en}}</ref> To promote the third season of the [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] original series ''[[Better Call Saul]]'' (a spin-off prequel of ''[[Breaking Bad]]''), a pop-up \"Los Pollos Hermanos\" restaurant, representing the fictional fast food chain featured in both series, appeared in downtown Austin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/austin/news/2017/03/10/sxsw-insider-why-the-los-pollos-hermanos-pop-up.html|title=SXSW Insider: Why the Los Pollos Hermanos pop-up came to Austin|last=Anderson|first=Will|date=March 10, 2017|website=www.bizjournals.com|access-date=2017-08-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.adweek.com/brand-marketing/have-a-look-inside-amcs-perfect-replica-of-breaking-bads-los-pollos-hermanos-at-sxsw/|title=Have a Look Inside AMC's Perfect Replica of Breaking Bad's Los Pollos Hermanos at SXSW|last=Maskeroni|first=Alfred|date=March 10, 2017|work=Adweek|access-date=2017-08-22|language=English}}</ref>\n\nGuest speakers included former mayor of Newark, NJ and current Senator [[Cory Booker]] (D-New Jersey),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2017/03/10/technology/sxsw-cory-booker/index.html|title=Cory Booker: We need to love each other|last=O'Brien|first=Sara Ashley|date=2017-03-10|website=CNNMoney|access-date=2017-07-22}}</ref> political activist and commentator [[Van Jones]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/daily/screens/2017-03-11/sxsw-panel-the-messy-truth-with-van-jones/|title=SXSW Panel: ''The Messy Truth'' With Van Jones|access-date=2017-07-22|language=English}}</ref> and former Vice President [[Joe Biden]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-joe-biden-cancer-sxsw-trump-2017-story.html|title=Joe Biden calls for SXSW tech innovators to join 'the only bipartisan thing left in America'|date=2017-03-12|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2017-07-22|language=English|issn=0458-3035}}</ref> who spoke about his cancer research initiative. [[Nile Rodgers]] gave the keynote address for the music portion of the festival,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/events/sxsw/7727781/sxsw-nile-rodgers-keynote-address|title=Nile Rodgers Talks Making Hits & Not Being a Music Snob During SXSW Keynote Address|work=Billboard|access-date=2017-07-22}}</ref> while filmmakers [[Gareth Edwards (director)|Gareth Edwards]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/gareth-edwards-rogue-one-sxsw-1202007727/|title=SXSW: Gareth Edwards Explains How a Starbucks Cup Influenced 'Rogue One'|last=Valentini|first=Valentina I.|date=2017-03-13|work=Variety|access-date=2017-07-22|language=English}}</ref> and [[Lee Daniels]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sxsw-lee-daniels-explains-why-trump-will-be-good-hollywood-details-childhood-ghetto-985428|title=SXSW: Lee Daniels Explains Why Trump Will Be Good for Hollywood, Details Childhood in \"the Ghetto\"|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2017-07-22|language=en}}</ref> gave the keynote presentations for the film portion.\n\nMajor companies and brands which exhibited at SXSW (many with standalone \"brand activation\" pavilions) included [[IBM]], [[Intel]], [[Panasonic]], [[Nintendo]], [[General Electric|GE]], [[Armani|Giorgio Armani]], [[Mazda]] and [[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]].\n\nMajor performers during the music component of the festival included [[Garth Brooks]], [[Lana Del Rey]], [[Lil Yachty]], [[The Roots]], [[The Avett Brothers]], [[Willie Nelson]], [[Solange Knowles]], [[Rae Sremmurd]], [[Migos]], and [[The Chainsmokers]] among others.\n\nEn route to SXSW 2017, [[Italy|Italian]] [[post-punk]] band Soviet Soviet, traveling on the [[Visa Waiver Program]], was denied entry to the United States, detained overnight and [[deportation|deported]] after an [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection|immigration officer]] at [[Seattle\u2013Tacoma International Airport]] claimed they were planning on conducting a paid performance, which would have required a work visa. The band presented a letter from their American [[record label]] stating that both their performances at [[KEXP-FM|KEXP]] (which was what had brought the band to Seattle) and at SXSW were for promotional purposes only, but this failed to convince officials at the airport.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tsioulcas|first1=Anastasia|title=Italian Band Soviet Soviet Denied Entry To The U.S., Jailed And Then Deported|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/therecord/2017/03/10/519707931/italian-band-soviet-soviet-denied-entry-to-the-u-s-jailed-and-then-deported|website=NPR|publisher=NPR|accessdate=13 March 2017}}</ref> There was a \"Contrabanned\" showcase on March 17, featuring various artists and musicians (residents of the U.S. and Canada) who are natives of, or have family connections to, countries affected by the [[Executive Order 13769|2017 U.S. travel ban]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/ct-sxsw-contrabanned-showcase-20170318-column.html|title=SXSW: Artists representing Muslim-majority countries band together|last=Kot|first=Greg|work=chicagotribune.com|access-date=2017-08-22|language=English}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/03/19/520752751/faarrow-joins-south-by-southwest-bands-in-drawing-attention-to-travel-ban|title=FAARROW Joins SXSW Bands In Drawing Attention To Travel Ban|website=NPR.org|access-date=2017-08-22}}</ref>\n\n[[Uber]] and [[Lyft]] pulled out of Austin in May 2016 as a result of a city ordinance mandating fingerprint-based background checks for drivers of any [[transportation network company]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bizjournals.com/austin/news/2016/05/07/uber-lyft-defeated-in-prop-1-referendum.html | title=Uber, Lyft defeated in Prop. 1 referendum | last=Theis | first=Michael | work=[[American City Business Journals]] | date=May 7, 2016}}</ref> However, other services such as (locally based) RideAustin, [[Fasten (company)|Fasten]] and Fare, were available, although in high demand. Uber and Lyft resumed service in Austin in May 2017.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/gulliver/2017/05/not-missed | title=An inglorious return to Austin for Uber and Lyft | work=[[The Economist]] | date=May 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2018====\n[[File:(L to R) IGN's Laura Prudom, Dan Jurgens, Jim Lee, Frank Miller, Brian Michael Bendis at SXSW 2018.jpg|alt=The panel seated in director's chairs|thumb|[[IGN]]'s Laura Prudom (far left) hosts a panel at 2018's South by Southwest convention discussing Superman's eightieth anniversary and the release of [[Action Comics 1000|''Action Comics'' #1000]], with (left to right): [[Dan Jurgens]], [[Jim Lee]], [[Frank Miller (comics)|Frank Miller]], and [[Brian Michael Bendis]].]]\nSXSW 2018 ran from March 9 to 18.\n\nFinalists of the 2018 SXSW Accelerator Pitch Event included Cambridge Cancer Genomics and Bluefield Technologies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sxsw.com/interactive/2018/50-startup-finalists-announced-for-2018-sxsw-accelerator-pitch-event/|title=SXSW 2018|date=January 16, 2018|website=www.sxsw.com|access-date=2018-01-16}}</ref> Two winners of the event were Austin-based: GrubTubs (in the Hyper-Connected Communities category) and ICON 3D (in the Social and Culture category).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.512tech.com/technology/two-austin-startups-win-big-sxsw-accelerator-pitch-event/OBntFCMxvqyf4wwYgmqegM/|title=Two Austin startups win big at SXSW Accelerator pitch event|last=|first=|date=|work=512 tech (Austin American-Statesman)|access-date=2018-03-18}}</ref>\n\nGuest speakers included politicians [[Bernie Sanders]], [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] and [[Sadiq Khan]]; journalists [[Christiane Amanpour]] and [[Ta-Nehisi Coates]]; filmmakers [[Barry Jenkins]], [[Darren Aronofsky]] and [[Steven Spielberg]]; and others including [[Elon Musk]] and [[David Banner]]. Actor and comedian [[Bill Murray]] appeared at several unofficial functions during SXSW.\n\nMajor performers during SXSW Music included [[Tinashe]], [[Rae Sremmurd]], [[Rita Coolidge]], [[Salt-N-Pepa]] and [[Khalid (singer)|Khalid]]. There was an apparent increased emphasis on locally based performers, international acts and relative unknowns.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bagot |first1=Hayden |title=Announcing 200+ Showcasing Artists for the 2018 SXSW Music Festival |url=https://www.sxsw.com/music/2017/2018-music-festival-artist-announcement-round-one/ |website=SXSW |accessdate=10 July 2019|date=2017-10-11 }}</ref>\n\nNew games announced during the 2018 SXSW Gaming Expo included ''[[Sonic Mania|Sonic Mania Plus]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bleedingcool.com/2018/03/16/sonic-mania-plus-announced-at-sxsw-with-physical-edition-and-new-characters/|title=Sonic Mania Plus Announced at SXSW with Physical Edition and New Characters|date=2018-03-16|work=Bleeding Cool News And Rumors|access-date=2018-03-17|language=en-US}}</ref> At the SXSW Gaming Awards (held March 17), the award for Game of the Year went to ''[[The Legend of Zelda: Breath of the Wild]].''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.512tech.com/technology/pubg-and-legend-zelda-take-top-prizes-2018-sxsw-gaming-awards/aP9g20knujXrF5T2CfxcbJ/|title='Legend of Zelda' and 'PUBG' top winners at SXSW Gaming Awards|last=|first=|date=|work=512tech (Austin American-Statesman)|access-date=2018-03-18}}</ref>\n\nFilms that premiered at the 2018 South By Southwest Film Festival include ''[[A Quiet Place (film)|A Quiet Place]],'' ''[[Blockers (film)|Blockers]]'' and ''[[Ready Player One (film)|Ready Player One]]''.<ref name=\"unveils 2018\">{{cite magazine |title=SXSW Unveils 2018 Festival Lineup, With John Krasinski's 'A Quiet Place' Opening-Night Film |url=https://deadline.com/2018/01/sxsw-2018-south-by-southwest-features-lineup-john-krasinksi-a-quiet-place-1202274955/ |magazine=Deadline |first=Dino-Ray |last=Ramos |date=January 31, 2018}}</ref> Films that had their U.S. premiere include ''[[Final Portrait]]'' and ''[[Who We Are Now]]''.<ref name=\"unveils 2018\" /> The film ''[[Thunder Road (2018 film)|Thunder Road]]'' won the grand jury prize. TV series that previewed include ''[[Barry (TV series)|Barry]]'', ''[[Krypton (TV series)|Krypton]]'', ''[[The Last O.G.]]''<ref name=\"unveils 2018\" /> and ''[[Cloak & Dagger (TV series)|Cloak & Dagger]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Marvel's 'Cloak & Dagger' holds watch party at SXSW |url=http://www.kvue.com/article/life/events/sxsw/marvels-cloak-dagger-holds-watch-party-at-sxsw/269-527699516 |publisher=KVUE |last1= Knight |first1= Drew | last2 = Yeates| first2 = Daysi |date=March 11, 2018}}</ref> To promote the second season of the HBO series ''[[Westworld (TV series)|Westworld]]'', a recreation of the show's fictional Western \"town\" of Sweetwater was built on two acres of open land just outside Austin. Fans took shuttles to the site, which was dressed in the Old West style, with over 60 actors playing the parts of the android \"hosts\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.adweek.com/brand-marketing/inside-hbo-and-giant-spoons-massive-immersive-westworld-activation-at-sxsw/|title=Inside HBO and Giant Spoon's Massive Immersive Westworld Activation at SXSW|access-date=2018-03-11|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/hbo-brings-westworld-to-sxsw/|title='Westworld's gritty western fantasy comes to life at SXSW|date=2018-03-09|work=CNET|access-date=2018-03-11|language=en}}</ref>\n\nSXSW 2018 coincided with a [[Austin serial bombings|string of bombings in Austin]], which had begun on March 2 and ended on March 21, when the presumed perpetrator, Mark Anthony Conditt, blew himself up after being discovered by police.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.statesman.com/news/crime--law/the-suspect-family-mark-conditt-grieving-and-shock/CQUCcXNJ9nb2iFs8sSq0pK/|title=THE SUSPECT: Family of Mark A. Conditt 'grieving' and 'in shock'|last=American-Statesman Staff|work=Austin American-Statesman|access-date=2018-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180322214622/https://www.statesman.com/news/crime--law/the-suspect-family-mark-conditt-grieving-and-shock/CQUCcXNJ9nb2iFs8sSq0pK/|archive-date=2018-03-22|url-status=dead}}</ref> Two of the bombings occurred during SXSW. On March 17, Live Nation Music, a company organizing events for SXSW, received a bomb threat via email. Police searched the area mentioned in the email and found nothing of concern, but planned performances by [[The Roots]] and [[Ludacris]], among others, were canceled.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/music/news/the-roots-sxsw-concert-cancelled-due-to-security-concern-1202729636/|title=The Roots' SXSW Concert Canceled Due to 'Security Concern'|date=2018-03-18|work=Variety|access-date=2018-03-22|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2018/03/18/594776934/man-arrested-for-bomb-threat-at-sxsw-festival-in-austin-texas|title=Austin Police Warn People To Avoid Packages After 4th Explosion Injures 2|work=NPR.org|access-date=2018-03-22|language=en}}</ref> Police arrested 26-year-old Trevor Weldon Ingram the next day; Ingram was charged with making a terroristic threat, a third-degree felony, in connection with the email.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trevor-weldon-ingram-arrested-for-austin-sxsw-bomb-threat/|title=Man arrested for bomb threat that shut down Roots concert at South by Southwest in Austin|last=|first=|date=March 18, 2018|work=CBS News|access-date=2018-03-22|language=en}}</ref>\n\n====2019====\nSouth by Southwest 2019 ran from March 8 to March 17.\n\nFilms entered at SXSW Film included ''[[Us (2019 film)|Us]]'', ''[[The Beach Bum]]'', ''[[Long Shot (2019 film)|Long Shot]]'', ''[[Booksmart (film)|Booksmart]]'' and ''[[The Highwaymen (film)|The Highwaymen]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title='The Beach Bum,' 'Us,' Johnny Cash Doc Lead 2019 SXSW Film Festival |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-news/the-beach-bum-us-johnny-cash-doc-2019-sxsw-film-festival-780147/ |date=January 16, 2019 |first=Daniel |last=Kreps |work=Rolling Stone}}</ref> TV series that previewed included [[FX (TV channel)|FX]]\u2019s ''[[What We Do in the Shadows (TV series)|What We Do in the Shadows]]'', [[Hulu]]\u2019s ''[[Shrill (TV series)|Shrill]]'' and [[Oprah Winfrey Network|OWN]]\u2019s ''[[David Makes Man]]''.\n\nAt the SXSW Gaming Awards (held March 16), the award for Game of the Year went to ''[[God of War (2018 video game)|God of War.]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.austin360.com/news/20190317/god-of-war-takes-top-honor-at-sxsw-gaming-awards|title='God of War' takes top honor at SXSW Gaming Awards|last=Gonzales|first=Chloe|date=March 17, 2019|website=Austin 360|language=en|access-date=2019-03-18}}</ref>\n\nMajor performers for SXSW Music included [[Edie Brickell & New Bohemians]] (their first-ever appearance at SXSW).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/events/sxsw/8502481/edie-brickell-new-bohemians-first-sxsw-set|title=Edie Brickell & New Bohemians Play Tight, Career-Spanning Set at SXSW|last=Graff|first=Gary|date=March 14, 2019|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-03-15}}</ref>\n\nWinners of the 2019 SXSW Pitch event, in which emerging startups pitch to potential investors, included Derq, Pathway and ENZO Tyres. The \u201cBest In Show\" winner was [[Nebula Genomics]];<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2018/11/15/667946213/startup-offers-to-sequence-your-genome-free-of-charge-then-let-you-profit-from-i|title=Startup Offers To Sequence Your Genome Free Of Charge, Then Let You Profit From It|last=Harris|first=Richard|date=November 15, 2018|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-03-15}}</ref> the \u201cBest Bootstrap\" award went to TwentyTables and the \u201cBest Speed Pitch\u201d went to Xplosion Tech.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/sxsw-announces-2019-winners-of-11th-annual-pitch-event-300809776.html|title=SXSW Announces 2019 Winners of 11th Annual Pitch Event|date=March 11, 2019|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-15}}</ref>\n\nSome of the first forums of the [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 presidential race]] took place at SXSW, with [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] presidential candidates [[Pete Buttigieg]], [[Julian Castro]], [[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|John Delaney]], [[Tulsi Gabbard]], [[John Hickenlooper]], [[Jay Inslee]], [[Amy Klobuchar]], [[Beto O'Rourke]], [[Elizabeth Warren]] and [[Andrew Yang]] all making appearances at the festival (though some had not yet announced their candidacy at the time).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sacbee.com/latest-news/article227347884.html|title=2020 Democrats flock to trendy SXSW festival in Texas|last=WEBER|first=PAUL J.|work=The Sacramento Bee|access-date=2019-03-09|language=en-US|issn=0890-5738}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Democratic Candidates Target Tech Giants, Who Are Major Party Donors |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/03/11/702102576/democratic-candidates-target-tech-giants-who-are-major-party-donors |first=Aarti |last=Shahani |date=March 11, 2019 |publisher=NPR}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freep.com/story/news/nation/2019/03/07/sxsw-austin-politics-president-2020-race-candidates-trump/3050647002/|title=The new Iowa? 2020 presidential candidates descend on Austin for SXSW conference|website=Detroit Free Press|language=en|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> Other scheduled guest speakers included politicians [[Mazie Hirono]] and [[Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez]]; musicians [[David Byrne]] and [[Wyclef Jean]]; actors and comedians [[Aidy Bryant]], [[Kathy Griffin]], [[Ethan Hawke]], [[Trevor Noah]] and [[Zoe Saldana]]; businessmen [[Tim Ferriss]], [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]] and [[Guy Kawasaki]]; and others including [[Priscilla Chan]], [[Neil Gaiman]], [[Valerie Jarrett]], [[Bill Nye]], [[Robert Rodriguez]] and [[Maria Shriver]].\n\nTo promote the final season of ''[[Game of Thrones]]'', [[HBO]] organized a [[blood donation|blood drive]] with the [[American Red Cross]] titled \"Bleed for the Throne\" which included actors in costumes similar to those on the series.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.adweek.com/digital/snap-and-hbo-use-ar-at-game-of-thrones-sxsw-experience/|title=Snap and HBO Use AR at Game of Thrones SXSW Experience|last=Swant|first=Marty|date=March 7, 2019|work=Adweek|access-date=2019-03-08|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.texasmonthly.com/the-culture/at-sxsw-hbo-and-amazon-go-over-the-top-on-immersive-experiences/|title=At SXSW, HBO and Amazon Go Over-the-Top on \"Immersive Experiences\"|last=Solomon|first=Dan|date=2019-03-08|website=Texas Monthly|language=en|access-date=2019-03-10}}</ref>\n\nTo promote the [[Amazon Prime]] original limited series ''[[Good Omens (TV series)|Good Omens]]'', a brand activation experience called \"Garden of Earthly Delights\" was installed in downtown Austin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cbsaustin.com/news/local/amazon-prime-brings-a-garden-of-earthly-delights-to-sxsw|title=Amazon Prime brings a Garden of Earthly Delights to SXSW|last=Cross|first=Bettie|date=2019-03-09|website=KEYE|access-date=2019-03-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/good-omens-sxsw-activation-amazon-prime-video-neil-gaiman-terry-pratchett-michael-cheen-david-tennant-1202572210/|title='Good Omens' Celebrates End Of Times With Elixirs, Manicures And Puppies At SXSW|last=Ramos|first=Dino-Ray|date=2019-03-08|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-03-10}}</ref>\n\n===2020 cancellation===\nSouth by Southwest 2020 was scheduled to run from March 13 to March 22, but was officially cancelled on March 6 due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/sxsw-canceled-coronavirus|title=SXSW 2020 Has Been Cancelled Following Coronavirus Fears|date=2020-03-06|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> the result of an order by the city of Austin.<ref name=\"city of austin cancels\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sxsw.com/2020-event-update/|title=City of Austin Cancels SXSW March Events|date=2020-03-06|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> The city's Mayor [[Steve Adler (politician)|Steve Adler]] announced the cancellation of the 2020 SXSW and also declared a local state of emergency.<ref>https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/austin-considers-spring-festivals-sxsw-in-light-of-covid-19-spread/2325885/</ref>\n\nIn the month prior to the conference, SXSW organizers had resisted calls to cancel the conference. On February 28, a spokesperson said:\n{{Quote\n| text=The SXSW 2020 event is proceeding as planned. Safety is a top priority for SXSW, and we work closely with local, state, and federal agencies year-round to plan for a safe event. Where travel has been impacted, especially in the case of China, we are seeing a handful of cancellations. However, we are on par with years past in regard to registrants who are unable to attend. We are increasing our efforts to prevent the spread of disease per Austin Public Health\u2019s recommendations. We will continue to monitor the situation closely and will provide updates as necessary.\n| author=SXSW spokesperson|source=Recode, Vox Media <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/2/27/21156676/coronavirus-facebook-f8-canceled-major-tech-conferences-covid-19|title=Here are all the major tech conferences canceled so far because of coronavirus\n| date=2020-02-28|website=Vox|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>\n}}\n\nHowever, in the run up to the conference, numerous companies and organizations began cancelling their SXSW attendance, including [[Twitter]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cbsaustin.com/news/local/twitter-cancels-sxsw-appearance-over-coronavirus-concerns|title=Twitter CEO cancels SXSW appearance over coronavirus concerns\n| date=2020-03-02|website=CBS Austin|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.twitter.com/en_us/topics/company/2020/keeping-our-employees-and-partners-safe-during-coronavirus.html|title=Keeping our employees and partners safe during #coronavirus\n| date=2020-03-01|website=Twitter|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref> [[Facebook]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/2/21162250/facebook-pulls-out-sxsw-conference-coronavirus-concerns|title=Facebook pulls out of the SXSW conference citing coronavirus concerns|date=2020-03-02|website=The Verge|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref> [[Vevo]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://adage.com/article/digital/facebook-and-vevo-cancel-sxsw-plans-amid-coronavirus-fears/2241951|title=FACEBOOK AND VEVO CANCEL SXSW PLANS AMID CORONAVIRUS FEARS|date=2020-03-02|website=Ad Age|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref> [[Intel]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303145813/https://www.kxan.com/news/coronavirus/facebook-intel-join-twitter-in-pulling-out-of-sxsw-over-coronavirus-fears/|title=Facebook, Intel join Twitter in pulling out of SXSW over coronavirus fears|date=2020-03-03|website=KXAN|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> [[Mashable]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/mashable/status/1234878736832647172|title=We\u2019ve decided to cancel the Mashable House and MashBash at SXSW|date=2020-03-03|website=Twitter|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> [[Universal Music Group]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/record-labels/9327781/record-labels-travel-coronavirus|title=Record Labels Restrict Travel Amid Escalating Coronavirus Threat|date=2020-03-03|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/amazon-studios-sxsw-2020-cancellation-coronavirus-1202873881/|title= Amazon Studios Pulls Out Of Fest Over Coronavirus Concerns|date=2020-03-03|website=Deadline|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> [[TikTok]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/tiktok-pulls-out-sxsw-amid-coronavirus-961657/|title=TikTok Is Pulling Out of SXSW Amid the Coronavirus Scare|date=2020-03-03|website=Rolling Stone|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> [[SAP SE|SAP]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SAP/status/1235012712209567744|title=We have made the decision to cancel all SAP in-person events for the month of March 2020|date=2020-03-04|website=Twitter|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> [[Netflix]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/netflix-cancels-sxsw-2020-1203524545/|title=Netflix Cancels SXSW 2020 Screenings, Panels Amid Coronavirus Fears (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Low|first=Elaine|last2=Low|first2=Elaine|date=2020-03-05|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> [[Apple Inc.|Apple]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/digital/news/apple-cancels-sxsw-2020-coronavirus-1203524430/|title=Apple Pulls Out of SXSW 2020 Over Coronavirus Concerns|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=2020-03-05|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> [[Indeed]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305101441/https://www.statesman.com/business/20200304/as-virus-concerns-swirl-austin-based-indeed-tells-employees-to-work-from-home|title=Austin-based Indeed tells employees to work from home|date=2020-03-04|website=Statesman|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> [[WarnerMedia]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306091637/https://www.kxan.com/news/sxsw/warnermedia-joins-list-of-companies-pulling-out-of-sxsw/|title=WarnerMedia joins list of companies pulling out of SXSW|date=2020-03-05|website=KXAN.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/davejorgenson/status/1235200866715566080|title= The Post has cancelled all non-essential business travel|date=2020-03-04|website=Twitter|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> and [[IBM]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305101903/https://www.statesman.com/business/20200304/ibm-to-skip-on-sxsw-after-issuing-travel-restrictions-due-to-coronavirus|title=IBM to skip on SXSW after issuing travel restrictions due to coronavirus|date=2020-03-04|website=Statesman|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> Additionally, many individual attendees, headliners and speakers had decided not to attend, including keynote speaker [[Tim Ferriss]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304090009/https://www.austin360.com/entertainment/20200303/sxsw-2020-and-coronavirus-herersquos-whos-not-coming|title=SXSW 2020 and coronavirus: Here's who's not coming|date=2020-03-03|website=Austin 360|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.crunchbase.com/news/not-worth-the-risk-startups-vcs-backing-out-of-sxsw-due-to-coronavirus-concerns/|title='Not Worth The Risk': Startups, VCs Backing Out Of SXSW Due To Coronavirus Concerns|date=2020-03-03|website=Crunchbase|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> and artists such as the [[Beastie Boys]], [[Ozzy Osbourne]] and [[Trent Reznor]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/beastie-boys-ozzy-osbourne-trent-reznor-pull-out-of-sxsw/|title=Beastie Boys, Ozzy Osbourne, Trent Reznor Pull Out of SXSW Due to Coronavirus|last=Bloom|first=Madison|date=2020-03-06|website=Pitchfork|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref>\n\nAn online petition was started that called for SXSW 2020 to be cancelled due to health concerns; by the time of the cancellation, it exceeded 50,000 signatures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/10000-call-for-sxsw-to-be-canceled-over-coronavirus-fears-2020-3|title=Nearly 15,000 sign petition calling for SXSW to be canceled over mounting coronavirus worries|date=2020-03-02|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/health/2020/03/02/coronavirus-outbreak-fears-spurs-petition-calling-halt-sxsw/4930937002/\n| title=Fears of coronavirus prompt online petition to cancel SXSW gathering in Austin\n| date=2020-03-02|website=USA Today|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n\nSXSW organizers said that they were \"devastated\" by the cancellation, stating that, \"'The show must go on' is in our DNA.\"<ref name=\"city of austin cancels\" /> They wrote that they were attempting to reschedule the event, and were at the same time working to create an online SXSW for 2020.<ref name=\"city of austin cancels\" />\n\nSXSW co-founder Nick Barbaro said the organization did not have cancellation insurance relating to a disease pandemic or triggered by the city declaring a \u201clocal state of disaster.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/daily/news/2020-03-06/sxsw-cancellation-not-covered-by-insurance/|title=SXSW Cancellation Not Covered by Insurance|last=Curtin|first=Kevin|last2=|date=2020-02-06|website=www.austinchronicle.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-07|last3=|first3=|last4=}}</ref>\n\nDespite the cancellation of SXSW 2020 amid concerns over COVID-19, unofficial SXSW events, as well as \u201calternative\u201d SXSW events, have gained momentum trying to rally around the local workers and businesses who would be hurt most by the cancellation.<ref>https://www.kxan.com/news/local/austin/despite-sxsw-cancellation-unofficial-and-alternative-events-look-to-gain-momentum/</ref>\n\nThe Austin Community Foundation launched a \u201cStand with Austin Fund\u201d for donations to \u201cindividuals and small businesses most negatively impacted by the cancellation of SXSW and least able to recover on their own.\u201d<ref>https://www.austincf.org/Stand-with-Austin</ref>\n\nA fundraiser called \"Banding Together\" was started by the Red River Cultural District to provide financial relief for artists venues and events within the district.\n\nOn March 13, 2020 festival organizers announced that they will proceed with juried and special awards, with judges viewing submissions via digital links.<ref>{{cite news|title=SXSW Revives Film Competition Digitally After Festival Cancellation|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sxsw-revives-film-competition-digitally-festival-cancellation-1284529?utm_source=twitter&utm_medium=social|magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collider.com/sxsw-2020-film-competition-digital-details/|title=SXSW Film Competition Going Digital in the Wake of Festival Cancellation| date=2020-03-13|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, SXSW announced the winners of the 2020 SXSW Gaming Awards on the SXSW website, and the honorees recorded acceptance messages for the SXSW [[YouTube]] channel and the SXSW website<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sxsw.com/news/2020/announcing-the-2020-sxsw-gaming-awards-winners/|title=Announcing the 2020 SXSW Gaming Awards Winners|date=2020-03-24|website=SXSW|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>. ''[[Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice]]'' was awarded Video Game of the Year.\n\nOn March 30, SXSW added a page on its website offering official merchandise intended for the 2020 event, such as t-shirts and posters, for sale online<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sxsw.com/news/2020/shop-official-2020-sxsw-merch/|title=Shop Official SXSW 2020 Merch|date=2020-03-31|website=SXSW|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>.\n\nOn April 2, SXSW announced a joint venture with [[Prime Video|Amazon Prime Video]] to launch a film festival collection. Filmmakers scheduled to screen films at SXSW were notified April 2, and will be able to opt in; those who do so will see their films play exclusively on Prime Video in the U.S. for the 10-day \"virtual film festival,\" which Amazon will likely launch in late April. The online event will be available in front of the Prime Video paywall and free to U.S. audiences.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/amazon-teams-sxsw-launch-a-virtual-fest-1288163|title=Amazon Teams With SXSW to Launch a Virtual Fest|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sxsw.com/film/2020/amazon-prime-video-presents-the-sxsw-2020-film-festival-collection/|title=Amazon Prime Video Presents the SXSW 2020 Film Festival Collection|date=2020-04-02|website=SXSW|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==Economic impact==\nSXSW is the highest revenue-producing event outside of athletic and other events associated with [[The University of Texas at Austin]] for the Austin economy, with an estimated economic impact of $190.3 million in 2012<ref>{{cite news|title=Report: SXSW's 2012 economic impact was $190 million|url=http://www.statesman.com/news/business/sxsws-2012-economic-impact-190-million/nSTKt/|newspaper=Austin American Statesman|accessdate=April 1, 2013}}</ref> increasing to $218 million in 2013,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.austinchamber.com/blog/2013/09/18/sxsw-announces-2013-impact-on-the-austin-economy/ |title=SXSW Announces 2013 Impact on the Austin Economy &#124; Austin Chamber Divisional Blogs |publisher=Austinchamber.com |date=September 18, 2013 |accessdate=March 17, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316024643/https://www.austinchamber.com/blog/2013/09/18/sxsw-announces-2013-impact-on-the-austin-economy/ |archivedate=March 16, 2014 }}</ref> $315 million in 2014,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.texasmonthly.com/the-daily-post/sxsws-economic-impact-on-austin-in-2014-was-worth-315-million/|title=SXSW's Economic Impact On Austin In 2014 Was Worth $315 Million|date=2014-09-12|work=Texas Monthly|access-date=2017-08-11|language=English}}</ref> $317 million in 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/austin/blog/techflash/2015/09/sxsw-economic-impact-grows-slightly-from-2014.html|title=SXSW economic impact grows slightly from 2014|last=Swiatecki|first=Chad|date=September 15, 2015|website=www.bizjournals.com|access-date=2017-08-11}}</ref> and $325 million in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/austin/news/2016/09/07/sxsw-economic-impact-up-slightly-in-2016-hotel.html|title=SXSW economic impact up slightly in 2016; hotel rates hit new high|last=Theis|first=Michael|date=September 7, 2016|website=www.bizjournals.com|access-date=2017-08-11}}</ref> (In comparison, [[Super Bowl LI]] brought a $347 million economic impact to the Houston economy<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/houston/news/2017/05/25/results-are-in-how-much-the-2017-super-bowl.html|title=Results are in: How much the 2017 Super Bowl brought to Houston|last=Martin|first=Joe|date=May 25, 2017|website=www.bizjournals.com/houston|access-date=2017-07-22}}</ref> and the [[2017 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|2017 Final Four]] brought a $324 million economic impact to the economy of Phoenix, Arizona.)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/money/business/2017/08/11/final-four-gave-phoenix-area-325-million-economic-slam-dunk-asu-study-says/555967001/|title=Final Four gave Phoenix area a $325 million economic slam dunk, ASU study says|last=Wiles|first=Russ|date=August 11, 2017|work=azcentral|access-date=2017-08-11|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, demand for hotel rooms in the Austin area continued to outstrip supply, pushing average nightly room rates up to an all-time high of $350 in 2016, a 60 percent increase over the average room rate seen during 2011's edition of SXSW. The average SXSW registrant also stayed in Austin longer in 2016, spending an average of 5.2 nights, up from 4.9 nights in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/austin/news/2016/09/07/sxsw-economic-impact-up-slightly-in-2016-hotel.html|title=SXSW economic impact up slightly in 2016; hotel rates hit new high|last=Theis|first=Michael|date=September 7, 2016|website=www.bizjournals.com|access-date=2017-07-22}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\nThe growth of the festival has brought concerns about violence, [[crowd control]], and safety.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.suntimes.com/music/2011/03/violence_and_crowd_control_pro.html|title=Violence and crowd control problems cause SXSW to consider limiting events|newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|accessdate=2015-08-13|first=Thomas|last=Conner|date=March 21, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141208100955/http://blogs.suntimes.com/music/2011/03/violence_and_crowd_control_pro.html|archivedate=December 8, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/03/27/sxsw-accident-fourth-death/6970477/|title=SXSW accident claims fourth life|last= Owens|first= Marjorie |date=27 March 2014|newspaper=USA Today|accessdate=2015-08-13}}</ref>{{update after|2018|11|28}}<!-- and then what? What happened with this 2014 lawsuit? Was the festival implicated? Festival organizers? Or was it just a drunk driving accident that, sadly, still happens a couple million times annually. -->\n\nThe 2014 drunk-driving incident prompted discussion about whether the festival had grown too large and raucous.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-sxsw-car-accident-tragedy-20140314,0,4850567.story |title=A tragic wake-up call for SXSW? |publisher=latimes.com |date=March 13, 2014 |first1=Mikael |last1=Wood |first2=August |last2=Brown}}</ref> The organizers of the festival\u2014SXSW Holdings LLC and SXSW Holdings Inc.\u2014were sued by families of the four victims.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170629220217/https://www.kxan.com/2014/12/18/lawsuits-deadly-sxsw-crash-could-have-been-prevented/|title=Lawsuits: Deadly SXSW crash could have been prevented|publisher=KXAN|accessdate=2015-08-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150824065806/http://kxan.com/2014/12/18/lawsuits-deadly-sxsw-crash-could-have-been-prevented/|archive-date=2015-08-24|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, partially motivated by the 2014 crash, Austin's Urban Transportation Commission announced that it was seeking to enhance safety at the festival, with an initial focus on implementing transportation measures to resolve issues linked to the festival. The Austin Music Commission also met to discuss music venues and sound problems linked to the festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khou.com/news/texas-news?fId=259080131&fPath=/news/local/&fDomain=10232 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140517065154/http://www.khou.com/news/texas-news?fId=259080131&fPath=/news/local/&fDomain=10232 |url-status=dead |archive-date=May 17, 2014 |accessdate=May 18, 2014 }}</ref> The city voted to limit the number of special events which would be approved to 114, a 32 percent decrease from the number of approved events during the 2014 festival.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/austin/blog/creative/2015/02/a-smaller-sxsw-austin-halts-applications-for.html|title=A smaller SXSW? Austin halts applications for special events|date=11 February 2015|work=Austin Business Journal}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, NPR writer Andrea Swensson wrote that she had decided to stop attending the festival, writing, \"I can't help but feel that it has strayed far away from its original premise as a grassroots gathering place for new, undiscovered talent and increasingly feels like a big ol' [[Times Square]] billboard-sized commercial.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Why I'm Not Going To SXSW This Year |url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/therecord/2013/03/05/173097673/why-im-not-going-to-sxsw-this-year |publisher=NPR |date=March 5, 2013 |first=Andrea |last=Swensson}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, SXSW cancelled two video game panels (\"#SavePoint: A Discussion on the Gaming Community\" and \"Level Up: Overcoming Harassment In Games\") scheduled for the 2016 festival due to threats of violence made to the festival hosting the sessions.<ref name=\"wash_SXSW\">{{Cite news | title = SXSW canceled two panels after threats \u2013 but did nothing when female panelists asked about harassment | last = Dewey | first = Caitlin | work = Washington Post | date = October 27, 2015 | accessdate = 2015-10-28 | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-intersect/wp/2015/10/27/sxsw-canceled-two-panels-after-threats-but-did-nothing-when-female-panelists-asked-about-harassment/ | language = | quote = }}</ref> In response to the cancellations, [[Buzzfeed]] and [[Vox Media]] made statements saying they would pull out of the festival if the two panels weren't reinstated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tech.blog.austin360.com/2015/10/26/sxsw-interactive-cancels-two-2016-panels-due-to-threats/|title=SXSW Interactive cancels two 2016 panels due to threats|last=Gallaga|first=Omar L.|work=[[Austin 360]]|date=October 27, 2015|accessdate=October 27, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305084400/http://tech.blog.austin360.com/2015/10/26/sxsw-interactive-cancels-two-2016-panels-due-to-threats/|archive-date=2016-03-05|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"reco_Buzz\">{{Cite news | title = BuzzFeed and Vox Media Threaten to Bail on SXSW Unless Canceled Panels Are Reinstated | last = Kulwin | first = Noah | work = Re/code | date = October 27, 2015 | accessdate = 2015-10-28 | url = https://recode.net/2015/10/27/buzzfeed-to-withdraw-from-sxsw-unless-organizers-reverse-panel-cancelations/ | quote = }}</ref> Organizers then apologized for the cancellations. In lieu of a panel, South by Southwest hosted a daylong \"online harassment summit\" on March 12, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title='We Made a Mistake': SXSW to Host Online Harassment Summit|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/we-made-mistake-sxsw-host-online-harassment-summit-n454651|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=30 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n* Comedian and actor [[Fred Armisen]] began his comic career with the short film ''Fred Armisen's Guide to Music and SXSW'', released in 1998, in which he poses as various characters, asking silly questions of musicians and other attendees at that year's SXSW Music Conference.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ifc.com/shows/portlandia/cast-and-crew/fred-armisen-co-creator-co-writer-co-star |title=Portlandia \u2013 Fred Armisen \u2013 co-creator, co-writer, co-star \u2013 IFC |publisher=Ifc.com |date=2011-02-23 |accessdate=2015-08-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150804085943/http://www.ifc.com/shows/portlandia/cast-and-crew/fred-armisen-co-creator-co-writer-co-star |archivedate=2015-08-04 }}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|tOp1uPpjYgo|Fred Armisen's Guide to Music and SXSW}}</ref>\n* SXSW was featured during the 2005 season of [[MTV]]'s, ''[[The Real World: Austin|The Real World]]''. Cast members were tasked with shooting and editing their own documentary on the music festival.\n* The 2011 documentary ''[[Winning America]]'' is about a US tour of Canadian band [[Said the Whale]] that culminates in that year's SXSW Music Festival.\n* In the 2014 British film ''[[Frank (film)|Frank]]'', an experimental band (led by the title character) is booked to play a show at the SXSW Music Festival, but the gig leads to the band's breakup.\n* In the 2019 anime ''[[Carole & Tuesday]]'', the titular duo is booked to perform at the SXSW Music Festival.\n\n==Similar festivals==\nThe creators of South by Southwest co-created two similar festivals in 1995: North by Northwest (NXNW) in [[Portland, Oregon]] (co-founded by the ''[[Willamette Week]]''), and [[North by Northeast]] (NXNE) in [[Toronto]] (co-founded by ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now]]'').<ref name=\"four-letter festivals\">{{cite web |title=Alt-Weeklies' Four-Letter Festivals: Movement Grows as Silicon Valley Launches C2SV |url=http://www.altweeklies.com/aan/alt-weeklies-four-letter-festivals-movement-grows-as-silicon-valley-launches-c2sv/Article?oid=7274104 |publisher=AAN News |date=September 20, 2013}}</ref> North by Northwest ended in 2001, and was replaced by [[MusicfestNW]] (MFNW), an event run entirely by the ''Willamette Week''. It was joined by [[TechfestNW]], a technology conference, in 2012.<ref>[http://tech.fortune.cnn.com/2012/08/28/tech-may-have-found-its-next-sxsw/ Tech may have found its next SXSW], John Patrick Pullen, ''CNNMoney'', August 28, 2012</ref> From 2006 to 2010, SXSW organizers also ran West by Southwest (WXSW) in [[Tucson, Arizona]], a music festival which occurred directly before South by Southwest and mostly featured bands that were also booked for SXSW.<ref>[http://tucsoncitizen.com/morgue2/2006/03/09/115421-go-west-by-southwest-young-band/ Go West (by Southwest), young band] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303232623/http://tucsoncitizen.com/morgue2/2006/03/09/115421-go-west-by-southwest-young-band/ |date=2016-03-03 }}, Polly Higgins, ''[[Tucson Citizen]]'', March 9, 2006</ref>\n\nOther active festivals inspired by SXSW include the following:\n* [[Web Summit]] \u2013 [[Lisbon, Portugal]]\n* Live at Heart \u2013 [[\u00d6rebro, Sweden]]\n* South by Due East \u2013 [[Houston, Texas]]\n* The Goa Project \u2013 [[Goa, India]]\n* [[The Great Escape Festival]] \u2013 [[Brighton, England]]\n* [[Tech Open Air]] (TOA) \u2013 [[Berlin]]\n* [[XOXO (festival)|XOXO]]<ref>{{cite web |title=XOXO Aims to Be an Alternative to South by Southwest |url=https://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/25/xoxo-aims-to-be-an-alternative-to-south-by-southwest/ |first=Jenna |last=Wortham |work=The New York Times Bits blog |date=May 25, 2012}}</ref> \u2013 [[Portland, Oregon]]\n\nFestivals inspired by SXSW that are no longer running include:\n* [[35 Denton]] (originally known as \"North by 35\" or \"NX35\", then \"35 Conferette\") \u2013 [[Denton, Texas]] (2009\u20132016)\n* [[C2SV]] (originally known as \"SVSX\") \u2013 [[San Jose, California]] (2012\u20132016)\n* [[Incubate (festival)|Incubate]] (originally known as \"ZXZW\") \u2013 [[Tilburg, Netherlands]] (2005\u20132016)\n* [[MidPoint Music Festival]] (MPMF) \u2013 [[Cincinnati, Ohio]] (2001\u20132017)\n* [[MoSo]] \u2013 [[Saskatoon, Canada]] (2011\u20132016)\n* So What?! Music Fest (originally known as \"South by So What?!\") \u2013 [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth Metroplex]] (2006\u20132017)\n* Sounds by South Bend (originally known as \"South by South Bend\") - [[South Bend, Indiana]] (2013\u20132015)\n* Yes and Yes Yes (YXYY) (originally known as \"Yes by Yes Yes\") \u2013 [[Palm Springs, California]] (2013\u20132017)\n\nFestivals inspired by South by Southwest have been collectively nicknamed \"four-letter festivals\". ''[[Metro Silicon Valley]]'', which founded C2SV, wrote in 2013 that such festivals were important revenue sources for the [[alternative newspaper|alternative weekly newspapers]] that founded them.<ref name=\"four-letter festivals\" />\n\nOn October 3, 2016, a one-day festival, called \"South by [[South Lawn]]\" (SXSL), was held at the [[White House]]; it was a collaboration between SXSW, US President [[Barack Obama]], and the [[American Film Institute]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/2016/09/01/announcing-south-south-lawn-white-house-festival-ideas-art-and-action|title=Announcing South by South Lawn: A White House Festival of Ideas, Art, and Action|date=1 September 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Austin}}\n{{Music venues of Texas}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:South By Southwest}}\n[[Category:Conferences in the United States]]\n[[Category:Film festivals in Austin, Texas]]\n[[Category:Annual events in Texas]]\n[[Category:Music festivals in Texas]]\n[[Category:March events]]\n[[Category:Music conferences]]\n[[Category:Electronic music festivals in the United States]]\n[[Category:Rock festivals in the United States]]\n[[Category:Computer conferences]]\n[[Category:Technology conferences]]\n[[Category:Music festivals established in 1987]]\n[[Category:Film festivals established in 1987]]\n[[Category:1987 establishments in Texas]]\n", "name_user": "Kailash29792", "label": "safe", "comment": "linkLos Pollos HermanosusingFind link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_by_Southwest"}
{"title_page": "Gulzar", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{short description|Urdu author}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Gulzar\n| image              = Gulzar 2008 - still 38227.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birthname          = Sampooran Singh Kalra\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1934|08|18}}\n| birth_place        = [[Dina, Pakistan|Dina]], [[Punjab Province (British India)|Punjab]], [[British Raj|British India]]<br/> (present-day [[Punjab, Pakistan]])\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = [[Film director]], [[lyricist]], [[screenwriter]], [[Film Producer|producer]], [[poet]], [[author]]\n| yearsactive        = 1971\u201399 (as director) (''retired'')<br>1956\u2013present (as lyricist)\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Raakhee]]|1973}}\n| parents            = Makhan Singh Kalra and Sujan Kaur\n| children           = [[Meghna Gulzar]]\n| signature          = Gulzar signature.jpg\n| signature_alt      = Gulzar signature\n| nationality        = [[Indian people|Indian]]\n| awards             = [[Sahitya Akademi Award]] (2002) , [[Padma Bhushan]] (2004), [[Dadasaheb Phalke Award]] (2013), [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]] (2008)\n}}\n\n'''Sampooran Singh Kalra''' (born 18 August 1934), known popularly by his pen name '''Gulzar''' and also Gulzar Saab, is an [[Academy Awards|Oscar]]-winning Indian film director, lyricist and poet.<ref name=a>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2004/20040104/spectrum/book2.htm|title=The poet as the father|author=Amar Chandel|work=[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]]|date=4 January 2004|accessdate=23 December 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111227043558/http://www.tribuneindia.com/2004/20040104/spectrum/book2.htm|archive-date=27 December 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He started his career with music director [[S.D. Burman]] as a lyricist in the 1963 film ''Bandini'' and worked with many music directors including [[R. D. Burman]], [[Salil Chowdhury]], [[Vishal Bhardwaj]] and [[A. R. Rahman]]. He was awarded [[Padma Bhushan]] in 2004, the third-highest civilian award in India,<ref name=\"Padma Awards\">{{cite web | url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf | title=Padma Awards | publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India | date=2015 | accessdate=July 21, 2015 | archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6U68ulwpb?url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf | archive-date=15 November 2014 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> the [[Sahitya Akademi Award]] and the [[Dadasaheb Phalke Award]]&nbsp;\u2014 the highest award in Indian cinema. He has won several Indian [[National Film Awards]], 21 [[Filmfare Awards]], one Academy Award and one [[Grammy Award]].<ref name=\"IndiaToday-20140412\">{{cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/gulzar-to-get-dadasaheb-phalke-award/1/355422.html|title=Gulzar to get Dadasaheb Phalke award|date=12 April 2014|work=Indiatoday.in|publisher=India Today Group|accessdate=12 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503214231/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/gulzar-to-get-dadasaheb-phalke-award/1/355422.html|archive-date=3 May 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=ix>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/gulzar-selected-for-dadasaheb-phalke-award/|title=Gulzar selected for Dadasaheb Phalke Award|work=The Indian Express|date=13 April 2014|accessdate=14 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415073009/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/gulzar-selected-for-dadasaheb-phalke-award/|archive-date=15 April 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nGulzar also wrote poetry, dialogues and scripts. He directed films such as ''[[Aandhi]]'' and ''[[Mausam (1975 film)|Mausam]]'' during the 1970s and the TV series ''[[Mirza Ghalib (TV series)|Mirza Ghalib]]'' in the 1980s. He also directed ''[[Kirdaar]]'' in 1993.\n\n== Early life ==\nGulzar was born in a Kalra [[Sikh]] family, to Makhan Singh Kalra and Sujan Kaur, in [[Dina, Pakistan|Dina]], [[Jhelum District]], [[British Raj|British India]] (present-day [[Pakistan]]). In school, he had read translations of the works of [[Tagore]] which he recounted as one of his life's many turning points. Due to the [[Partition of India|partition]], his family split and he had to stop his studies and come to [[Mumbai]] (then called Bombay) to support his family. Sampooran took up many small jobs in Mumbai to eke out a living,  including one at a garage at ''Vichare motors'' on Bellasis road ([[Mumbai]]).<ref>{{cite AV media|title=Guftagoo - Interview with Gulzar|publisher=Rajyasabha TV|work=YouTube|date=31 July 2012|location=India}}</ref> There he used to touch up accident-damaged cars by mixing shades of paint, in his own words \"I had a knack for colours\". His father rebuked him for being a writer initially. He took the pen name '''Gulzar Deenvi''' and later simply '''Gulzar'''.<ref name = meghna>{{cite book| title = ''Because he is'' | author = [[Meghna Gulzar]] | publisher = Rupa & Co. | year = 2004}}</ref> In an interview with Rajyasabha TV, he recounted enjoying his work as a painter as it allowed him a lot of time to simultaneously read, write, attend college and be involved with the PWA (Progressive Writers Association).<ref name=a/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2009/20090315/spectrum/main6.htm |title=A life in music |work=The Tribune |date=15 March 2009 |accessdate=3 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130706014034/http://www.tribuneindia.com/2009/20090315/spectrum/main6.htm |archive-date=6 July 2013 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j5JXzf7sY0c |title=The Anupam Kher show |date=9 August 2015 |accessdate=5 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151015210853/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j5JXzf7sY0c |archive-date=15 October 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Lyricist ===\nIt was during his interactions in the PWA Sunday meetings that [[Shailendra (lyricist)|Shailendra]] and [[Bimal Roy]] encouraged him to join films. Gulzar began his career under film directors [[Bimal Roy]] and [[Hrishikesh Mukherjee]]. His book ''Ravi Paar'' has a narrative of Bimal Roy and the agony of creation. He started his career as a songwriter with the music director [[Sachin Dev Burman]] for the movie ''[[Bandini (1963 film)|Bandini]]'' (1963). In films, he found an environment associated with literature in the group he worked with, including Bimal Roy, most of whose films were based on literary works.<ref name=\"Man-Of-many-seasons\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-02-24/india/28029446_1_bandini-gulzar-first-film|title=Gulzar: Man Of many seasons|accessdate=14 August 2011|work=The Times of India|date=24 February 2009|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130103195628/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-02-24/india/28029446_1_bandini-gulzar-first-film|archive-date=3 January 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Shailendra (lyricist)|Shailendra]], who has penned the rest of the songs in the movie requested Gulzar to write the song \"Mora Gora Ang Layle\", sung by [[Lata Mangeshkar]].<ref name=\"IndiaToday-20140412\"/><ref name=ix/><ref name=toik>{{cite news|url=http://m.timesofindia.com/india/Director-lyricist-Gulzar-to-get-Dadasaheb-Phalke-award/articleshow/33670237.cms|title=Director-lyricist Gulzar to get Dadasaheb Phalke award|first=Avijit|last=Ghosh|work=The Times of India|date=12 April 2014|accessdate=14 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415005856/http://m.timesofindia.com/india/Director-lyricist-Gulzar-to-get-Dadasaheb-Phalke-award/articleshow/33670237.cms|archive-date=15 April 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nDirected and produced by [[Hrishikesh Mukherjee]], the 1968 film ''[[Aashirwad]]'' had dialogues and lyrics written by Gulzar. Song lyrics and poems written by Gulzar gave the poetic attribute and the \"much-needed additional dimension\"<ref name=Aashirwad/> to [[Ashok Kumar]]'s role in the film. Ashok Kumar received the Best Actor [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor|at the Filmfare]] and [[National Film Award for Best Actor|at the National Film Awards]] for this role.<ref name=\"Aashirwad\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2003/jan/25dinesh.htm|title=Aashirwad tugs at the heartstrings|date=January 2003|publisher=Rediff.com|author=[[Dinesh Raheja]]|accessdate=7 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503231912/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2003/jan/25dinesh.htm|archive-date=3 May 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Gulzar's lyrics, however, did not gain much attention until 1969's ''[[Khamoshi (1970 film)|Khamoshi]]'', where his song \"Humne Dekhi Hai Un Aankhon Ki Mehekti Khushboo\" (lit., \"I have seen the fragrance of those eyes\") became popular. Ganesh Anantharaman in his book ''Bollywood Melodies'' describes Gulzar's lyrics, with the purposeful mixing of the senses, to be \"daringly defiant\".<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lmrSLuBwbKkC&pg=PA69#v=onepage&q=gulzar | title=Bollywood Melodies: A History of the Hindi Film Song | publisher=Penguin Books India | author=Anantharaman, Ganesh | year=2008 | page=122 | isbn=0143063405 |accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref>{{efn|Author Ganesh Anantharaman's book ''Bollywood Melodies'' won the [[National Film Award for Best Book on Cinema|Best Book on Cinema award]] at the [[56th National Film Awards]].}}<ref name=\"56thawardgiven\">{{cite web|title=130 awardees receive the 56th national film awards from President|url=http://pib.nic.in/release/rel_print_page.asp?relid=59802|publisher=[[Press Information Bureau]] (PIB), India|accessdate=4 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503231806/http://pib.nic.in/release/rel_print_page.asp?relid=59802|archive-date=3 May 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> For the 1971 film ''[[Guddi (1971 film)|Guddi]]'', he penned two songs, of which \"Humko Man Ki Shakti Dena\" was a prayer which is still sung in many schools in India.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gGAyEpXtK3UC&pg=PA76#v=onepage&q=gulzar%20song | title=The Desai Trio and the Movie Industry of India | publisher=Author House | author=Gavankar, Nilu | year=2011 | page=76 | isbn=9781468599817 |accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nAs a lyricist, Gulzar had a close association with the music director [[Rahul Dev Burman]]. He has also worked with [[Sachin Dev Burman]], [[Shankar Jaikishan]], [[Hemanta Kumar Mukhopadhyay|Hemant Kumar]], [[Laxmikant-Pyarelal]], [[Madan Mohan (music director)|Madan Mohan]], [[Rajesh Roshan]], and [[Anu Malik]].<ref name=\"IndiaToday-20140412\"/><ref name=ix/><ref name=toik/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/gulzar-pancham-was-an-anchor-in-my-life/638840/ |title=Gulzar: Pancham was an anchor in my life |date=26 June 2010 |accessdate=23 December 2011 |publisher=[[Screen (magazine)|Screen]]/Indian Express |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100701220155/http://www.indianexpress.com/news/gulzar-pancham-was-an-anchor-in-my-life/638840/ |archive-date=1 July 2010 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Gulzar worked with [[Salil Chowdhury]] in ''[[Anand (1971 film)|Anand]]'' (1971) and ''[[Mere Apne]]'' (1971); [[Madan Mohan]] in ''[[Mausam (1975 film)|Mausam]]'' (1975), and more recently with [[Vishal Bhardwaj]] in ''[[Maachis]]'' (1996), ''[[Omkara (2006 film)|Omkara]]'' (2006) and ''[[Kaminey]]'' (2009); [[A. R. Rahman]] in ''[[Dil Se..]]'' (1998), ''[[Guru (2007 film)|Guru]]'' (2007), ''[[Slumdog Millionaire]]'' (2008) and ''[[Raavan]]'' (2010) and [[Shankar\u2013Ehsaan\u2013Loy]] in ''[[Bunty Aur Babli]]'' (2005).<ref name=\"IndiaToday-20140412\"/><ref name=ix/><ref name=toik/> Gulzar took inspiration from [[Amir Khusrow]]'s \"Ay Sarbathe Aashiqui\" to pen \"Ay Hairathe Aashiqui\" for [[Mani Ratnam]]'s 2007 Hindi film ''[[Guru (soundtrack)|Guru]]'', which had music composed by [[A. R. Rahman]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Rahman on how the music of ''Guru'' was born|work=The Telegraph|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1061222/asp/etc/story_7144101.asp|accessdate=3 May 2014|date=22 December 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081024030524/http://www.telegraphindia.com/1061222/asp/etc/story_7144101.asp|archive-date=24 October 2008|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Another Ratnam-Rahman hit, \"[[Chaiyya Chaiyya]]\" from ''Dil Se..'' also had lyrics written by Gulzar, based on the Sufi folk song \"Thaiyya Thaiyya\", with lyrics by poet [[Bulleh Shah]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/oldStory/54571/ |title=Music, like religion, has a soul. If you get this right, you can have different arrangements|date=7 September 2004|work=Indian Express|accessdate=3 May 2014}}</ref> For another collaboration with Rahman for [[Danny Boyle]]'s 2007 Hollywood film ''[[Slumdog Millionaire]]'', Rahman and Gulzar won the [[Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] for \"[[Jai Ho (song)|Jai Ho]]\" at the [[81st Academy Awards]]. The song received international acclaim and won him a [[Grammy Award]] (shared with Rahman) in the category of [[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media]].<ref name=\"IndiaToday-20140412\"/><ref name=ix/><ref name=ffall>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulzar.info/gulzarawards.html|title= Awards & Honours|work=www gulzar.info|year=2006|accessdate =17 April 2014}}</ref><ref name=gk>{{cite news|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/140412/entertainment-bollywood/article/gulzar-honoured-dadasaheb-phalke-award|title=Gulzar honoured with Dadasaheb Phalke Award|work=Deccan Chronicle|date=12 April 2014|accessdate=17 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140418120036/http://www.deccanchronicle.com/140412/entertainment-bollywood/article/gulzar-honoured-dadasaheb-phalke-award|archive-date=18 April 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He also wrote a song for the Pakistani Drama ''[[Shehryar Shehzadi]]'', and this song ''Teri Raza'', has been sung by [[Rekha Bhardwaj]] and was composed by [[Vishal Bhardwaj]].\n\n=== Direction ===\nAfter writing dialogues and screenplay for films such as ''Aashirwad'', ''Anand'' and ''Khamoshi'', Gulzar directed his first film ''[[Mere Apne]]'' (1971). The film was a remake of [[Tapan Sinha]]'s Bengali film ''[[Apanjan]]'' (1969). [[Meena Kumari]] played the lead role of Anandi Devi, an old widow caught in between the local fights of unemployed and tormented youngsters. Anandi Devi's death in one of the fights makes them realise the futility of violence. The film was rated \"Above Average\" at the box office.<ref name=toik/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=177&catName=MTk3MQ== |title=Box Office 1971 |publisher=Box Office India |accessdate=4 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020094955/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=177&catName=MTk3MQ== |archivedate=20 October 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He then directed ''[[Parichay (film)|Parichay]]'' and ''[[Koshish]]''. ''Parichay'' was based on a Bengali novel, ''Rangeen Uttarain'' by Raj Kumar Maitra and inspired from the Hollywood film ''[[The Sound of Music (film)|The Sound of Music]]''.<ref name=\"EHC_2003\">{{cite book | title = Encyclopaedia of Hindi cinema | editors = Gulzar, Govind Nihalani, Saibal Chatterjee | work = Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica (India) | publisher = Popular Prakashan | year = 2003 | isbn = 978-81-7991-066-5}}</ref> He wrote the story of ''Koshish'' based on the struggle faced by a deaf-dumb couple wherein [[Sanjeev Kumar]] won [[National Film Award for Best Actor]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://iffi.nic.in/Dff2011/Frm20thNFAAward.aspx?PdfName=20NFA.pdf |title=20th National Awards for excellence in Motion Pictures Arts & Science (1972) |publisher=Directorate of Film Festivals |accessdate=30 November 2011 |page=41 |format=PDF |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721170649/http://iffi.nic.in/Dff2011/Frm20thNFAAward.aspx?PdfName=20NFA.pdf |archive-date=21 July 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 1973, he directed ''[[Achanak (1973 film)|Achanak]]'', inspired by the 1958 murder case [[KM Nanavati v State of Maharashtra]], and the story writer [[Khwaja Ahmad Abbas]] earned a [[Filmfare Awards|Filmfare]] nomination for [[Filmfare Award for Best Story|Best Story]].<ref name=toik/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/news/specials/proj_tabloid/inspired1.shtml|title=Inspired by Nanavati|publisher=HindistanTimes.com|accessdate=3 December 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018155408/http://www.hindustantimes.com/news/specials/proj_tabloid/inspired1.shtml|archivedate=18 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Later he directed ''[[Aandhi]]'', based on the Hindi novel \"Kaali Aandhi\" by [[Kamleshwar (writer)|Kamleshwar]]. Along with various wins and nominations, the film also won [[Filmfare Critics Award for Best Movie]]. Although the film was believed to be based on the life of former Indian Prime Minister [[Indira Gandhi]], the film was based on life of [[Tarkeshwari Sinha]]. In the [[The Emergency (India)|1975's emergency]], the film was banned from theatres.<ref name=toik/><ref name=\"EHC_2003\"/><ref name=Reality>{{cite news |url = http://www.hinduonnet.com/2001/07/20/stories/09200221.htm |title = Where is reality? |author = V. Gangadhar |work = [[The Hindu]] |date = 20 July 2001 |accessdate = 3 December 2011 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100902131655/http://www.hinduonnet.com/2001/07/20/stories/09200221.htm |archive-date = 2 September 2010 |url-status = dead |df = dmy-all }}</ref> His next film  ''[[Khushboo (1975 film)|Khushboo]]'' was based on [[Sharat Chandra Chattopadhyay]]'s ''Pandit Mashay''. His ''[[Mausam (1975 film)|Mausam]]'', which won the National Award for 2nd Best Feature Film,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://iffi.nic.in/Dff2011/Frm23rdNFAAward.aspx?PdfName=23NFA.pdf|title=23rd National Film Festival|publisher=Directorate of Film Festivals|access-date=30 July 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526091043/http://iffi.nic.in/Dff2011/Frm23rdNFAAward.aspx?PdfName=23NFA.pdf|archive-date=26 May 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Filmfare Best Movie Award|Filmfare Best Movie]] and [[Filmfare Best Director Award|Filmfare Best Director]] awards, along with other six Filmfare nominations, was loosely based on the story ''\"Weather\"'', from the novel, ''[[The Judas Tree]]'', by [[A.J. Cronin]]. His 1982 film ''[[Angoor (1982 film)|Angoor]]'' was based on [[Shakespeare]]'s play ''[[The Comedy of Errors]]''.<ref name=ix/><ref name=toik/>\n\nHis films told stories of human relationships entangled in social issues. ''[[Libaas]]'' was a story of an extra-marital affair of an urban couple. Due to its objectionable subject, the film never got released in India.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rxpgnews.com/entertainment/Rice-Plate-brings-together-Naseer-Shabana_27569.shtml |title='Rice Plate' brings together Naseer, Shabana |date=12 May 2007 |accessdate=3 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930021844/http://www.rxpgnews.com/entertainment/Rice-Plate-brings-together-Naseer-Shabana_27569.shtml |archive-date=30 September 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> ''Mausam'' pictured a story of a father who tries to improve the life of his prostitute-daughter. In ''[[Maachis]]'', a young Punjabi boy engages in terrorism to fight a bad situation only to realise its temporary nature. ''[[Hu Tu Tu]]'' dealt with corruption in India and how a man decides to fight it.<ref name=ix/><ref name=toik/><ref name=\"Hu Tu Tu review\">{{cite web |url=http://in.rediff.com/movies/1999/jan/21hut.htm |title=The power game |publisher=[[Rediff.com]] |date=21 January 1999 |accessdate=3 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712111751/http://in.rediff.com/movies/1999/jan/21hut.htm |archive-date=12 July 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=Upperstall/>\n\nGulzar uses \"flashback\" in the narration of his stories very effectively (''Aandhi, Mausam, Ijaazat, Machis, Hu Tu Tu''). He also has mutual partnerships with various actors and other crew. The Gulzar \u2013 [[Sanjeev Kumar]] partnership resulted in few fine films (''Koshish, Aandhi, Mausam, Angoor, Namkeen'') which represent Sanjeev Kumar's finest work as an actor.<ref name=Upperstall/> Actors like [[Jeetendra]] (''Parichay, Khushboo, Kinara''), [[Vinod Khanna]] (''Achanak, Meera, Lekin'') and [[Hema Malini]] (''Khushboo, Kinara, Meera'') worked with Gulzar to gain respectability as artists and delivered some of their best and most introspective work in films.<ref name=Upperstall/> [[R D Burman]] composed songs for almost all the movies directed by him in the 1970s and the 1980s (''Parichay, Khushboo, Aandhi, Angoor, Ijaazat, Libaas''). Many of their popular songs were sung by [[Kishore Kumar]], [[Lata Mangeshkar]] and [[Asha Bhosle]]. These include \"Musafir Hoon Yaron\" (''Parichay''), \"Tere Bina Zindagi Se Koi\" (''Aandhi''), and \"[[Mera Kuch Samaan]]\" (''Ijaazat'').<ref name=Upperstall>{{cite web |url=http://www.upperstall.com/people/gulzar |title=Gulzar Profile: Upperstall |accessdate=3 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111110155239/http://www.upperstall.com/people/gulzar |archive-date=10 November 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n<!--- hidden quote\nGulzar says:<blockquote>''\"Music has a natural place in our lives. Right from the shloka you recite in your morning puja and the milkman who comes whistling on his cycle, to the fakir singing as he begs for alms and your mother humming around the kitchen... Music fills our spaces naturally. It will always be dear to us.\"'' </blockquote> --->\n\nIn 1988, Gulzar directed an [[eponym]]ous television serial ''[[Mirza Ghalib]]'', starring [[Naseeruddin Shah]] and broadcast on [[Doordarshan]]. Later he also directed ''Tahreer Munshi Premchand Ki'' about the novels of [[Premchand]].<ref name=ix/>\n\n=== Poetry ===\nGulzar primarily writes in Urdu and [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]; besides several dialects of [[Hindi]] such as [[Braj Bhasha]], [[Khariboli]], [[Haryanvi language|Haryanvi]] and [[Marwari language|Marwari]]. His poetry is in the [[Triveni (poetry)|Triveni]] type of stanza.<ref name=ix/> His poems are published in three compilations; ''Chand Pukhraaj Ka'', ''Raat Pashminey Ki'' and ''Pandrah Paanch Pachattar''. His short stories are published in ''Raavi-paar'' (also known as ''Dustkhat'' in Pakistan) and ''Dhuan'' (smoke).<ref name=ix/>\n\nFor the peace campaign ''[[Aman ki Asha]]'', jointly started by India's and Pakistan's leading media houses, Gulzar wrote the anthem \"Nazar Main Rehte Ho\", which was recorded by [[Shankar Mahadevan]] and [[Rahat Fateh Ali Khan]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/amankiasharticleshow/5415788.cms |work=The Times of India |title=Aman ki Asha |date=6 January 2010 |accessdate=4 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130205234050/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/amankiasharticleshow/5415788.cms |archive-date=5 February 2013 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Gulzar has written ghazals for Ghazal Maestro [[Jagjit Singh]]'s albums \"Marasim\" (1999) and \"Koi Baat Chale\" (2006).<ref>{{cite news|title=Brushes, bruises and splashes of life|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/brushes-bruises-and-splashes-of-life/article3231235.ece|date=3 November 2006|accessdate=16 April 2014|work =The Hindu|location=Chennai, India}}</ref>\n\n=== Other contributions ===\nGulzar has written lyrics and dialogues for several [[Doordarshan]] TV series including ''[[Jungle Book Sh\u014dnen Mowgli|Jungle Book]]'', ''[[Fushigi no Kuni no Alice|Alice in Wonderland]]'', ''[[Hello Zindagi]]'', ''Guchche'' and ''[[Potli Baba Ki]]'' with [[Vishal Bhardwaj]]. He has more recently written and narrated for the children's audiobook series ''[[Karadi Tales]]''.<ref name=ix/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.karaditales.com/AboutUs.aspx?From=Behind_the_scenes |title=Behind the Scenes: Karadi Tales |accessdate=4 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928162858/http://www.karaditales.com/AboutUs.aspx?From=Behind_the_scenes |archivedate=28 September 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\nGulzar is also associated with Aarushi,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bhopal/moved-by-special-kids-musical-feat-gulzar-presents-his-piano/articleshow/56654218.cms|title=Moved by special kids' musical feat, Gulzar presents his piano - Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=2019-02-05}}</ref> [[Eklavya foundation]] an NGO based in Bhopal, Madhya Pradesh working in the field of education.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/celebrity/gulzar-s-poems-raise-awareness-about-struggles-of-disabled_87818.html|title=Gulzar`s poems raise awareness about struggles of disabled|date=2011-05-15|website=Zee News|language=en|access-date=2019-02-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/mp/bhopal/news/gulzar-an-evening-with-gulzar-arushi-5894862.html|title=\u091c\u093c\u093f\u0928\u094d\u0926\u0917\u0940 \u0938\u0947 \u0932\u092c\u0930\u0947\u091c\u093c \u090f\u0915 \u0917\u0941\u0932\u091c\u093c\u093e\u0930 \u0936\u093e\u092e 16 \u0915\u094b \u0930\u0935\u0940\u0902\u0926\u094d\u0930 \u092d\u0935\u0928 \u092e\u0947\u0902, \u0928\u091c\u093c\u094d\u092e\u094b\u0902 \u0914\u0930 \u0905\u092b\u0938\u093e\u0928\u094b\u0902 \u092e\u0947\u0902 \u092e\u093f\u0932\u0947\u0902\u0917\u0947 \u0938\u0935\u093e\u0932\u094b\u0902 \u0915\u0947 \u091c\u0935\u093e\u092c|date=2018-06-14|website=Dainik Bhaskar|language=hi|access-date=2019-02-05}}</ref> He has written stories and poetry for the magazine [[Chakmak]].\n\n=== Academic ===\nIn April 2013, Gulzar was appointed as the Chancellor of the [[Assam University]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Lyricist-writer Gulzar appointed chancellor of Assam University|url=http://m.indiatoday.in/story/gulzar-appointed-chancellor-of-assam-university/1/268527.html|agency=IAN|place=Mumbai|date=30 April 2013|accessdate=16 April 2014|work=India Today|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415121335/http://m.indiatoday.in/story/gulzar-appointed-chancellor-of-assam-university/1/268527.html|archive-date=15 April 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nGulzar is married to actress [[Raakhee]]. The couple has a daughter, [[Meghna Gulzar]]. Meghna Gulzar grew up with her mother and father and, after completing her graduation in filmmaking from New York University, went on to become a director of films such as ''[[Filhaal]]'', ''[[Just Married (2007 film)|Just Married]]'', ''[[Dus Kahaniyaan]]'', [[Talvar (film)|Talvar]], ''[[Raazi]]'', and [[Chhapaak]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/asia/chhapaak-deepika-padukone-1203462409/|title=Bollywood Film \u2018Chhapaak\u2019 Makes Serious Splash|last=Dore|first=Shalini|last2=Dore|first2=Shalini|date=2020-01-10|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref> (for which Gulzar wrote the lyrics)<ref>{{cite news |title=Women directors scale Bollywood |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/low/entertainment/1832430.stm |publisher=BBC News |date=21 February 2002 |access-date=20 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040606000021/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/low/entertainment/1832430.stm |archive-date=6 June 2004 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and authored the biography of her father Gulzar, in 2004.<ref>{{cite news |title=On the Shelf |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/oldStory/38822/ |work=[[The Indian Express]] |date=11 January 2004 }}</ref>\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Gulzar}}\nAs on 2019, Gulzar has won a total of 36 awards and honours, including 5 [[National Film Awards]], 21 [[Filmfare Awards]], 1 [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]] (2008), 1 [[Grammy Award]] (2010), [[List of Sahitya Akademi Award winners for Urdu|2002 Sahitya Akademi Award for Urdu]], [[Padma Bhushan]] (2004), and 2013 [[Dadasaheb Phalke Award]].\n\n== Filmography ==\n{{main|Gulzar filmography}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{Cite book| title=Raavi Paar|author= Gulzar| year=1999| publisher=Rupa & Co.| isbn=8171673899}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Dhuan|author= Gulzar| year=2001| publisher=Sahitya Akademi Publications | isbn=8126019360}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Raat Pashmine Ki|author= Gulzar| year=2002| publisher=Rupa & Co.| isbn=8129102242}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Kharashein|author= Gulzar| year=2003| publisher=Radhakrishna Prakashan| isbn=9788171198498}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Meera|author= Gulzar| year=2004| publisher=Radhakrishna Prakashan| isbn=8171198813}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Pukhraj|author= Gulzar| year=2005| publisher=Rupa & Co.}}\n* {{Cite book| title=[[Triveni (poetry)|Triveni]]|author= Gulzar| year=2005| publisher=Rupa & Co.}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Autumn Moon|author= Gulzar| year=2006| publisher=Rupa & Co.| isbn=8129109778}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Kuchh Aur Nazmein|author= Gulzar| year=2008| publisher=Radhakrishna Prakashan| isbn=8171198929}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Magical Wishes: The Adventures Of Goopy & Bagha|author= Gulzar| year=2010| publisher=Scholastic | isbn=8184778449}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Mirza Ghalib A Biographical Scenario|first=|publisher=Rupa & Co.|year=2011|isbn=8129117177|location=|pages=|quote=|via=|author= Gulzar}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Selected Poems|author= Gulzar| year=2012| publisher=Penguin| isbn=0143418211}}\n* {{Cite book| title=My Favourite Stories : Boskys Panchatantra|author= Gulzar| year=2013| publisher=Rupa & Co.| isbn=8129121182}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Half a Rupee Stories|author= Gulzar| year=2013| publisher=Penguin| isbn=9780143068792}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Meelo Se Din|author= Gulzar| year=2013| publisher=Rupa & Co.| isbn=8129120011}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Green Poems |author= Gulzar| year=2014| publisher=Penguin Books India| isbn=0143422820}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Suspected Poems |author= Gulzar| year=2017| publisher=Penguin Books India| isbn=0670089613}}\n\n== Audiobooks ==\n* {{Cite book| title=Rangeela Geedhad|author= Gulzar| year=2000| publisher=Karadi Tales.| isbn=8186838422}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Parwaaz|author= Gulzar| year=2004| publisher=Karadi Tales.| isbn=8181900413}}\n\n== English novel ==\n''Two'' is Gulzar's [[debut novel]] released in English. It examines the status of refugees after partition. ''Two'' was originally written in Urdu.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livemint.com/Consumer/9tiHYLHqZT3BCuqdjeLffI/Two-Gulzars-debut-novel-in-English-brings-trauma-of-Parti.html|title=Two, Gulzar's debut novel in English, brings trauma of Partition 'painfully alive'|last=PTI|date=30 November 2017|website=Livemint.com|access-date=9 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171209100411/http://www.livemint.com/Consumer/9tiHYLHqZT3BCuqdjeLffI/Two-Gulzars-debut-novel-in-English-brings-trauma-of-Parti.html|archive-date=9 December 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Comics ==\nGulzar served as the Script Consultant for the ''[[Supremo (comics)|Supremo]]'' comic book series by Pammi Bakshi.<ref>{{cite web|title=Remembering Amitabh, the Supremo superhero|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-pammi-bakshi-on-supremo/20091110.htm|publisher=Rediff.com}}</ref>\n\n== Biographies ==\n* {{Cite book|title = In the Company of a Poet: Gulzar in Conversation with Nasreen Munni Kabir|first= Nasreen Munni|last= Kabir| year= 2012| publisher =Rainlight Rupa| isbn= 978-81-291-2083-0}}\n* {{Cite book|title = Echoes and Eloquences: The Life and Cinema of Gulzar|first= Saibal|last= Chatterjee| year= 2007| publisher =Rupa & Co.| isbn= 978-81-291-1235-4}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Because He Is...|first= Meghna| last= Gulzar| year=2004| publisher=Rupa & Co.| isbn=81-291-0364-8}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{commons category|Gulzar (poet)}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0347899|name=Gulzar}}\n*[https://dil-se-dil-tak.site/best-ghazal-in-hindi-and-urdu/ Gulzar Ghazal]\n\n\n\n\n\n{{Gulzar}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Gulzar|Awards for Gulzar]]\n| list =\n{{AcademyAwardBestOriginalSong 2001\u20132010}}\n{{Dadasaheb Phalke Award}}\n{{FilmfareAwardBestDirector}}\n{{FilmfareAwardBestDialogue}}\n{{FilmfareAwardBestStory}}\n{{FilmfareAwardBestLyricist}}\n{{FilmfareLifetimeAchievementAward}}\n{{Grammy Award for Best Song Written for Visual Media}}\n{{National Film Award Best Lyrics}}\n{{NationalFilmAwardBestScreenplay}}\n{{PadmaBhushanAwardRecipients 2000\u201309}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gulzar}}\n[[Category:Gulzar| ]]\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language lyricists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian poets]]\n[[Category:Indian male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Bhushan in arts]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Sahitya Akademi Award in Urdu]]\n[[Category:Best Original Song Academy Award-winning songwriters]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Punjab, India]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Punjab, India]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language film directors]]\n[[Category:Indian Sikhs]]\n[[Category:Urdu poets]]\n[[Category:Urdu short story writers]]\n[[Category:Urdu writers from India]]\n[[Category:Hindi poets]]\n[[Category:Filmfare Awards winners]]\n[[Category:People from Jhelum District]]\n[[Category:Punjabi people]]\n[[Category:Pseudonymous writers]]\n[[Category:Dadasaheb Phalke Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Indian Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian film directors]]\n[[Category:Best Lyrics National Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Original Screenplay National Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:Directors who won the Best Popular Film Providing Wholesome Entertainment National Film Award]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Gangadhar National Award]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{short description|Urdu author}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Gulzar\n| image              = Gulzar 2008 - still 38227.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birthname          = Sampooran Singh Kalra\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1934|08|18}}\n| birth_place        = [[Dina, Pakistan|Dina]], [[Punjab Province (British India)|Punjab]], [[British Raj|British India]]<br/> (present-day [[Punjab, Pakistan]])\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = [[Film director]], [[lyricist]], [[screenwriter]], [[Film Producer|producer]], [[poet]], [[author]]\n| yearsactive        = 1971\u201399 (as director) (''retired'')<br>1956\u2013present (as lyricist)\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Raakhee]]|1973}}\n| parents            = Makhan Singh Kalra and Sujan Kaur\n| children           = [[Meghna Gulzar]]\n| signature          = Gulzar signature.jpg\n| signature_alt      = Gulzar signature\n| nationality        = [[Indian people|Indian]]\n| awards             = [[Sahitya Akademi Award]] (2002) , [[Padma Bhushan]] (2004), [[Dadasaheb Phalke Award]] (2013), [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]] (2008)\n}}\n\n'''Sampooran Singh Kalra''' (born 18 August 1934), known popularly by his pen name '''Gulzar''' and also Gulzar Saab, is an [[Academy Awards|Oscar]]-winning Indian film director, lyricist and poet.<ref name=a>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2004/20040104/spectrum/book2.htm|title=The poet as the father|author=Amar Chandel|work=[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]]|date=4 January 2004|accessdate=23 December 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111227043558/http://www.tribuneindia.com/2004/20040104/spectrum/book2.htm|archive-date=27 December 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He started his career with music director [[S.D. Burman]] as a lyricist in the 1963 film ''Bandini'' and worked with many music directors including [[R. D. Burman]], [[Salil Chowdhury]], [[Vishal Bhardwaj]] and [[A. R. Rahman]]. He was awarded [[Padma Bhushan]] in 2004, the third-highest civilian award in India,<ref name=\"Padma Awards\">{{cite web | url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf | title=Padma Awards | publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India | date=2015 | accessdate=July 21, 2015 | archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6U68ulwpb?url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf | archive-date=15 November 2014 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> the [[Sahitya Akademi Award]] and the [[Dadasaheb Phalke Award]]&nbsp;\u2014 the highest award in Indian cinema. He has won several Indian [[National Film Awards]], 21 [[Filmfare Awards]], one Academy Award and one [[Grammy Award]].<ref name=\"IndiaToday-20140412\">{{cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/gulzar-to-get-dadasaheb-phalke-award/1/355422.html|title=Gulzar to get Dadasaheb Phalke award|date=12 April 2014|work=Indiatoday.in|publisher=India Today Group|accessdate=12 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503214231/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/gulzar-to-get-dadasaheb-phalke-award/1/355422.html|archive-date=3 May 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=ix>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/gulzar-selected-for-dadasaheb-phalke-award/|title=Gulzar selected for Dadasaheb Phalke Award|work=The Indian Express|date=13 April 2014|accessdate=14 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415073009/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/gulzar-selected-for-dadasaheb-phalke-award/|archive-date=15 April 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nGulzar also wrote poetry, dialogues and scripts. He directed films such as ''[[Aandhi]]'' and ''[[Mausam (1975 film)|Mausam]]'' during the 1970s and the TV series ''[[Mirza Ghalib (TV series)|Mirza Ghalib]]'' in the 1980s. He also directed ''[[Kirdaar]]'' in 1993.\n\n== Early life ==\nGulzar was born in a Kalra [[Sikh]] family, to Makhan Singh Kalra and Sujan Kaur, in [[Dina, Pakistan|Dina]], [[Jhelum District]], [[British Raj|British India]] (present-day [[Pakistan]]). In school, he had read translations of the works of [[Tagore]] which he recounted as one of his life's many turning points. Due to the [[Partition of India|partition]], his family split and he had to stop his studies and come to [[Mumbai]] (then called Bombay) to support his family. Sampooran took up many small jobs in Mumbai to eke out a living,  including one at a garage at ''Vichare motors'' on Bellasis road ([[Mumbai]]).<ref>{{cite AV media|title=Guftagoo - Interview with Gulzar|publisher=Rajyasabha TV|work=YouTube|date=31 July 2012|location=India}}</ref> There he used to touch up accident-damaged cars by mixing shades of paint, in his own words \"I had a knack for colours\". His father rebuked him for being a writer initially. He took the pen name '''Gulzar Deenvi''' and later simply '''Gulzar'''.<ref name = meghna>{{cite book| title = ''Because he is'' | author = [[Meghna Gulzar]] | publisher = Rupa & Co. | year = 2004}}</ref> In an interview with Rajyasabha TV, he recounted enjoying his work as a painter as it allowed him a lot of time to simultaneously read, write, attend college and be involved with the PWA (Progressive Writers Association).<ref name=a/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2009/20090315/spectrum/main6.htm |title=A life in music |work=The Tribune |date=15 March 2009 |accessdate=3 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130706014034/http://www.tribuneindia.com/2009/20090315/spectrum/main6.htm |archive-date=6 July 2013 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j5JXzf7sY0c |title=The Anupam Kher show |date=9 August 2015 |accessdate=5 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151015210853/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j5JXzf7sY0c |archive-date=15 October 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Lyricist ===\nIt was during his interactions in the PWA Sunday meetings that [[Shailendra (lyricist)|Shailendra]] and [[Bimal Roy]] encouraged him to join films. Gulzar began his career under film directors [[Bimal Roy]] and [[Hrishikesh Mukherjee]]. His book ''Ravi Paar'' has a narrative of Bimal Roy and the agony of creation. He started his career as a songwriter with the music director [[Sachin Dev Burman]] for the movie ''[[Bandini (1963 film)|Bandini]]'' (1963). In films, he found an environment associated with literature in the group he worked with, including Bimal Roy, most of whose films were based on literary works.<ref name=\"Man-Of-many-seasons\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-02-24/india/28029446_1_bandini-gulzar-first-film|title=Gulzar: Man Of many seasons|accessdate=14 August 2011|work=The Times of India|date=24 February 2009|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130103195628/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-02-24/india/28029446_1_bandini-gulzar-first-film|archive-date=3 January 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Shailendra (lyricist)|Shailendra]], who has penned the rest of the songs in the movie requested Gulzar to write the song \"Mora Gora Ang Layle\", sung by [[Lata Mangeshkar]].<ref name=\"IndiaToday-20140412\"/><ref name=ix/><ref name=toik>{{cite news|url=http://m.timesofindia.com/india/Director-lyricist-Gulzar-to-get-Dadasaheb-Phalke-award/articleshow/33670237.cms|title=Director-lyricist Gulzar to get Dadasaheb Phalke award|first=Avijit|last=Ghosh|work=The Times of India|date=12 April 2014|accessdate=14 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415005856/http://m.timesofindia.com/india/Director-lyricist-Gulzar-to-get-Dadasaheb-Phalke-award/articleshow/33670237.cms|archive-date=15 April 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nDirected and produced by [[Hrishikesh Mukherjee]], the 1968 film ''[[Aashirwad]]'' had dialogues and lyrics written by Gulzar. Song lyrics and poems written by Gulzar gave the poetic attribute and the \"much-needed additional dimension\"<ref name=Aashirwad/> to [[Ashok Kumar]]'s role in the film. Ashok Kumar received the Best Actor [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor|at the Filmfare]] and [[National Film Award for Best Actor|at the National Film Awards]] for this role.<ref name=\"Aashirwad\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2003/jan/25dinesh.htm|title=Aashirwad tugs at the heartstrings|date=January 2003|publisher=Rediff.com|author=[[Dinesh Raheja]]|accessdate=7 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503231912/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2003/jan/25dinesh.htm|archive-date=3 May 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Gulzar's lyrics, however, did not gain much attention until 1969's ''[[Khamoshi (1970 film)|Khamoshi]]'', where his song \"Humne Dekhi Hai Un Aankhon Ki Mehekti Khushboo\" (lit., \"I have seen the fragrance of those eyes\") became popular. Ganesh Anantharaman in his book ''Bollywood Melodies'' describes Gulzar's lyrics, with the purposeful mixing of the senses, to be \"daringly defiant\".<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lmrSLuBwbKkC&pg=PA69#v=onepage&q=gulzar | title=Bollywood Melodies: A History of the Hindi Film Song | publisher=Penguin Books India | author=Anantharaman, Ganesh | year=2008 | page=122 | isbn=0143063405 |accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref>{{efn|Author Ganesh Anantharaman's book ''Bollywood Melodies'' won the [[National Film Award for Best Book on Cinema|Best Book on Cinema award]] at the [[56th National Film Awards]].}}<ref name=\"56thawardgiven\">{{cite web|title=130 awardees receive the 56th national film awards from President|url=http://pib.nic.in/release/rel_print_page.asp?relid=59802|publisher=[[Press Information Bureau]] (PIB), India|accessdate=4 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503231806/http://pib.nic.in/release/rel_print_page.asp?relid=59802|archive-date=3 May 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> For the 1971 film ''[[Guddi (1971 film)|Guddi]]'', he penned two songs, of which \"Humko Man Ki Shakti Dena\" was a prayer which is still sung in many schools in India.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gGAyEpXtK3UC&pg=PA76#v=onepage&q=gulzar%20song | title=The Desai Trio and the Movie Industry of India | publisher=Author House | author=Gavankar, Nilu | year=2011 | page=76 | isbn=9781468599817 |accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nAs a lyricist, Gulzar had a close association with the music director [[Rahul Dev Burman]]. He has also worked with [[Sachin Dev Burman]], [[Shankar Jaikishan]], [[Hemanta Kumar Mukhopadhyay|Hemant Kumar]], [[Laxmikant-Pyarelal]], [[Madan Mohan (music director)|Madan Mohan]], [[Rajesh Roshan]], and [[Anu Malik]].<ref name=\"IndiaToday-20140412\"/><ref name=ix/><ref name=toik/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/gulzar-pancham-was-an-anchor-in-my-life/638840/ |title=Gulzar: Pancham was an anchor in my life |date=26 June 2010 |accessdate=23 December 2011 |publisher=[[Screen (magazine)|Screen]]/Indian Express |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100701220155/http://www.indianexpress.com/news/gulzar-pancham-was-an-anchor-in-my-life/638840/ |archive-date=1 July 2010 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Gulzar worked with [[Salil Chowdhury]] in ''[[Anand (1971 film)|Anand]]'' (1971) and ''[[Mere Apne]]'' (1971); [[Madan Mohan]] in ''[[Mausam (1975 film)|Mausam]]'' (1975), and more recently with [[Vishal Bhardwaj]] in ''[[Maachis]]'' (1996), ''[[Omkara (2006 film)|Omkara]]'' (2006) and ''[[Kaminey]]'' (2009); [[A. R. Rahman]] in ''[[Dil Se..]]'' (1998), ''[[Guru (2007 film)|Guru]]'' (2007), ''[[Slumdog Millionaire]]'' (2008) and ''[[Raavan]]'' (2010) and [[Shankar\u2013Ehsaan\u2013Loy]] in ''[[Bunty Aur Babli]]'' (2005).<ref name=\"IndiaToday-20140412\"/><ref name=ix/><ref name=toik/> Gulzar took inspiration from [[Amir Khusrow]]'s \"Ay Sarbathe Aashiqui\" to pen \"Ay Hairathe Aashiqui\" for [[Mani Ratnam]]'s 2007 Hindi film ''[[Guru (soundtrack)|Guru]]'', which had music composed by [[A. R. Rahman]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Rahman on how the music of ''Guru'' was born|work=The Telegraph|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1061222/asp/etc/story_7144101.asp|accessdate=3 May 2014|date=22 December 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081024030524/http://www.telegraphindia.com/1061222/asp/etc/story_7144101.asp|archive-date=24 October 2008|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Another Ratnam-Rahman hit, \"[[Chaiyya Chaiyya]]\" from ''Dil Se..'' also had lyrics written by Gulzar, based on the Sufi folk song \"Thaiyya Thaiyya\", with lyrics by poet [[Bulleh Shah]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/oldStory/54571/ |title=Music, like religion, has a soul. If you get this right, you can have different arrangements|date=7 September 2004|work=Indian Express|accessdate=3 May 2014}}</ref> For another collaboration with Rahman for [[Danny Boyle]]'s 2007 Hollywood film ''[[Slumdog Millionaire]]'', Rahman and Gulzar won the [[Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] for \"[[Jai Ho (song)|Jai Ho]]\" at the [[81st Academy Awards]]. The song received international acclaim and won him a [[Grammy Award]] (shared with Rahman) in the category of [[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media]].<ref name=\"IndiaToday-20140412\"/><ref name=ix/><ref name=ffall>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulzar.info/gulzarawards.html|title= Awards & Honours|work=www gulzar.info|year=2006|accessdate =17 April 2014}}</ref><ref name=gk>{{cite news|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/140412/entertainment-bollywood/article/gulzar-honoured-dadasaheb-phalke-award|title=Gulzar honoured with Dadasaheb Phalke Award|work=Deccan Chronicle|date=12 April 2014|accessdate=17 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140418120036/http://www.deccanchronicle.com/140412/entertainment-bollywood/article/gulzar-honoured-dadasaheb-phalke-award|archive-date=18 April 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He also wrote a song for the Pakistani Drama ''[[Shehryar Shehzadi]]'', and this song ''Teri Raza'', has been sung by [[Rekha Bhardwaj]] and was composed by [[Vishal Bhardwaj]].\n\n=== Direction ===\nAfter writing dialogues and screenplay for films such as ''Aashirwad'', ''Anand'' and ''Khamoshi'', Gulzar directed his first film ''[[Mere Apne]]'' (1971). The film was a remake of [[Tapan Sinha]]'s Bengali film ''[[Apanjan]]'' (1969). [[Meena Kumari]] played the lead role of Anandi Devi, an old widow caught in between the local fights of unemployed and tormented youngsters. Anandi Devi's death in one of the fights makes them realise the futility of violence. The film was rated \"Above Average\" at the box office.<ref name=toik/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=177&catName=MTk3MQ== |title=Box Office 1971 |publisher=Box Office India |accessdate=4 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020094955/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=177&catName=MTk3MQ== |archivedate=20 October 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He then directed ''[[Parichay (film)|Parichay]]'' and ''[[Koshish]]''. ''Parichay'' was based on a Bengali novel, ''Rangeen Uttarain'' by Raj Kumar Maitra and inspired from the Hollywood film ''[[The Sound of Music (film)|The Sound of Music]]''.<ref name=\"EHC_2003\">{{cite book | title = Encyclopaedia of Hindi cinema | editors = Gulzar, Govind Nihalani, Saibal Chatterjee | work = Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica (India) | publisher = Popular Prakashan | year = 2003 | isbn = 978-81-7991-066-5}}</ref> He wrote the story of ''Koshish'' based on the struggle faced by a deaf-dumb couple wherein [[Sanjeev Kumar]] won [[National Film Award for Best Actor]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://iffi.nic.in/Dff2011/Frm20thNFAAward.aspx?PdfName=20NFA.pdf |title=20th National Awards for excellence in Motion Pictures Arts & Science (1972) |publisher=Directorate of Film Festivals |accessdate=30 November 2011 |page=41 |format=PDF |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721170649/http://iffi.nic.in/Dff2011/Frm20thNFAAward.aspx?PdfName=20NFA.pdf |archive-date=21 July 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 1973, he directed ''[[Achanak (1973 film)|Achanak]]'', inspired by the 1958 murder case [[KM Nanavati v State of Maharashtra]], and the story writer [[Khwaja Ahmad Abbas]] earned a [[Filmfare Awards|Filmfare]] nomination for [[Filmfare Award for Best Story|Best Story]].<ref name=toik/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/news/specials/proj_tabloid/inspired1.shtml|title=Inspired by Nanavati|publisher=HindistanTimes.com|accessdate=3 December 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018155408/http://www.hindustantimes.com/news/specials/proj_tabloid/inspired1.shtml|archivedate=18 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Later he directed ''[[Aandhi]]'', based on the Hindi novel \"Kaali Aandhi\" by [[Kamleshwar (writer)|Kamleshwar]]. Along with various wins and nominations, the film also won [[Filmfare Critics Award for Best Movie]]. Although the film was believed to be based on the life of former Indian Prime Minister [[Indira Gandhi]], the film was based on life of [[Tarkeshwari Sinha]]. In the [[The Emergency (India)|1975's emergency]], the film was banned from theatres.<ref name=toik/><ref name=\"EHC_2003\"/><ref name=Reality>{{cite news |url = http://www.hinduonnet.com/2001/07/20/stories/09200221.htm |title = Where is reality? |author = V. Gangadhar |work = [[The Hindu]] |date = 20 July 2001 |accessdate = 3 December 2011 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100902131655/http://www.hinduonnet.com/2001/07/20/stories/09200221.htm |archive-date = 2 September 2010 |url-status = dead |df = dmy-all }}</ref> His next film  ''[[Khushboo (1975 film)|Khushboo]]'' was based on [[Sharat Chandra Chattopadhyay]]'s ''Pandit Mashay''. His ''[[Mausam (1975 film)|Mausam]]'', which won the National Award for 2nd Best Feature Film,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://iffi.nic.in/Dff2011/Frm23rdNFAAward.aspx?PdfName=23NFA.pdf|title=23rd National Film Festival|publisher=Directorate of Film Festivals|access-date=30 July 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526091043/http://iffi.nic.in/Dff2011/Frm23rdNFAAward.aspx?PdfName=23NFA.pdf|archive-date=26 May 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Filmfare Best Movie Award|Filmfare Best Movie]] and [[Filmfare Best Director Award|Filmfare Best Director]] awards, along with other six Filmfare nominations, was loosely based on the story ''\"Weather\"'', from the novel, ''[[The Judas Tree]]'', by [[A.J. Cronin]]. His 1982 film ''[[Angoor (1982 film)|Angoor]]'' was based on [[Shakespeare]]'s play ''[[The Comedy of Errors]]''.<ref name=ix/><ref name=toik/>\n\nHis films told stories of human relationships entangled in social issues. ''[[Libaas]]'' was a story of an extra-marital affair of an urban couple. Due to its objectionable subject, the film never got released in India.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rxpgnews.com/entertainment/Rice-Plate-brings-together-Naseer-Shabana_27569.shtml |title='Rice Plate' brings together Naseer, Shabana |date=12 May 2007 |accessdate=3 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930021844/http://www.rxpgnews.com/entertainment/Rice-Plate-brings-together-Naseer-Shabana_27569.shtml |archive-date=30 September 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> ''Mausam'' pictured a story of a father who tries to improve the life of his prostitute-daughter. In ''[[Maachis]]'', a young Punjabi boy engages in terrorism to fight a bad situation only to realise its temporary nature. ''[[Hu Tu Tu]]'' dealt with corruption in India and how a man decides to fight it.<ref name=ix/><ref name=toik/><ref name=\"Hu Tu Tu review\">{{cite web |url=http://in.rediff.com/movies/1999/jan/21hut.htm |title=The power game |publisher=[[Rediff.com]] |date=21 January 1999 |accessdate=3 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712111751/http://in.rediff.com/movies/1999/jan/21hut.htm |archive-date=12 July 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=Upperstall/>\n\nGulzar uses \"flashback\" in the narration of his stories very effectively (''Aandhi, Mausam, Ijaazat, Machis, Hu Tu Tu''). He also has mutual partnerships with various actors and other crew. The Gulzar \u2013 [[Sanjeev Kumar]] partnership resulted in few fine films (''Koshish, Aandhi, Mausam, Angoor, Namkeen'') which represent Sanjeev Kumar's finest work as an actor.<ref name=Upperstall/> Actors like [[Jeetendra]] (''Parichay, Khushboo, Kinara''), [[Vinod Khanna]] (''Achanak, Meera, Lekin'') and [[Hema Malini]] (''Khushboo, Kinara, Meera'') worked with Gulzar to gain respectability as artists and delivered some of their best and most introspective work in films.<ref name=Upperstall/> [[R D Burman]] composed songs for almost all the movies directed by him in the 1970s and the 1980s (''Parichay, Khushboo, Aandhi, Angoor, Ijaazat, Libaas''). Many of their popular songs were sung by [[Kishore Kumar]], [[Lata Mangeshkar]] and [[Asha Bhosle]]. These include \"Musafir Hoon Yaron\" (''Parichay''), \"Tere Bina Zindagi Se Koi\" (''Aandhi''), and \"[[Mera Kuch Samaan]]\" (''Ijaazat'').<ref name=Upperstall>{{cite web |url=http://www.upperstall.com/people/gulzar |title=Gulzar Profile: Upperstall |accessdate=3 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111110155239/http://www.upperstall.com/people/gulzar |archive-date=10 November 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n<!--- hidden quote\nGulzar says:<blockquote>''\"Music has a natural place in our lives. Right from the shloka you recite in your morning puja and the milkman who comes whistling on his cycle, to the fakir singing as he begs for alms and your mother humming around the kitchen... Music fills our spaces naturally. It will always be dear to us.\"'' </blockquote> --->\n\nIn 1988, Gulzar directed an [[eponym]]ous television serial ''[[Mirza Ghalib]]'', starring [[Naseeruddin Shah]] and broadcast on [[Doordarshan]]. Later he also directed ''Tahreer Munshi Premchand Ki'' about the novels of [[Premchand]].<ref name=ix/>\n\n=== Poetry ===\nGulzar primarily writes in Urdu and [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]; besides several dialects of [[Hindi]] such as [[Braj Bhasha]], [[Khariboli]], [[Haryanvi language|Haryanvi]] and [[Marwari language|Marwari]]. His poetry is in the [[Triveni (poetry)|Triveni]] type of stanza.<ref name=ix/> His poems are published in three compilations; ''Chand Pukhraaj Ka'', ''Raat Pashminey Ki'' and ''Pandrah Paanch Pachattar''. His short stories are published in ''Raavi-paar'' (also known as ''Dustkhat'' in Pakistan) and ''Dhuan'' (smoke).<ref name=ix/>\n\nFor the peace campaign ''[[Aman ki Asha]]'', jointly started by India's and Pakistan's leading media houses, Gulzar wrote the anthem \"Nazar Main Rehte Ho\", which was recorded by [[Shankar Mahadevan]] and [[Rahat Fateh Ali Khan]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/amankiasharticleshow/5415788.cms |work=The Times of India |title=Aman ki Asha |date=6 January 2010 |accessdate=4 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130205234050/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/amankiasharticleshow/5415788.cms |archive-date=5 February 2013 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Gulzar has written ghazals for Ghazal Maestro [[Jagjit Singh]]'s albums \"Marasim\" (1999) and \"Koi Baat Chale\" (2006).<ref>{{cite news|title=Brushes, bruises and splashes of life|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/brushes-bruises-and-splashes-of-life/article3231235.ece|date=3 November 2006|accessdate=16 April 2014|work =The Hindu|location=Chennai, India}}</ref>\n\n=== Other contributions ===\nGulzar has written lyrics and dialogues for several [[Doordarshan]] TV series including ''[[Jungle Book Sh\u014dnen Mowgli|Jungle Book]]'', ''[[Fushigi no Kuni no Alice|Alice in Wonderland]]'', ''[[Hello Zindagi]]'', ''Guchche'' and ''[[Potli Baba Ki]]'' with [[Vishal Bhardwaj]]. He has more recently written and narrated for the children's audiobook series ''[[Karadi Tales]]''.<ref name=ix/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.karaditales.com/AboutUs.aspx?From=Behind_the_scenes |title=Behind the Scenes: Karadi Tales |accessdate=4 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928162858/http://www.karaditales.com/AboutUs.aspx?From=Behind_the_scenes |archivedate=28 September 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\nGulzar is also associated with Aarushi,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bhopal/moved-by-special-kids-musical-feat-gulzar-presents-his-piano/articleshow/56654218.cms|title=Moved by special kids' musical feat, Gulzar presents his piano - Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=2019-02-05}}</ref> [[Eklavya foundation]] an NGO based in Bhopal, Madhya Pradesh working in the field of education.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/celebrity/gulzar-s-poems-raise-awareness-about-struggles-of-disabled_87818.html|title=Gulzar`s poems raise awareness about struggles of disabled|date=2011-05-15|website=Zee News|language=en|access-date=2019-02-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/mp/bhopal/news/gulzar-an-evening-with-gulzar-arushi-5894862.html|title=\u091c\u093c\u093f\u0928\u094d\u0926\u0917\u0940 \u0938\u0947 \u0932\u092c\u0930\u0947\u091c\u093c \u090f\u0915 \u0917\u0941\u0932\u091c\u093c\u093e\u0930 \u0936\u093e\u092e 16 \u0915\u094b \u0930\u0935\u0940\u0902\u0926\u094d\u0930 \u092d\u0935\u0928 \u092e\u0947\u0902, \u0928\u091c\u093c\u094d\u092e\u094b\u0902 \u0914\u0930 \u0905\u092b\u0938\u093e\u0928\u094b\u0902 \u092e\u0947\u0902 \u092e\u093f\u0932\u0947\u0902\u0917\u0947 \u0938\u0935\u093e\u0932\u094b\u0902 \u0915\u0947 \u091c\u0935\u093e\u092c|date=2018-06-14|website=Dainik Bhaskar|language=hi|access-date=2019-02-05}}</ref> He has written stories and poetry for the magazine [[Chakmak]].\n\n=== Academic ===\nIn April 2013, Gulzar was appointed as the Chancellor of the [[Assam University]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Lyricist-writer Gulzar appointed chancellor of Assam University|url=http://m.indiatoday.in/story/gulzar-appointed-chancellor-of-assam-university/1/268527.html|agency=IAN|place=Mumbai|date=30 April 2013|accessdate=16 April 2014|work=India Today|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415121335/http://m.indiatoday.in/story/gulzar-appointed-chancellor-of-assam-university/1/268527.html|archive-date=15 April 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nGulzar is married to actress [[Raakhee]]. The couple has a daughter, [[Meghna Gulzar]]. Meghna Gulzar grew up with her mother and father and, after completing her graduation in filmmaking from New York University, went on to become a director of films such as ''[[Filhaal]]'', ''[[Just Married (2007 film)|Just Married]]'', ''[[Dus Kahaniyaan]]'', [[Talvar (film)|Talvar]], ''[[Raazi]]'', and [[Chhapaak]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/asia/chhapaak-deepika-padukone-1203462409/|title=Bollywood Film \u2018Chhapaak\u2019 Makes Serious Splash|last=Dore|first=Shalini|last2=Dore|first2=Shalini|date=2020-01-10|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref> (for which Gulzar wrote the lyrics)<ref>{{cite news |title=Women directors scale Bollywood |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/low/entertainment/1832430.stm |publisher=BBC News |date=21 February 2002 |access-date=20 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040606000021/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/low/entertainment/1832430.stm |archive-date=6 June 2004 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and authored the biography of her father Gulzar, in 2004.<ref>{{cite news |title=On the Shelf |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/oldStory/38822/ |work=[[The Indian Express]] |date=11 January 2004 }}</ref>\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Gulzar}}\nAs on 2019, Gulzar has won a total of 36 awards and honours, including 5 [[National Film Awards]], 21 [[Filmfare Awards]], 1 [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]] (2008), 1 [[Grammy Award]] (2010), [[List of Sahitya Akademi Award winners for Urdu|2002 Sahitya Akademi Award for Urdu]], [[Padma Bhushan]] (2004), and 2013 [[Dadasaheb Phalke Award]].\n\n== Filmography ==\n{{main|Gulzar filmography}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{Cite book| title=Raavi Paar|author= Gulzar| year=1999| publisher=Rupa & Co.| isbn=8171673899}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Dhuan|author= Gulzar| year=2001| publisher=Sahitya Akademi Publications | isbn=8126019360}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Raat Pashmine Ki|author= Gulzar| year=2002| publisher=Rupa & Co.| isbn=8129102242}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Kharashein|author= Gulzar| year=2003| publisher=Radhakrishna Prakashan| isbn=9788171198498}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Meera|author= Gulzar| year=2004| publisher=Radhakrishna Prakashan| isbn=8171198813}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Pukhraj|author= Gulzar| year=2005| publisher=Rupa & Co.}}\n* {{Cite book| title=[[Triveni (poetry)|Triveni]]|author= Gulzar| year=2005| publisher=Rupa & Co.}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Autumn Moon|author= Gulzar| year=2006| publisher=Rupa & Co.| isbn=8129109778}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Kuchh Aur Nazmein|author= Gulzar| year=2008| publisher=Radhakrishna Prakashan| isbn=8171198929}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Magical Wishes: The Adventures Of Goopy & Bagha|author= Gulzar| year=2010| publisher=Scholastic | isbn=8184778449}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Mirza Ghalib A Biographical Scenario|first=|publisher=Rupa & Co.|year=2011|isbn=8129117177|location=|pages=|quote=|via=|author= Gulzar}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Selected Poems|author= Gulzar| year=2012| publisher=Penguin| isbn=0143418211}}\n* {{Cite book| title=My Favourite Stories : Boskys Panchatantra|author= Gulzar| year=2013| publisher=Rupa & Co.| isbn=8129121182}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Half a Rupee Stories|author= Gulzar| year=2013| publisher=Penguin| isbn=9780143068792}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Meelo Se Din|author= Gulzar| year=2013| publisher=Rupa & Co.| isbn=8129120011}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Green Poems |author= Gulzar| year=2014| publisher=Penguin Books India| isbn=0143422820}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Suspected Poems |author= Gulzar| year=2017| publisher=Penguin Books India| isbn=0670089613}}\n\n== Audiobooks ==\n* {{Cite book| title=Rangeela Geedhad|author= Gulzar| year=2000| publisher=Karadi Tales.| isbn=8186838422}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Parwaaz|author= Gulzar| year=2004| publisher=Karadi Tales.| isbn=8181900413}}\n\n== English novel ==\n''Two'' is Gulzar's [[debut novel]] released in English. It examines the status of refugees after partition. ''Two'' was originally written in Urdu.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livemint.com/Consumer/9tiHYLHqZT3BCuqdjeLffI/Two-Gulzars-debut-novel-in-English-brings-trauma-of-Parti.html|title=Two, Gulzar's debut novel in English, brings trauma of Partition 'painfully alive'|last=PTI|date=30 November 2017|website=Livemint.com|access-date=9 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171209100411/http://www.livemint.com/Consumer/9tiHYLHqZT3BCuqdjeLffI/Two-Gulzars-debut-novel-in-English-brings-trauma-of-Parti.html|archive-date=9 December 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Comics ==\nGulzar served as the Script Consultant for the ''[[Supremo (comics)|Supremo]]'' comic book series by Pammi Bakshi.<ref>{{cite web|title=Remembering Amitabh, the Supremo superhero|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-pammi-bakshi-on-supremo/20091110.htm|publisher=Rediff.com}}</ref>\n\n== Biographies ==\n* {{Cite book|title = In the Company of a Poet: Gulzar in Conversation with Nasreen Munni Kabir|first= Nasreen Munni|last= Kabir| year= 2012| publisher =Rainlight Rupa| isbn= 978-81-291-2083-0}}\n* {{Cite book|title = Echoes and Eloquences: The Life and Cinema of Gulzar|first= Saibal|last= Chatterjee| year= 2007| publisher =Rupa & Co.| isbn= 978-81-291-1235-4}}\n* {{Cite book| title=Because He Is...|first= Meghna| last= Gulzar| year=2004| publisher=Rupa & Co.| isbn=81-291-0364-8}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{commons category|Gulzar (poet)}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0347899|name=Gulzar}}\n\n\n\n\n{{Gulzar}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Gulzar|Awards for Gulzar]]\n| list =\n{{AcademyAwardBestOriginalSong 2001\u20132010}}\n{{Dadasaheb Phalke Award}}\n{{FilmfareAwardBestDirector}}\n{{FilmfareAwardBestDialogue}}\n{{FilmfareAwardBestStory}}\n{{FilmfareAwardBestLyricist}}\n{{FilmfareLifetimeAchievementAward}}\n{{Grammy Award for Best Song Written for Visual Media}}\n{{National Film Award Best Lyrics}}\n{{NationalFilmAwardBestScreenplay}}\n{{PadmaBhushanAwardRecipients 2000\u201309}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gulzar}}\n[[Category:Gulzar| ]]\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language lyricists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian poets]]\n[[Category:Indian male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Bhushan in arts]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Sahitya Akademi Award in Urdu]]\n[[Category:Best Original Song Academy Award-winning songwriters]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Punjab, India]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Punjab, India]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language film directors]]\n[[Category:Indian Sikhs]]\n[[Category:Urdu poets]]\n[[Category:Urdu short story writers]]\n[[Category:Urdu writers from India]]\n[[Category:Hindi poets]]\n[[Category:Filmfare Awards winners]]\n[[Category:People from Jhelum District]]\n[[Category:Punjabi people]]\n[[Category:Pseudonymous writers]]\n[[Category:Dadasaheb Phalke Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Indian Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian film directors]]\n[[Category:Best Lyrics National Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Original Screenplay National Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:Directors who won the Best Popular Film Providing Wholesome Entertainment National Film Award]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Gangadhar National Award]]\n", "name_user": "Seodesigns", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Need to add gulzar ghazal", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gulzar"}
{"title_page": "C\u00e9sar Ruiz", "text_new": "{{about||the Cuban sprinter|C\u00e9sar Ruiz (athlete)|the Filipino poet|C\u00e9sar Ruiz Aquino|the American football center|Cesar Ruiz (American football)}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{BLP sources|date=November 2008}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = C\u00e9sar Ruiz\n| image = \n| fullname = C\u00e9sar Augusto Ruiz S\u00e1nchez\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1990|01|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Lima, Peru]]\n| height = 1.78 m\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthclubs1 = [[Sporting Cristal]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| years1 = 2007\u20132010\n| years2 = 2009\u20132010\n| years3 = 2011\n| years4 = 2012\n| years5 = 2013\n| years6 = 2014\u20132016\n| years7 = 2018\n| clubs1 = [[Sporting Cristal]]\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Coronel Bolognesi]] (loan)\n| clubs3 = [[Hijos de Acosvinchos]]\n| clubs4 = [[Sport Boys]]\n| clubs5 = [[Le\u00f3n de Hu\u00e1nuco]]\n| clubs6 = [[Sport Huancayo]]\n| clubs7 = [[Uni\u00f3n Comercio]]\n| caps2 = 10\n| goals2 = 0\n| goals3 = 1\n| caps3 = 20\n| caps4 = 38\n| goals4 = 3\n| caps5 = 15\n| goals5 = 0\n| caps6 = 48\n| goals6 = 0\n| caps7 = 10\n| goals7 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2007\n| nationalteam1 = [[Peru national under-17 football team|Peru U-17]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 23\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| pcupdate = 27 January 2019\n| ntupdate = \n}}\n\n'''C\u00e9sar Augusto Ruiz S\u00e1nchez''' (born 10 January 1990 in [[Lima, Peru]]) is a [[Peru]]vian [[association football|footballer]] who most recently played for [[Uni\u00f3n Comercio]].\n\n==Profile==\nComing from the popular district of Puente Piedra, C\u00e9sar Ruiz joined Sporting Cristal in 1999.\nIn 2007 C\u00e9sar Ruiz, along with 8 other U-20 players, were called up to the first team. For 2009, he was on loan at [[Coronel Bolognesi]].\n\nHe was also part of the [[Peru national under-17 football team|Peru U-17 team]] that reached the quarterfinal stage at the [[2007 FIFA U-17 World Cup]] played in [[South Korea]].<ref>{{FIFA player|275271}}</ref>\n\nAfter playing [[Copa Peru]] with [[Coronel Bolognesi]] when they were relegated from the first division, he played for [[Hijos de Acosvinchos]]. This year signed a contract with Sport Boys.<ref name=\"Cesar Ruiz out of the shell\">[http://trome.pe/deportes/1411486/noticia-cesar-ruiz-salio-cascaron Trome.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120508221607/http://trome.pe/deportes/1411486/noticia-cesar-ruiz-salio-cascaron |date=8 May 2012 }}, 7 May 2012.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerway|cesar-ruiz/24030}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ruiz, Cesar}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Lima]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Peruvian footballers]]\n[[Category:Sporting Cristal footballers]]\n[[Category:Coronel Bolognesi footballers]]\n[[Category:Sport Boys footballers]]\n[[Category:Le\u00f3n de Hu\u00e1nuco footballers]]\n[[Category:Sport Huancayo footballers]]\n[[Category:Peruvian Primera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n\n\n{{Peru-footy-midfielder-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Cuban sprinter|C\u00e9sar Ruiz (athlete)}}\n{{for|the Filipino poet|C\u00e9sar Ruiz Aquino}}\n{{for|the American football center|Cesar Ruiz (American football)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{BLP sources|date=November 2008}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = C\u00e9sar Ruiz\n| image = \n| fullname = C\u00e9sar Augusto Ruiz S\u00e1nchez\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1990|01|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Lima, Peru]]\n| height = 1.78 m\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthclubs1 = [[Sporting Cristal]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| years1 = 2007\u20132010\n| years2 = 2009\u20132010\n| years3 = 2011\n| years4 = 2012\n| years5 = 2013\n| years6 = 2014\u20132016\n| years7 = 2018\n| clubs1 = [[Sporting Cristal]]\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Coronel Bolognesi]] (loan)\n| clubs3 = [[Hijos de Acosvinchos]]\n| clubs4 = [[Sport Boys]]\n| clubs5 = [[Le\u00f3n de Hu\u00e1nuco]]\n| clubs6 = [[Sport Huancayo]]\n| clubs7 = [[Uni\u00f3n Comercio]]\n| caps2 = 10\n| goals2 = 0\n| goals3 = 1\n| caps3 = 20\n| caps4 = 38\n| goals4 = 3\n| caps5 = 15\n| goals5 = 0\n| caps6 = 48\n| goals6 = 0\n| caps7 = 10\n| goals7 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2007\n| nationalteam1 = [[Peru national under-17 football team|Peru U-17]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 23\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| pcupdate = 27 January 2019\n| ntupdate = \n}}\n\n'''C\u00e9sar Augusto Ruiz S\u00e1nchez''' (born 10 January 1990 in [[Lima, Peru]]) is a [[Peru]]vian [[association football|footballer]] who most recently played for [[Uni\u00f3n Comercio]].\n\n==Profile==\nComing from the popular district of Puente Piedra, C\u00e9sar Ruiz joined Sporting Cristal in 1999.\nIn 2007 C\u00e9sar Ruiz, along with 8 other U-20 players, were called up to the first team. For 2009, he was on loan at [[Coronel Bolognesi]].\n\nHe was also part of the [[Peru national under-17 football team|Peru U-17 team]] that reached the quarterfinal stage at the [[2007 FIFA U-17 World Cup]] played in [[South Korea]].<ref>{{FIFA player|275271}}</ref>\n\nAfter playing [[Copa Peru]] with [[Coronel Bolognesi]] when they were relegated from the first division, he played for [[Hijos de Acosvinchos]]. This year signed a contract with Sport Boys.<ref name=\"Cesar Ruiz out of the shell\">[http://trome.pe/deportes/1411486/noticia-cesar-ruiz-salio-cascaron Trome.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120508221607/http://trome.pe/deportes/1411486/noticia-cesar-ruiz-salio-cascaron |date=8 May 2012 }}, 7 May 2012.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerway|cesar-ruiz/24030}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ruiz, Cesar}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Lima]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Peruvian footballers]]\n[[Category:Sporting Cristal footballers]]\n[[Category:Coronel Bolognesi footballers]]\n[[Category:Sport Boys footballers]]\n[[Category:Le\u00f3n de Hu\u00e1nuco footballers]]\n[[Category:Sport Huancayo footballers]]\n[[Category:Peruvian Primera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n\n\n{{Peru-footy-midfielder-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C%C3%A9sar_Ruiz"}
{"title_page": "MLS Cup 1997", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{short description|1997 edition of the MLS Cup}}\n{{Infobox football match\n| title\t= MLS Cup 1997\n| image\t= MLS Cup 97 logo.gif\n| event\t= [[MLS Cup]]\n| team1\t= [[D.C. United]]\n| team1score = 2\n| team2\t= [[Colorado Rapids]]\n| team2score = 1\n| details = \n| date = October 26, 1997 \n| stadium = [[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium]] \n| city = [[Washington, D.C.]], US\n| man_of_the_match1a = [[Jaime Moreno (footballer, born 1974)|Jaime Moreno]] (D.C. United) \n| referee = [[Brian Hall (referee)|Brian Hall]]\n| attendance = 57,431 \n| weather = Rain, {{convert|46|\u00b0F|\u00b0C}}\n| previous = [[MLS Cup 1996|1996]]\n| next = [[MLS Cup 1998|1998]]\n}}\n\n'''MLS Cup 1997''' was the second edition of the [[MLS Cup]], the post-season championship match of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS) in the United States. It was played on October 26, 1997, between [[D.C. United]] and the [[Colorado Rapids]] to determine the champion of the [[1997 Major League Soccer season|1997 season]]. The match was played in front of 57,431 spectators at [[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium|RFK Memorial Stadium]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]\n\nD.C. United were defending champions and finished atop the [[Eastern Conference (MLS)|Eastern Conference]] and the [[Supporters' Shield|overall league standings]] despite being strained by runs in multiple competitions. Colorado had overhauled their roster after finishing last overall in the 1996 season and qualified for the playoffs with a [[Win\u2013loss record|losing record]], finishing fourth in the [[Western Conference (MLS)|Western Conference]], but earned two [[upset (sports)|upset]] victories in the playoffs. As finalists, D.C. United and the Colorado Rapids both earned berths to play in the [[1998 CONCACAF Champions' Cup]].\n\nDuring a rainstorm that mirrored the [[MLS Cup 1996|previous final]], D.C. repeated as MLS Cup champions by winning 2\u20131. The hosts took a lead through [[Jaime Moreno (footballer, born 1974)|Jaime Moreno]] in the 37th minute and extended it with a header by [[Tony Sanneh]] in the 68th minute. Substitute [[Adri\u00e1n Paz]] scored a consolation goal for Colorado in the 75th minute, but the team were unable to draw level despite several chances. The announced crowd of 57,431 was the second-largest attendance for a sporting event at RFK Memorial Stadium.\n\n==Venue==\n[[File:RFK Stadium satellite view.png|thumb|left|Aerial view of [[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium|RFK Memorial Stadium]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], the host venue of MLS Cup 1997]]\n\n[[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium|RFK Memorial Stadium]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], the home of defending champions [[D.C. United]], was selected as the host of the second MLS Cup on December 17, 1996.<ref>{{cite news |date=December 18, 1996 |title=MLS likes weekend matches |page=D2 |work=[[The Mercury News]]}}</ref> The stadium was opened in 1961 and was primarily used for American football and baseball, but previously hosted the 1980 [[Soccer Bowl]] and the [[1996 U.S. Open Cup|1996 U.S. Open Cup Final]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 31, 1996 |title=United Captures Another Title |page=C1 |work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref> It also hosted several matches during the [[1994 FIFA World Cup]] and [[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|1996 Olympics men's soccer tournament]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 20, 2017 |title=American soccer made its home at aging, funky RFK Stadium |page= |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/soccer-insider/wp/2017/10/19/soccer-at-rfk-stadium-its-dirty-and-disgusting-and-ugly-but-its-ours/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe league sold 32,000 tickets for the final in mid-October after D.C. United advanced to the [[1997 MLS Cup Playoffs#Conference Finals|Conference Finals]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Stevens |date=October 15, 1997 |title=On Novel Field, D.C. Hopes To Say: Goodbye, Columbus |page=C2 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> After the team clinched an appearance in the final, the remainder of the stadium's 56,000 seats were sold out and 1,000 [[bleacher]] seats were added.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 21, 1997 |title=D.C. Is United for MLS Title Game |page=E1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n==Road to the final==\n\nThe [[MLS Cup]] is the post-season championship of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS), a professional club [[Association football|soccer]] league based in the United States that began play in 1996. The league's [[1997 Major League Soccer season|second season]] was contested by ten teams organized into two conferences, each playing 32 matches during the regular season from April to September. Teams faced opponents from the same conference four times during the regular season and from outside their conference three or four times.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=December 5, 1995 |title=Major League Soccer Sets Inaugural Schedule |page=C5 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-12-05/sports/sp-10453_1_major-league-soccer |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref> MLS continued to use the modified version of the sport's rules that it adopted for the 1996 season, including a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)#North American experiments|penalty shootout]] from {{convert|35|yd|m}} to decide tied matches (for which the winners earned one point) and a [[countdown clock]] that stopped during [[Ball in and out of play|dead plays]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Macguire |first=Eoghan |date=March 6, 2015 |title=MLS at 20: Sunrise on football's final frontier? |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2015/03/06/football/mls-20-sunrise-sunset/index.html |publisher=[[CNN]] |accessdate=March 7, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Dure22\">{{cite book |last=Dure |first=Beau |year=2010 |title=Long-Range Goals: The Success Story of Major League Soccer |pages=22\u201324 |publisher=[[Potomac Books]] |location=Washington, D.C. |isbn=978-1-59797-509-4 |oclc=500783910 |ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nThe top four teams from each conference qualified for the playoffs, which were organized into three rounds and played in October. The first two rounds, named the Conference Semifinals and Conference Finals, were [[two-legged tie|home-and-away]] series organized into a best-of-three format with a hosting advantage for the higher seed. The winners of the Conference Finals advanced to the single-match MLS Cup final, which would be held at a predetermined neutral venue.<ref name=\"MLS-2015\">{{cite news |last=Rodriguez |first=Alicia |date=October 21, 2015 |title=Audi MLS Cup Playoffs: Tracing the evolution of the postseason format since 1996 |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2015/10/21/audi-mls-cup-playoffs-tracing-evolution-postseason-format |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMLS Cup 1997 was contested by defending champions and hosts D.C. United, who finished first in the regular season standings, and the [[Colorado Rapids]], who finished fourth in the Western Conference. The two finalists swept through the playoffs by winning the Conference Semifinals and Conference Finals in two legs. During three regular season meetings between the two teams, D.C. won 5\u20132 in April and 5\u20130 in June, while Colorado won in a shootout following a 2\u20132 draw in August.<ref>{{cite news |last=Timmermann |first=Tom |date=October 26, 1997 |title=In Final, 'White Shoes' Rapids Hope To Remain On Yellow Brick Road |page=F2 |work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31279201/in_final_white_shoes_rapids_hope_to/ |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=May 5, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> The Rapids reached the final through a \"[[Cinderella (sports)|Cinderella run]]\" in the playoffs and were considered [[underdog]]s to defending champions D.C. United.<ref name=\"Tampa-Preview\"/>\n\n===D.C. United===\n{{see also|1997 D.C. United season}}\n\nInaugural season champions D.C. United retained most of their players and made few changes during the offseason, trading midfielder [[Shawn Medved]] to the [[San Jose Clash]] and acquiring defender [[Carlos Llamosa]] in the [[1997 MLS Supplemental Draft|supplemental draft]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Haydon |first=John |date=March 29, 1997 |title=United looks strong for defense of title |page=D4 |work=[[The Washington Times]]}}</ref> Nine of their starting players were called up at various times to their national teams for [[1998 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 CONCACAF Fourth Round|World Cup qualifying]], giving reserve players an opportunity to earn a starting spot.<ref>{{cite news |last=Langdon |first=Jerry |date=January 7, 1997 |title=MLS teams have to cope with World Cup qualifying |page=C8 |work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref><ref name=\"DC-Review\">{{cite web |title=History: 1997 season |url=https://www.dcunited.com/media-guide/history/1997 |publisher=D.C. United |accessdate=October 15, 2019}}</ref> D.C. went on a preseason tour that included matches in Japan and Hong Kong, earning a 6\u20132 [[win\u2013loss record]], and returned to open the season against MLS Cup opponents [[Los Angeles Galaxy]] with a shootout win.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sunderland |first=Lowell E. |date=March 29, 1997 |title=MLS opens second season with more refined outlook |page=C4 |work=[[The Baltimore Sun]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40103290/mls_opens_second_season_with_more/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 4, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=March 30, 1997 |title=Galaxy Stumbles in Home Opener to D.C. United |page=C3 |work=Los Angeles Times |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40104351/galaxy_stumbles_in_home_opener_to_dc/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 4, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\nD.C. earned one shootout win and three wins in regulation time to put them atop the Eastern Conference standings early in the season, highlighted by the performance of rookie goalkeeper [[Scott Garlick]], who replaced starter [[Mark Simpson (soccer)|Mark Simpson]] during his stint with an indoor team.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wright |first=Ken |date=April 24, 1997 |title=Team collects outstanding keepers, and the strategy is paying off nicely |page=B6 |work=The Washington Times}}</ref> The team then drew four times and lost three of the shootouts,<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=May 19, 1997 |title=No Practice Is Perfect In Shootout Tiebreaker |page=D2 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> briefly losing first place in the East in May before retaking it by the end of the month.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sunderland |first=Lowell E. |date=May 23, 1997 |title=United dashes Clash, 3-1, to regain 1st place |page=D8 |work=The Baltimore Sun |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40154216/united_dashes_clash_31_to_regain_1st/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 5, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> Despite losing Bolivian players [[Marco Etcheverry]] and [[Jaime Moreno (footballer, born 1974)|Jaime Moreno]] to the national team for six weeks, D.C. won their next five matches but lost 6\u20131 to the [[Kansas City Wizards]] on June 21, ending a 22-match unbeaten streak in regulation time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Satterly |first=Rich J. |date=June 22, 1997 |title=Wizards Make History Out of United, 6-1 |page=D1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> D.C. United also had six players in the starting lineup for the [[1997 MLS All-Star Game|All-Star Game]], which was won 5\u20134 by the East.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=July 10, 1997 |title=East Bests West in a Goalfest; Valderrama Is MVP In 5-4 All-Star Win |page=C1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nAfter the All-Star Game in early July, D.C. United went through a series of underwhelming performances, including three regulation losses and one shootout loss in six matches, blamed in part on injuries to Etcheverry and captain [[John Harkes]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=August 4, 1997 |title=United's Recent Losses Are Missed Opportunities |page=D9 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Sherman |first=Mitch |date=August 3, 1997 |title=Shootout loss to Rapids extends United's slump |page=C1 |work=The Washington Times}}</ref> The team then entered a stretch of 13 matches in 36 days, forced by their participation in the [[1997 CONCACAF Champions' Cup|CONCACAF Champions' Cup]] (finishing third) and [[1997 U.S. Open Cup|U.S. Open Cup]] (advancing to the semifinals). D.C. United went 8\u20134\u20131 in all competitions through the end of August, including three wins out of four matches in regular season play during a stretch of five matches in twelve days.<ref name=\"DC-Review\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=August 28, 1997 |title=United Retaliates, Quells Revolution, 3\u20132 |page=C3 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> The team made further changes to their goalkeepers, as Simpson had undergone two knee surgeries and backup [[Jeff Causey]] was signed by the [[New England Revolution]]; in their place, Scott Garlick and rookie [[Tom Presthus]] were rotated between matches as starters.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=August 27, 1997 |title=United Hopes Goalkeepers Have Saved Their Best for Last |page=C2 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> On August 17, [[Mario Gori]] and [[Ra\u00fal D\u00edaz Arce]] were arrested for an alleged rape at a Columbus hotel, but released the following day on bail and allowed to continue playing for the team;<ref>{{cite news |last=Wright |first=Ken |date=August 29, 1997 |title=United players' hearing continued |page=B3 |work=The Washington Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Knight |first=Athelia |date=September 6, 1997 |title=Ohio Grand Jury Indicts United's Diaz Arce, Gori |page=B1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1997/09/06/ohio-grand-jury-indicts-uniteds-diaz-arce-gori/75b6b9e1-f978-475b-8d67-3dfa660c5941/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 5, 2019}}</ref> the case was later dropped without charges in January 1998 after the alleged victim declined to continue.<ref>{{cite news |last=Knight |first=January 16, 1998 |title=United Charges Dismissed |page=D1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1998/01/16/united-charges-dismissed/d717876b-5f56-4b2a-b257-aad495ac4bff/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nD.C. earned their playoff berth with their first win against the Kansas City Wizards in franchise history after five earlier losses,<ref>{{cite news |last=Sunderland |first=Lowell E. |date=September 1, 1997 |title=D.C. United finds way to upend Wizards, 2\u20130 |page=C3 |work=The Baltimore Sun |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40154989/dc_united_finds_way_to_upend_wizards/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 5, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> and subsequently clinched first place in the Eastern Conference with a 3\u20132 shootout win against New England.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=September 17, 1997 |title=D.C. Clinches 1st Place In Eastern Conference |page=C5 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> The team continued to heavily rotate lineups and rested eight starting players in the second of a home-and-away series against the [[Tampa Bay Mutiny]], winning 5\u20131 despite losing the first match with most of their regular starters.<ref>{{cite news |last=Page |first=Rodney |date=September 27, 1997 |title=D.C. subs embarrass Mutiny |page=C9 |work=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40155123/dc_subs_embarrass_mutiny/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 5, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> D.C. finished the regular season atop the league-wide standings with 55 points and a 21\u201311 record, but fell short of matching the Mutiny's record 58 points from the 1996 season after losing to the MetroStars in their last match.<ref name=\"DC-Review\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=September 29, 1997 |title=MetroStars 3, United 1: D.C. Loses in a Daze at RFK |page=C1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> The team showed its roster depth by using a different lineup for all 39 league and cup matches, including 24 different starting players.<ref name=\"DC-Review\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 8, 1997 |title=Its Depth Charges D.C. United; Wegerle Will Start Over Diaz Arce |page=C1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> Bruce Arena was named [[MLS Coach of the Year Award|MLS Coach of the Year]], [[Eddie Pope]] was named [[MLS Defender of the Year Award|Defender of the Year]], and four United players were included in the [[MLS Best XI]].<ref name=\"Tampa-Preview\">{{cite news |last=Bachelor |first=Blaine |date=October 26, 1997 |title=Underdog Rapids play for title |page=10 |work=[[The Tampa Tribune]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31279070/underdog_rapids_play_for_title/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=May 5, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\nD.C. faced New England in the Conference Semifinals and earned a 4\u20131 victory in the first leg of the series at home. [[Roy Wegerle]], a midseason signing from Colorado, scored to give United a halftime lead and added a second before Jaime Moreno scored two more; New England defender [[Mike Burns (soccer)|Mike Burns]] scored a consolation goal with a minute left in the match.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 6, 1997 |title=United Kicks Things Off Right, 4-1 |page=C1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1997/10/06/united-kicks-things-off-right-4-1/661cca9c-ae61-4fbc-b061-ffe3da34c3ec/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 5, 2019}}</ref> In the away leg at [[Foxboro Stadium]], D.C. were held to a 1\u20131 draw in regulation time, with a goal for [[Richie Williams]] canceled out by [[Joe-Max Moore]]'s penalty kick in the 72nd minute. The two teams played in a seven-round shootout that ended 4\u20133 in United's favor after a series of saves from goalkeepers [[Walter Zenga]] and Tom Presthus that was broken up by defender Carlos Llamosa's conversion.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kuhns |first=Will |date=October 9, 1997 |title=D.C. United Eliminates Revolution in Shootout |page=B1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nIn the Conference Finals, D.C. played the third-seeded [[Columbus Crew SC|Columbus Crew]] after they had eliminated the Tampa Bay Mutiny. In the first leg, played without Etcheverry who was on national team duty, United took a three-goal halftime lead that was reduced by two for a 3\u20132 victory after a second half surge in pressure and chances from the Crew.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 13, 1997 |title=United Thrives in the 1st Half, Survives the Crew in 2nd, 3\u20132 |page=D1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> D.C. clinched their second MLS Cup appearance with a 1\u20130 win at [[Ohio Stadium]] in Columbus, with D\u00edaz Arce scoring the lone goal in the 47th minute from within the {{convert|6|yd|m|adj=mid|spell=in}} box.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 16, 1997 |title=United Sweeps Crew, Advances to Title Game |page=E1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1997/10/16/united-sweeps-crew-advances-to-title-game/13ceff67-89db-4121-9d0e-f21106aae392/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Colorado Rapids===\n\nThe Colorado Rapids finished last overall in MLS during the league's inaugural season, with a 11\u201321 record under head coach [[Bob Houghton]], who was replaced in the offseason by [[Glenn Myernick]].<ref>{{cite news |last=French |first=Scott |date=October 25, 1997 |title=Rapids rapidly shed laughing stock role |page=B4 |work=[[Long Beach Press-Telegram]]}}</ref> Myernick and new general manager [[Dan Counce]] implemented a possession-oriented style and overhauled the Rapids roster by signing eleven new players, including trades to acquire defender [[Peter Vermes]] and midfielders [[Paul Bravo]] and [[Adri\u00e1n Paz]]. The team also signed goalkeeper [[Marcus Hahnemann]] and forward [[Wolde Harris]] from the second-division [[A-League (1995\u20132004)|A-League]] and were allocated Mexican midfielder [[David Pati\u00f1o]] by the league.<ref name=\"Tampa-Changes\">{{cite news |last=Landman |first=Brian |date=May 3, 1997 |title=Need for Rapid changes recognized, met in Denver |page=C7 |work=Tampa Bay Times |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40004580/need_for_rapid_changes_recognized_met/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 2, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Timmermann |first=Tom |date=May 3, 1997 |title=Mr. Fix-It When It Counce |page=17 |work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40004749/mr_fixit_when_it_counce/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 2, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\nAfter a short preseason tour in Mexico and Florida, the Rapids opened the season without forward [[Jean Harbor]] and several defenders who were either injured or called up to national team duty, winning only twice in their first seven matches.<ref name=\"Tampa-Changes\"/><ref>{{cite news |date=March 8, 1997 |title=Rapids shift camp to Florida |page=C16 |work=[[Rocky Mountain News]]}}</ref> The team were able to consistently earn wins through the summer, with a 9\u201310 record by mid-July that allowed them to reach second in the Western Conference.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pearce |first=Alan |date=July 20, 1997 |title=Rapids need to burn Dallas to say in hunt |page=C10 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref> Their record improved to 14\u201312 in mid-August while remaining in second place, trailing the conference-leading Kansas City Wizards by eight points.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pearce |first=Alan |date=August 16, 1997 |title=Harris, Rapids shoot down exasperated MetroStars 2\u20130 |page=C6 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref>\n\nThe final seven matches of the Rapids season would be played against fellow teams in the Western Conference with higher stakes in playoffs positioning.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pearce |first=Alan |date=August 15, 1997 |title=Rapids' hopes rise as season wanes |page=C18 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref> The team entered a six-match losing streak, which included three losses to the Wizards, but qualified for the playoffs despite dropping to fourth place.<ref>{{cite news |date=September 22, 1997 |title=Rapids gain playoffs |page=C28 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref> Colorado won their final regular season match against San Jose and finished with a losing record of 14 wins and 18 losses.<ref name=\"AP-Rapids\">{{cite news |last=White |first=Joseph |date=October 24, 1997 |title=Rapids make rapid rise to title game |page=15 |work=[[Hawaii Tribune-Herald]] |agency=Associated Press |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40005459/rapids_make_rapid_rise_to_title_game/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 2, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Haydon |first=John |date=October 17, 1997 |title=D.C. feels at home defending its title |page=B3 |work=The Washington Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Sulat |first=Nate |date=November 9, 2010 |title=History of conference championship upsets |url=https://www.coloradorapids.com/post/2010/11/09/history-conference-championship-upsets |publisher=[[Colorado Rapids]] |accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref> Leading goalscorers Bravo and [[Chris Henderson]], along with defender [[Marcelo Balboa]], were credited with the team's improved regular season performance.<ref name=\"AP-Rapids\"/>\n\nIn the Conference Semifinals, Colorado faced the Wizards, who had defeated the Rapids in all of their regular season meetings.<ref>{{cite news |last=Luder |first=Bob |date=October 4, 1997 |title=Wizards hope to ride Rapids again in series |page=D1 |work=[[The Kansas City Star]]}}</ref> The first leg at Kansas City's [[Arrowhead Stadium]] finished in a 3\u20130 [[upset (sports)|upset]] victory for the Rapids, despite missing Paz and Balboa. The victory was credited to a disciplined performance by the Rapids defense, several saves from goalkeeper Marcus Hahnemann, and attackers who took advantage of mistakes from the Wizards.<ref>{{cite news |date=October 5, 1997 |title=Rapids' disciplined game stuns Kansas City in playoff opener |page=C5 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Luder |first=Bob |date=October 5, 1997 |title=Rapids stun Wizards |page=C15 |work=The Kansas City Star}}</ref> The Rapids began the second leg at home by conceding a goal to Wizards forward [[Vitalis Takawira]], but equalized within minutes and took a lead after halftime with goals from Paul Bravo. The match ended in a 3\u20132 win for Colorado, who swept the playoffs series.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pearce |first=Alan |date=October 9, 1997 |title=Rapids see Wizards off and out of the playoffs |page=C16 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref>\n\nThe Rapids advanced to play in the Conference Final against the [[Dallas Burn]], who had defeated the Los Angeles Galaxy in another upset from the semifinals.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pearce |first=Alan |date=October 12, 1997 |title=Surprising Rapids aim to cool off Burn in conference finals |page=C9 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref> Colorado won 1\u20130 in the first leg, played in Dallas, with a [[Header (association football)|header]] in the 42nd minute from defender [[Sean Henderson]]; the Burn had several chances to equalize, including a [[Free kick (association football)|free kick]] in the final five seconds that hit the [[Goalpost|post]], but were unable to capitalize.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dorson |first=Jill R. |date=October 13, 1997 |title=Last-second effort not enough for Burn |page=1 |work=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=October 13, 1997 |title=Rapids win on Henderson's goal |page=C10 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref> In the second leg, played at [[Mile High Stadium]] in Denver, Dallas took an early lead in the fifth minute but were set back by an equalizer from David Pati\u00f1o in the 23rd minute. The match remained tied until a scissored [[Volley (association football)|volley]] from Chris Henderson in the 87th minute clinched a 2\u20131 victory to win the conference championship for Colorado.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pearce |first=Alan |date=October 16, 1997 |title=Rapids stay on right foot with 2\u20131 win |page=C1 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref> The team became the first to take a pair of brothers, Chris and Sean Henderson, to the MLS Cup.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rodriguez |first=Alicia |date=November 19, 2016 |title=Top 5 MLS Conference Championship moments |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2016/11/19/top-5-mls-conference-championship-moments |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Summary of results===\n\n:''Note: In all results below, the score of the finalist is given first (H: home; A: away). Playoffs were in [[best of three|best-of-three]] format with [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)#North American experiments|penalty shootout]] if scores were tied.''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=2|[[D.C. United]]\n!Round\n!colspan=2|[[Colorado Rapids]]\n|-\n|colspan=2 valign=top align=center|1st place in [[1997 Major League Soccer season#Eastern Conference|Eastern Conference]]<br />&nbsp;\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; border-collapse: collapse; margin:0;\" \n!{{tooltip|Pos.|Position}}\n!width=195| Club \n!{{tooltip|Pld.|Games played}}\n!{{tooltip|W|Wins}}\n!{{tooltip|SW|Shootout wins}}\n!{{tooltip|L|Losses}}\n!{{tooltip|Pts.|Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#BBF1BD;\"\n|'''1'''||align=left|'''[[D.C. United]]''' ([[Supporters' Shield|SS]])||'''32'''||'''17'''||'''4'''||'''11'''||'''55'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|2||align=left|[[Tampa Bay Mutiny]]||32||14||3||15||'''45'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|3||align=left|[[Columbus Crew]]||32||12||3||17||'''39'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|4||align=left|[[New England Revolution]]||32||11||4||17||'''37'''\n|-\n|5||align=left|[[New York/New Jersey MetroStars|NY/NJ MetroStars]]||32||11||2||19||'''35'''\n|}\n\n{{small|Source: [https://www.mlssoccer.com/standings/mls/1997 MLS]}}\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|[[1997 Major League Soccer season|Regular season]]\n|colspan=2 valign=top|4th place in [[1997 Major League Soccer season#Western Conference|Western Conference]]<br />&nbsp;\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; border-collapse: collapse; margin:0;\" \n!{{tooltip|Pos.|Position}}\n!width=195| Club \n!{{tooltip|Pld.|Games played}}\n!{{tooltip|W|Wins}}\n!{{tooltip|SW|Shootout wins}}\n!{{tooltip|L|Losses}}\n!{{tooltip|Pts.|Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|1||align=left|[[Kansas City Wizards]]||32||14||7||11||'''49'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|2||align=left|[[Los Angeles Galaxy]]||32||14||2||16||'''44'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|3||align=left|[[Dallas Burn]]||32||13||3||16||'''42'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|'''4'''||align=left|'''[[Colorado Rapids]]'''||'''32'''||'''12'''||'''2'''||'''18'''||'''38'''\n|-\n|5||align=left|[[San Jose Clash]]||32||9||3||20||'''30'''\n|}\n\n{{small|Source: [https://www.mlssoccer.com/standings/mls/1997 MLS]}}\n|- style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"\n|Opponent\n|Results\n|[[1997 MLS Cup Playoffs|MLS Cup Playoffs]]\n|Opponent\n|Results\n|-\n|align=left|{{nowrap|[[New England Revolution]] (2\u20130)}}\n|4\u20131 (H), 1\u20131 {{nowrap|(4\u20133 [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)#North American experiments|SO]])}} (A)\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Conference Semifinals\n|align=left|{{nowrap|[[Kansas City Wizards]] (2\u20130)}}\n|3\u20130 (A), 3\u20132 (H)\n|-\n|align=left|{{nowrap|[[Columbus Crew]] (2\u20130)}}\n|3\u20132 (H), 1\u20130 (A)\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Conference Finals\n|align=left|{{nowrap|[[Dallas Burn]] (2\u20130)}}\n|1\u20130 (A), 2\u20131 (H)\n|}\n\n==Broadcasting==\n\nThe match was broadcast on [[ESPN on ABC|ABC]] in the United States, where it was watched by an estimated television audience of 2.2&nbsp;million viewers, setting a record that would stand until the [[MLS Cup 2016|2016 final]].<ref>{{cite news |date=December 13, 2016 |title=Sounders score big on TV in MLS Cup final |url=https://www.kitsapsun.com/story/sports/mls/sounders/2016/12/13/sounders-score-big-tv-mls-cup-final/95409760/ |work=[[Kitsap Sun]] |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref> [[Phil Schoen]] and [[Ty Keough]] reprised their roles from the previous final as play-by-play and [[color commentator]], respectively.<ref>{{cite news |last=Langdon |first=Jerry |date=October 17, 1997 |title=MLS announces six-year TV deal with ABC, ESPN |page=C24 |work=USA Today}}</ref> The match was also televised in more than 100 foreign markets by [[ESPN International]].<ref name=\"Post-Dream\">{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 26, 1997 |title=MLS, United on Verge Of Realizing a Dream |page=D1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n==Match==\n\n===Summary===\n[[File:Moreno-toronto-rfk.jpg|thumb|right|D.C. forward [[Jaime Moreno (footballer, born 1974)|Jaime Moreno]] scored the opening goal and was named the match's [[most valuable player]].]]\n\nThe MLS Cup final kicked off at 3:30&nbsp;p.m. with an announced [[sellout]] crowd of 57,431 spectators at RFK Memorial Stadium, setting a new attendance record for a single playoff match.<ref name=\"Sun-Recap\">{{cite news |date=October 27, 1997 |title=United reigns and MLS shines despite rain |page=C3 |work=The Baltimore Sun |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40245859/united_reigns_and_mls_shines_despite/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 7, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> The match was played during a rainstorm in cold conditions, which mirrored the weather during the [[MLS Cup 1996|inaugural final]] and deterred some ticket-holding fans from attending.<ref name=\"Post-Rain\">{{cite news |last=Gildea |first=William |date=October 27, 1997 |title=A Great Day for Playing in the Rain |page=A1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/dcunited/longterm/1997/mlscup/launch/scene27.htm |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Globe-Recap\">{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 27, 1997 |title=United reaches MLS goal again |page=D2 |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48895364/united-reaches-mls-goal-again/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020}} {{free access}}</ref> D.C. controlled the opening minutes, taking their first shot within 25 seconds, but Colorado used counterattacks to find chances and force goalkeeper Scott Garlick to make three saves and a foul that earned him a [[yellow card (sport)|yellow card]].<ref name=\"Sun-Recap\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Kuhns |first=Will |date=October 27, 1997 |title=Garlick Saves Best in Last Game |page=D10 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/dcunited/longterm/1997/mlscup/launch/mlside27.htm |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref> The hosts responded with their own counterattacking plays that were channeled by [[Tony Sanneh]] towards Jaime Moreno, who could not finish his first few chances.<ref name=\"Goff\">{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 27, 1997 |title=D.C. United Defeats Rapids, 2\u20131, Wins Second Title |page=D1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/dcunited/longterm/1997/mlscup/launch/mls27.htm |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"MLS-Blonde\">{{cite news |last=Freedman |first=Jonah |date=October 26, 2011 |title=Top 50 MLS Cup Moments: #25 Blonde Bombshell |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2011/10/27/top-50-mls-cup-moments-25-blonde-bombshell |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nD.C. took a 1\u20130 lead in the 37th minute after a cross from Sanneh to Ra\u00fal D\u00edaz Arce, who [[dummy (football)|dummied]] the ball at the top of the [[penalty area]]. The cross fell to Moreno, who took a shot from {{convert|12|yd|m}} that rolled past Marcus Hahnemann and two Colorado defenders.<ref name=\"Goff\"/><ref name=\"MLS-Blonde\"/> The Rapids were outshot 8\u20135 in the first half, with only one shot in the final 24 minutes.<ref name=\"Rocky\">{{cite news |last=Lindsay |first=John |date=October 27, 1997 |title=United way isn't generous to Rapids |page=C4 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref> They attempted to find an equalizer early in the second half and had two chances through David Pati\u00f1o that were not finished after missing a through ball and later hitting teammate [[Steve Rammel]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Davidson |first=Gary |date=October 26, 1997 |title=D.C. United, again |page=S12 |work=USA Today}}</ref><ref name=\"SS-Recap\">{{cite news |last=Rusnak |first=Jeff |date=October 22, 1997 |title=United they stand |pages=[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48894986/united-they-stand-p-c9/ C9], [https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48894996/united-they-stand-p-c14/ C14] |work=[[Sun-Sentinel]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48894986/united-they-stand-p-c9/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=April 16, 2020}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\nSanneh extended the lead for D.C. in the 68th minute, scoring with a header at the far post on a high cross from John Harkes after cleaning up a cleared corner kick. The team continued its attacking pressure, but shifted to a defensive style to prepare for counterattacks from the Rapids.<ref name=\"Goff\"/> Marcelo Balboa moved up into the midfield and attempted a [[bicycle kick]] in the 70th minute that was saved by Garlick.<ref>{{cite news |last=Firchau |first=Nick |date=October 23, 2011 |title=Top 50 MLS Cup Moments: #28 Biker Boss |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2011/10/24/top-50-mls-cup-moments-28-biker-boss |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> Colorado scored a consolation goal in the 75th minute from substitute Adri\u00e1n Paz, who struck the ball from a tight angle in the penalty area on an assist from Pati\u00f1o.<ref name=\"SS-Recap\"/> A chance to equalize came less than a minute later as Rapids forward Wolde Harris took an unimpeded shot from {{convert|20|yd|m}} that flew over the crossbar.<ref name=\"Goff\"/><ref name=\"NYT-Recap\">{{cite news |last=Yannis |first=Alex |date=October 27, 1997 |title=United Takes Lead, Then Holds On to Retain Its Title |page=C3 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/10/27/sports/soccer-united-takes-lead-then-holds-on-to-retain-its-title.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> D.C. responded with their own attacks that were shut down by the Rapids, including two fouls that were described as potential [[penalty kick]]s that went uncalled by referee [[Brian Hall (referee)|Brian Hall]].<ref name=\"Globe-Recap\"/> The hosts won 2\u20131 to claim their second MLS Cup title;<ref name=\"Goff\"/> Moreno was named the MLS Cup [[most valuable player]] for his performance, which included setting up plays throughout the match.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tucker |first=Bryan |date=October 27, 1997 |title=Moreno Makes Most of Opportunity |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/dcunited/longterm/1997/mlscup/launch/bryan27.htm |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Philly\">{{cite news |last=Jensen |first=Mike |date=October 27, 1997 |title=D.C. United again reigns in the rain |page=D3 |work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28394764/dc_united_again_reigns_in_the_rain/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 6, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\n===Details===\n{{football box\n|date = October 26, 1997\n|time = 3:30&nbsp;p.m. [[Eastern Time|EDT]]\n|team1 = [[D.C. United]]\n|score = 2\u20131\n|report= [https://www.mlssoccer.com/history/mls-cup/1997 Report]\n|team2 = [[Colorado Rapids]]\n|goals1 = \n*[[Jaime Moreno (footballer, born 1974)|Moreno]] {{goal|37}}\n*[[Tony Sanneh|Sanneh]] {{goal|68}}\n|goals2 = [[Adri\u00e1n Paz|Paz]] {{goal|75}}\n|stadium = [[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium]]\n|location = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n|attendance = 57,431\n|referee = [[Brian Hall (referee)|Brian Hall]]\n}}\n\n{| style=\"width:92%;\"\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n |pattern_la = _thinredborder\n |pattern_b  = _DCU_96h\n |pattern_ra = _thinredborder\n |pattern_sh = _DCU_96\n |pattern_so = _3_stripes_white\n |leftarm    = 000000\n |body       = FFFFFF\n |rightarm   = 000000\n |shorts     = 000000\n |socks      = 000000\n |title      = D.C. United\n}}\n|{{Football kit\n |pattern_la = \n |pattern_b  = \n |pattern_ra = \n |pattern_sh = \n |pattern_so = \n |leftarm    = FFFFFF\n |body       = FFFFFF\n |rightarm   = FFFFFF\n |shorts     = FFFFFF\n |socks      = FFFFFF\n |title      = Colorado Rapids\n}}\n|}\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Scott Garlick]] || {{yel|20}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''12''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jeff Agoos]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''18''' ||{{flagicon|COL}} [[Carlos Llamosa]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''23''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Eddie Pope]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''24''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[David Vaudreuil]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''10''' ||{{flagicon|BOL}} [[Marco Etcheverry]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''6''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[John Harkes]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|MF ||'''20''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Tony Sanneh]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''16''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Richie Williams]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''21''' ||{{flagicon|SLV}} [[Ra\u00fal D\u00edaz Arce]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''9''' ||{{flagicon|BOL}} [[Jaime Moreno (footballer, born 1974)|Jaime Moreno]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|colspan=3|{{in5}}''None used''\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Head coach:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Bruce Arena]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\"|\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=center\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Marcus Hahnemann]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''12''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Matt Kmosko]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''21''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Chris Martinez (soccer)|Chris Martinez]] || || {{suboff|59}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''4'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Steve Trittschuh]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''2'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Peter Vermes]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''17''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Marcelo Balboa]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]]) || {{yel|86}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''8'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Paul Bravo]] || || {{suboff|27}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''19'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Chris Henderson]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''3'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Sean Henderson]] || || {{suboff|81}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''6''' ||{{flagicon|MEX}} [[David Pati\u00f1o]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''10'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Steve Rammel]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|FW ||'''23'''||{{flagicon|JAM}} [[Wolde Harris]] || || {{subon|27}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''11'''||{{flagicon|URU}} [[Adri\u00e1n Paz]] || || {{subon|59}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''20'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Ross Paule]] || || {{subon|81}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Head coach:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Glenn Myernick]]\n|}\n|}\n{| style=\"width:100%;font-size:90%\"\n|\n'''MLS Cup Most Valuable Player:'''\n<br />[[Jaime Moreno (footballer, born 1974)|Jaime Moreno]] (D.C. United)\n\n'''Assistant referees:'''\n<br />Steve Olson\n<br />Greg Barkey\n\n|style=\"width:60%; vertical-align:top\"|\n'''Match rules'''\n*90 minutes of regulation time with a [[countdown clock]]\n*Two 15-minute periods of [[Extra time (association football)|extra time]] with [[golden goal]]s to decide a winner.\n*[[Penalty shoot-out (association football)#North American experiments|Penalty shootout]] from 35 yards if scores still tied.\n*Maximum of three substitutions.\n|}\n\n==Post-match==\n\nMLS Cup 1997 was the first sports championship for the Washington, D.C., area to be won at a stadium in the city.<ref>{{cite press release |date=October 8, 2007 |title=D.C. United announce ticket prices for 2008 season |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2010/01/23/dc-united-announce-ticket-prices-2008-season |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> The announced attendance of 57,431 came within 600 spectators of breaking the overall record for largest sporting event at RFK Memorial Stadium, held by the United States\u2013Portugal match during the 1996 Summer Olympics.<ref name=\"Post-Dream\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=White |first=Joseph |date=October 26, 1997 |title=United 2, Rapids 1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/dcunited/longterm/1997/mlscup/united27.htm |work=The Washington Post |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref> It was the first day in which there were large sporting events at both of the major outdoor stadiums in the D.C. area, as [[Jack Kent Cooke Stadium]] also hosted a [[National Football League]] game.<ref name=\"Post-Rain\"/> A railing in the upper stands at RFK Memorial Stadium collapsed during the celebrations after the match, causing minor injuries to 50 fans.<ref>{{cite news |date=October 27, 1997 |title=Dozens injured when railings collapse at RFK after MLS Cup |page=8 |work=[[The Independent-Record]] |location=Helena, Montana |agency=Associated Press |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28394737/mls_cup_1997_recap/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 6, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\nThree days after the MLS Cup final, D.C. United played the Dallas Burn in the [[1997 U.S. Open Cup Final|U.S. Open Cup Final]] with a chance to earn the league's first \"[[Treble (association football)|treble]]\". The Burn and United played to a scoreless draw and D.C. lost 5\u20133 in the ensuing penalty shootout.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stejskal |first=Sam |date=November 27, 2017 |title=Could Toronto FC become the first MLS team to win a domestic treble? |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2017/11/27/could-toronto-fc-become-first-mls-team-win-domestic-treble |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref> The team, with the exception of Etcheverry and Moreno on national team duty, was honored with a reception at the [[White House]] by President [[Bill Clinton]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Clarke |first=Liz |date=April 7, 1998 |title=Two-Time Champion United Honored at White House |page=E6 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1998/04/07/two-time-champion-united-honored-at-white-house/4a2da7f9-c817-4ccf-a00a-afe3d4cad126/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> D.C. returned to the MLS Cup in [[MLS Cup 1998|1998]], where they lost to the [[Chicago Fire SC|Chicago Fire]], and in [[MLS Cup 1999|1999]], where they defeated the Los Angeles Galaxy.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=November 22, 1999 |title=D.C.'s Two First-Half Goals Doom Galaxy |page=D1 |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/dcunited/longterm/1999/mlscup/united22.htm |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nD.C. and Colorado qualified as the U.S. representatives for the [[1998 CONCACAF Champions' Cup]], which was hosted at RFK Memorial Stadium in Washington, D.C.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=April 26, 1998 |title=On Second Thought, United Seeks Change |page=D6 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> The Rapids were eliminated in the qualifying playoff round, played in a home-and-away series against [[Club Le\u00f3n]] of Mexico, by a 4\u20133 aggregate score.<ref>{{cite news |date=July 16, 1998 |title=Leon preys on, eliminates shorthanded Rapids 4\u20132 |page=C13 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref> D.C. entered the competition in the quarterfinals and eliminated Trinidadian club [[Joe Public F.C.|Joe Public]], Le\u00f3n, and Mexican champion [[Deportivo Toluca F.C.|Toluca]] on their way to winning the Champions' Cup, becoming the first American team to be crowned as continental champions.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=August 17, 1998 |title=United Steps Up, Wins Champions' Cup |page=C1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=August 16, 1998 |title=United Faces Toluca Seeking Title, Respect |page=D6 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> United then advanced to the [[1998 Copa Interamericana]], where they defeated South American champions [[CR Vasco da Gama|Vasco da Gama]] of Brazil over two legs played in the United States.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rusnak |first=Jeff |date=December 6, 1998 |title=D.C. stops Brazilians |page=C17 |work=Sun-Sentinel |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/18125728/interamerican_cup_recap/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 6, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{MLSCup}}\n{{1997 in American soccer}}\n{{D.C. United matches}}\n{{Colorado Rapids}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1997 Mls Cup}}\n[[Category:MLS Cup]]\n[[Category:1997 Major League Soccer season|*Cup]]\n[[Category:D.C. United matches|MLS Cup 97]]\n[[Category:Colorado Rapids matches|MLS Cup 97]]\n[[Category:Soccer in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:October 1997 sports events in the United States]]\n[[Category:1997 in sports in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{short description|1997 edition of the MLS Cup}}\n{{Infobox football match\n| title\t= MLS Cup 1997\n| image\t= MLS Cup 97 logo.gif\n| event\t= [[MLS Cup]]\n| team1\t= [[D.C. United]]\n| team1score = 2\n| team2\t= [[Colorado Rapids]]\n| team2score = 1\n| details = \n| date = October 26, 1997 \n| stadium = [[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium]] \n| city = [[Washington, D.C.]], US\n| man_of_the_match1a = [[Jaime Moreno (footballer, born 1974)|Jaime Moreno]] (D.C. United) \n| referee = [[Brian Hall (referee)|Brian Hall]]\n| attendance = 57,431 \n| weather = Rain, {{convert|46|\u00b0F|\u00b0C}}\n| previous = [[MLS Cup 1996|1996]]\n| next = [[MLS Cup 1998|1998]]\n}}\n\n'''MLS Cup 1997''' was the second edition of the [[MLS Cup]], the post-season championship match of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS) in the United States. It was played on October 26, 1997, between [[D.C. United]] and the [[Colorado Rapids]] to determine the champion of the [[1997 Major League Soccer season|1997 season]]. The match was played in front of 57,431 spectators at [[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium|RFK Memorial Stadium]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]\n\nD.C. United were defending champions and finished atop the [[Eastern Conference (MLS)|Eastern Conference]] and the [[Supporters' Shield|overall league standings]] despite being strained by runs in multiple competitions. Colorado had overhauled their roster after finishing last overall in the 1996 season and qualified for the playoffs with a [[Win\u2013loss record|losing record]], finishing fourth in the [[Western Conference (MLS)|Western Conference]], but earned two [[upset (sports)|upset]] victories in the playoffs. As finalists, D.C. United and the Colorado Rapids both earned berths to play in the [[1998 CONCACAF Champions' Cup]].\n\nDuring a rainstorm that mirrored the [[MLS Cup 1996|previous final]], D.C. repeated as MLS Cup champions by winning 2\u20131. The hosts took a lead through [[Jaime Moreno (footballer, born 1974)|Jaime Moreno]] in the 37th minute and extended it with a header by [[Tony Sanneh]] in the 68th minute. Substitute [[Adri\u00e1n Paz]] scored a consolation goal for Colorado in the 75th minute, but the team were unable to draw level despite several chances. The announced crowd of 57,431 was the second-largest attendance for a sporting event at RFK Memorial Stadium.\n\n==Venue==\n[[File:RFK Stadium satellite view.png|thumb|left|Aerial view of [[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium|RFK Memorial Stadium]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], the host venue of MLS Cup 1997]]\n\n[[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium|RFK Memorial Stadium]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], the home of defending champions [[D.C. United]], was selected as the host of the second MLS Cup on December 17, 1996.<ref>{{cite news |date=December 18, 1996 |title=MLS likes weekend matches |page=D2 |work=[[The Mercury News]]}}</ref> The stadium was opened in 1961 and was primarily used for American football and baseball, but previously hosted the 1980 [[Soccer Bowl]] and the [[1996 U.S. Open Cup|1996 U.S. Open Cup Final]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 31, 1996 |title=United Captures Another Title |page=C1 |work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref> It also hosted several matches during the [[1994 FIFA World Cup]] and [[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|1996 Olympics men's soccer tournament]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 20, 2017 |title=American soccer made its home at aging, funky RFK Stadium |page= |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/soccer-insider/wp/2017/10/19/soccer-at-rfk-stadium-its-dirty-and-disgusting-and-ugly-but-its-ours/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe league sold 32,000 tickets for the final in mid-October after D.C. United advanced to the [[1997 MLS Cup Playoffs#Conference Finals|Conference Finals]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Stevens |date=October 15, 1997 |title=On Novel Field, D.C. Hopes To Say: Goodbye, Columbus |page=C2 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> After the team clinched an appearance in the final, the remainder of the stadium's 56,000 seats were sold out and 1,000 [[bleacher]] seats were added.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 21, 1997 |title=D.C. Is United for MLS Title Game |page=E1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n==Road to the final==\n\nThe [[MLS Cup]] is the post-season championship of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS), a professional club [[Association football|soccer]] league based in the United States that began play in 1996. The league's [[1997 Major League Soccer season|second season]] was contested by ten teams organized into two conferences, each playing 32 matches during the regular season from April to September. Teams faced opponents from the same conference four times during the regular season and from outside their conference three or four times.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=December 5, 1995 |title=Major League Soccer Sets Inaugural Schedule |page=C5 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-12-05/sports/sp-10453_1_major-league-soccer |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref> MLS continued to use the modified version of the sport's rules that it adopted for the 1996 season, including a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)#North American experiments|penalty shootout]] from {{convert|35|yd|m}} to decide tied matches (for which the winners earned one point) and a [[countdown clock]] that stopped during [[Ball in and out of play|dead plays]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Macguire |first=Eoghan |date=March 6, 2015 |title=MLS at 20: Sunrise on football's final frontier? |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2015/03/06/football/mls-20-sunrise-sunset/index.html |publisher=[[CNN]] |accessdate=March 7, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Dure22\">{{cite book |last=Dure |first=Beau |year=2010 |title=Long-Range Goals: The Success Story of Major League Soccer |pages=22\u201324 |publisher=[[Potomac Books]] |location=Washington, D.C. |isbn=978-1-59797-509-4 |oclc=500783910 |ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nThe top four teams from each conference qualified for the playoffs, which were organized into three rounds and played in October. The first two rounds, named the Conference Semifinals and Conference Finals, were [[two-legged tie|home-and-away]] series organized into a best-of-three format with a hosting advantage for the higher seed. The winners of the Conference Finals advanced to the single-match MLS Cup final, which would be held at a predetermined neutral venue.<ref name=\"MLS-2015\">{{cite news |last=Rodriguez |first=Alicia |date=October 21, 2015 |title=Audi MLS Cup Playoffs: Tracing the evolution of the postseason format since 1996 |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2015/10/21/audi-mls-cup-playoffs-tracing-evolution-postseason-format |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMLS Cup 1997 was contested by defending champions and hosts D.C. United, who finished first in the regular season standings, and the [[Colorado Rapids]], who finished fourth in the Western Conference. The two finalists swept through the playoffs by winning the Conference Semifinals and Conference Finals in two legs. During three regular season meetings between the two teams, D.C. won 5\u20132 in April and 5\u20130 in June, while Colorado won in a shootout following a 2\u20132 draw in August.<ref>{{cite news |last=Timmermann |first=Tom |date=October 26, 1997 |title=In Final, 'White Shoes' Rapids Hope To Remain On Yellow Brick Road |page=F2 |work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31279201/in_final_white_shoes_rapids_hope_to/ |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=May 5, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> The Rapids reached the final through a \"[[Cinderella (sports)|Cinderella run]]\" in the playoffs and were considered [[underdog]]s to defending champions D.C. United.<ref name=\"Tampa-Preview\"/>\n\n===D.C. United===\n{{see also|1997 D.C. United season}}\n\nInaugural season champions D.C. United retained most of their players and made few changes during the offseason, trading midfielder [[Shawn Medved]] to the [[San Jose Clash]] and acquiring defender [[Carlos Llamosa]] in the [[1997 MLS Supplemental Draft|supplemental draft]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Haydon |first=John |date=March 29, 1997 |title=United looks strong for defense of title |page=D4 |work=[[The Washington Times]]}}</ref> Nine of their starting players were called up at various times to their national teams for [[1998 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 CONCACAF Fourth Round|World Cup qualifying]], giving reserve players an opportunity to earn a starting spot.<ref>{{cite news |last=Langdon |first=Jerry |date=January 7, 1997 |title=MLS teams have to cope with World Cup qualifying |page=C8 |work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref><ref name=\"DC-Review\">{{cite web |title=History: 1997 season |url=https://www.dcunited.com/media-guide/history/1997 |publisher=D.C. United |accessdate=October 15, 2019}}</ref> D.C. went on a preseason tour that included matches in Japan and Hong Kong, earning a 6\u20132 [[win\u2013loss record]], and returned to open the season against MLS Cup opponents [[Los Angeles Galaxy]] with a shootout win.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sunderland |first=Lowell E. |date=March 29, 1997 |title=MLS opens second season with more refined outlook |page=C4 |work=[[The Baltimore Sun]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40103290/mls_opens_second_season_with_more/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 4, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=March 30, 1997 |title=Galaxy Stumbles in Home Opener to D.C. United |page=C3 |work=Los Angeles Times |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40104351/galaxy_stumbles_in_home_opener_to_dc/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 4, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\nD.C. earned one shootout win and three wins in regulation time to put them atop the Eastern Conference standings early in the season, highlighted by the performance of rookie goalkeeper [[Scott Garlick]], who replaced starter [[Mark Simpson (soccer)|Mark Simpson]] during his stint with an indoor team.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wright |first=Ken |date=April 24, 1997 |title=Team collects outstanding keepers, and the strategy is paying off nicely |page=B6 |work=The Washington Times}}</ref> The team then drew four times and lost three of the shootouts,<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=May 19, 1997 |title=No Practice Is Perfect In Shootout Tiebreaker |page=D2 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> briefly losing first place in the East in May before retaking it by the end of the month.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sunderland |first=Lowell E. |date=May 23, 1997 |title=United dashes Clash, 3-1, to regain 1st place |page=D8 |work=The Baltimore Sun |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40154216/united_dashes_clash_31_to_regain_1st/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 5, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> Despite losing Bolivian players [[Marco Etcheverry]] and [[Jaime Moreno (footballer, born 1974)|Jaime Moreno]] to the national team for six weeks, D.C. won their next five matches but lost 6\u20131 to the [[Kansas City Wizards]] on June 21, ending a 22-match unbeaten streak in regulation time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Satterly |first=Rich J. |date=June 22, 1997 |title=Wizards Make History Out of United, 6-1 |page=D1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> D.C. United also had six players in the starting lineup for the [[1997 MLS All-Star Game|All-Star Game]], which was won 5\u20134 by the East.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=July 10, 1997 |title=East Bests West in a Goalfest; Valderrama Is MVP In 5-4 All-Star Win |page=C1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nAfter the All-Star Game in early July, D.C. United went through a series of underwhelming performances, including three regulation losses and one shootout loss in six matches, blamed in part on injuries to Etcheverry and captain [[John Harkes]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=August 4, 1997 |title=United's Recent Losses Are Missed Opportunities |page=D9 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Sherman |first=Mitch |date=August 3, 1997 |title=Shootout loss to Rapids extends United's slump |page=C1 |work=The Washington Times}}</ref> The team then entered a stretch of 13 matches in 36 days, forced by their participation in the [[1997 CONCACAF Champions' Cup|CONCACAF Champions' Cup]] (finishing third) and [[1997 U.S. Open Cup|U.S. Open Cup]] (advancing to the semifinals). D.C. United went 8\u20134\u20131 in all competitions through the end of August, including three wins out of four matches in regular season play during a stretch of five matches in twelve days.<ref name=\"DC-Review\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=August 28, 1997 |title=United Retaliates, Quells Revolution, 3\u20132 |page=C3 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> The team made further changes to their goalkeepers, as Simpson had undergone two knee surgeries and backup [[Jeff Causey]] was signed by the [[New England Revolution]]; in their place, Scott Garlick and rookie [[Tom Presthus]] were rotated between matches as starters.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=August 27, 1997 |title=United Hopes Goalkeepers Have Saved Their Best for Last |page=C2 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> On August 17, [[Mario Gori]] and [[Ra\u00fal D\u00edaz Arce]] were arrested for an alleged rape at a Columbus hotel, but released the following day on bail and allowed to continue playing for the team;<ref>{{cite news |last=Wright |first=Ken |date=August 29, 1997 |title=United players' hearing continued |page=B3 |work=The Washington Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Knight |first=Athelia |date=September 6, 1997 |title=Ohio Grand Jury Indicts United's Diaz Arce, Gori |page=B1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1997/09/06/ohio-grand-jury-indicts-uniteds-diaz-arce-gori/75b6b9e1-f978-475b-8d67-3dfa660c5941/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 5, 2019}}</ref> the case was later dropped without charges in January 1998 after the alleged victim declined to continue.<ref>{{cite news |last=Knight |first=January 16, 1998 |title=United Charges Dismissed |page=D1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1998/01/16/united-charges-dismissed/d717876b-5f56-4b2a-b257-aad495ac4bff/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nD.C. earned their playoff berth with their first win against the Kansas City Wizards in franchise history after five earlier losses,<ref>{{cite news |last=Sunderland |first=Lowell E. |date=September 1, 1997 |title=D.C. United finds way to upend Wizards, 2\u20130 |page=C3 |work=The Baltimore Sun |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40154989/dc_united_finds_way_to_upend_wizards/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 5, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> and subsequently clinched first place in the Eastern Conference with a 3\u20132 shootout win against New England.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=September 17, 1997 |title=D.C. Clinches 1st Place In Eastern Conference |page=C5 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> The team continued to heavily rotate lineups and rested eight starting players in the second of a home-and-away series against the [[Tampa Bay Mutiny]], winning 5\u20131 despite losing the first match with most of their regular starters.<ref>{{cite news |last=Page |first=Rodney |date=September 27, 1997 |title=D.C. subs embarrass Mutiny |page=C9 |work=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40155123/dc_subs_embarrass_mutiny/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 5, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> D.C. finished the regular season atop the league-wide standings with 55 points and a 21\u201311 record, but fell short of matching the Mutiny's record 58 points from the 1996 season after losing to the MetroStars in their last match.<ref name=\"DC-Review\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=September 29, 1997 |title=MetroStars 3, United 1: D.C. Loses in a Daze at RFK |page=C1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> The team showed its roster depth by using a different lineup for all 39 league and cup matches, including 24 different starting players.<ref name=\"DC-Review\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 8, 1997 |title=Its Depth Charges D.C. United; Wegerle Will Start Over Diaz Arce |page=C1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> Bruce Arena was named [[MLS Coach of the Year Award|MLS Coach of the Year]], [[Eddie Pope]] was named [[MLS Defender of the Year Award|Defender of the Year]], and four United players were included in the [[MLS Best XI]].<ref name=\"Tampa-Preview\">{{cite news |last=Bachelor |first=Blaine |date=October 26, 1997 |title=Underdog Rapids play for title |page=10 |work=[[The Tampa Tribune]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31279070/underdog_rapids_play_for_title/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=May 5, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\nD.C. faced New England in the Conference Semifinals and earned a 4\u20131 victory in the first leg of the series at home. [[Roy Wegerle]], a midseason signing from Colorado, scored to give United a halftime lead and added a second before Jaime Moreno scored two more; New England defender [[Mike Burns (soccer)|Mike Burns]] scored a consolation goal with a minute left in the match.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 6, 1997 |title=United Kicks Things Off Right, 4-1 |page=C1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1997/10/06/united-kicks-things-off-right-4-1/661cca9c-ae61-4fbc-b061-ffe3da34c3ec/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 5, 2019}}</ref> In the away leg at [[Foxboro Stadium]], D.C. were held to a 1\u20131 draw in regulation time, with a goal for [[Richie Williams]] canceled out by [[Joe-Max Moore]]'s penalty kick in the 72nd minute. The two teams played in a seven-round shootout that ended 4\u20133 in United's favor after a series of saves from goalkeepers [[Walter Zenga]] and Tom Presthus that was broken up by defender Carlos Llamosa's conversion.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kuhns |first=Will |date=October 9, 1997 |title=D.C. United Eliminates Revolution in Shootout |page=B1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nIn the Conference Finals, D.C. played the third-seeded [[Columbus Crew SC|Columbus Crew]] after they had eliminated the Tampa Bay Mutiny. In the first leg, played without Etcheverry who was on national team duty, United took a three-goal halftime lead that was reduced by two for a 3\u20132 victory after a second half surge in pressure and chances from the Crew.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 13, 1997 |title=United Thrives in the 1st Half, Survives the Crew in 2nd, 3\u20132 |page=D1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> D.C. clinched their second MLS Cup appearance with a 1\u20130 win at [[Ohio Stadium]] in Columbus, with D\u00edaz Arce scoring the lone goal in the 47th minute from within the {{convert|6|yd|m|adj=mid|spell=in}} box.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 16, 1997 |title=United Sweeps Crew, Advances to Title Game |page=E1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1997/10/16/united-sweeps-crew-advances-to-title-game/13ceff67-89db-4121-9d0e-f21106aae392/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Colorado Rapids===\n\nThe Colorado Rapids finished last overall in MLS during the league's inaugural season, with a 11\u201321 record under head coach [[Bob Houghton]], who was replaced in the offseason by [[Glenn Myernick]].<ref>{{cite news |last=French |first=Scott |date=October 25, 1997 |title=Rapids rapidly shed laughing stock role |page=B4 |work=[[Long Beach Press-Telegram]]}}</ref> Myernick and new general manager [[Dan Counce]] implemented a possession-oriented style and overhauled the Rapids roster by signing eleven new players, including trades to acquire defender [[Peter Vermes]] and midfielders [[Paul Bravo]] and [[Adri\u00e1n Paz]]. The team also signed goalkeeper [[Marcus Hahnemann]] and forward [[Wolde Harris]] from the second-division [[A-League (1995\u20132004)|A-League]] and were allocated Mexican midfielder [[David Pati\u00f1o]] by the league.<ref name=\"Tampa-Changes\">{{cite news |last=Landman |first=Brian |date=May 3, 1997 |title=Need for Rapid changes recognized, met in Denver |page=C7 |work=Tampa Bay Times |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40004580/need_for_rapid_changes_recognized_met/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 2, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Timmermann |first=Tom |date=May 3, 1997 |title=Mr. Fix-It When It Counce |page=17 |work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40004749/mr_fixit_when_it_counce/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 2, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\nAfter a short preseason tour in Mexico and Florida, the Rapids opened the season without forward [[Jean Harbor]] and several defenders who were either injured or called up to national team duty, winning only twice in their first seven matches.<ref name=\"Tampa-Changes\"/><ref>{{cite news |date=March 8, 1997 |title=Rapids shift camp to Florida |page=C16 |work=[[Rocky Mountain News]]}}</ref> The team were able to consistently earn wins through the summer, with a 9\u201310 record by mid-July that allowed them to reach second in the Western Conference.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pearce |first=Alan |date=July 20, 1997 |title=Rapids need to burn Dallas to say in hunt |page=C10 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref> Their record improved to 14\u201312 in mid-August while remaining in second place, trailing the conference-leading Kansas City Wizards by eight points.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pearce |first=Alan |date=August 16, 1997 |title=Harris, Rapids shoot down exasperated MetroStars 2\u20130 |page=C6 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref>\n\nThe final seven matches of the Rapids season would be played against fellow teams in the Western Conference with higher stakes in playoffs positioning.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pearce |first=Alan |date=August 15, 1997 |title=Rapids' hopes rise as season wanes |page=C18 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref> The team entered a six-match losing streak, which included three losses to the Wizards, but qualified for the playoffs despite dropping to fourth place.<ref>{{cite news |date=September 22, 1997 |title=Rapids gain playoffs |page=C28 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref> Colorado won their final regular season match against San Jose and finished with a losing record of 14 wins and 18 losses. Their regular season run ended with a six-match losing streak, all against Western Conference teams, and a win against San Jose.<ref name=\"AP-Rapids\">{{cite news |last=White |first=Joseph |date=October 24, 1997 |title=Rapids make rapid rise to title game |page=15 |work=[[Hawaii Tribune-Herald]] |agency=Associated Press |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40005459/rapids_make_rapid_rise_to_title_game/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 2, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Haydon |first=John |date=October 17, 1997 |title=D.C. feels at home defending its title |page=B3 |work=The Washington Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Sulat |first=Nate |date=November 9, 2010 |title=History of conference championship upsets |url=https://www.coloradorapids.com/post/2010/11/09/history-conference-championship-upsets |publisher=[[Colorado Rapids]] |accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref> Leading goalscorers Bravo and [[Chris Henderson]], along with defender [[Marcelo Balboa]], were credited with the team's improved regular season performance.<ref name=\"AP-Rapids\"/>\n\nIn the Conference Semifinals, Colorado faced the Wizards, who had defeated the Rapids in all of their regular season meetings.<ref>{{cite news |last=Luder |first=Bob |date=October 4, 1997 |title=Wizards hope to ride Rapids again in series |page=D1 |work=[[The Kansas City Star]]}}</ref> The first leg at Kansas City's [[Arrowhead Stadium]] finished in a 3\u20130 [[upset (sports)|upset]] victory for the Rapids, despite missing Paz and Balboa. The victory was credited to a disciplined performance by the Rapids defense, several saves from goalkeeper Marcus Hahnemann, and attackers who took advantage of mistakes from the Wizards.<ref>{{cite news |date=October 5, 1997 |title=Rapids' disciplined game stuns Kansas City in playoff opener |page=C5 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Luder |first=Bob |date=October 5, 1997 |title=Rapids stun Wizards |page=C15 |work=The Kansas City Star}}</ref> The Rapids began the second leg at home by conceding a goal to Wizards forward [[Vitalis Takawira]], but equalized within minutes and took a lead after halftime with goals from Paul Bravo. The match ended in a 3\u20132 win for Colorado, who swept the playoffs series.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pearce |first=Alan |date=October 9, 1997 |title=Rapids see Wizards off and out of the playoffs |page=C16 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref>\n\nThe Rapids advanced to play in the Conference Final against the [[Dallas Burn]], who had defeated the Los Angeles Galaxy in another upset from the semifinals.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pearce |first=Alan |date=October 12, 1997 |title=Surprising Rapids aim to cool off Burn in conference finals |page=C9 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref> Colorado won 1\u20130 in the first leg, played in Dallas, with a [[Header (association football)|header]] in the 42nd minute from defender [[Sean Henderson]]; the Burn had several chances to equalize, including a [[Free kick (association football)|free kick]] in the final five seconds that hit the [[Goalpost|post]], but were unable to capitalize.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dorson |first=Jill R. |date=October 13, 1997 |title=Last-second effort not enough for Burn |page=1 |work=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=October 13, 1997 |title=Rapids win on Henderson's goal |page=C10 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref> In the second leg, played at [[Mile High Stadium]] in Denver, Dallas took an early lead in the fifth minute but were set back by an equalizer from David Pati\u00f1o in the 23rd minute. The match remained tied until a scissored [[Volley (association football)|volley]] from Chris Henderson in the 87th minute clinched a 2\u20131 victory to win the conference championship for Colorado.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pearce |first=Alan |date=October 16, 1997 |title=Rapids stay on right foot with 2\u20131 win |page=C1 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref> The team became the first to take a pair of brothers, Chris and Sean Henderson, to the MLS Cup.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rodriguez |first=Alicia |date=November 19, 2016 |title=Top 5 MLS Conference Championship moments |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2016/11/19/top-5-mls-conference-championship-moments |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Summary of results===\n\n:''Note: In all results below, the score of the finalist is given first (H: home; A: away). Playoffs were in [[best of three|best-of-three]] format with [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)#North American experiments|penalty shootout]] if scores were tied.''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=2|[[D.C. United]]\n!Round\n!colspan=2|[[Colorado Rapids]]\n|-\n|colspan=2 valign=top align=center|1st place in [[1997 Major League Soccer season#Eastern Conference|Eastern Conference]]<br />&nbsp;\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; border-collapse: collapse; margin:0;\" \n!{{tooltip|Pos.|Position}}\n!width=195| Club \n!{{tooltip|Pld.|Games played}}\n!{{tooltip|W|Wins}}\n!{{tooltip|SW|Shootout wins}}\n!{{tooltip|L|Losses}}\n!{{tooltip|Pts.|Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#BBF1BD;\"\n|'''1'''||align=left|'''[[D.C. United]]''' ([[Supporters' Shield|SS]])||'''32'''||'''17'''||'''4'''||'''11'''||'''55'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|2||align=left|[[Tampa Bay Mutiny]]||32||14||3||15||'''45'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|3||align=left|[[Columbus Crew]]||32||12||3||17||'''39'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|4||align=left|[[New England Revolution]]||32||11||4||17||'''37'''\n|-\n|5||align=left|[[New York/New Jersey MetroStars|NY/NJ MetroStars]]||32||11||2||19||'''35'''\n|}\n\n{{small|Source: [https://www.mlssoccer.com/standings/mls/1997 MLS]}}\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|[[1997 Major League Soccer season|Regular season]]\n|colspan=2 valign=top|4th place in [[1997 Major League Soccer season#Western Conference|Western Conference]]<br />&nbsp;\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; border-collapse: collapse; margin:0;\" \n!{{tooltip|Pos.|Position}}\n!width=195| Club \n!{{tooltip|Pld.|Games played}}\n!{{tooltip|W|Wins}}\n!{{tooltip|SW|Shootout wins}}\n!{{tooltip|L|Losses}}\n!{{tooltip|Pts.|Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|1||align=left|[[Kansas City Wizards]]||32||14||7||11||'''49'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|2||align=left|[[Los Angeles Galaxy]]||32||14||2||16||'''44'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|3||align=left|[[Dallas Burn]]||32||13||3||16||'''42'''\n|- style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|'''4'''||align=left|'''[[Colorado Rapids]]'''||'''32'''||'''12'''||'''2'''||'''18'''||'''38'''\n|-\n|5||align=left|[[San Jose Clash]]||32||9||3||20||'''30'''\n|}\n\n{{small|Source: [https://www.mlssoccer.com/standings/mls/1997 MLS]}}\n|- style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"\n|Opponent\n|Results\n|[[1997 MLS Cup Playoffs|MLS Cup Playoffs]]\n|Opponent\n|Results\n|-\n|align=left|{{nowrap|[[New England Revolution]] (2\u20130)}}\n|4\u20131 (H), 1\u20131 {{nowrap|(4\u20133 [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)#North American experiments|SO]])}} (A)\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Conference Semifinals\n|align=left|{{nowrap|[[Kansas City Wizards]] (2\u20130)}}\n|3\u20130 (A), 3\u20132 (H)\n|-\n|align=left|{{nowrap|[[Columbus Crew]] (2\u20130)}}\n|3\u20132 (H), 1\u20130 (A)\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Conference Finals\n|align=left|{{nowrap|[[Dallas Burn]] (2\u20130)}}\n|1\u20130 (A), 2\u20131 (H)\n|}\n\n==Broadcasting==\n\nThe match was broadcast on [[ESPN on ABC|ABC]] in the United States, where it was watched by an estimated television audience of 2.2&nbsp;million viewers, setting a record that would stand until the [[MLS Cup 2016|2016 final]].<ref>{{cite news |date=December 13, 2016 |title=Sounders score big on TV in MLS Cup final |url=https://www.kitsapsun.com/story/sports/mls/sounders/2016/12/13/sounders-score-big-tv-mls-cup-final/95409760/ |work=[[Kitsap Sun]] |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=May 4, 2019}}</ref> [[Phil Schoen]] and [[Ty Keough]] reprised their roles from the previous final as play-by-play and [[color commentator]], respectively.<ref>{{cite news |last=Langdon |first=Jerry |date=October 17, 1997 |title=MLS announces six-year TV deal with ABC, ESPN |page=C24 |work=USA Today}}</ref> The match was also televised in more than 100 foreign markets by [[ESPN International]].<ref name=\"Post-Dream\">{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 26, 1997 |title=MLS, United on Verge Of Realizing a Dream |page=D1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n==Match==\n\n===Summary===\n[[File:Moreno-toronto-rfk.jpg|thumb|right|D.C. forward [[Jaime Moreno (footballer, born 1974)|Jaime Moreno]] scored the opening goal and was named the match's [[most valuable player]].]]\n\nThe MLS Cup final kicked off at 3:30&nbsp;p.m. with an announced [[sellout]] crowd of 57,431 spectators at RFK Memorial Stadium, setting a new attendance record for a single playoff match.<ref name=\"Sun-Recap\">{{cite news |date=October 27, 1997 |title=United reigns and MLS shines despite rain |page=C3 |work=The Baltimore Sun |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40245859/united_reigns_and_mls_shines_despite/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 7, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> The match was played during a rainstorm in cold conditions, which mirrored the weather during the [[MLS Cup 1996|inaugural final]] and deterred some ticket-holding fans from attending.<ref name=\"Post-Rain\">{{cite news |last=Gildea |first=William |date=October 27, 1997 |title=A Great Day for Playing in the Rain |page=A1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/dcunited/longterm/1997/mlscup/launch/scene27.htm |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Globe-Recap\">{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 27, 1997 |title=United reaches MLS goal again |page=D2 |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48895364/united-reaches-mls-goal-again/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020}} {{free access}}</ref> D.C. controlled the opening minutes, taking their first shot within 25 seconds, but Colorado used counterattacks to find chances and force goalkeeper Scott Garlick to make three saves and a foul that earned him a [[yellow card (sport)|yellow card]].<ref name=\"Sun-Recap\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Kuhns |first=Will |date=October 27, 1997 |title=Garlick Saves Best in Last Game |page=D10 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/dcunited/longterm/1997/mlscup/launch/mlside27.htm |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref> The hosts responded with their own counterattacking plays that were channeled by [[Tony Sanneh]] towards Jaime Moreno, who could not finish his first few chances.<ref name=\"Goff\">{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=October 27, 1997 |title=D.C. United Defeats Rapids, 2\u20131, Wins Second Title |page=D1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/dcunited/longterm/1997/mlscup/launch/mls27.htm |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"MLS-Blonde\">{{cite news |last=Freedman |first=Jonah |date=October 26, 2011 |title=Top 50 MLS Cup Moments: #25 Blonde Bombshell |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2011/10/27/top-50-mls-cup-moments-25-blonde-bombshell |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nD.C. took a 1\u20130 lead in the 37th minute after a cross from Sanneh to Ra\u00fal D\u00edaz Arce, who [[dummy (football)|dummied]] the ball at the top of the [[penalty area]]. The cross fell to Moreno, who took a shot from {{convert|12|yd|m}} that rolled past Marcus Hahnemann and two Colorado defenders.<ref name=\"Goff\"/><ref name=\"MLS-Blonde\"/> The Rapids were outshot 8\u20135 in the first half, with only one shot in the final 24 minutes.<ref name=\"Rocky\">{{cite news |last=Lindsay |first=John |date=October 27, 1997 |title=United way isn't generous to Rapids |page=C4 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref> They attempted to find an equalizer early in the second half and had two chances through David Pati\u00f1o that were not finished after missing a through ball and later hitting teammate [[Steve Rammel]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Davidson |first=Gary |date=October 26, 1997 |title=D.C. United, again |page=S12 |work=USA Today}}</ref><ref name=\"SS-Recap\">{{cite news |last=Rusnak |first=Jeff |date=October 22, 1997 |title=United they stand |pages=[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48894986/united-they-stand-p-c9/ C9], [https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48894996/united-they-stand-p-c14/ C14] |work=[[Sun-Sentinel]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48894986/united-they-stand-p-c9/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=April 16, 2020}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\nSanneh extended the lead for D.C. in the 68th minute, scoring with a header at the far post on a high cross from John Harkes after cleaning up a cleared corner kick. The team continued its attacking pressure, but shifted to a defensive style to prepare for counterattacks from the Rapids.<ref name=\"Goff\"/> Marcelo Balboa moved up into the midfield and attempted a [[bicycle kick]] in the 70th minute that was saved by Garlick.<ref>{{cite news |last=Firchau |first=Nick |date=October 23, 2011 |title=Top 50 MLS Cup Moments: #28 Biker Boss |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2011/10/24/top-50-mls-cup-moments-28-biker-boss |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> Colorado scored a consolation goal in the 75th minute from substitute Adri\u00e1n Paz, who struck the ball from a tight angle in the penalty area on an assist from Pati\u00f1o.<ref name=\"SS-Recap\"/> A chance to equalize came less than a minute later as Rapids forward Wolde Harris took an unimpeded shot from {{convert|20|yd|m}} that flew over the crossbar.<ref name=\"Goff\"/><ref name=\"NYT-Recap\">{{cite news |last=Yannis |first=Alex |date=October 27, 1997 |title=United Takes Lead, Then Holds On to Retain Its Title |page=C3 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/10/27/sports/soccer-united-takes-lead-then-holds-on-to-retain-its-title.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> D.C. responded with their own attacks that were shut down by the Rapids, including two fouls that were described as potential [[penalty kick]]s that went uncalled by referee [[Brian Hall (referee)|Brian Hall]].<ref name=\"Globe-Recap\"/> The hosts won 2\u20131 to claim their second MLS Cup title;<ref name=\"Goff\"/> Moreno was named the MLS Cup [[most valuable player]] for his performance, which included setting up plays throughout the match.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tucker |first=Bryan |date=October 27, 1997 |title=Moreno Makes Most of Opportunity |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/dcunited/longterm/1997/mlscup/launch/bryan27.htm |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Philly\">{{cite news |last=Jensen |first=Mike |date=October 27, 1997 |title=D.C. United again reigns in the rain |page=D3 |work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28394764/dc_united_again_reigns_in_the_rain/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 6, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\n===Details===\n{{football box\n|date = October 26, 1997\n|time = 3:30&nbsp;p.m. [[Eastern Time|EDT]]\n|team1 = [[D.C. United]]\n|score = 2\u20131\n|report= [https://www.mlssoccer.com/history/mls-cup/1997 Report]\n|team2 = [[Colorado Rapids]]\n|goals1 = \n*[[Jaime Moreno (footballer, born 1974)|Moreno]] {{goal|37}}\n*[[Tony Sanneh|Sanneh]] {{goal|68}}\n|goals2 = [[Adri\u00e1n Paz|Paz]] {{goal|75}}\n|stadium = [[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium]]\n|location = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n|attendance = 57,431\n|referee = [[Brian Hall (referee)|Brian Hall]]\n}}\n\n{| style=\"width:92%;\"\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n |pattern_la = _thinredborder\n |pattern_b  = _DCU_96h\n |pattern_ra = _thinredborder\n |pattern_sh = _DCU_96\n |pattern_so = _3_stripes_white\n |leftarm    = 000000\n |body       = FFFFFF\n |rightarm   = 000000\n |shorts     = 000000\n |socks      = 000000\n |title      = D.C. United\n}}\n|{{Football kit\n |pattern_la = \n |pattern_b  = \n |pattern_ra = \n |pattern_sh = \n |pattern_so = \n |leftarm    = FFFFFF\n |body       = FFFFFF\n |rightarm   = FFFFFF\n |shorts     = FFFFFF\n |socks      = FFFFFF\n |title      = Colorado Rapids\n}}\n|}\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Scott Garlick]] || {{yel|20}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''12''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jeff Agoos]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''18''' ||{{flagicon|COL}} [[Carlos Llamosa]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''23''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Eddie Pope]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''24''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[David Vaudreuil]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''10''' ||{{flagicon|BOL}} [[Marco Etcheverry]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''6''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[John Harkes]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|MF ||'''20''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Tony Sanneh]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''16''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Richie Williams]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''21''' ||{{flagicon|SLV}} [[Ra\u00fal D\u00edaz Arce]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''9''' ||{{flagicon|BOL}} [[Jaime Moreno (footballer, born 1974)|Jaime Moreno]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|colspan=3|{{in5}}''None used''\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Head coach:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Bruce Arena]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\"|\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=center\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Marcus Hahnemann]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''12''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Matt Kmosko]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''21''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Chris Martinez (soccer)|Chris Martinez]] || || {{suboff|59}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''4'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Steve Trittschuh]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''2'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Peter Vermes]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''17''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Marcelo Balboa]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]]) || {{yel|86}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''8'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Paul Bravo]] || || {{suboff|27}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''19'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Chris Henderson]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''3'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Sean Henderson]] || || {{suboff|81}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''6''' ||{{flagicon|MEX}} [[David Pati\u00f1o]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''10'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Steve Rammel]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|FW ||'''23'''||{{flagicon|JAM}} [[Wolde Harris]] || || {{subon|27}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''11'''||{{flagicon|URU}} [[Adri\u00e1n Paz]] || || {{subon|59}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''20'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Ross Paule]] || || {{subon|81}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Head coach:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Glenn Myernick]]\n|}\n|}\n{| style=\"width:100%;font-size:90%\"\n|\n'''MLS Cup Most Valuable Player:'''\n<br />[[Jaime Moreno (footballer, born 1974)|Jaime Moreno]] (D.C. United)\n\n'''Assistant referees:'''\n<br />Steve Olson\n<br />Greg Barkey\n\n|style=\"width:60%; vertical-align:top\"|\n'''Match rules'''\n*90 minutes of regulation time with a [[countdown clock]]\n*Two 15-minute periods of [[Extra time (association football)|extra time]] with [[golden goal]]s to decide a winner.\n*[[Penalty shoot-out (association football)#North American experiments|Penalty shootout]] from 35 yards if scores still tied.\n*Maximum of three substitutions.\n|}\n\n==Post-match==\n\nMLS Cup 1997 was the first sports championship for the Washington, D.C., area to be won at a stadium in the city.<ref>{{cite press release |date=October 8, 2007 |title=D.C. United announce ticket prices for 2008 season |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2010/01/23/dc-united-announce-ticket-prices-2008-season |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> The announced attendance of 57,431 came within 600 spectators of breaking the overall record for largest sporting event at RFK Memorial Stadium, held by the United States\u2013Portugal match during the 1996 Summer Olympics.<ref name=\"Post-Dream\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=White |first=Joseph |date=October 26, 1997 |title=United 2, Rapids 1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/dcunited/longterm/1997/mlscup/united27.htm |work=The Washington Post |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref> It was the first day in which there were large sporting events at both of the major outdoor stadiums in the D.C. area, as [[Jack Kent Cooke Stadium]] also hosted a [[National Football League]] game.<ref name=\"Post-Rain\"/> A railing in the upper stands at RFK Memorial Stadium collapsed during the celebrations after the match, causing minor injuries to 50 fans.<ref>{{cite news |date=October 27, 1997 |title=Dozens injured when railings collapse at RFK after MLS Cup |page=8 |work=[[The Independent-Record]] |location=Helena, Montana |agency=Associated Press |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28394737/mls_cup_1997_recap/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 6, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\nThree days after the MLS Cup final, D.C. United played the Dallas Burn in the [[1997 U.S. Open Cup Final|U.S. Open Cup Final]] with a chance to earn the league's first \"[[Treble (association football)|treble]]\". The Burn and United played to a scoreless draw and D.C. lost 5\u20133 in the ensuing penalty shootout.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stejskal |first=Sam |date=November 27, 2017 |title=Could Toronto FC become the first MLS team to win a domestic treble? |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2017/11/27/could-toronto-fc-become-first-mls-team-win-domestic-treble |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref> The team, with the exception of Etcheverry and Moreno on national team duty, was honored with a reception at the [[White House]] by President [[Bill Clinton]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Clarke |first=Liz |date=April 7, 1998 |title=Two-Time Champion United Honored at White House |page=E6 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1998/04/07/two-time-champion-united-honored-at-white-house/4a2da7f9-c817-4ccf-a00a-afe3d4cad126/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> D.C. returned to the MLS Cup in [[MLS Cup 1998|1998]], where they lost to the [[Chicago Fire SC|Chicago Fire]], and in [[MLS Cup 1999|1999]], where they defeated the Los Angeles Galaxy.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=November 22, 1999 |title=D.C.'s Two First-Half Goals Doom Galaxy |page=D1 |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/dcunited/longterm/1999/mlscup/united22.htm |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nD.C. and Colorado qualified as the U.S. representatives for the [[1998 CONCACAF Champions' Cup]], which was hosted at RFK Memorial Stadium in Washington, D.C.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=April 26, 1998 |title=On Second Thought, United Seeks Change |page=D6 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> The Rapids were eliminated in the qualifying playoff round, played in a home-and-away series against [[Club Le\u00f3n]] of Mexico, by a 4\u20133 aggregate score.<ref>{{cite news |date=July 16, 1998 |title=Leon preys on, eliminates shorthanded Rapids 4\u20132 |page=C13 |work=Rocky Mountain News}}</ref> D.C. entered the competition in the quarterfinals and eliminated Trinidadian club [[Joe Public F.C.|Joe Public]], Le\u00f3n, and Mexican champion [[Deportivo Toluca F.C.|Toluca]] on their way to winning the Champions' Cup, becoming the first American team to be crowned as continental champions.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=August 17, 1998 |title=United Steps Up, Wins Champions' Cup |page=C1 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=August 16, 1998 |title=United Faces Toluca Seeking Title, Respect |page=D6 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> United then advanced to the [[1998 Copa Interamericana]], where they defeated South American champions [[CR Vasco da Gama|Vasco da Gama]] of Brazil over two legs played in the United States.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rusnak |first=Jeff |date=December 6, 1998 |title=D.C. stops Brazilians |page=C17 |work=Sun-Sentinel |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/18125728/interamerican_cup_recap/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=December 6, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{MLSCup}}\n{{1997 in American soccer}}\n{{D.C. United matches}}\n{{Colorado Rapids}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1997 Mls Cup}}\n[[Category:MLS Cup]]\n[[Category:1997 Major League Soccer season|*Cup]]\n[[Category:D.C. United matches|MLS Cup 97]]\n[[Category:Colorado Rapids matches|MLS Cup 97]]\n[[Category:Soccer in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:October 1997 sports events in the United States]]\n[[Category:1997 in sports in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "name_user": "SounderBruce", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eColorado Rapids:redundant", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MLS_Cup_1997"}
